<HEADLINE>
RED SOX BEAT ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ On paper, the game looked like a mismatch:
Pedro Martinez of the Boston Red Sox facing the Angels' Allen
Watson.
</P>
<P>
   And the paper was right.
</P>
<P>
   Watson pitched well Saturday until an error by first baseman
Dave Hollins paved the way for a two-run fourth inning for the Red
Sox. Then Watson caved in. And the Angels followed, ultimately
losing 11-3 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Watson gave up a two-run home run to No. 8 hitter Mike Benjamin
to put Boston ahead 4-0 in the fifth. In the sixth, Damon Buford
hit a two-run homer for a 6-0 Red Sox lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels managed three runs off Martinez, but the Angels
bullpen allowed five runs in the ninth to finish the game with a
thud.
</P>
<P>
   It was Angels' fourth loss in five games on an important
homestand that is matching this team against the American League's
best: New York, Boston, Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew coming into the homestand who we were playing, who was
pitching (for the opposition),'' Angels manager Terry Collins said.
``We knew we couldn't afford to make mistakes against teams like
that. We've got to capitalize on our opportunities, we've got to
pitch better. It's the complete package. We're not playing well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is we're just not getting it done. You can't
point the finger at any one part of our game.''
</P>
<P>
   The beginning of the end started in the bottom of the third
inning when the Angels put runners on first and third with nobody
out. Darin Erstad hit a chopper to Martinez on the mound, and
Martinez caught Matt Walbeck between third and home and threw him
out.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez escaped without giving up a run, and the Red Sox seized
the opportunity in the top of the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   John Valentin led off with a popup behind the mound. Hollins
called for the ball but dropped it. The Red Sox took advantage by
scoring two runs in the inning and rolled from there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if (the error) broke his concentration or not,''
Collins said of Watson, ``but you've got to be able to battle
through it and we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   There was talk of possible trades before Friday night's
deadline. Then nothing happened. But shortstop Gary DiSarcina, who
had two hits off Martinez, said the uncertainty shouldn't have been
distracting to the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come here to play baseball,'' he said. ``You know, playing
shortstop in the major leagues is pretty difficult. And facing
Pedro Martinez is pretty difficult. I can only speak for myself,
because everybody's different. Some guys speak their mind and put
blame somewhere else. But the bottom line is you're here to play.
You don't get paid to worry about other things.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have plenty to worry about without looking elsewhere.
The bullpen has been horrible in the past three games, allowing 12
runs in 62/3 innings. And the offense continues to struggle when it
has opportunities to score.
</P>
<P>
   With two out and runners in scoring position this season, the
Angels are hitting .190 as a team. Saturday, they were 1 for 7 with
runners in scoring position, the only hit being Orlando Palmeiro's
two-run single with the bases loaded. Jim Edmonds drove in the
Angels' other run with his 16th homer of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez (15-3) joined the Yankees' David Cone as the only
15-game winners in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been playing good teams,'' said Garret Anderson, whose
hitting streak ended at 28 with an 0-for-4 performance. ``You can't
give these teams too many mistakes. It seems like we're playing
just good enough to lose. And (in) some other games, these teams
are just flat-out beating us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston is pretty comparable to New York,'' DiSarcina said.
``They may not have the starting pitching New York has, but they're
solid. We're short right now. We can't give these teams any extra
outs. We've got to move runners over. We can't make errors. We have
to do all the little things. If we don't, we lose to these teams.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
