<SLUG> BC-ROY-ROGERS-FAREWELL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOY'S FRIENDS, FANS WISH HIM `HAPPY TRAILS'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY MELISSA SCHMITT  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``Goodbye, good luck and may the good Lord take a
liking to ya.''
</P>
<P>
   These were some of Roy Rogers' own words that friends,
acquaintances and fans spoke in saying farewell to the cowboy star
at a suburban Los Angeles church during a simple memorial service
Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers died &UR;  &LR; July 6 at the age of 86 at his home in the Southern
California desert community of Apple Valley, near Victorville, a
hero to the fans of his TV show and 100 movies.
</P>
<P>
   And long ago, while his face was a regular on the television
screen and in Hollywood, he touched the lives of a small group of
people who knew him as a congregation member of Pioneer Church,
before it was moved to Oakwood Memorial Park and preserved as a
landmark 33 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It was $1,000 of the beloved cowboy's money that started the
fund that eventually paid for the moving of the church.
</P>
<P>
   Those who filled the wooden pews at the church Saturday morning,
as a breeze fluttered the white embroidered curtains, remembered
those days with pride.
</P>
<P>
   Fanning themselves with programs, they remembered Rogers as
patient, loving, charitable and wonderful with children.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was true to the values of his on-screen performance,'' said
Lila Schepler, who went to church with Rogers and organized the
service. ``He has graduated to his new role as one of God's
angels.''
</P>
<P>
   The service attracted about 100 people to Pioneer Church, now
standing in the rear of Oakwood Memorial Park.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers was honored at the service with a rendition of ``Happy
Trails,'' the reading of ``The Cowboy's Prayer'' and by guitarist
David Arlen, who played ``Cool Clear Water.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the service, those in attendance dropped cash into
a Stetson that will go to benefit the Roy Rogers Museum in
Victorville.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, people gathered to share their stories and memories of
Rogers and his wife, Dale Evans.
</P>
<P>
   Leo Alexander and his daughter Sharon Thornton are in Los
Angeles this week visiting friends they knew in Houston long ago.
The friends now live in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've liked Roy Rogers ever since I was a little girl in
Houston,'' said Thornton, 56, of Giddings, Texas, a small town
about 50 miles outside Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daddy took me to see Roy Rogers, and he shook my hand,'' she
said with a Texas drawl. ``I won a bicycle in a coloring contest,
tickets to the rodeo and lunch with Roy Rogers. But Daddy is the
one who wanted to come today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Daddy'' is now 84, but he can still remember seeing Rogers in
a Houston parade and running up to him for a handshake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was hollerin','' Alexander said outside the church.
``I raced over and shook his hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Dolezal, 52; his wife, Barbara, 50; and their daughter
Clarissa, 15, enjoyed the service as well.
</P>
<P>
   Marlene Winstead, 60, and Mark Davis, 54, of Chatsworth said
they attended the service after seeing a notice at the public
library.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing that we live in Chatsworth, we felt this is something
we should participate in,'' Winstead said.
</P>
<P>
   One of Rogers' daughters attended the ceremony, which was
organized by the Chatsworth Historical Society.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboy's Prayer
</P>
<P>
   Oh Lord, I reckon I'm not much just by myself.
</P>
<P>
   I fail to do a lot of things I ought to do.
</P>
<P>
   But Lord, when the trails are steep and the passes high,
</P>
<P>
   Help me to ride it straight the whole way through.
</P>
<P>
   And when in the falling dusk I get the final call,
</P>
<P>
   I do not care how many flowers they send _
</P>
<P>
   Above all else the happiest trail would be
</P>
<P>
   For You to say to me, ``Let's ride, my friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Amen.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
