<SLUG> BC-TEN-MERCEDES-FINAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TITLE MATCH PITS POWER VS. PATIENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DANA HADDAD  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fifth-seeded Andre Agassi figures to face his toughest opponent
of the Mercedes-Benz Cup when he plays second-seeded Tim Henman
today in the final, and vice versa. The two have never faced each
other.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, 28, is on a roll with 10 consecutive straight-set
victories in ATP tournament play. Henman, 23, is ranked No.12 on
the ATP Tour, one spot ahead of Agassi, and nobody has been able to
overcome his 142-mph serve. Henman entered Saturday's semifinals
leading the tournament with 42 aces, 17 more than No.2 man Kenneth
Carlsen. He will have a decided advantage over Agassi in power.
</P>
<P>
   But Agassi, who appears to have whipped himself back into Grand
Slam form, will have the edge in savvy and experience.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the contrasts: Henman, of England, is a
6-foot-1 right-handed serve-and-volleyer who uses a one-hand
backhand. Agassi is a 5-11 right-handed baseliner who uses a
two-hand backhand. Henman prefers to win his points quickly with
first-serve bombs followed by volleys to an open court. Agassi
likes to spar from the baseline, patiently setting up his winners.
</P>
<P>
   Edge: Agassi. He's playing too well. In the semifinals against
Justin Gimelstob, whose style closely resembles Henman's, Agassi
made only nine unforced errors while repeatedly tying Gimelstob up
at the net or passing him with well-placed ground strokes. Henman
has been erratic with his best weapon. He entered Saturday with one
of the worst first-serve percentages in the tournament at 49
percent while winning only 52 percent of his second-serve points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
