<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM DUQUETTE FILLS HOLES WITH TRADES 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-TRADES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette said
Saturday he is still hopeful designated hitter Reggie Jefferson and
second baseman Lou Merloni will be back before the end of the
season, but Friday's trades for lefthanded-hitting Orlando Merced
and minor league infielder Eddy Diaz were clearly hedges against
their extended absence.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of lefthanded reliever Greg Swindell, meanwhile,
brought to an end the brief, inglorious career of David West in the
Sox bullpen. In the week he was with the team, West managed to
record five outs, but he also gave up five hits and five walks.
Also designated for assignment was Billy Ashley, who had just 24
at-bats in five weeks with the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox failed, however, to accomplish what they had
targeted as their prime objective _ to obtain another starting
pitcher. Up until the final minutes before the trading deadline,
the Sox thought they were still in the running for Seattle's Randy
Johnson, who wound up going to the Houston Astros for two prospects
and a player to be named.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn, meanwhile, took comfort in the fact that he wasn't
traded, and, in another 180-degree spin, expressed renewed
enthusiasm for staying with the Red Sox for the long term.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't start thinking about being traded until I got here
and it was three or four hours before the deadline,'' Vaughn said.
``Baseball is a big business. You don't know what's going to
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad this organization gave me the opportunity to
stay with this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after Vaughn's diatribe a week ago accusing the club of
tailing him with private investigators and accusing him of using
drugs, Duquette said it was ``doubtful'' the club would trade him.
But as reported by the Globe last week, even before Vaughn's
outburst there were internal discussions about trading him to the
Chicago White Sox for first baseman Frank Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   White Sox general manager Ron Schueler told the Chicago
Sun-Times Saturday that the Red Sox did call. ``I'm not going to
lie about it,'' Schueler said. ``They called about three weeks ago,
but it was very casual talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn also expressed hope that it was more than casual talk
when Red Sox CEO John Harrington told Globe columnist Will
McDonough that the club still wants to sign Vaughn to a contract
extension.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad John Harrington did say that and was willing to put
it on the line like that,'' said Vaughn, whose performance has not
suffered during the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   He has hit in nine straight games (15 for 35, .429) since
telling the Toronto Sun his No. 1 preference was to play for the
Blue Jays. That may change when he learns that Roger Clemens's
agent, Alan Hendricks, asked Toronto GM Gord Ash to explore trading
the Rocket to a contender, a revelation that led to Clemens being
blasted in the Toronto papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come down to it,'' Vaughn said of his situation with
the Red Sox, ``I hope there will be no hard feelings, no anything
except an opportunity to stay here.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, asked if he had had any communications, either directly
or through back channels, that caused him to feel encouraged that
his contract situation would be resolved, said, ``By the
organization keeping me here is enough. Right now, I don't know of
any discussions taking place, but keeping me here is enough for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Johnson situation, in the end the front-runners for
the Big Unit, the Indians and Yankees, balked at parting with the
starting pitchers (Dave Burba and Ramiro Mendoza, respectively)
that the Mariners were seeking in return. The Red Sox were offering
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trade of Randy Johnson was a curious trade,'' Duquette
said. ``There were a number of teams involved, but from the
beginning the Mariners engaged other ball clubs instead of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette held out the possibility that the Red Sox still might
be able to claim a pitcher on waivers in the next month. A number
of veteran pitchers went untraded Friday night, most notably Tim
Belcher of the Royals, Mark Portugal of the Phillies, and Jon
Lieber of the Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   Merced, playing almost exclusively against righthanded pitchers,
was batting .289 this season with 5 home runs in 204 at-bats, but
just .208 in 24 at-bats in July.
</P>
<P>
   Merced made his last start July 13 and had just two pinch
hitting appearances since. Merced, who signed a one-year deal with
the Twins for $800,000, had asked to be traded.
</P>
<P>
   The Twins had attempted to re-sign Swindell, who is being paid
$1.3 million this season and is eligible for free agency. When it
became apparent that the price might get too high, Minnesota
reportedly entertained offers from the Cubs, Padres, and Mets
before trading him to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   A former 18-game winner with the Indians, Swindell signed a rich
free agent contract with the Astros but wound up being released by
Houston in early June 1996. The Indians signed him 12 days later,
but he pitched poorly in Cleveland before winding up with the
Twins, with whom he had a 3-3 record and 3.66 ERA in 51 appearances
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our need for a professional lefty in the bullpen has been
demonstrated in the last couple of weeks,'' said Duquette, alluding
to the failure of West and Ron Mahay to handle that role.
</P>
<P>
   Swindell, however, also has shown a penchant for giving up home
runs. He has allowed 10 in just 66 1/3 innings, including one to
Jose Canseco in his last appearance for the Twins Friday night.
That's more home runs than any reliever on the Red Sox roster.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn said he was encouraged by the acquisitions the team made.
``We looked at the situation and were prepared to do what we have
to do with what we had,'' he said. ``But anything (Duquette) can do
to help is good. We got some help. That's what happened. We got
some guys that can help this team. We're all glad in here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
