<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ANGELS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMERS HELP MARTINEZ TO NO. 15 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ They are exactly two-thirds of the way through
the season and showing no signs of being anything less than they've
been since April.
</P>
<P>
   It's been written before: When the calendar turns to August and
the Red Sox are in playoff contention, that's when New England
feels the first chill of winter.
</P>
<P>
   But only the darkest Calvinist can take a dim view of the way
the Red Sox continue to carve up the West Coast, taking their
second straight from the Anaheim Angels, 11-3, with a bloodless
efficiency that sucked the life out of a crowd of 29,893 Saturday
at Edison International Field.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Eckersley, for one, knows about the immutable laws of
diminished expectations back home. But he has news for those
waiting for this team _ 20 games over .500 for the first time this
season _ to collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``That 15-game lead the Yankees have on us feels like it takes
the pressure off us,'' Eckersley said. ``Everybody treats us like
we're 15 out instead of up by six in the wild-card. We can lay in
the weeds till it's time to get after it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know if I'm the Yankees, I'd be afraid I'm (peaking) now,
and worry about losing in the first round of the playoffs. Now
that's pressure. Anybody can win a five-game series.''
</P>
<P>
   Backed by home runs by Mike Benjamin, Damon Buford, and Troy
O'Leary, Pedro Martinez joined David Cone as the major leagues'
only 15-game winners, limiting the Angels to three hits, including
Jim Edmonds's 16th home run, until weakening in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, winning for the ninth time in his last 10 starts,
received a huge assist from Derek Lowe, who entered after Orlando
Palmeiro's two-run single made it 6-3 in the eighth and set down
the last six Angels in order.
</P>
<P>
   ``Derek Lowe was probably the key to me getting that win,''
Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe came on with runners at first and third and no outs and
overpowered the next three hitters, strikeouts of Cecil Fielder and
rookie Troy Glaus sandwiched around a tapper to the mound by Garret
Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``That all comes from Jimy (Williams) putting me in so many
tight situations early in the season, when I was able to have some
success,'' Lowe said. ``I'm very confident to go out in tight
situations. I'm relaxed. I know I can get out of those
situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson went 0 for 4, bringing to an end his 28-game hitting
streak, the longest in the majors this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sorry that I had to stop it,'' Martinez said. ``But
it's a jungle out there. You have to kill to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, meanwhile, are in major freefall, despite their
standing atop the AL West. They're just 9-19 in their last 28 games
and have lost 12 of their last 16 at home.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who helped himself with a snatch and throw to the
plate in the second inning when the Angels had runners on the
corners with none out, has not allowed more than three earned runs
in his last nine starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team looks fine right now,'' Martinez said. ``We're very
confident, we're healthy, thanks to God and knock on wood. I hope
we keep it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got key guys in key trades. (Mike Stanley) makes us a
lot more stable, more experienced. We're still waiting for
(Orlando) Merced and (Greg) Swindell. Things should get better as
we go along.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, who have outscored the Angels, 18-5, in the last
two days, exploited a missed popup on the mound to break through
with two runs in the fourth inning, then added two-run home runs by
Benjamin in the fifth and Buford in the sixth off Angels starter
Allen Watson for a 6-1 lead. They scored five more runs in the
ninth, when they sent nine men to the plate, including O'Leary, who
hit his 19th home run.
</P>
<P>
   Buford, a native of Los Angeles, continues to confound those who
believed his usefulness began and ended with his glove. The platoon
specialist is batting .388 (19 for 49) in his last dozen starts,
having driven in 13 runs.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin, meanwhile, missed a bunt attempt after Scott
Hatteberg's walk to lead off the fifth, then hit his third home run
in less than a month after going more than two years without going
deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody talked about how we didn't want to jell too soon,''
Benjamin said. ``We needed everybody to pick it up and pitch in
again, especially on this road trip.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox have now won four out of five on this 14-day,
12-game trip to four cities and have assured themselves of winning
their second straight series on this trek.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of fun to play with these guys,'' said Stanley, who
registered his first RBI since coming back to the Red Sox with a
sacrifice fly. ``I've kept my eye on them. They've been playing
like this all year long, that's for sure. It's fun to be on the
same side.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
