<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-WHITESOX-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW-LOOK RANGERS RIP WHITE SOX, 8-1
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Todd Zeile knows how to make a powerful first
impression.
</P>
<P>
   And Royce Clayton isn't bad at saying hello, either.
</P>
<P>
   The newest Rangers acquisitions provided a much-needed spark in
their first appearance last night, combining to drive in four runs
in last night's 8-1 victory against the Chicago White Sox at The
Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile lofted a 368-foot solo home run over the right-field fence
in the fifth inning, then drove in two more runs with singles in
the first and third innings. The first-inning hit scored Clayton,
who had stolen a base and later drove in a run in the fourth with a
sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   The victory temporarily lifted the Rangers out of a funk that
had seen them lose six of seven games. It also moved them into a
first-place tie with the Anaheim Angels, who haven't been setting
the American League West on fire lately, either.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Zeile and shortstop Clayton were obtained Friday
in trades. Zeile was the latest Florida Marlins departure, and
Clayton came from the St. Louis Cardinals along with pitcher Todd
Stottlemyre.
</P>
<P>
   General manager ``Doug Melvin should feel very good,'' Rangers
manager Johnny Oates said. ``There was electricity in the stands. I
know the crowd really seemed to appreciate the game Todd had,
offensively and defensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives everybody a pick-me-up. Other players look around and
see you've got two veterans that know how to play the game.
Hopefully, we'll carry this attitude for at least the next two
months, and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeile introduced himself by handling a scorching Frank Thomas
liner three batters into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Three innings later, his diving stop at the foul line held Mike
Cameron to a single, saving one run and possibly two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they don't expect that every night, but what better way
to start somewhere?'' Zeile said. ``I guess you could tell I was
excited and enthusiastic about coming here to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go from the absolute bottom of the cellar to a team in first
place. No way to describe it.''
</P>
<P>
   The energy also seemed to carry over to the mound, as Rick
Helling got back on track with a decent five-inning performance.
</P>
<P>
   Helling scattered eight hits and struggled at times, but gave up
only one run, and that came with an asterisk. Texas right fielder
Roberto Kelly got a slow jump on Mike Caruso's line drive that went
over Kelly's head for a first-inning triple. That scored Ray
Durham, who led off the game with a single.
</P>
<P>
   Helling, (14-6), had allowed 18 earned runs in 23 innings in his
three most recent starts before last night.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers put the game out of reach with a three-run outburst
in the eighth, capped by Bill Haselman's two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   Middle reliever Xavier Hernandez took over from Helling in the
fifth and pitched three scoreless innings, allowing one hit. John
Wetteland worked a scoreless ninth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
