</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S SHOW TIME FOR PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SAN FRANCISCO _ Sunday night the real football begins for the
men clinging to the edges of the New England Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   For the bulk of the Patriots, the Lawyer Milloys, Drew Bledsoes,
Terry Glenns, Willie McGinests and Bruce Armstrongs, Sunday night's
season-opening exhibition game against the San Francisco 49ers will
be only a brief continuation of what they have gone through the
past two weeks. It will be a dress rehearsal for a game they are
not yet fully ready to play, like a show opening in Boston or
Baltimore on its way to Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   For them this is a time for tinkering with their performances,
working on the new offense being installed by offensive coordinator
Ernie Zampese, or perfecting the defense Steve Sidwell put in a
year ago and ran so effectively at the end of the season that an
injury-riddled team came within 1 point of returning to the AFC
Championship Game.
</P>
<P>
   That game, a 7-6 loss in Pittsburgh, is one whose bitter memory
those Patriots will begin to try and erase Sunday night, but that
will not be what is on the minds of the men on the edges.
</P>
<P>
   For Vincent Brisby, Todd Rucci, Chris Canty, or the runners Shaw
_ Sedrick and Harold _ this game will be a showcase or a first
black mark against them. It will be a game in which they most often
face players the 49ers no more intend to have on the 3Com Park
field in September than the Patriots intend to have Canty or the
runners Shaw on the field at Foxboro Stadium. To change that, to
get on the field or to just stay near it, they must play this one
for real, because for them it is no exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   For a kid like Canty, games like this were not supposed to carry
with them such pressure so soon. A year ago, he was a first-round
draft choice of the defending AFC champions. He was a cornerback
with a future.
</P>
<P>
   But after struggling all season to find himself (as well as the
receivers he was supposed to be covering), Canty has come into 1998
with many questions surrounding him, but the simplest one is this _
can he or Canty?
</P>
<P>
   A job is open at right cornerback, but frankly the Patriots
don't want him to win it. They want their new No. 1 draft choice,
their new love, Tebucky Jones, to win it. Failing that, they want a
guy so often injured in his career he should be known as Beth
Israel instead of Steve Israel to win it.
</P>
<P>
   Canty is in that sweepstakes, too, and there is an opening
because Israel has continued to spend more time on a bicycle than a
competitor in the Tour de France and Jones has been limping with a
sore hamstring. But where Canty had the inside edge by virtue of
being Mr. No. 1 last year, now he's clinging to the outside, and
after a quick start in camp, already there are those saying he has
begun to fade because of tired legs and too many reps in practice
that reveal his shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   So for Canty, Sunday night is not what it is for the man who
will start opposite him. For Ty Law, this is just a formal practice
session. Law will play little more than a quarter and what he does
during that time will say nothing about him. He is a fixture. Chris
Canty is not.
</P>
<P>
   Same is true for veteran wide receiver Brisby, who wasn't even
supposed to be here. By the end of last season it appeared Brisby
would be a salary cap casualty, a victim of too many receivers
having snuck in ahead of him last year when he never got untracked
after feeling he'd outplayed Shawn Jefferson in camp (which he did)
and not been awarded the job he'd earned.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday night he starts ahead of Jefferson, who also has a
sore hamstring. Because of Glenn's injury history and
disinclination to join strength coach Johnny Parker's offseason
workouts fully, Brisby stayed alive all winter and has been
promised a chance to win his job back. And so he is here, looking
to show that he can still get open in the middle and catch the ball
when he does, even if he lacks Jefferson's deep speed.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Brisby understands how things work in the NFL. He knows
coaches love speed first and Jefferson has more of it, so while
this may be an exhibition for some, it is real for him. He must
shine because someone at his position won't be around next month
and because of the $1.2 million he stands to make he is still the
leading candidate for unemployment, unless he shows enough to make
the choice hard on his coaches. That process begins at 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   And what of the runners Shaw? With Curtis Martin limping on Long
Island this summer instead of in New England, the Patriots are
looking for a No. 1 running back. If they are realists, the runners
Shaw know the most likely candidate is No. 1 draft choice and
newest Patriot millionaire, Robert Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Sunday night Sedrick Shaw, a third-round choice who didn't
play a down until the postseason last year, starts at running back,
and rookie Harold Shaw also gets a chance to show if the first
impression he made during two weeks facing friendly fire counts for
anything when he's in with strange faces.
</P>
<P>
   If either impresses, he gets another chance to compete with
Edwards next weekend for a job that it seems has already been
handed out. Poor Sedrick knows he is running with the first unit
against one of the best defenses in the NFL because of tradition
and nothing more. A rookie does not start ahead of the most senior
man in the first exhibition game except in most unusual
circumstances, so Shaw is in with the Bledsoes and Armstrongs
instead of Edwards, and their presence is his best chance to make
this a real competition because he is less likely to get a second
chance like this if he fails to take advantage of the first one.
Regardless of what you may be told in the days ahead, this is his
moment.
</P>
<P>
   In front of the runners Shaw will stand Rucci, a guy who should
be on top of the world. Rucci has started the last several seasons
at right guard on some very good teams and signed a five-year, $10
million contract in the offseason. One might assume he feels like
the Armstrongs of the world. He does not.
</P>
<P>
   That is because there is no five-year contract in the NFL. There
are five one-year contracts, which means short of the bonus money
he got, he could be fired at any time and collect nothing. Worse,
young Heath Irwin, who comes a lot cheaper, is being given a chance
to battle Rucci for his job and will split time with him Sunday
night with the first unit.
</P>
<P>
   There is a clear message there. It is that a new contract has
not given Rucci more security than he had before, when it seemed he
was in a constant fight for his life. For Rucci and the others in
his position, that fight begins Sunday night. That is the real life
drama of games like this one, where the score means less than
nothing, and the injury report is the most important bit of
information to people watching with blind eyes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
