<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS KICK IT OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ After 13 days of drills, 7-on-7s, one scrimmage,
and some 50 hours of practice time, the New England Patriots get to
travel 3,000 miles to play a team other than their own Sunday night
at 3Com Park.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots coach Pete Carroll returns to his hometown to play
against the San Francisco 49ers, for whom he spent two seasons as
the defensive coordinator. Carroll termed the homecoming
``special'' this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody wants to go home and play,'' said Carroll.
``My family will all be there, and there's a sense of pride you
have that you want to show off your team and show them what you can
do. We can't lose sight of the goals we have for this game, which
are really getting to watch our units play together and continue to
see the different competitions we have on our team unfolding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have five of these, so the first game won't reflect badly
on anyone. Everybody will have some chances to redeem themselves or
put a better foot forward if they don't play as well as we'd want
them to.''
</P>
<P>
   And the meeting is also special for a few faces on the Patriots
squad, most notably sophomore running back Sedrick Shaw, who will
start, No. 1 draft pick Robert Edwards, who will spell Shaw and
probably see some third-down duty early in the game, and defensive
back Tebucky Jones, the Patriots' second first-round pick who will
spell last year's No. 1 pick, Chris Canty, and second-year corner
Mark Tate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just go out there and follow my blocks and show everyone what
I can do,'' said Shaw, a man of few words.
</P>
<P>
   One of the knocks on Shaw is that he's the most likely to get
Drew Bledsoe hurt, because he hasn't shown great blocking ability,
and is likely to come out on third down.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, who has suffered the past week from a strained left
groin, says he's not yet 100 percent, but expects to play some.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be the first time I play in an NFL game, so I want to
get out there and perform,'' he said. ``After being in camp for a
couple of weeks, I'm starting to get a better understanding of the
pro game and what it takes. To play your first game against the
49ers, that's a team with a lot of great history. It's exciting
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll wouldn't commit to how long Edwards or Jones would play.
He also wouldn't reveal the number of plays the first offense would
run. A major part of the first exhibition game will be to measure
how Bledsoe and his receivers have adapted to the Ernie Zampese
quick-pass offense. Based mostly on timing, the receivers will have
to run precision routes in a game situation. Top receiver Terry
Glenn has played superbly in training camp, showing no ill effects
of a broken collarbone he sustained in the team's playoff loss to
the Pittsburgh Steelers Jan. 3. Glenn has also shown that he's
taking camp seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The cornerbacks will also be under a microscope. Canty, who is
taking pro life a little more seriously, needs to show it on the
field. Unfortunately, there will be no Jerry Rice to provide the
ultimate test for Canty or Jones.
</P>
<P>
   One place where the competition is getting stiff is the right
guard spot, where third-year man Heath Irwin is pushing Todd Rucci.
The Patriots are trying to light a fire under Rucci, who elected to
spend most of the offseason at his La Jolla, Calif., home rather
than take part in the conditioning program.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coaches Steve Sidwell and Ray Hamilton will look
closely at the line play. Ferric Collons, Mark Wheeler, Henry
Thomas, and Willie McGinest will start, but three of the four
players may be fighting off the likes of Chad Eaton, Chris
Sullivan, Brandon Mitchell, and rookie Greg Spires for playing
time.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll is also looking to see much more fire on special teams,
which he will stack with rookies and second-year players around
All-Pro Larry Whigham, Marty Moore, and Tedy Bruschi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right from the start we're looking for a unit that will create
some hits and maybe some turnovers,'' said Carroll. ``It took us a
while to get going last year. We'd like to have that energy right
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the other agenda is keeping key players such as Ted
Johnson, Bledsoe, Glenn, Ty Law, and Lawyer Milloy healthy.
Already, the Patriots' two major rivals _ Miami and New York _ have
suffered tough injuries, particularly the Jets, who have lost
linebacker Marvin Jones for the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
