<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-02 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4135 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-JOHNSON-GM-HNS &LR;      08-02 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-JOHNSON-GM-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros GM Hunsicker makes the call
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PITTSBURGH _ The Randy Johnson sweepstakes came down to two phone
calls.
</P>
<P>
   The one Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker decided to make.
And the one he made that was almost too late.
</P>
<P>
   After a frantic day of on-again, off-again trade inquiries and
counter-proposals, it was the Astros who landed Johnson, the 6-10
lefthander from the Seattle Mariners, just minutes before the 11
p.m. CDT open trade deadline.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Hunsicker could call New York to report the deal,
his deadline was down to seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Bidding against deep-pocket teams like the New York Yankees and
Cleveland Indians, the Astros were an unlikely destination for The
Big Unit, who for months had been the center of incessant trade
talk.
</P>
<P>
   Houston became a quiet player in the race only in the final few
days. And an hour before the deadline, Hunsicker says he had lost
hope of acquiring the overpowering pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even sure I believe what's happened,'' Hunsicker said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``With an hour to go, I really did not think we had a chance at
anything. We still had a few things (trade possibilities) going,
and this obviously was one of them. I had not heard from Seattle
for three or four hours and that was significant, because prior to
that we had a half-dozen conversations, (speaking) almost hourly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last hour seemed like 24 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point (around 10 p.m.), Hunsicker called Seattle general
manager Woody Woodward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't heard from them in awhile so I got antsy because we
obviously were dealing with some pretty stout competition when you
think about the Yankees and Indians,'' Hunsicker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, with an hour to go, I said I was going to make the
call. I couldn't stand it anymore. If we were going down and were
not going to make this happen, I told myself I would at least give
it my last shot and see if I could make it work.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier discussions with the Mariners had broken down,
reportedly because Hunsicker refused Seattle's request for
righthander Scott Elarton, a player Hunsicker calls
``untouchable.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle informed the Astros at 10:20 p.m. that their offer _
without Elarton _ was under ``serious consideration,'' and
Hunsicker immediately alerted owner Drayton McLane Jr. and team
president Tal Smith.
</P>
<P>
   McLane agreed to spend the extra $2 million it would take to pay
Johnson's salary for the rest of this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next 20 minutes were like waiting for your first born,''
Hunsicker said.
</P>
<P>
   When he had not heard back from the Mariners at 10:45, ``I
thought, I knew it, the Yankees and Indians are making a
last-minute effort to up the ante and it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, at 10:50 p.m., Seattle accepted Hunsicker's proposal of
infielder Carlos Guillen, pitcher Freddy Garcia and a player to be
named.
</P>
<P>
   Even after the sides reached agreement, the deal almost didn't
happen because Hunsicker made his call to New York at precisely 11
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``The person on the other end of the phone (at the league
office) told me that when the phone rang their clock showed
midnight (EDT),'' Hunsicker said. ``They said if I would have
called one minute later, it would have really put them in a bind
and possibly voided the trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker also said the Astros inquired about Toronto
righthander Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some discussions with Toronto, but never got
anywhere,'' Hunsicker said. ``I don't think they were really
interested in trading Roger Clemens, by the laundry list of names
they wanted in return.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in this to win a championship this year. We're pulling
out all the stops that make sense to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of Johnson gives the Astros a dominant No. 1
starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can look good on paper and it doesn't work,'' Hunsicker
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Astros are probably one of those teams that is playing
better than most people thought. Those of us that knew the talent
aren't surprised. If anything, the pitching has exceeded our
expectations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-98 0055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
