<DOCNO> NYT19980802.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-02 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4136 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-JOHNSON-PITCHERS-     08-02 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-JOHNSON-PITCHERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Intimidating lefthander carries on Astros tradition
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PITTSBURGH _ In an effort to bring a first World Series to Houston,
the Astros are returning to their roots.
</P>
<P>
   That can mean only one thing to fans: dust off the ``K''
placards.
</P>
<P>
   When was the last time you saw the familiar KKKKKKKKKK _ a
baseball tradition for charting strikeouts _ hanging from the
railings in the Astrodome?
</P>
<P>
   For a franchise that goes by a ``pitching-first'' motto, it's
been almost a decade since a dominating,
strike-fear-in-the-heart-of-an-opponent pitcher has taken the mound
for the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Astros tradition begins _ and ends _ with Nolan Ryan,
major-league baseball's all-time strikeout leader who terrorized
opposing batters with a 100-mph fastball that helped lead the
Astros to two division titles in nine seasons.
</P>
<P>
   J.R. Richard, whose career was cut short by injury, set a club
record with 313 strikeouts in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   And who could forget Mike Scott, who baffled hitters with a
sinking split-finger fastball and recorded one of the most
memorable moments in franchise history with his no-hitter against
San Francisco to clinch the 1986 National League West championship?
</P>
<P>
   In a matter of one day, things have gotten even bigger _ as in
the Big Unit.
</P>
<P>
   Needing a dominant No. 1 pitcher to complete what many baseball
observers view as a turnaround from first-round playoff outcasts to
possible World Series contenders, the Astros pulled off arguably
the biggest trade in franchise history late Friday night for
Seattle Mariners lefthander Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   With an immeasurable intimidation factor _ not to mention an
American League-leading 213 strikeouts in his suitcase _ the
balance of power might have taken a southwest turn. And the
excitement level generated by the Astros' latest bold move could
create the most excitement since the club signed Ryan in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Since breaking into the major leagues in 1989, Johnson has
developed into one of the premier power pitchers of all-time. He
was only 9-10 with a 4.33 ERA in 23 starts for the Mariners this
season _ largely because of the cloud of controversy of a pending
trade _ but is 130-74 in nine-plus seasons. Johnson, 34, has lost
two consecutive starts since pitching consecutive shutouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of unhappy hitters in the NL right now,''
Astros left fielder Moises Alou said.
</P>
<P>
   Fear.
</P>
<P>
   That's what general manager Gerry Hunsicker had in mind when he
joined the Johnson sweepstakes this week and pulled off a stunning
coup by stealing away the 1995 AL Cy Young winner for a trio of
minor-league prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker consummated the deal in the final minutes of Friday's
11 p.m. non-waiver trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you look toward winning a championship nd beyond,
especially in a short series, the ability of a team to have a
dominant starter that has the potential to shut down the other team
is a terrific advantage,'' Hunsicker said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Johnson's subpar numbers, Hunsicker thinks the 6-10
lefthander will have the advantage of relative obscurity in his
return to the NL since beginning his career with the Montreal
Expos.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy is one of the great talents of the game,'' Hunsicker
said. ``Plus the fact you don't have the designated hitter in this
league. Plus the fact I don't care if this is the NL, AL or Mars,
any lefthanded hitter that gets into that batter's box, I guarantee
isn't going to dig in against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Said second baseman Craig Biggio: ``There's a lot of guys in
this league who haven't seen him _ and a lot of guys who are going
to wish they hadn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitching was the cornerstone of the Astros' success in the 1980s
and last year with staff ace Darryl Kile, who left via free agency.
</P>
<P>
   But as dominant as Ryan, Richard, Scott and Kile were, none took
the club to the World Series. With improved pitching and an
explosive offense this season, Hunsicker believes the possibilities
are limitless for the NL Central-leading Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to pitching,'' Hunsicker said. ``We've said so
many times that pitching is really the cornerstone of every
championship-caliber club.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
