<SLUG> BC-TEN-CROUSE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL RAFTER'S GAME MATCH HIS HUNK QUOTIENT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Patrick Rafter would hate for people to think he's
a sex machine just because ladies send him suggestive faxes on the
road and occasionally invite themselves up to his hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in the current issue of Tennis Match magazine,
the fifth-ranked tennis player in the world spoke plainly about how
girls come up to his room for a drink and get a little too friendly
and he has to remind them he has a girlfriend, as if this, along
with room key cards that don't work, is endemic to life on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   What, happy hour isn't included in room service where you stay?
</P>
<P>
   Rafter is not raffish, but he's no recluse, either. The
25-year-old Australian, who will team with Sandon Stolle to try to
win the doubles title today at the Mercedes-Benz Cup, likes to go
out at night with his mates _ and not to nurse diet sodas and
mineral water.
</P>
<P>
   That much was borne out last year, after the Australians
clinched a win over the Czech Republic in Davis Cup play. After
losing a meaningless singles match the next day, Rafter admitted he
had played with a hangover and promptly apologized to Aussies
everywhere. Hey, at least he showed up, which is more than can be
said of the United States' Davis Cup ducker Pete Sampras, who
apparently gets intoxicated only on Grand Slam championships.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras' single-minded focus on tennis, and more specifically,
the four majors, goes a long way toward explaining his six-year
stranglehold on the No. 1 world ranking, which Marcelo Rios has
only recently managed somewhat to loosen.
</P>
<P>
   And therein lies Rafter's dilemma as he approaches the defense
of his breakthrough U.S. Open title four weeks hence: Does he want
to be No. 1 or have fun? The two seem to be mutually exclusive,
like baseliners and serve-and-volleyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very difficult to be like Pete,'' Rafter riffed
Saturday after he and Stolle dispatched Martin Damm and Jim Grabb
7-6 (7-5), 6-4 in the semifinals at the Los Angeles Tennis Center.
</P>
<P>
   In a hurry to get to the UCLA Medical Center to visit fellow
Aussie Rod Laver, who is recovering from a stroke, Rafter
nonetheless hung around long enough to add, ``There's a fine line
(between enjoying life and enjoying life at the expense of your
tennis ranking).''
</P>
<P>
   His conclusion?
</P>
<P>
   A top ranking is not an impossibility, but ``at the end of the
day, it's a short life,'' said Rafter, who rose to No.2 last year
on the strength of his U.S. Open victory and his appearances in six
other finals.
</P>
<P>
   There may be four players ranked higher right now than Rafter,
but nobody sets more hearts aflutter. ``RAFTER YOU ARE A SEX GOD''
proclaimed a banner at the Australian Open two years ago when he
was just another pretty face hoping to crack the top 50.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sexiest Athlete'' pronounced People Magazine in 1997,
lumping Rafter with the likes of Batman's George Clooney.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter has said adjectives like hunk, heartthrob and dreamboat,
when applied to him, are mildly discomfiting. And yet he acquiesced
to a beefcake pose on the beach for the People photo layout when a
more bashful bachelor might have insisted on a nice portrait in a
tuxedo or a tennis action shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe around you guys he acts like he doesn't like (the focus
on his looks),'' sniggled third-year pro Justin Gimelstob, who
disposed of Rafter in straight sets in the quarterfinals of the
singles Friday, ``but when he's out at night he doesn't look
uncomfortable with it.''
</P>
<P>
   You want to talk uncomfortable, heartthrob emeritus Andre Agassi
recalled the pair of tennis shorts from his signature line a few
years back that were, in his words, ``very gripping.''
</P>
<P>
   Wedgies notwithstanding, Agassi wore the terribly tight shorts
for a few months because, as he was paid handsomely to declare in
those days, image is everything.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone has taken that torch and run with it over the past few
years it is the latest generation of female tennis pros. Led by
Anna Kournikova, that paradigm of minxhood, the women's tour is
creating the most buzz this side of Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of men's tennis, meantime, has receded as
inexorably as Agassi's hairline. It could use someone who wears his
long hair like Pebbles Flintstone, covers his nose with snow-white
zinc oxide and generally inspires fans to spill their beers and
fall all over themselves.
</P>
<P>
   During the second set, Rafter made a bad service toss and said
to Stolle, ``Sorry, mate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you hear that?'' one fan gushed. ``He's so cute.''
</P>
<P>
   But enough from Rafter's male fans.
</P>
<P>
   After the match, girls hung over the railing and moaned, ``Oh,
Pat.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter glanced up and gave them a sheepish wave before
disappearing into the tunnel wearing a puckish grin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-98 0103EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
