<SLUG> BC-TEN-MERCEDES-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS APPEARANCE REMAINS A GOAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DANA HADDAD  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Mercedes-Benz Cup tournament director Bob Kramer
said he was distraught when Pete Sampras announced he was pulling
out three days before the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, of course, is the world's No.1 ranked player and would
have been the biggest draw here since 1993, when he last played
here. His injury _ tenderness caused by the removal of a wart on
his right foot _ has been much joked about this week.
</P>
<P>
   While Kramer has no complaints about the attendance, he is
almost single-minded about acquiring Sampras and other Grand Slam
winners for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident we'll get him,'' Kramer said. ``Now we just got
to get him on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Kramer said the 1998 event will go down in history for the
number of name players who withdrew. Boris Becker, Greg Rusedski
and Thomas Enqvist also bailed out, but with much less impact than
Rancho Palos Verdes product Sampras, who notified Kramer through
his management company.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sort of knocked the wind out of my stomach,'' said Kramer,
son of Hall of Famer Jack Kramer. ``It was a brand new sinking
feeling. We worked very hard to get him.''
</P>
<P>
   Also tops on Kramer's recruiting list for next year are Michael
Chang, Andre Agassi and Marcelo Rios.
</P>
<P>
   Strong ticket sales: Mercedes-Benz Cup officials were glad the
wart on Sampras' foot didn't become a blemish on their tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Through Friday, the tournament had drawn 58,789, meaning the
final total will probably be around 80,000.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer said the event will exceed $1 million in ticket revenue
and could approach its goal of $1.1 million in receipts. A record
was set with $700,000 in season-ticket sales. No doubt they were
lured by the chance to see Sampras play here for the first time in
five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pete really helped make the event, no question,'' Kramer said.
``But I'd rather have Pete playing and winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Say what? Agassi seemed captivated about some comments by
Gimelstob that showed up in print Saturday before their semifinal
showdown.
</P>
<P>
   Gimelstob boasting that the Los Angeles Tennis Center is ``his
house'' during his quarterfinal upset of Patrick Rafter, his
post-match comment saying Agassi ``wants a piece of me'' and Agassi
being portrayed as a sometime critic seemed to rub at the Grand
Slam champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more personal than professional,'' Agassi said
Saturday, while noting that he had mentored Gimelstob and had him
as a house guest. ``Maybe he plans to be No.1 in the world. I wish
him the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Gimelstob, ``It's still my house. I'll let him lease it for
this year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-98 0105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
