A4139 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLNOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      08-02 2453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONCERN OVER PATRIOTS BUILDING 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ The NFL is like an affluent neighborhood.
It has great little features like a superb TV deal, modern stadiums
that generate many millions for their owners, a worldwide audience
that generates big TV numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland will once again have a franchise in 1999. The
Tennessee Oilers will play in a beautiful new stadium in Nashville,
and also be given a new nickname. Houston and Los Angeles, which
lost franchises, will be the next two cities awarded expansion
teams, and both are building new stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   There is a spirit of cooperation between the players' union and
the ownership. There's revenue sharing, and a healthy salary cap
that pleases the players.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Paul Tagliabue seems to be a competent overseer of
the sports paradise, able to broker major deals and get everyone on
the same page.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one eyesore: the New England Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have such great cooperation between the teams and the
cities,'' said Tagliabue in a phone interview from Canton, Ohio,
where he was attending the Hall of Fame game. ``We have terrific
public/-private partnerships that seem to benefit all concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Concerned'' is the key word.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very concerned about the Patriots,'' he said. ``There are
a lot of people in the league concerned. It was a franchise that
went through such instability over the years and for so long there
was so much doubt whether the team would stay in New England. And
then Bob Kraft comes along and has provided such great leadership
and solidified that franchise. And now they can't get a stadium
built. His proposal is unprecedented in our league, willing to fund
the construction himself and asking only for infrastructure. My
concern is that there is such an atmosphere of frustration up there
that it's creating a failed hope of getting something done.''
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue appears to be at a loss about what he can do. He
always hopes that owners will do everything in their power to fund
stadiums with as much private money as possible. So when an owner
like Kraft does that and gets a negative response from the State
House, what more can be done?
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue expects to pursue a meeting with House Speaker Thomas
M. Finneran soon to revisit the issue of why he won't agree to the
Senate version of the stadium plan, which would give Kraft $72
million in infrastructure, including a buy-back plan for Kraft's
land for $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met with Mr. Finneran about five years ago and nothing came
of it,'' said Tagliabue. ``When the Senate passed the stadium bill,
I thought that was a big breakthrough for that area, but then the
House wouldn't go along with it. I've asked different people up
there why such an impasse continues to occur. In other areas of the
country, we've been able to bring the private and public sector
together in a spirit of cooperation. But it seems there continue to
be roadblocks at every turn in New England.''
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue said that 90 days ago he was hoping that the
approximately $20 million that is at odds between the House and
Senate versions could be a gap the NFL could solve. Under the new
basic agreement, visiting teams give up their share of the gate and
the money is placed into a stadium construction fund. In order for
Tagliabue to tap into those funds, he must have the permission of
the Players' Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met with (union head) Gene Upshaw to see if we could use the
fund to help the Patriots, but the union would not agree to an
amendment,'' Tagliabue said. ``Basically the funds can be used only
to supplement the construction costs of the stadium. None of the
money can be used for infrastructure, and the union thought that
the Patriots had made a huge commitment to finance the stadium
privately, and that the $72 million in infrastructure was a
reasonable amount that the state would have to pay for
infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue cites Jack Kent Cooke Stadium as a prime example of
what Kraft is trying to do. While Cooke is lauded for building his
own stadium, he received $75 million in infrastructure from the
state of Maryland. New York state's legislature recently approved
$80 milllion for improvements at Rich Stadium in Buffalo. And
Seattle approved a new stadium for owner Paul Allen with a public
investment of more than half the cost of the $400 million stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within a five-year period from 1994-99, we'll have had
commitments to build 18-20 new stadiums or renovations around the
NFL,'' said Tagliabue. ``That means two-thirds of the league have
already solved whatever problems they had.''
</P>
<P>
   What advice does he have for Kraft?
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep telling Bob to be patient,'' said Tagliabue. ``I
thought he accomplished a lot when he got the Senate to back his
plan. I've been counseling clubs to walk the extra mile in their
communities, but it seems that Bob keeps walking into every maze
imaginable. Obviously there will come a point when he walks away
from it, and that would be a shame. The franchise finally has
tremendous ownership. He's a considerate owner who demands that the
fans come first. In everything he does, that comes across. It comes
across in the way he runs the New England Patriots, and the way in
which he's handled many of the big jobs I've asked him to undertake
for the league. He played a great role in the television deal; he
was a huge help in the labor agreement. In everything he did, he
put the best interest of the fans first.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft's op-ed piece in Friday's Globe nicely laid out his
proposal. The buyback of the land would in turn generate a ``$1.5
million revenue stream in perpetuity, in addition to the payment of
regular taxes, to help support the infrastructure work that would
be done on Route 1 in Foxboro. Our willingness to pay in perpetuity
for the infrastructure is, to our knowledge, unprecedented in state
history.''
</P>
<P>
   Finneran, grilled by WEEI talk show host Ted Sarandis and
co-host Gene Lavanchy last week, opposed the land deal and also
said that whatever the legislature approved for the Patriots it
would have to approve for the Red Sox. Well, that would go without
saying. Both teams, vital to the community, should receive the same
support.
</P>
<P>
   However, if this situation is now beyond repair, Tagliabue feels
Kraft has an outstanding alternative in Hartford, which is willing
to make the Patriots part of a $1 billion downtown redevelopment
project in a 70,000-seat open air stadium that would house the
Patriots and the University of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be a high-quality situation,'' said Tagliabue. ``It's
a great example of the public and private sector coming together
for a common goal. It would be a serious alternative for Bob.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Tagliabue is concerned that the team would move out of
an area that has such a strong fan base. He believes that the
Patriots have now tied, if not surpassed, the Red Sox in local
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are such rabid fans,'' said Tagliabue. ``They have an
owner who has put a winning organization together. You hate to have
this happen to stable, productive ownerships. The people of Seattle
bought into Paul Allen's ownership even before he's been able to
show he can put a winning team on the field. Bob has already shown
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft won't tip his hand. There seems no chance he would accept
Finneran's ``compromise'' of $57 million in infrastructure with no
land buyback.
</P>
<P>
   Said one person close to the situation, ``The next time he
speaks on the topic of what he'll do next, it will be to announce
he's moved the team.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bill Parcells  &LR; was walking by some fans at Hofstra and noticed
one trying to take his picture. ``I hope you have a wide-angle
lens,'' The Tuna quipped. Parcells has been much more accommodating
to the media in this camp, including allowing interviews with
assistant coaches, which he rarely allowed in New England.
Parcells, 57 next month, sounded like a man who has retirement in
sight. ``One of these days, I don't know when _ it's not this year,
I'll tell you that _ God's going to say, `Hey, Parcells, you just
don't want to do this anymore.' I don't believe there will be any
shame in that. If it was two months from now, if it was the end of
the season, there will be no shame in that. When it happens to me,
I'm going to take a look at myself and see what I want to do.''
Parcells said he also doesn't envision himself being just a general
manager. ``I'm a nuts-and-bolts guy. That's what I like. I like
this. I never thought very much about the other thing. I'd almost
rather consult _ just call me if you need me.'' ...  &UR; Curtis Martin
 &LR; isn't due back to practice until  &UR; tomorrow &LR; . He's missed an entire
week with a left hamstring strain. The Jets don't appear overly
concerned, but they have been very cautious with their $6 million
man ... While most of New York is feeling good about Martin, WBCN
statistician  &UR; Dick Tarpey  &LR; makes a great case for why Martin is
just a good back, not a great one. Last year, 88 of Martin's 274
carries went for no more than 1 yard. Fifty-five percent of his
carries went for 3 yards or fewer. That figure was actually better
last year than it was in '96, under Parcells, when 60 percent of
his runs were for 3 yards or fewer. Martin certainly has the
ability to break the long one. Against the Bears last year, for
example, Martin gained 79 yards on 15 carries _ one for 70 yards,
the 14 others for a total of 9 ... The Jets did receive a
devastating jolt when middle linebacker  &UR; Marvin Jones &LR; , &UR;  &LR; their
leading tackler last year, tore both the anterior cruciate and
medial collateral ligaments in his left leg and will miss the
entire season. Jones was injured when a teammate fell on him during
running drills. He will have reconstructive surgery next week ...
Nebraska quarterback  &UR; Scott Frost &LR; , &UR;  &LR; now a backup strong safety for
the Jets, has looked like a man who is enjoying hitting people
after spending so many years getting hit. Frost is also being used
as a kick returner and has made a strong impression ... Meanwhile,
although  &UR; Vinny Testaverde  &LR; outplayed  &UR; Glenn Foley  &LR; in a recent
scrimmage, Parcells is still leaning toward Foley as his starter.
Parcells said he was giving Foley ``the benefit of the doubt.'' ...
The Cleveland Browns will get the same advantages as the
Jacksonville Jaguars and the Carolina Panthers in terms of
available players when they start play in 1999. An ``access draft''
will be held next February in which all teams must submit a list of
five players eligible for the draft. Teams have until Jan. 19 to
make their decisions, except the two Super Bowl participants, which
must submit their lists by Feb. 2. Each team can recall one player
from the list after one has been chosen. Of the five players, only
one player can have 10 or more years experience, and only one
player could have been on injured reserve the previous year. The
Browns will have to select 30 to 42 players. The Browns will also
have the first pick in each of the seven rounds. They'll also
receive seven additional picks in Rounds 2-7 after teams with a
winning percentage of less than .500 select. They also have the
final selection in the seventh round, which ensures they will pick
Mr. Irrelevant. The Browns will make their normal picks in 2000 but
also receive seven additional picks unless they make the playoffs.
The Browns can also begin signing free agents as of Dec. 17, 12
days before other NFL teams. They can sign a maximum of 10 free
agents. ``The plan is designed to give the Browns the opportunity
to become competitive at an early date,'' said Tagliabue ...
Preliminary bids on the Browns by prospective owners are due by
Aug. 6. The bids are expected to start at around $350 million and
go as high as $700 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Patriots defensive end  &UR; Devin Wyman  &LR; is on the verge of a rap
career. He's already produced a CD on his own label. Wyman says
he's trying to get  &UR; Terry Glenn  &LR; and  &UR; Chris Canty &LR; , &UR;  &LR; both of whom
are supposedly good rappers, to join him in future ventures. ``My
music is my outlet,'' said Wyman. ``I love it. There's a lot of
things I have to say, and I can say them with my music.'' ... Now
that  &UR; Dave Meggett  &LR; will be out for the season, the Patriots may
have to pay him an injury settlement. The maximum amount is
$200,000 ... 49ers quarterback  &UR; Steve Young  &LR; expects coach  &UR; Steve
Mariucci  &LR; to allow him to throw more this season now that he's
completely recovered from his concussions. ``We'll throw the ball
more on first down,'' said Young. ``We'll line up with three and
four wideouts more on first down. If  &UR; Jerry  &LR; ( &UR; Rice &LR; ) stays
healthy, we'll probably throw 40 times instead of the 30 times we
averaged last year.'' ... With  &UR; Carmen Policy  &LR; out of the 49ers
picture, it appears San Francisco and Oakland may restart their
exhibition game rivalry again. Policy never liked Raiders owner  &UR; Al
Davis  &LR; and therefore didn't want to schedule any games against him.
The teams met from 1967-1993, but then the rivalry ended. Both
teams have the third week of the exhibition season open next year
...  &UR; Charles Woodson  &LR; is already taking the pressure off himself in
the Raider camp. Arguably the best athlete in the draft, Woodson
said, ``People are looking for me to play right off the bat. And
they're looking at me to make things happen. My only obligation
here is to the team. I know from experience that you can't please
everybody.'' ... It's no secret why so many NFL rookies get injured
in their first training camp. It's hard work, and the players they
go up against are bigger and faster. The conditioning programs of
pro teams are far superior to those of most college programs. Canty
found that out last year when admittedly he wasn't in the best
shape. An offseason with  &UR; Johnny Parker &LR;  changed that. Now  &UR; Robert
Edwards  &LR; and  &UR; Tebucky Jones &LR; , &UR;  &LR; both of whom have fought off
injuries in the early part of camp, are coming to that same
realization. ``There's so much of a difference in my body from last
year to this year,'' said Canty. ``If you think you're in shape
coming out of college, you find out pretty quickly that you're
not.'' That's why, a year later, offensive linemen such as  &UR; Scott
Rehberg &LR; , &UR; Ed Ellis &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Damon Denson  &LR; can now begin competing
for playing time. One player who found this out was Tampa Bay's
 &UR; Warrick Dunn &LR; . ``It got to the point at one time last year where I
just hit a wall,'' he said. ``My legs were tired, and I couldn't do
anything. To be a pro athlete, you have to be in incredible shape.
You find that everything moves so much faster than in college.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
