<SLUG> BC-BKO-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD WISHES THEY WERE HERE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS _ In case the boycotting United States stars are
interested, yeah, they're missed. Big time.
</P>
<P>
   The empty seats in the Olympic Stadium and the Peace and
Friendship Stadium in games not involving the host country are
obvious evidence that something is missing here, but it's more than
that. You can feel it. People had gotten used to having the mighty
NBA players around.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time since the 1990 World Championships in
Buenos Aires that a major open men's tournament has been held
without the presence of the very best players America _ and,
therefore, the world _ has to offer. The breakthrough came with the
institution of the one and only official Dream Team in 1992, and
continued with NBA juggernauts that swept to victory in the 1994
Worlds in Toronto and the 1996 Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Americans simply have no idea how important the Dream Team was
in the eyes of the world. All the folks back home saw was an
average victory margin of 43 points a game. What everyone else saw
was a level of basketball that fired their imagination. They saw a
bar raised beyond their current grasp. They saw their future.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the world had gotten used to beating up on the
youthful Americans who we kept sending out to fulfill a man's
mission. Now they were confronted with reality. They had become
aware that winning major tournaments in which the US was being
represented with less than its best were hollow achievements. They
knew they would have to improve.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the world had also gotten used to playing for two
medals. Time and again you would hear, ``For us, the silver is the
gold.'' And they really didn't mind. They had come to accept
reality, and reality was that the NBA was where the greatest
players resided.
</P>
<P>
   They really don't understand why the NBA players are not here.
They don't know anything about lockouts or Larry Bird exceptions.
They don't quite understand why an NBA labor problem should be a
USA Basketball problem, and, you know what? They have a point.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that the NBA players made a commitment, and they
should be here. The commitment was to USA Basketball, not the NBA.
There was also an unspoken commitment to a basketball world that
has come to expect, and enjoy, their presence at these events. This
is a big deal. They signed on to represent their country, not the
NBA Players Association.
</P>
<P>
   OK, technically speaking, they were taken off the team before
they had a chance to boycott. But the folks at USA Basketball had
no choice. The NBA players were rattling their sabres and USA
Basketball had to cover itself. They had to assemble an alternate
team, and they couldn't wait to see what the NBA players were going
to do.
</P>
<P>
   There actually is one NBA player here _ Australian center Chris
Anstey, who plays for Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to represent my country, not the NBA,'' he explains.
``I wish the American NBA players were here, but I respect their
decision. It's an individual decision on their part, although I
believe it was best for them to all do the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   You might be wondering if anyone in the Players Association
pressured Anstey to make it a complete non-NBA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not at all,'' he says. ``No one rang me. No one asked me
not to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Anstey can see both the benefits and the drawbacks of not having
the NBA stars here. His own country agonizes about its place in the
international basketball world. Australia has produced some good
players (Luc Longley, Andrew Gaze, etc.), and it has had a measure
of success. But the powers that be somehow feel Australia should be
doing better. Winning a medal _ any medal _ in a tournament such as
this is almost an obsession.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why it's good for us that the NBA players aren't
here,'' Anstey says. ``It opens things up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But we are all missing a lot by not having them here,'' he
adds. ``The fact is you always want to measure yourself against the
best _ and they are the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Without the US's great NBA stars, the tournament is heading for
financial catastrophe. The US team has played its three games
before ``crowds'' of approximately 1,000, not that anyone is
bothering to issue attendance figures for anything other than the
Greek games, which are being played before raucous gatherings of
between 15,000 and 20,000 people. There are pockets of Lithuanians,
Spaniards, Brazilians, and eminently lovable Nigerians who have
enlightened the proceedings. The Nigerians are particularly
entertaining. They bring a band, and it plays for the entire 40
minutes. They dress in colorful robes. They have themselves a great
old time. Unfortunately, their team has gone 0-3 and has been
eliminated from medal competition.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that the NBA stars would have had a spillover
effect on attendance. They would have dignified the tournament.
People know that if someone other than the substitute NBA team
wins, it will be a tainted victory. Of course, all bets are off if
that winner turns out to be Greece. That would be hailed by the
Greek press as the greatest Greek triumph of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the NBA stars) should be here,'' insists Donn Nelson,
the Mavericks assistant who is an assistant with Lithuania. ``I'm
working with Lithuania because Sarunas (Marciulionis) asked me to.
If USA Basketball had asked me to come, I'd work for the USA. In my
opinion, there's nothing more important than your country, and if
your country asks you to step up to the plate, you should be
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA players are not accountable for the stagnation in the
international game their absence has brought, nor are they
accountable for the financial plight of the local organizers. But
they are accountable for holding their country hostage because of
league politics that have nothing to do with what's going on here.
</P>
<P>
   But why should we be surprised? Responsibility is not exactly
the hallmark of the modern American athlete, is it?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-98 0109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
