<HEADLINE>
GERMAN STEROID TRIAL PUTS IOC IN DEEP 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Now that former East German swimmers Andrea Pollack and
Christiane Knacke-Sommer say they'll return their Olympic medals
because they took steroids, the US Olympic Committee wants the
International Olympic Committee to give them to the Americans they
beat in 1976 and 1988. And if the Lords won't do it, the USOC will
give the swimmers a special award. As more evidence of massive
state-administered doping is introduced at the lengthy trial of
former DDR doctors, coaches, and officials in Germany, critics are
urging that all East German swimming medals be revoked and their
records stricken from the books.
</P>
<P>
   Though the IOC is said to be sympathetic, it's a thorny issue.
Despite the evidence, none of the East Germans tested positive at
the Games. Recalculating the results and redistributing the medals
would be an administrative nightmare, since the DDR dominance
covered four Olympiads. And the doping scandal isn't limited to
swimming. The East German track and field teams were heavily
drugged, too. Frank Shorter, who lost the 1976 Olympic marathon to
Waldemar Cierpinski, says he has proof that Cierpinski had taken
steroids.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the USOC was aghast at recent quotes from IOC
president Juan Antonio Samaranch, who said that he had no problem
with athletes using performance-enhancing drugs that aren't harmful
to their health (``For me, that's not doping'') and that the banned
list should be ``reduced drastically.'' Samaranch said last week
that he had been misinterpreted, and the Lords have called a
special meeting this month to discuss doping.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the amateur US baseball team failing to make the
quarterfinals of the world championships after losing to the
Koreans, Dutch, and Nicaraguans, look for a renewed push to use
minor leaguers next time. After winning the silver in 1988, the
Americans haven't made the medal round since. With the rest of the
planet improving rapidly, Uncle Sam clearly can't keep sending
college freshmen and sophomores ... As promised, the International
Skating Union made several historic changes at this year's
congress. Besides going to video replay to help judges determine
marks, the ISU also changed the scoring system to prevent skaters
from switching places when the ordinals are scrambled by later
competitors and decided to count the qualifying round in the final
result, making it 20 percent of the total. Which means that the
long program, which now counts for two-thirds, will be reduced to
one half. The ISU also struck a blow against boredom in
speedskating, allowing four racers at a time in the long-track
distance events instead of pairs ... The US women's softball team
may have won their fourth straight world title last week in Japan,
but they got another warning shot from the Australians, who beat
them for the fourth time in four tournaments before the Yanks
prevailed, 1-0, in the final ... Looks like the day of the
seven-medal Olympic swimmer, like  &UR; Mark Spitz  &LR; and  &UR; Matt
Biondi &LR; , &UR;  &LR; could be over. The international federation has decided
to have both heats and semifinals for all events up to 200 meters,
which means another four races in a seven-day span for sprinters
competing in the 50-100-200 freestyles and the 100 butterfly. Good
for TV (and for spectators, who won't have to watch consolation
finals any more); grueling for the swimmers ... Next week's US
diving championships at Georgia Tech will mark the first time
Atlanta has hosted a nationals in a major Olympic sport since the
Summer Games two years ago. So much for the oft-stated theory that
host cities have a big edge in landing events after the Games ...
Now that France has hosted (and won) soccer's World Cup, Olympus
could be the next challenge. The French, who haven't staged the
Summer Games since Paris in 1924, are considering tossing in their
chapeau for 2008, along with Toronto, Osaka, Istanbul, Seville, and
Buenos Aires. Paris lost out to Barcelona in 1992, when Albertville
got the Winter Games. Opting out of the 2008 chase is London, which
figures the IOC won't choose another European city after going to
Athens in 2004 ... The battered yen may be causing migraines in
Japan but it proved a boon for the Nagano organizers, who collected
their TV and sponsorship revenues in dollars, paid their expenses
in yen, and ended up with a $32 million surplus. Their bottom-line
operating costs: $814 million ... Could  &UR; Ilia Kulik  &LR; be the next
 &UR; Sonja Henie &LR; ? Word is the Olympic men's skating champ is eyeing
the silver screen. Scripts and acting lessons are said to be
forthcoming, plus a move from his Marlborough training center to
either Broadway or Hollywood. Which means that the 21-year-old
Russian almost certainly wouldn't defend his crown in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dream draw for the US men's ice hockey team for November's
special global relegation tournament in Austria. The Americans are
grouped with the Austrians, Estonians, and Kazakhs, with the top
two qualifying for the A pool in next year's world championships.
France, Germany, Slovenia, and Ukraine are in the other group. The
Yanks, who didn't survive the prelims in this year's worlds,
haven't had to play in the relegation tournament since 1983 ...
Huge post-Olympic turnover for the US men's singles lugers.  &UR; Duncan
Kennedy  &LR; retired before the Games and  &UR; Wendel Suckow &LR; , &UR; Larry
Dolan &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Robert Pipkins  &LR; have all decided to move on. That
leaves 20-year-old  &UR; Adam Heidt  &LR; as the only man with Olympic
experience ... As expected, Olympic veterans  &UR; Tommy Moe &LR; , &UR; AJ
Kitt &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Matt Grosjean  &LR; are all hanging up the skis after a
decade on the World Cup circuit. Among them, they competed in 10
Winter Games, with Moe winning gold and silver in 1994 ... Newest
member of the US Ski Hall of Fame is Lincoln's  &UR; Diana Golden
Brosnihan &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who earned a demonstration gold medal in the disabled
giant slalom at the Calgary Olympics and won 10 world titles before
retiring in 1990. Golden, who lost her right leg to cancer as a
child, has since had a double mastectomy and has been undergoing
chemotherapy treatments. Since she couldn't attend last fall's
ceremony, Golden Brosnihan was inducted at a special luncheon in
Providence last month ... No more crash-and-burn for short-track
speedskater  &UR; Nikki Ziegelmeyer &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who's switching to long-track
after slamming into the boards in Lake Placid last winter and
nearly ending up paralyzed. ``I don't want to press my luck,'' says
the 22-year-old Ziegelmeyer, who won Olympic medals in both 1992
and 1994. ``I think the worst injury you can have in long-track is
a pulled groin.'' ... After finishing out of the women's medals at
both the Olympics and World Cup, the US Field Hockey Association
has created an elite summer league for 150 players, Olympians to
high school stars. The idea, borrowed from the world-champion
Australians, is to provide year-round competition and build a
deeper athlete pool ... Joining the growing line of Winter Games
wannabe sports like skeleton sledding and sled dog racing is ski
archery _ biathlon with arrows instead of rifles. The International
Biathlon Union and International Archery Federation are talking
about hooking up to get the sport added to the Olympic program.
They have history on their side: Ski archery dates back to 3,000
B.C. ... Why won't the Salt Lake organizers unveil their mascot
until next year? Because they don't want to repeat the Atlanta
fiasco of Whatizit?, the bizarre insect/-alien that became a global
laughingstock. ``I hope we come up with a better name,'' says
committee president  &UR; Frank Joklik &LR; . ``And we hope it will be very
plain what (the mascot) is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
