<HEADLINE>
LOWE, HRUDEY PUT PAST BEHIND THEM 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ The curtain closed last week on the careers of two
terrific players: Edmonton defenseman Kevin Lowe and San Jose
goalie Kelly Hrudey. Lowe will move behind the Oilers bench as an
assistant coach to Ron Low, while Hrudey, who worked for ``Hockey
Night in Canada'' during the playoffs, says he has reached a
three-year agreement with the Canadian Broadcasting Corp. to
provide commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's retirement at 39 likely will leave Bruins captain Ray
Bourque as the only active member of the 21-member draft class of
1979 that earned full-time jobs in the NHL. The only other possible
survivor is Mike Gartner, but he is a free agent and has no takers
so far.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe made his retirement decision on instinct. ``I just listened
to myself and knew that, although last year wasn't great, it wasn't
bad, and perhaps that's a good way to call it quits,'' he said. ``I
played my whole career on instinct and heart, and that's what I
followed. I've never quit anything in my life, and I'm quitting. It
involved a lot of soul searching. I wanted to play 20 years like
Wayne Gretzky, (Mark) Messier, Ray Bourque, and (possibly) Mike
Gartner. But this is where I wanted to begin my coaching career.
This is where my heart is and where I choose to be with my family.
But it wasn't an easy decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe was the first draft choice ever for the Oilers, taken No.
21 in the first round in '79. He went on to play on five Stanley
Cup champions with Edmonton and one with the Rangers. After being
limited to just seven games last season because of an ear
infection, he ends his career having played 1,468 games, regular
season and playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   As for Hrudey, he is hanging up the goalie pads after 15 years,
the last two with the Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no feelings of sadness,'' said Hrudey, whose best
seasons were with the Los Angeles Kings. ``I just cannot believe
the opportunity I've had.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Center  &UR; Joe Thornton &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who has been working out hard this
summer in anticipation of taking on a much more important role on
the Bruins this season, has added an additional challenge to his
offseason. The 19-year-old, who has bulked up from last season's
198 pounds to 225, has taken up golf. Thornton lives a 9-iron away
from The Country Club in Brookline and has become smitten with the
sport that is played by nearly all NHL players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' said Thornton, his face lighting up like a
Christmas tree. ``It's a good pastime. It kind of kills the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Before this summer, Thornton hadn't played much. Now he is
lugging the clubs every chance he gets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went over to Brookline the other day and they showed me what
to do,'' he said of The Country Club, which will host the Ryder Cup
in 13 months. ``I never played there. I just hit off the tee blocks
and stuff. They haven't allowed me on the course. I don't think
they would or they'd be fixing a lot of divots.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton said he got hooked when he played in the team outing at
the end of the season at the Ridge Club in Sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was going so I thought, `Why not?' It's fun. I like
driving around the cart and hitting the balls. I'm doing all right
on the putting. I try not to three-putt. I played in our tournament
with  &UR; Steve Heinze &LR; , &UR; Dmitri Khristich &LR; , &UR; Sergei  &LR; ( &UR; Samsonov &LR; ), &UR; and
P.J.  &LR; ( &UR; Axelsson &LR; ). We almost won the tournament. But not because
of me. We had some good golfers.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton, who plays lefthanded, said he hasn't quite mastered
the art of the driver just yet. ``I've got a slice that's
unbelievable,'' he said. ``I aim for the rightest part of the
fairway and it goes to the leftest part of the fairway. My game is
not too good. I find all my balls in the woods. That's no fun. But
I love it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yankees manager  &UR; Joe Torre &LR; , &UR;  &LR; whose family has been tragically
affected by heart disease, offered some words of advice to Detroit
coach  &UR; Scotty Bowman &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who is mulling whether to return to the Red
Wings' bench next season. Bowman has been diagnosed with high blood
pressure and diabetes and recently underwent an angioplasty to help
clear a blocked artery. He is also scheduled to undergo a knee
replacement that will likely force him to miss the first month of
the season even if he decides to come back. Torre lost a brother to
a heart attack and his father to a fatal stroke, and his older
brother,  &UR; Frank &LR; , &UR;  &LR; had to undergo a heart transplant. ``Your mind
should rule your body,'' said the classy Torre. ``But you can't let
your mind get away from you. You have to do it in a positive way.
To sit around and wait for something to happen is crazy.'' Torre
said that when Frank first became ill, he too went to the doctor to
get checked out. His cholesterol was too high, so he altered his
diet and has added physical fitness to his regimen, something
Bowman hopes to do once he is able to rehab from knee surgery ...
Former Bruin  &UR; Joe Juneau &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who was one of the better players in
the Capitals' run to the Stanley Cup finals, has signed a one-year
contract with the club that will pay him $2.2 million. The
30-year-old opted for the one-season pact because he is scheduled
to become an unrestricted free agent next summer. Look for Juneau
to have a terrific season. He should lobby hard to play with center
 &UR; Adam Oates &LR; , who was a good part of the reason Juneau scored 102
points in his rookie year in Boston in 1992-93 and was a good part
of the reason Juneau had seven goals and 17 points in 21 playoff
games last season ... Nice ending to the playing career of
40-year-old  &UR; Viacheslav Fetisov &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who retired last week rather
than accept a reduced playing role with Detroit. The defenseman
started the influx of players from the former Soviet Union to the
NHL and has now returned to the team he broke in with in 1989 _ the
New Jersey Devils _ as an assistant coach under  &UR; Robbie Ftorek &LR; .
``His career speaks for itself,'' Devils general manager  &UR; Lou
Lamoriello  &LR; told reporters. ``We're just delighted to have him back
here in New Jersey. But more important, what we feel that he can
bring to our organization and to our defense.'' Fetisov said he's
very happy to be back with the Devils. ``The New Jersey Devils
showed me respect,'' Fetisov said. ``I've been in contact with Lou
for the last month. He called me and asked if there was anything
they could do to make me feel comfortable. I know I can play
another year or two. I'm the type of player who can't play 30
games; I have to play more.'' ... Count veteran referee  &UR; Kerry
Fraser  &LR; among those who think the two-referee system, which will be
implemented for some games this season, is a good idea. ``I think
there are a great many benefits to be gained,'' said Fraser, who
has been officiating for 23 years, including eight Stanley Cup
finals. ``This can help prolong a referee's career and improve a
younger official, which results in a better game. And maybe the
two-ref system doesn't allow the officiating to become such a
focus, the way it is now. ... Contrary to what people think, I'm
not an egomaniac. I want what's best for hockey, and I think that
through good officiating you can enhance the product. I've worked
with a second ref four times in preseason games over the last few
years. I have no problem with it. It promotes more coverage of the
ice.'' ... With Lowe moving behind the bench,  &UR; Bob McCammon  &LR; is the
odd man out in Edmonton after three years as assistant coach. The
Oilers have offered him a scouting job, but McCammon, disappointed
in the turn of events, may not take it. ``I haven't decided,'' he
said ... Tampa Bay, the worst team in the league last year,
continues to retool. The Lightning recently added veteran center
 &UR; Benoit Hogue &LR; , &UR;  &LR; signing the free agent from Dallas. ``We had to
fight off other teams to get this guy,'' said Tampa GM  &UR; Phil
Esposito &LR; . ``We're back to where we were three years ago in terms
of depth. We feel we've improved dramatically with these moves.
Everything is so upbeat for us right now. I wish we were playing
tomorrow.'' ... Former Bruin  &UR; Shawn McEachern  &LR; is scheduled to have
an arbitration hearing on Friday to settle his contract with the
Ottawa Senators. McEachern took the Penguins to arbitration earlier
in his career, won that hearing, and named his boat the
``Arbitrator'' in celebration of the extra cash ... Nice to see
that the Islanders are making improvements to their rink. Although
they won't have a new stadium to replace the dark Nassau Coliseum
any time soon, they are installing a new scoreboard. The $3 million
board will enable fans to see replays, something they really
couldn't do on the muddy old one ... If you haven't yet seen it
among the inserts of  &UR; today &LR; 's paper, the Globe is featuring a
1998-99 Bruins schedule alongside a poster of coach  &UR; Pat Burns  &LR; and
Samsonov, who were honored as coach of the year and rookie of the
year, respectively, at the NHL Awards in June ... Sixty-nine days
until opening night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
