<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALDERRAMA DEAL NEAR COMPLETION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Carlos Valderrama wants to join the Revolution
and rejoin Thomas Rongen, who coached him in 1996. And the
Revolution, with the worst record in Major League Soccer,
desperately want the creative midfielder.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which would send Joe-Max Moore and David Nakhid to the
Miami Fusion, was on the verge of being completed Saturday. The
only holdup apparently was that the Revolution want to make it a
three-way trade that would also include the return to New England
of defender Francis Okaroh, now with Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know Boston, just the stadium and the hotel,''
Valderrama said while preparing for Sunday's MLS All-Star Game.
``And it's a good stadium, I like it. I also know the coaching
staff and how Thomas works. That makes it easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Could Valderrama be available for the Revolution's game against
San Jose Wednesday?
</P>
<P>
   ``First, I have to settle things with my family,'' Valderrama
said. ``I can't just move there.''
</P>
<P>
   Valderrama, who turns 37 next month, became available after a
conflict with newly hired Miami coach Ivo Wortmann the day before
the Fusion's 2-1 win over the Revolution last Saturday. Valderrama
did not travel to Foxborough and missed the next Miami game, both
victories. He was fined an MLS-record $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Now Valderrama is seeking to rejuvenate his career and to
possibly save Rongen's position. Rongen guided Tampa Bay to the
regular-season title and Valderrama was named most valuable player
in 1996, the league's first year.
</P>
<P>
   Though Valderrama, nicknamed ``El Pibe'' (``The Kid''), has
ended his international career with Colombia, he has found a home
in the MLS. He is probably the league's most accomplished player,
with three World Cup finals appearances and a club career in
Colombia, France, and Spain. Valderrama is among the league's
highest-paid players and is about to complete the third year of a
10-year contract that includes an unspecified position after he
retires as a player.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange would also accommodate a request by Moore to be
sent to the hometown of his wife, Marta. But it would cost the
Revolution one of their best domestic players, plus Nakhid, one of
their top internationals. And, unless Okaroh arrives, it would fail
to solve the Revolution's defensive problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a desperate situation for us,'' Revolution general
manager Brian O'Donovan said. ``We have 10 games left to make the
playoffs. But if we are going to use a major chip, a young and
valuable star such as Joe-Max, to make the Revolution better, we
have to make sure we maximize its value. We have to correct a
myriad of deficiencies.''
</P>
<P>
   But the chance seems slim of Okaroh leaving Chicago. ``(Okaroh)
has become an important player on our team,'' said Fire coach Bob
Bradley, ``and he has done a great job with developing some of our
younger players.''
</P>
<P>
   Valderrama is from Santa Marta, on the Caribbean coast, and has
played mostly in Mediterranean and tropical climates. But he seemed
eager to confront New England's weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to go skiing when I played in France,'' Valderrama
said. ``You have to be able play in all conditions _ hot, cold,
rain.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Rongen: ``Carlos wants to be with someone with the same
mentality, a winner's mentality. He would like to get what he had
the first year in the league, and I would love that, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would also give New England fans the internationally
recognized player they have been waiting for for two years. I think
he can still do the job in this league for another two or three
years. And now he has something to prove.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The US women's national team will meet Canada in a preliminary
game at noon Sunday ... The Revolution's Salvadoran striker, Raul
Diaz Arce, will join Valderrama in the World All-Stars starting
lineup. Revolution captain Mike Burns is a reserve for the domestic
team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
