<HEADER>
A4150 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMER-MOVIES-LADN     08-02 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-MOVIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER BLOCKBUSTERS FAIL TO FIND AUDIENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The popcorn movies aren't cutting the mustard
this summer. But fortunately for Hollywood, plenty of other films
are.
</P>
<P>
   That's the stunning reality studio executives face as their most
crucial season between mid-May to late July drew to a close. Their
pricey slam-bangers, ``Godzilla'' and ``Armageddon,'' crashed far
short of expectations despite carrying ``Titanic''-like production
and marketing costs.
</P>
<P>
   But don't cry for studios and theater chains. Less expensive
fare like ``The Truman Show,'' ``Dr. Dolittle,'' ``Mulan,'' ``The
Mask of Zorro'' and ``Saving Private Ryan'' have more than salvaged
the summer.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, people went to the movies in record numbers this
summer. Revenues from Memorial Day through last weekend rose 9
percent over the record '97 summer to $1.59 billion and ticket
sales were also up 9 percent to 348 million. With most of the
summer gone, there is only one out-and-out flop -- ``The Quest for
Camelot,'' an overpriced project written off long ago.
</P>
<P>
   So if 20-screen megaplexes have become common and there's more
hype than ever, why did ``Godzilla'' and ``Armageddon'' fail to
connect? Analysts believe moviegoers are tired of
testosterone-driven end-of-the-world products, and are looking for
old-fashioned attractions like plot and character development in
movies like ``Titanic'' and ``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Audiences are sending a real message to Hollywood -- they want
to see great stories told,'' said analyst Kevin Skislock of LH
Friend, Weinress, Frankson &AMP; Presson. ``They're getting tired of
the gratuitous violence accompanied by wisecracks by someone like
Bruce Willis. When you see `Saving Private Ryan,' it places the
cartoonishness of movie violence into context.''
</P>
<P>
   The summer's results also mean that under-25 males, who had been
the most prized demographic, have lost their luster.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trend has really shifted away from big action films
targeted at young adult males and toward movies that appeal to at
least two distinct audiences,'' said Robert Bucksbaum, head of the
Reel Source forecasting service. ``The problem with young males is
they get bored easily.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Armageddon'' will be the summer's box office leader at about
$175 million unless it gets beaten by ``Saving Private Ryan,''
which has generated powerful word-of-mouth momentum. But
``Armageddon's'' costs were so massive -- $150 million to produce,
$80 million for worldwide marketing -- that Disney's profits will
be minimal even after contributions from foreign box office ($41
million as of last weekend) and home video.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armageddon'' will turn out to be the lowest summer leader
since 1992, when ``Batman Returns'' led with $163 million.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't supposed to happen like this. Hollywood figured
``Godzilla'' and ``Armageddon'' would each hit $250 million
domestically, based on how audiences behaved during the past two
summers toward the four leading films -- ``Twister,''
``Independence Day,'' ``Jurassic Park: The Lost World'' and ``Men
In Black.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopes for a supercharged summer heated up in early May when
``Deep Impact,'' Paramount's bargain-priced version of
``Armageddon,'' opened with $41 million. That buoyed everyone's
expectations because it matched ``Twister's'' debut in the same
1996 weekend. Suddenly, the prospect of another summer of 1994,
when ``Forrest Gump'' and ``The Lion King'' went past $300 million,
seemed achievable.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, customers decided ``Godzilla'' and ``Armageddon''
didn't deliver as promised. Their combined $300 million in tickets
isn't chump change, but both movies were backed by the two most
expensive promotional campaigns ever seen, meaning that the studios
essentially ``bought'' the first week of grosses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Godzilla'' had a hard time appealing to anyone older than 11
years old and faded like a one-day tan. ``Armageddon'' was hurt by
``Dr. Dolittle'' and the fact that ``Deep Impact'' had already
soaked up much of the interest in seeing the Earth destroyed by
space debris.
</P>
<P>
   All this has Hollywood trackers wondering about the future of
special-effects-laden movies. ``If `Independence Day' was released
today, it would have a hard time getting half the domestic gross it
did two years ago,'' Bucksbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   That would mean ``ID4,'' instead of hitting $306 million, would
wind up in the $150 million range. That's the same territory
occupied by the summer's three most expensive films --
``Armageddon,'' ``Godzilla'' and ``Lethal Weapon 4'' -- and it's a
result that's vaguely disappointing, particularly in a
post-``Titanic'' world. Taking in $150 million on an expensive film
means virtually all of a studio's revenues goes toward covering its
massive costs.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with these films may be audiences feel they're
seeing variations on the same film, according to analyst David
Davis of Houlihan Lokey Howard &AMP; Zukin. `` `Independence Day' would
clearly have a harder time now because there are a lot of films
that have been derived from it,'' Davis said. ``So we could be at
the tail end of a trend of big films about aliens and outer
space.''
</P>
<P>
   The first sign of a shift came a year ago when ``Men In Black''
became a must-see film. Though the special effects were impressive,
``MIB'' was more spoof than action film, delivering big laughs
rather than just spills and chills.
</P>
<P>
   Warnings No. 2 and No. 3 came last November when two high-priced
outer-space films, ``Starship Troopers'' and ``Alien
Resurrection,'' badly underperformed. And finally, the most obvious
indication of a shift in tastes came this winter when ``Titanic''
became everyone's favorite film as young women began bragging about
seeing it half a dozen times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about who goes to megaplexes -- it's mostly kids,
teen-agers, women and people on dates,'' Bucksbaum points out,
noting that the last two groups have emerged as the most critical
in determining a film's financial success. ``If you don't have
something that's going to draw women, you're really out of luck.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
