<HEADER>
A4151 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-O'MEARA-BOS &LR;      08-02 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-O'MEARA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJOR DIFFERENCE IN O'MEARA IN '98 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ Mark O'Meara is golf's improbable dreamer. Doesn't
Tiger Woods call him his big brother? O'Meara has spent the better
part of the last two years talking about Woods, his potential, his
energy, his talent. They play practice rounds together at Isleworth
outside Orlando. Didn't Tiger shoot a 59 in the presence of O'Meara
the week before he dismantled the Augusta National Golf Course and
won the Masters by a rec-ord 12 shots?
</P>
<P>
   That was in 1997; now it's 1998. Guess what? The game's best
player is O'Meara. At age 41, he became the oldest player to win
two majors in the same year when he added to his Masters green
jacket the British Open claret jug. The guys who used to share the
distinction were Ben Hogan and Jack Nicklaus. They were 40. Hogan
won the Masters, US Open, and British Open in 1953. Nicklaus won
the US Open and PGA Championship in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara has a chance to join Hogan in the game's most exclusive
club. Hogan is the only player to win three of golf's four major
professional championships in the same year. O'Meara's bid to match
that feat _ at 41 _ begins a week from Thursday at Sahalee CC in
Redmond, Wash., site of the PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   After years as one of the game's most consistent, considerate
players, O'Meara has aged so gracefully that he's shed the tag of
being the best player never to have won a major championship. Leave
that to Colin Montgomerie, Phil Mickelson, and David Duval. O'Meara
got his two before anybody noticed.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara has won 16 PGA Tour events, but before this year his
rec-ord in golf's major championships didn't go begging for
attention. Before winning the Masters, he had missed the cut in 17
of his first 56 majors. He didn't even own a second-place finish.
Even though he has won the Pebble Beach National Pro-Am five times,
he missed the cut in blustery conditions when the US Open was
contested there in 1992. His best finishes in majors had been four
third-place ties _ in the 1988 US Open at The Country Club, the
1991 US Open at Hazeltine, the 1985 British Open at Royal St.
George's, and the 1991 British at Royal Birkdale.
</P>
<P>
   The guys on the PGA Tour have long known how good O'Meara is,
however, and they marvel at how well he's played this year. He was
a popular topic of discussion during the CVS Charity Classic, which
ended last Sunday at Pleasant Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what Mark's done has been really incredible,'' said
Larry Rinker. ``If you go back a few years, he was in a slump and
really playing bad. He came out of it and won the Honda. He could
have gone the way of Corey Pavin and Ian Baker-Finch. He's always
been one of the top 30 players out here, but he was having a really
bad year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just played incredibly. He's won two of the last three
majors, and he's ranked fourth in the world. I can't believe the
ranking system. I think something's wrong with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark's a great guy. I think he just said, `I'm going to be
Tiger's big brother. I'm going to help this kid out.' I think in
the end Tiger has ended up helping him. I think Tiger's helped him
with his attitude. You're playing with a guy who hits it 60 yards
by you, and he can beat that guy. Mark befriended him, and it's
turned out that being a nice guy has actually helped him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Blaine McCallister, who lost in a playoff at Pleasant Valley in
1986 and won there in 1989, points to the putt O'Meara made at
Augusta National to win the Masters as the trigger to what's
happened this year. ``It's just a matter of his coming into his own
time,'' said McCallister. ``The guy's always been a good player.
He's proved that over his career. What it took is one putt at
Augusta to make him realize how really good he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now he's gone from one of the top-echelon players to one of
the premier players. When he birdied 17 and 18, that proved to him
he knew what he needed to do. Then he goes off to the British Open
and proves to himself he can do it any time. It was a basic way of
saying, `I know what I can do.' Being a friend of Tiger maybe
inspired him a little, but I believe what happened was basically
inside Mark O'Meara.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can he win the PGA? I think he can. You look at a baseball
player who gets in that groove. With Mark, he's always had the
groove but he didn't have that extra thing that got him over it.
That putt he made at Augusta is going to always stand out in his
career as a leaping point.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Hoch, who has demonstrated the same consistency that has
been O'Meara's trademark and is also seeking his first major
championship, said clutch putting has been an O'Meara strength.
``He's proven throughout his career he's one of the best clutch
putters there is,'' said Hoch. ``To tell you the truth, I don't
know of anyone I'd rather have putt it when we need it than him
right now. There's a lot of good putters out there, but to putt it
when you really need it, I'd want him to putt it. He impresses me
because when he's hitting pretty decent and keeps it in play he can
win. He doesn't have to hit it great to do it. I don't think many
people realize what a great short game he has.''
</P>
<P>
   Loren Roberts pointed to O'Meara's ball-striking ability and his
patience. ``He's been a great ball striker for a long time,'' said
Roberts. ``When I've watched him play this year, he's playing with
such patience. That's the key to it. He's just letting things
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   John Cook assessed O'Meara more simply. ``I think it's called
talent,'' he said. ``He's got a lot of it. He was just waiting for
his time. Sometimes things happen quickly. Sometimes things happen
slowly. It's not like he didn't do anything before he won these
last two tournaments. He won 15 times. He's one of the leading
career money winners. He's had a more than respectable career, and
then to add these two is not surprising. He just has an immense
talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Brad Faxon, a native of Barrington, R.I., who can relate to
O'Meara's record based on his own career, also put is simply.
``He's a great player,'' said Faxon. ``He's been around for a long
time, and he's got a great temperament for the game and a great
tempo for the game. He waited a long time for some good things to
happen. I really believe that having Tiger Woods as a neighbor has
helped make him a better player. They practice a lot together, and
he's not intimidated by Tiger coming down the stretch. He said last
year at Pebble Beach he knew Tiger was there and it brought out the
best in him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
