r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     08-02 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS BEAT DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The game had everything, including an unhappy ending
for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   But as July became August, even Saturday night's 2-1 loss to the
New York Mets in front of 42,224 at Shea Stadium could be
appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Perez arrived from Montreal just an hour before gametime
and pitched a two-hit shutout for seven innings. Shortstop Mark
Grudzielanek, acquired with Perez on Friday in a seven-player deal,
had two hits and saved a run with his glove.
</P>
<P>
   The demons revisited Mike Piazza, who drew more boos after
popping out with a chance to tie the game in the eighth, which made
him 0 for 7 in the series against his former team.
</P>
<P>
   And though Jeff Shaw blew his first Dodger save opportunity when
he allowed a game-tying pinch homer to former Westlake High star
Matt Franco and game-winning double by Edgardo Alfonzo in the
ninth, for the first time in months the Dodgers appeared whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``We flew in on the plane today and I turned to Mark and told
him, `This is going to be pretty special,' '' Perez said. ``We're
playing in a big town for a big team.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it didn't hurt so much because the Dodgers stole a victory
from the Mets the night before when Piazza let the tying run score
on a not-so-wild pitch in the ninth. But the three teams ahead of
the Dodgers in the wild-card race, Chicago, San Francisco and the
Mets, all won.
</P>
<P>
   Perez's contribution, however, was quite a boost. Already this
season, the Dodgers have lost Ramon Martinez, Hideo Nomo and Ismael
Valdes from the starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   And the flamboyant Perez arrived with a style that is unique.
While Grudzielanek came straight to the ballpark after the plane
landed, Perez was met by his mother, who lives in New York, and
taken to lunch.
</P>
<P>
   He hadn't pitched in a week after suffering a broken nose in an
automobile accident. Hadn't even played catch or run a sprint. Then
he showed up, was introduced to his new manager, Glenn Hoffman, and
said he was ready to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Sunday, I did nothing,'' Perez said. ``I couldn't. I
knew my control would be a little off (six walks), but I figured
everything would be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   He also gave the Dodgers an early glimpse of the on-field antics
that often get him in trouble with opposing teams. When
Grudzielanek saved a run in the third by going behind second to rob
Brian McRae of a base hit, Perez danced off the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been telling me to change my whole career,'' said
Perez, who was 7-10 with a 3.75 in 23 starts with Montreal. ``Even
a manager in the minors said I needed to tone that down if I was
going to make it. I'm better, but I still let stuff out.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez left after seven innings with the game scoreless, but the
Dodgers got an unearned run against Rick Reed (12-7) in the eighth.
With two outs, pinch hitter Alex Cora reached on an error by second
baseman Luis Lopez and scored on a double by Eric Young.
</P>
<P>
   For Young, it was the second consecutive night he had a
critical, late-inning, RBI double. He drove in the game-winning run
Friday in his first game since coming off the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another big part of the trade was getting EY back,'' Eric
Karros said. ``We didn't want to lose Wilton Guerrero, but having
EY in there puts another piece of our team in place.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had a chance to tie the game in the eighth against
Scott Radinsky when Alfonzo singled and John Olerud reached on an
error by Grudzielanek. But Antonio Osuna came on and retired the
next three batters to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw was nine for nine in save opportunities since joining the
Dodgers at the All-Star break. He got the first out of the ninth
when Young made a great, over-the-shoulder catch on a ball hit by
Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   Franco, who had three pinch homers last season, was next, and he
crushed a 1-0 slider into the right-field stands. Shaw then walked
pinch hitter Todd Hundley and pitching coach Charlie Hough came to
the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw was appearing in his third consecutive game, but he claimed
that was no excuse. He struck out new Met Tony Phillips, but
Alfonzo followed by doubling home Hundley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made two bad pitches and they beat us,'' Shaw said. ``I
wasn't tired. I told them that. Things have been going well and I
wanted the ball. Now I'll just start on another run.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
