<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-02 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4155 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINALS-FERGUSO     08-02 2209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-FERGUSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRESH START: FERGUSON COULD BE JUST WHAT CARDINALS NEED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dues? Bob Ferguson can tell you about those he's paid.
</P>
<P>
   About his days as a training camp gofer.
</P>
<P>
   Or selling season tickets to church groups.
</P>
<P>
   Or traveling the country, dragging NFL prospects out of homes,
bars and Lord knows where else, just to measure their vertical
jumps.
</P>
<P>
   Determination? Ferguson can tell you about that.
</P>
<P>
   About groveling for a job in pro football while working nights
as a bartender. About living in airports and hotels for half a
year, doing a job no one else wanted. About coming back from being
fired for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Bravado? Sure, Ferguson has a little of that, too.
</P>
<P>
   He'll tell you about how good-looking he was a decade or two
ago. Or about how he can help the Cardinals finally become a
winner. Or bust your chops when you call, loudly asking why you are
bothering him.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, Ferguson, the 47-year-old Cardinals vice president
in charge of player personnel, can tell you about faith, about
believing that one of the NFL's worst franchises will win
championships one day, about how it can capture the imagination of
an apathetic public, about how a reviled owner can become beloved.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson has seen these things happen and he believes. His high
school team in Federal Way, Wash., was a perennial loser but won
the conference championship by his senior year. The University of
Washington was 1-9 his freshman year but improved to 8-3 by his
junior year. The Buffalo Bills were horrid when Ferguson was hired
as a personnel man, but eventually went to four Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I've gone into something, it was (expletive) and
then got better,'' he said. ``Reclamation projects, call them what
you will. You have to believe, and I believe. You have to roll with
the punches and do things differently in every spot you're in. And
you have to have some used car salesman in you.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson is large, opinionated, occasionally emotional and often
funny. He has injected some personality into an organization that,
with the exception of Buddy Ryan's two-year regime, has been as
staid as Queen Elizabeth II.
</P>
<P>
   At news conferences, ``Fergie'' stands behind the podium like a
preacher behind a pulpit, telling a faithless congregation of
reporters that the Cardinals know what they are doing. His size and
sincerity keep them from laughing aloud.
</P>
<P>
   After selecting defensive end Andre Wadsworth with the the third
overall pick in April's draft, Ferguson met the press and actually
cried because he was so overjoyed with the pick. He joked about it
later, but in that moment, it was obvious how much the job meant to
him.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson is being lauded across the league for the team's
off-season moves. The team traded down one pick in the draft to
take Wadsworth, receiving from San Diego wide receiver/returner
Eric Metcalf, linebacker Patrick Sapp, a second-round choice and a
first-round pick next season.
</P>
<P>
   The club also traded a third-round pick to the New York Jets for
running back Adrian Murrell and a seventh-round pick, shoring up
another weakness.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the team has succeeded in re-signing its own free
agents. In Ferguson's two seasons with the team, the Cardinals have
re-signed All-Pro players such as fullback Larry Centers,
cornerback Aeneas Williams and defensive tackle Eric Swann. &QL; 
Many experts think the Cardinals will dramatically improve on their
4-12 record of last year, and the off-season decisions made by
Ferguson and others are the main reasons.
</P>
<P>
   In its preseason issue, ``Pro Football Weekly'' predicted, ``If
(owner) Bill Bidwill and his sons keep the team of Coach Vince
Tobin and front office executives of Bob Ferguson and Rod Graves
together, they could end up with a big winner in time.''
</P>
<P>
   Others believe Ferguson should be a contender for Executive of
the Year, which he thinks is ridiculous. ``Right here with all
that,'' he told a local radio show host who dared suggest it.
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt, however, that Ferguson's leadership has
contributed to the renewed optimism surrounding the franchise. It's
a franchise that hasn't had a winning season since moving to
Arizona 10 years ago, hasn't been to the playoffs in a non-strike
year and hasn't won a playoff game since 1947.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the biggest problems in the past was I don't
think anybody, or the right person, had full rein on the situation,
to make put-your-foot-down type decisions,'' Centers said. `I think
Bob Ferguson is really making an effort to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson is not an autocrat, however. Bidwill is still active in
personnel decisions. Michael Bidwill, son of the owner and a team
vice president, carries great influence. Tobin's opinion still
counts heavily. Bill Bidwill Jr., another vice president, is
involved in personnel decisions, and Graves, who works in
personnel, has input.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys I owe a lot to are Mr. Bidwill and Vince,'' Ferguson
said. ``Vince is a major, major reason I'm here. I love them both.
I sincerely mean that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson isn't just making a sales pitch. When Ferguson was
fired as the director of player personnel for the Denver Broncos,
Bidwill gave him a chance when jobs around the league were scarce.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson was hired temporarily at first. The Cardinals had no
one directing football operations and needed help through free
agency and the draft. Tobin and Ferguson found they worked well
together, and with the support of the head coach, Ferguson was
hired full time. In early 1997, he was promoted to his current
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have a big ego that everything has to be one way,''
Tobin said. ``He has opinions, which you need to have and you need
to feel strongly about them, but you have to have the ability to
work within an organization and arrive at what's best for an
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of his wife, Colleen, and three daughters,
the Cardinals are Ferguson's life. He has no hobbies, and he's not
good on vacations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes him about a week just to relax,'' Colleen Ferguson
said. ``He used to tell me that we'd get to do this or do that in
the off-season. It took me about four years to realize there is no
off-season. He's obsessed with it, but I love it, too, and it's
always been fun for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if he had the time, Ferguson is useless around the house.
He can't fix much _ she's the one with the toolbox, not him. ``His
answer to everything is duct tape,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Once Ferguson volunteered to trim a bush and left it with a
gaping hole, displaying the brown branches and leaves near the
stem. He solved the problem with a can of green spray paint.
</P>
<P>
   Football has always been the one thing Ferguson knew. He tried
living without the sport once, and it didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   An overachieving 210-pound college linebacker, Ferguson
succeeded because he was smart and devoted to the game. He tried
out for the San Diego Chargers but failed a physical because a torn
leg muscle gave him ``drop-foot syndrome,'' forcing him to wear a
brace, which didn't exactly work with his favorite shoes, a pair of
Beatle boots.
</P>
<P>
   He played some games as a scab when a strike stopped the 1974
NFL season, but that was the end of his playing career. He bounced
around a bit after that, even living for a time in Hawaii with a
buddy, making and selling puka shell necklaces on the beaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trim, lean and good-looking then,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he is far heavier than his playing weight of 210 pounds,
although he tries to exercise when he can.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see him walking every day, but he never seems to lose
weight,'' Centers said, jokingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, it took me 10 years to look like this, and it's going to
take me maybe that long to get back to where I was,'' Ferguson
responds. &QL; 
Ferguson eventually returned to Seattle, taking a bartending job.
The city had just been awarded a franchise, and every day on his
way to work, Ferguson stopped by the office of Herman Sarkowsky,
one of the Seahawks owners, and bugged his secretary for a job.
</P>
<P>
   One day, she pointed to five bags full of letters requesting
season tickets, and a career in pro football started.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat on Sarkowsky's floor for about two weeks and just
circled addresses and names,'' Ferguson said. `And they kept me
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson did anything and everything. He answered mail, tended
bar for the owners, drove their cars to Florida. He and another guy
went to the Kingdome when it was being built and measured each row
and estimated how many seats the place could hold. When training
camp started, he and Rick Thompson, now the Seahawks assistant
player personnel director, were assistants.
</P>
<P>
   In his tenure with the Seahawks, Ferguson also worked in group
sales (``I was great with church groups''), directed special events
and was even in charge of the cheerleaders for a year.
</P>
<P>
   With the Seahawks, he learned the value of paying attention to
detail. Once, Ferguson was sticking address labels on about 2,000
envelopes containing questionnaires to prospective players. Dick
Mansperger, who worked in player personnel, dropped in and noticed
some of the labels were crooked.
</P>
<P>
   He chewed out Ferguson. ``And he was right,'' Ferguson said.
``His point was that one of the kids who got a letter with a
crooked label would think, `Those guys don't care.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the long hours took a personal toll. Ferguson's
first marriage was failing and he decided to get out of football
for a while. He held several jobs, including selling radio
advertising, driving a beer truck and serving as a public relations
director for a professional hydroplane team.
</P>
<P>
   Divorced and working as a salesman, he dropped into a men's
store in Bellevue, Wash., one day to see if he could sell some air
time. The manager, a woman named Colleen, caught his eye. ``I
thought I was pretty hot stuff,'' Ferguson said. ``I went in and
bought three pairs of slacks and made her measure my pants.''
</P>
<P>
   Colleen thought the Ferguson was a little cocky, but there was
something about him she liked. ``I thought he looked like Robert
Redford,'' she said. ``You can tell how long ago that was. He's put
on a few, but I still see him that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Colleen, who had two daughters from a previous marriage, and
Ferguson married and became parents of another daughter. All three
will ``knock your (uh, socks) off with football knowledge,''
Ferguson said.
</P>
<P>
   While Ferguson was out of football, Gil Brandt, personnel
director in Dallas, and others were trying to lure him back.
Ferguson took a job working for a four-team scouting combine, which
included Dallas, Seattle, Buffalo and San Francisco. Ferguson
lugged around a black box containing all the equipment he needed,
and he traveled everywhere and anywhere to test players.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson searched for players on the main highways of college
football and along its dirt roads. He worked out one kid in a
driveway. He found players when and where they didn't want to be
found. On draft day, he'd wait by the phone for someone such as
49ers Coach Bill Walsh or Cowboys Coach Tom Landry to call for
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it for about three years, and it was great,'' Ferguson
said.
</P>
<P>
   He worked for the Cowboys for two seasons and then was offered a
job in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   The Fergusons were married in Buffalo and stayed for eight
seasons. He held various personnel positions, including assistant
general manager under Bill Polian, who is with the Colts. The Bills
were awful when Ferguson joined, and owner Ralph Wilson was
unpopular with fans, as is his counterpart here, Bill Bidwill.
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo front office decided to take chances to attract
quality players. ``We figured, what the hell, we were in Buffalo
anyway,'' Ferguson said.
</P>
<P>
   Through astute drafts and trades, and a little luck, they built
a Super Bowl team.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Polian was fired and Ferguson went to Denver, where
he was player personnel director. He was ripped for many moves,
including trading first- and third-round picks for receiver Mike
Pritchard.
</P>
<P>
   But he also made some savvy moves. He took center Tom Nalen, who
made the Pro Bowl last year, in the seventh round. Receiver Rod
Smith, signed as a rookie free agent, has become one of the better
deep threats in the league. Thirteen starters on last year's Super
Bowl champion team were acquired during Ferguson's tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson, however, knew his days were numbered with Coach Mike
Shanahan was hired in 1995. Shanahan wanted control of personnel
decisions and eventually fired Ferguson, who holds no grudges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing that ever happened to Denver was Mike
Shanahan,'' Ferguson said.
</P>
<P>
   That's what some people are saying about Ferguson and the
Cardinals, although he dismisses such talk and admits the team
hasn't accomplished anything yet.
</P>
<P>
   But it will, Ferguson said, you just have to believe. The former
puka shell necklace salesman/training camp gofer/vagabond scout
does.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will build a stadium in this Valley,'' he said. ``When?
Hopefully, soon. We have to win. And if they give me the chance, I
know what we can do to get there.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-98 0125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
