<HEADER>
A4157 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BICKLEY-CARDINALS     08-02 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BICKLEY-CARDINALS-TOBIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOBIN'S TURN TO SHOW WHO RULES ROOST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF _ He has been ridiculed by a former player for
conducting a sing-along with his soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   He has been categorized as a quiet strategist, more bland than a
scoop of vanilla, a man who wouldn't know the first thing about
whipping his players into a mad-dog frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Mr. Beige has had enough. And this is a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a fiery side,'' Vince Tobin says, edge in his voice.
``I'm in charge of this football team. I'm going to run this
football team. I've never been accused of not having a fiery side.
If anything, I have to work on my temper.''
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary. What Tobin needs to do is whip more tail, throw
some chairs, get in the face of players who need to learn about
toughness. And if he's really got a problem with anger management,
hey, this is football. Let it all hang out.
</P>
<P>
   When El Nino hit Cardinals' camp on Friday, when Tobin and Eric
Swann engaged in a heated argument at midfield, it may have been
nothing more than a pair of overheated engines. Or it may have
marked a turning point in Tobin's tenure. The day when Tobin
recognized the chaos, the lack of cohesion and commitment, and saw
the need for General Patton. Or, at the very least, an infusion of
Ditka.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, by the time the Cardinals arrived for their first
scrimmage on Saturday, everyone was downplaying the confrontation.
But one player said Swann's refusal to practice was directly
related to the work ethic of Simeon Rice, who has once again missed
much practice time under the pine trees.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie year, he was a hold-out. Last year, altitude sickness.
This year, bronchitis.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as Rice coughed all over the artificial turf on Saturday,
it was fairly obvious the ailment was genuine. It was also obvious
that both men went out of their way to avoid each other during
Saturday's festivities, an exercise in which both were spectators.
</P>
<P>
   Swann, handed a $25 million contract with a $7.5 million bonus
in the off-season, should know better than to walk out of a
practice session, regardless of motive. But this is the tantrum
stage of training camp, when two-a-days fray the nerves, and
everyone gets a mulligan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're cool,'' Rice said of his teammate. ``I don't feel like
there's a rift. But I don't know. I can only go on my own merits
and pursue what I'm pursuing. I've never really known him on a
friend level, but as a teammate, he's been cool.''
</P>
<P>
   What all of this represents is something much larger than
whether a silly feud exists. It is the reason why people question
the Cardinals' mental toughness, the leading theory why they have a
special knack for losing all the close games. They are simply
leadership-deficient on defense, and this is where Tobin comes in.
</P>
<P>
   He must take the reins, command respect, serve as the lightning
rod. He must instill fear, produce passion, be the man. If not,
then who? Andre Wadsworth?
</P>
<P>
   No one says players must get along to succeed. As Tobin can
attest, the fury of those great Bears defenses in the 1980s was
simply an extension of the locker room acrimony. But there has to
be one man who stands above the rest, one voice that transcends
everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you don't have it in you,'' Rice said. ``It's going to
seem flawed.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it must be legitimate, and that's the rub. There are
defensive coordinators, there are head coaches and there are men
who never make the transition. Despite all of his experience and
chalkboard ingenuity, Tobin has never distinguished himself as a
leader of men.
</P>
<P>
   Until Friday, that is, when Tobin displayed a side rarely seen
by veteran bird watchers. And later that night, he addressed the
team, clearing the air of any lingering animosity.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, this is a pivotal year for the Cardinals. For the new
stadium. For the head coach's future in the Valley. Maybe Tobin
senses the urgency, sees the void. And we can only hope that Mr.
Beige has a little Lombardi in him, after all. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
