<SLUG> BC-CAR-AUTO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORNADAY ANGRY HE WAS KNOCKED FROM RACE 
</HEADLINE>
 RACING NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ Jack Sprague says it wasn't anything intentional. The
bumping incident he had with Ron Hornaday on Lap 171 of Thursday
night's NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series race at Indianapolis Raceway
Park was, as most drivers are wont to say after a racing incident,
``just one of them racin' deals.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem with that, however, is that if you ask Hornaday, it
was far from being ``just one of them racin' deals.'' It wasn't
even close.
</P>
<P>
   As he was racing Lonnie Rush for second place, Hornaday's run
came to an abrupt halt when he was clipped from behind by Sprague
and spun and crashed into the wall. Sprague surged to the lead and
eventually won the race, vaulting over Hornaday to take the lead in
the NCTS point standings, 2,199 to 2,167.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to get around the No. 10 truck _ high and low _
and I made a move on the bottom,'' said Hornaday, who entered with
the points lead after having won his fifth race of the season at
Pikes Peak, Colo., last Saturday. ``Jack charged in there (in Turn
1) and turned me. It's a long season _ if that's the way we are
going to race the rest of the season, then that's fine. I'm sure he
sees it different.''
</P>
<P>
   Hornaday will no doubt let his driving settle any differences
with Sprague when the two arrive at New Hampshire International
Speedway Sunday for the resumption of racing in Race 12 of the
NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I hated that deal with Ron,'' said Sprague, driver
of the No. 24 GMAC Financial Chevrolet. ``I was underneath him down
the front straightaway and I felt I was over the lane and I don't
feel like I did anything wrong. ... I hate it for Ron, because I
damned sure didn't want to wreck him. Like I said, there was
nowhere I could go.''
</P>
<P>
   But once the accident occurred, Hornaday knew where to go, by
diving into the pits. Hornaday climbed from his truck, which
sustained serious damage to the rear deck, and walked over to
Sprague's pit area, where he engaged Sprague's crew chief in a
heated discussion. NASCAR officials intervened, and the parties
were pulled apart before the altercation came to blows.
</P>
<P>
   ``IRP's been good to me,'' Hornaday said. ``But Jack wasn't
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Sprague, ``I hope Ron looks at the tape and sees that I
didn't do nothing wrong. I mean, I was on the bottom (of the
track), and we normally run the third lane. I really didn't think
he'd come there, or I wouldn't have stayed there. He did come down
and I couldn't get out of there, got into him, and he spun. It's
cool that we got the points lead back and I'm happy for everybody,
but I hate that that situation happened. I really do. I don't drive
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indy was a hotbed of racing activity last week, with the trucks
at IRP Thursday night, the International Race of Champions season
finale at Indianapolis Motor Speedway Friday, and the NASCAR
Winston Cup series making its whistlestop for Saturday's Brickyard
400. But the return to Indy was particularly bittersweet for  &UR; Al
Unser Jr. &LR; , who would've preferred Friday to be racing open-wheel
CART cars at Indy instead of one of the 12 identically prepared
IROC Firebird Trans Ams. ``Anytime you get to run at the
Indianapolis Motor Speedway, it's a dream come true,'' said Unser,
a two-time winner of the Indy 500 who had not taken a lap around
the 2.5-mile oval since his unsuccessful qualifying attempt in
1995. ``But I wish it was in an open-wheeler, a Champ car.'' But
because of CART's lingering feud with the fledgling Indy Racing
League, founded by IMS president  &UR; Tony George &LR; , &UR;  &LR; Unser has not had
the opportunity to do so. Will he get the chance before calling it
a career? ``My feeling is there is always hope,'' said Unser, 36,
who finished second in Friday's IROC race. He was heartened by the
wild fan reaction he received when he turned out to support cousins
 &UR; Robby Unser  &LR; and  &UR; Johnny Unser  &LR; during their time trial
qualifications for the 1998 Indy 500. ``I came down pit road, and I
was overwhelmed,'' Unser recalled. ``I wasn't sure what to expect
with the crowd.'' ... Winston Cup driver  &UR; Mark Martin  &LR; clinched his
fourth IROC title in the last five years and his third in a row by
winning Friday's inaugural race at Indy. ``I really wanted to make
it four championships because I can't believe it's anything but
luck with these kinds of drivers in this kind of race,'' Martin
said. ``My luck is going to run out one of these days.'' Martin had
86 points to finish 29 ahead of Roush Racing teammate  &UR; Jeff Burton
 &LR; in the final IROC standings, which paid Martin a $225,000 purse.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last week's US 500 at Michigan Speedway would have gone down as
the best CART race of the season _ especially after the
breathtaking 62 lead changes, which set a series record _ but,
tragically,  &UR; Greg Moore's  &LR; stirring last-lap pass of  &UR; Jimmy Vasser
 &LR; was rendered an afterthought in the wake of an accident that
killed three spectators and injured six others, five of whom were
released from a Detroit area hospital last week. The fatalities
took place with 75 laps to go when  &UR; Adrian Fernandez's  &LR; car lost
control as it traveled through Turn 4 at more than 200 miles per
hour. It slammed the wall and sustained heavy suspension damage
from an impact that, onboard sensors indicated, measured 92Gs.
Fernandez's right front tire and pieces of suspension debris were
catapulted over the 11-foot high catch fence and sailed into the
grandstands, killing  &UR; Kenneth Fox &LR; , &UR; Michael Terry Tautkus &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and
 &UR; Sheryl Ann Laster &LR; . Fernandez, who had won his first career pole
at Michigan, had yet another career milestone tied to yet another
tragedy. His first career victory in the Molson Indy Toronto two
years ago was overshadowed by the race fatalities of driver  &UR; Jeff
Krosnoff  &LR; and a track worker who was killed when Krosnoff's
airborne car careened off track. ``I can only express the deep
sorrow felt by everyone within the CART community,'' CART chairman
Andrew Craig said in a statement. ``There is, of course, nothing
that we can say or do that in any way will reduce the deep sadness
felt by the families and friends of the victims.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
