<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-02 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4159 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-BREW     08-02 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-BREWERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STINNETT BRUISES MILWAUKEE  
 D-BACKS CATCHER'S RUN-IN SPARKS COME BACK VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Of all the hits the Diamondbacks had Saturday night,
the biggest was not Yamil Benitez's home run to lead off the fifth
inning. Nor was it Andy Fox's double in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest was by Kelly Stinnett in the third inning. And he
didn't have to use his bat.
</P>
<P>
   Stinnett, a former all-state quarterback at Lawton (Okla.) High
School and a former Milwaukee Brewer, sent Brewers catcher Bobby
Hughes sprawling with a crunching body-block, knocking the ball
loose in the process and scoring Arizona's first run.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes seemed to be in a fog the rest of the night. He was
caught napping when Andy Fox sprinted from third for the uncovered
plate to score the tying run in the eighth. And Hughes' passed ball
a few moments later on Bernard Gilkey's strikeout allowed Danny
Klassen to score what proved to be the winning run in Arizona's 5-4
victory at Milwaukee County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks' third straight victory raised their record to
41-69, while Milwaukee fell to .500 at 55-55.
</P>
<P>
   Stinnett played with Hughes in the minor leagues in the Brewers'
system the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel for him. I've been there, had tough nights myself,''
Stinnett said.
</P>
<P>
   But business is business.
</P>
<P>
   Stinnett was at first base after leading off with a single off
left-hander Rafael Roque, making his first major league start.
Stinnett took off when Andy Fox hit a sharp double into the
right-field corner.
</P>
<P>
   The ball bounced off the fence a little farther than right
fielder Jeromy Burnitz anticipated, and Stinnett kept his legs
churning around third base. The ball got to Hughes just before
Stinnett did, and . . . boom! Contact between the 5-foot-11,
195-pound Stinnett and the 6-4, 237-pound Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the very first time I ever had to do that, and I
really had nowhere to go,'' Stinnett said. ``Usually, the catcher
gives you one side (of the plate). You never want to do it, but you
have to. I have a pretty low center of gravity and I got under his
neck a little enough to knock the ball loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Stinnett never has been on the receiving end of such a play,
``knock on wood,'' he said, tapping his knuckles on the edge of his
wood dressing cubicle.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers still held a 3-1 lead at that point, thanks to a
three-run homer in the first inning by Burnitz off right-hander
Clint Sodowsky, making his first start of the season after the
trade of right-hander Willie Blair and catcher Jorge Fabregas to
the New York Mets on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez's homer to lead off the fifth and an RBI single by Karim
Garcia tied the game at 3, but Brewers relief pitcher Bronswell
Patrick hit a home run off right-hander Felix Rodriguez to lead off
the Milwaukee fifth for a 4-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Fox led off the eighth with a single to right off Milwaukee
right-hander Chad Fox. Klassen then laid down a bunt, which third
baseman Jeff Cirillo fielded and threw to second baseman Fernando
Vina, who was covering the bag at first. The throw was a bit wide,
tipped off Vina's glove and rolled down the line into shallow left.
Klassen was given a hit, but Cirillo was charged with an error on
the throw, allowing Fox to advance to third.
</P>
<P>
   That's when things got confusing.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes had gone to cover third as Cirillo charged on the bunt.
Andy Fox saw Hughes standing near him and nobody covering the
plate. Vina still had the ball and Hughes, the most likely person
to call time, had not done so nor made a move to go back to the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   Fox sprinted home to score the tying run and the fans sent a
cascade of boos onto the field. It got even worse later when Gilkey
swung at a pitch from Eric Plunk for strike three and the ball went
through Hughes' legs, allowing Klassen to score to make it 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see anyone call time, so I looked over at Butter
(third-base coach Brian Butterfield) and took off. I thought I
could make it, even though you're not really sure in those
situations when someone is going to call time. I take a lot of
pride in my baserunning. Fortunately, this worked out.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
