<HEADLINE>
GORDON COMES UP BIG AT BRICKYARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Such a small man to win such a big race.
</P>
<P>
   And now mighty Jeff Gordon, all 5-feet-7 and 150 pounds of him,
has won it twice.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, with much of the state and an estimated crowd of 320,000
cheering his every move, again won the Brickyard 400 on Saturday at
Indianapolis Motor Speedway, edging runner-up Mark Martin by a
scant 0.404 of a second in a race that finished under an
anticlimactic caution flag.
</P>
<P>
   It took nearly all of Gordon's strength to hoist a large
winner's trophy over his head.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, however, will have to start pumping iron if he expects
to lift the pot of gold he won for winning his sixth race of the
season and 35th overall in a career spanning a remarkably measly 5{
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Along with a sizeable $637,625 share of the total purse, Gordon
also pocketed the $1 million Winston No Bull 5 bonus.
</P>
<P>
   The top five finishing drivers in the Coca Cola 600 at Charlotte
Motor Speedway on May 24 were eligible to claim the prize. The
trick was, one of them had to win at Indy.
</P>
<P>
   It was Gordon, whose combined $1,637,625 earnings this season is
a motorsports record. He also moved into second place behind Dale
Earnhardt on the all-time list with a cool $20.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Did we mention that Gordon is only 26? Or is now 72 points ahead
of Martin in the driver's standings and is nearing a third
championship over the past four years?
</P>
<P>
   Didn't think so.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1994, everything went our way,'' said Gordon, referring to
the inaugural race, which he won. ``Everything went our way again
today. I don't know what else to say. I guess when it's meant to
be, it's meant to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon doesn't have to repeat the sentence twice. Martin
understands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of hard to beat a man when he's got a faster car and
the lead,'' summarized Martin, who finished ahead of third-place
Bobby Labonte, fourth-place Mike Skinner and fifth-place Dale
Earnhardt. ``We threw everything at them that we had. It just
wasn't enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the command to start the engines was echoed by NASCAR
Winston Cup President Bill France Jr., Gordon's rainbow-colored
DuPont Automotive Finishes Chevrolet Monte Carlo behaved
beautifully, meaning it roared, not sputtered.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who started on the inside of the second row, grabbed the
lead for the first time on Lap 19 and eventually led a whopping 97
of the 160 total laps.
</P>
<P>
   As dominating a performance as it might appear, it truly wasn't
a one-man show.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, pole-sitter Ernie Irvan led the first 18 laps.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, Dale Jarrett nearly completed an improbable run after
falling four laps down when he ran out of fuel on Lap 81.
</P>
<P>
   A slew of caution flags helped Jarrett fully recover from the
deficit, and when the checkered flag fell, he was back on the lead
lap in 16th position.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Martin became the hunter, sliding by Bobby Labonte on
Lap 144 to move into second.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the aid of three late caution flags over the final 10
laps, Martin still wasn't able to bully his Valvoline Ford Taurus
past Gordon's purring Chevy.
</P>
<P>
   The ninth and final caution flag appeared seconds after Gordon
led the field on a restart on Lap 158, caused by a multicar crash
in front of the main grandstands along the front straightaway.
</P>
<P>
   No one was hurt, and Gordon outmotored Martin around the
2.5-mile oval to maintain the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the debris, which included defending champion Ricky
Rudd's mangled Ford along the inner concrete wall, there wasn't
enough time or laps remaining to create one final green-flag run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark made a heck of a run at me going into Turn 2 (on Lap
158),'' Gordon said. ``He knew we were racing back to the caution
and I saw him drive deeper (into Turn 2) than I've seen him do all
weekend long. I could really feel him there.
</P>
<P>
   ``But once he got close to me, his front end washed out on
him.''
</P>
<P>
   And that was that.
</P>
<P>
   Martin reasoned that he might have been able to pester Gordon
over the final three laps had they been green-flag laps, but even
he recognized it likely was a waste of thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I might catch him,'' Martin said. ``I thought I was
gaining on him. But I don't know how much he was playing with me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly wasn't going to catch him and pass him unless
something strange happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing strange happened. Nothing at all. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-98 0129EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
