<HEADLINE>
SAMUELSON'S RACE HEATS UP AT FINISH 
</HEADLINE>
 TO BEACON-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE ELIZABETH, Maine _ Part of what made her such a tough
competitor, Joan Benoit Samuelson has often said, were the frozen
eyelashes and icy roads endured during long, blustery Maine winters
of training. So it was a gorgeous irony when her Beach to Beacon
10K was greeted in its first running Saturday by only the bluest of
skies and balmiest of summer days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maine isn't all bad,'' said the 1984 Olympic marathon gold
medalist with a huge smile, the shimmering Casco Bay as a backdrop
for the 2,337 finishers crossing the line near Portland Head Light.
</P>
<P>
   First across, in 28 minutes 18 seconds, was Johannes Mabitle, a
30-year-old South African, who beat Kenyans William Kiptum and
Peter Ndirangu (both clocked at 28:19) in a thrilling duel to the
tape. The duel was duplicated soon after by the women when
26-year-old Catherine Ndereba of Kenya (32:15) outsprinted Libbie
Hickman of Fort Collins, Colo., (32:17) and countrywoman Helen
Kimaiyo-Kipkoskei (32:18) for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Americans Steve Plasencia (29:37, an American master's record)
and Kim Jones (34:35) won in the master's division.
</P>
<P>
   Mabitle ran with the lead pack all the way, but by the time it
was whittled to five at the 4-mile mark, most bets were on Mexico's
German Silva to kick for the win. But Silva ended up fourth
(28:23), dropping back just before the push to the finish from
about 150 meters out. At that point Mabitle was still third, but
with 50 meters to go he edged ahead to his first victory in a major
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very tough for me,'' he said. ``I was tired. I said,
`Where's the finish line?'''
</P>
<P>
   Ndereba, meanwhile, had no easier task of it. She went out to a
quick lead but was caught by Kimaiyo-Kipkoskei at 2 miles. They
shared it until 6 miles, when Hickman surged ahead of them.
Suddenly, just as with the men, it was a three-way dash.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Helen tried to kick, I just put on my heels,'' said
Ndereba, enjoying a successful comeback season after the May 1997
birth of her daughter, Jane. ``I feel good, because even when I
finished, I was still strong. I could go a further distance.''
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing but praise for the 6.2-mile course, which
began on a sunny flat for about 2 miles before turning onto windy,
shady Shore Road, with ocean vistas reminiscent of the Falmouth
Road Race. ``You could tell a runner put it together,'' praised
Plascencia.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, despite the shoulder-to-shoulder finishes, the sparkling
clear skies, and her frequent protests to the contrary, the day
belonged to Samuelson, who founded this race to give back to her
hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half the people who were out there watching this year, I bet,
will be running next year,'' said an ebullient Samuelson, 41, who
did not compete but did everything else, from wishing the
wheelchair competitors well at the starting line to congratulating
the winners at the finish, with commentary for local TV in between.
``It's literally and physically the people's race _ it's no longer
Joan's race.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
