<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COLLEGE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENTRAL FLORIDA HOPEFUL 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ While the Big East fiddles with a new system, a
school in waiting _ Central Florida _ burns with desire to be part
of the family.
</P>
<P>
   This is nothing new. Ever since it made the move to Division 1A
in 1995, Central Florida has been looking for a conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Knights talked to Conference USA, which wasn't
interested, and have courted the Big East for a couple of seasons,
without much of a response.
</P>
<P>
   If you believe some critics of the league, that isn't all that
surprising, since they believe the Big East is near life-support
status.
</P>
<P>
   The fact of the matter is that the Big East _ which should have
one very good team (West Virginia) and a couple of good teams
(Miami and Syracuse) _ needs a jump start. The conference needs new
blood, because the vultures of other conferences are already
checking out teams such as Syracuse, Boston College, and Miami, all
of whom are on wish lists of expansion plans in the Big Ten and
Atlantic 10.
</P>
<P>
   Ask the Big East people about expansion and they shake their
head. ``Don't see it happening,'' says commissioner Mike Tranghese
with a sigh. ``And who would we take?''
</P>
<P>
   Ask Mike Kruczek. ``We'd love to be part of the Big East,'' said
the new Central Florida coach, sitting in his office last week.
``That would be a dream come true for us. Look what we have to
offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Kruczek then began to talk about a university that is now
pushing 30,000 on a sprawling 1,400-acre campus in the heart of the
richest recruiting area in the country.
</P>
<P>
   He talked about plans for a new athletic complex on campus that
will include an expanded weight room, five football practice
fields, new offices, baseball stadium, and tennis complex. It will
be on par with anything in the Southeast, Big East, or any other
major conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first made the move to 1A, this was OK,'' said
Kruczek, who knows about the Big East from his playing days as a BC
quarterback in the mid '70s. ``But I told our people: If you want
to compete with Florida and Florida State, you need the
facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   CFU already has a first-class stadium, as it plays in the
70,000-seat Citrus Bowl, 15 miles away in downtown Orlando. The
school has a commitment to play 1A football, and it draws from a
talent pool in Florida that can field a Top 20 team.
</P>
<P>
   ``But life as an independent is not really possible in 1A,''
said Kruczek, who took over from Gene McDowell last winter on an
interim basis, although Kruczek feels he will get a fair chance to
retain the job. ``We need a conference like the Big East. But
that's out of our hands right now. We just have to do what we can
do and hope for the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Central Florida did its part by going 5-6 in its
second season in 1A, losing by a point to Ole Miss, 2 to South
Carolina, and giving co-national champion Nebraska all that it
could handle for a half before eventually losing by a pair of
touchdowns in Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   The effort was a good-news, bad-news experience for CFU.
Athletic director Steve Sloan watched the Golden Knights with a
mixture of pride and pain as he saw his team compete against the
best team in college football, but also understood when a couple of
schools later called and backed out of contracts, fearful of losing
to a ``nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   Central Florida has had its growing pains, the most serious
being the cellular phone calling card scandal last year that
brought in federal authorities and led to the dismissal of
McDowell, who had nurtured CFU from a Division 2 program to a 1A
wannabe with a $2.2 million football budget that is growing
steadily.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the downside for anyone taking us?'' asked Kruczek, who
has a team that could be bowl-eligible this year, with a
talent-loaded roster led by quarterback Daunte Culpepper, who could
make a serious run at the Heisman Trophy this season and is
projected as a top-five NFL draft pick next spring. ``We play in a
great market, with lots of talent, in a big-time stadium, and the
commitment is firm.''
</P>
<P>
   So it is. The Golden Knights will open their season at Louisiana
Tech Sept. 5 and hope they can make another step toward becoming a
Division 1A power, if not partner in a major conference.
</P>
<P>
   They'd love the Big East to call, but the phone hasn't rung.
They also want the world _ and the Big East _ to know that they
would come as a football-only member.
</P>
<P>
   Why, then, is the Big East doing nothing? Afraid of offending
Miami? Please. A Central Florida-Miami rivalry would probably help
the Hurricanes, and trips to Orlando would help every other Big
East school.
</P>
<P>
   But the call to Sloan or CFU president Dr. John Hitt has not
been made, and the question you have to ask is why.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We understand the need for some Top 10 teams to play easy games,
but why is Alabama-Birmingham on Nebraska's schedule Sept. 5? ...
Isn't it interesting that the NCAA has taken a strong stance
against gambling but allows athletic directors and conferences to
hold conventions in gambling dens such as Las Vegas? Latest
example: Western Athletic Conference football media day was last
week at the MGM Grand Hotel. The conference will also again hold
its championship game in Vegas ... Nebraska goes into the season
with the longest winning streak in 1A at 14. Michigan is next at
12, followed by UCLA (10) and, surprise, Colorado State (9) ...
Every team in the WAC has at least 10 starters returning, topped by
Nevada-Las Vegas with 20 ... Iowa State has chosen an unusual way
to build its program. The Cyclones have 18 junior college transfers
on their roster ... It was a victory for supporters of big-time
football when a proposal to reduce football scholarships was
rejected by the Division 1 Management Council. A movement to reduce
scholarships from 85 to 75 has been in the works for the past few
years ... The Big East has bowl commitments for three teams _ in
the Alliance, Gator, and Insight.com. A fourth bowl commitment is
still in the works. Tranghese is working on the Liberty Bowl in
Memphis, Music City in Nashville, and the Motor City Bowl in
Pontiac, Mich.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-98 0132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
