<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONASTATE-DBACKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASU'S PALMORE ITCHING TO PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanks to Professor Freedman and Professor Richardson, redshirt
freshman Courtney Palmore finds himself in the running to start at
strong safety for Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   Palmore played student last season and took plenty of mental
notes while watching starting safeties Mitchell Freedman and Damien
Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot from them,'' he said. ``They both work really
hard. They both know what they're doing. I kind of looked at them
as another coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both are very smart players, and that's what it takes. It
isn't just about physical ability.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmore hopes to step in for Richardson, who has graduated. It
won't be easy. Richardson was one of the headiest players on the
team and ranked second in unassisted (42) and total tackles (71)
and also posted two interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Palmore also hopes to be joined by Freedman, the heart of the
secondary. Freedman is finishing summer school, and a source said
he is in good shape to retain his academic eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   A strong spring put Palmore, who said he is 10 pounds heavier
than last season, in the running for the starting job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm young, but I know my material,'' he said. ``I'm
anxious to get on the field like everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Battling Palmore for the job will be Christon Rance, who
substituted for Richardson last season. Rance will try to use Camp
Tontozona to make up for his tough outing in the spring-ending
scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   There's no chance Freedman will move to strong safety, as was
speculated in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes years of experience to play in the middle,''
defensive coordinator Phil Snow said. ``If you look at (Freedman)
two years ago, he had one interception. Last year he had four. He's
starting to understand how to play the whole field, which is what
you have to do in that position.''
</P>
<P>
   Junior cornerback Courtney Jackson returns and will move from
the right to the left side where Jason Simmons played so adeptly
last season. His new partner at cornerback likely will be junior
J'Juan Cherry, a physically gifted player who just needs to
fine-tune his technique and gain game experience. There may be no
player on the team with more potential than Cherry.
</P>
<P>
   The staff also will look at junior Kareem Clark, who appeared in
nickel and dime packages in eight games last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll play a lot of people on defense this year,'' Snow said.
``I bet 18 to 20 every week. There are a lot of young guys that are
close, and it's hard for them to understand what it takes to play
70 to 75 snaps. It takes years to build up to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Can a team rotating so many players on defense emerge as one of
the top teams in the country, as so many are predicting?
</P>
<P>
   ``We try not to focus on what people think about us,'' Palmore
said. ``Of course, we want to win the national championship, we
have the potential to do it. It's up to us to produce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we can get it done.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-98 0132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
