</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYCLING-TOUR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JULICH RIDING HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
 DE FRANCE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LE CREUSOT, France _ The Tour de France edged a little closer to
Paris Saturday, and Bobby Julich edged a little closer to the
podium. It might not be in the second-place spot he held two days
ago, but barring a crash that sidelines the rider, Julich, a
26-year-old from Glenwood Springs, Colo., should take the stand
Sunday as third-place finisher.
</P>
<P>
   In front of him will be Italian Marco Pantani as leader and
German defending champion Jan Ullrich, who won Saturday's time
trial.
</P>
<P>
   The course Saturday was determined not to be kind to the riders,
and not just because of the rolling, 32-mile ride in central
France. Rain fell on the first racers who set out one by one, and
even though it subsided into an occasional drizzle, the skies
remained gray and the temperature dipped to 60 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the riders, who set out at two-minute intervals, rode a
blistering pace of an average of 30 m.p.h. as they covered the
course on their bikes with disc wheels and triathlon handlebars.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler Hamilton of Brookline, Mass., had the lead for the first
hour and ended up in a respectable 15th place. He is 51st overall.
</P>
<P>
   When Ullrich started off in the race against the clock, it was
clear that he was determined to swallow the 14-second deficit he
had against Julich. He did, easily beating all others with a time
of 1 hour 3 minutes 52 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Julich came in second, a minute behind Ullrich, and dropped to
third place overall. But he seemed to take it in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time trial is very hard,'' Julich said, smiling but
coughing after the race. ``All I could think of was how hard I
worked to get here.''
</P>
<P>
   So is a place on the podium a dream come true?
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of a dream,'' he said. ``I won't be satisfied until I
really see what my limits are. I'm not sure if I quite found out my
limits in this race. I know there were a lot of things that tried
to get in the way of my dream, and I just know that in the future,
with the support of all my close friends and family, I can get back
here and do even better. But it's so nice to climb the mountain and
look down and see the view a little bit. I'm not quite there;
there's a few more steps.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I won't stop until I either win the Tour de France or I'm
too old to ride my bike.''
</P>
<P>
   Julich's father, Bob, stood nearby beaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to come here; I knew it would be confusing,''
he said, looking at the swarm of cameras and journalists
surrounding his son. ``But I talked to him on Monday and he was
tired, so I knew I had to come over and give him a little boost.''
</P>
<P>
   So he, his ex-wife, Bernadette, and daughter, Robin, flew over
to catch the end of the Tour. Also following the rider has been
Julich's girlfriend, Angela Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   And it's no wonder where Julich gets his pragmatic attitude.
When his father was asked what he thought about his son's
third-place, not second-place, finish, he just shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you work harder when you've got two steps to climb
instead on one,'' he said. ``I'm just so happy. His goal was to be
in the top 10, and this will just make him hungrier.''
</P>
<P>
   Barring a major accident Sunday, all 96 remaining riders should
roll into Paris as a pack, with one rider sprinting to the finish.
</P>
<P>
   No one dares say that anything is for certain in the Tour de
France _ not after Greg LeMond came from almost a minute deficit to
win the race in 1989 on the final day. The difference was that that
was an individual time trial; Sunday's race is a flat road race.
</P>
<P>
   Frankie Andreau of Dearborn, Mich., knows it well. He's been
there six times before, and once missed the winning sprint by less
than a wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good race for everybody,'' he said of the frenzy that
takes place at the finish on the Champs Elysees. ``There's 30 guys
going for the win, there's 10 or 15 guys worrying about their
overall standing, and there's 80 guys who don't care what happens.
They're just waiting for the bell lap.''
</P>
<P>
   But be assured that after the past three weeks of racing results
mixed with drug news, everyone will be glad when the race is
finally over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-98 0133EDT &QL; 
