<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIGIBILITY OF PLAYERS REMAINS UNKNOWN  
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-NOTEBOOK-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Definitive word on the academic eligibility of several ASU
players and recruits may not be known until the start of Camp
Tontozona, Sun Devils Coach Bruce Snyder said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the process is complete and I have the paper work in
front of me, I don't believe anything,'' he said. ``The process
sometimes takes a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Two defensive starters _ safety Mitchell Freedman and linebacker
Larry Johnson _ are enrolled in junior colleges to regain
eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder also is awaiting paper work on several recruits. Two who
aren't expected to be eligible this season are Mesa Mountain View
offensive lineman Damien Niko and Tucson High offensive lineman
Ralph Zarate. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The White line &QL; 
 &QL; 
ASU Athletics Director Kevin White had no idea what was in store
when he decided recently to do his weekly radio show from Ireland,
where he was vacationing.
</P>
<P>
   As White was wrapping up on KMVP-AM (860), he hung up quickly.
No one was sure why.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, White was calling from a pub and another patron was
upset White was tying up the line. He kept bugging White while he
was on the air and finally threatened to throw some punches.
</P>
<P>
   White wisely hung up. &QL; 
 &QL; 
I need my space &QL; 
 &QL; 
On one of his first days at work, new basketball Coach Rob Evans
pulled into his ASU parking space. Or so he thought.
</P>
<P>
   Little did Evans know it actually belonged to Bruce Snyder, who
spotted an unfamiliar car in ``his'' space and decided to box in
the culprit.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Evans innocently asked another staff member if
the spot he parked in was OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh no,'' he was told. ``That belongs to our football coach.''
</P>
<P>
   A sheepish Evans explained his mistake to Snyder, who apologized
to Evans for boxing him in.
</P>
<P>
   The next day Snyder couldn't resist asking Evans if it was OK if
he took his parking space back. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Caught in the web &QL; 
 &QL; 
Wide receiver Lenzie Jackson was a popular guest recently on
Arizona Central's Web chat area. He fielded more than 70 questions
from fans (even his mom, Joyce Boyd, of Milpitas, Calif., made a
surprise appearance) and addressed ASU's prospects for the upcoming
season.
</P>
<P>
   Among the highlights:
</P>
<P>
   Question: What defensive back gives you the most trouble in
practice?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: None of them. (He laughs.) Probably Courtney Jackson
because he's fast and has really long arms. And he runs his mouth
the entire time.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's your favorite Tempe hangout?
</P>
<P>
   A: The library. (He laughs again.)
</P>
<P>
   Q: What player will be the biggest surprise this season?
</P>
<P>
   A: (Cornerback) J'Juan Cherry. He has a knack for the ball. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quick hits &QL; 
 &QL; 
``ESPN Magazine'' recently photographed J.R. Redmond for an
upcoming issue featuring college football's most exciting players.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Amey, one of ASU's starting defensive ends last season,
has been praised in Bay Area newspapers by Oakland Raiders Coach
Jon Gruden. The Raiders took Amey in the seventh round.
</P>
<P>
   Former safety Damien Richardson has been making an impression on
the Carolina Panthers and is projected to make the team and play in
nickel and dime packages. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
