<HEADLINE>
GREAT BARRINGTON SET FOR 20-DAY MEET 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ Great Barrington Race Course, having survived a
six-year hiatus and a tornado, conducted a successful 12-day
meeting last year and returns Friday with a 20-date meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Idle since 1991, the fairgrounds was struck by a tornado in 1995
that leveled everything in its wake, including the track's
grandstand. The track was restored at a cost of $3 million and now
even features a Terrace Club, complete with dining tables. ``Last
year, we were overwhelmed by the response of the fans and the
community,'' said Patty Nee, Great Barrington vice president.
``They know we are committed to restoring racing as a tradition in
Western Massachusetts. We are ready to go and excited to offer
eight additional days.''
</P>
<P>
   Great Barrington will race on a four-day schedule of Fridays
through Mondays, running Friday through Aug. 10, Aug. 14-17, and
Aug. 21-24. There will then be a break to allow Northampton Fair,
which has traditionally run on Labor Day, to conduct its 10-date
meeting over 12 days, Aug. 27-Sept. 7. Racing at Great Barrington
will return Sept. 11-14 and Sept. 18-21. Post time on Fridays and
Mondays will be 3 p.m.; post on Saturdays and Sundays will be 1:30.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Abbey, who works at Hialeah, will return as racing
secretary, and Frank Mirahmadi will be back as track announcer.
``We expect more horses than last year and we should be able to
offer the fans competitive races with good fields of well-matched
horses,'' said Abbey, who indicated the track would be open for
training beginning Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Admission will be free on opening day and $2 thereafter. For you
collectors, there will be a T-shirt giveaway Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The $1 million Haskell Invitational, to be run Aug. 9 at
Monmouth Park, is a handicap, which is unusual for races restricted
to 3-year-olds. Real Quiet, winner of the Kentucky Derby and
Preakness, was assigned high weight of 126 pounds, while Victory
Gallop, the victor in the Belmont Stakes, was given 125. Coronado's
Quest, who is on a three-race winning streak, including the Dwyer
at Belmont July 12, was assigned 124.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet worked 6 furlongs in 1:124/5 at Del Mar July 25.
Asked why Real Quiet was held out of the Swaps Stakes at Hollywood,
trainer  &UR; Bob Baffert  &LR; replied: ``He was a little funky in his hind
end, but he's over it. We're starting to lean on him now. He's
great. He's all set for the Haskell.''
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gallop zipped 6 panels in 1:113/5 at Churchill Downs
July 22, the best move at that distance that day. ``He's doing
great,'' said trainer  &UR; Elliott Walden &LR; . ``He started out about 10
lengths behind two other horses and beat them by about 15 lengths.
The next-fastest 6 furlongs work was in 1:15. It was an awful good
work for him.'' After being shipped to Saratoga, Victory Gallop
authored another bullet work, going 5 furlongs in :593/5 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Coronado's Quest, who worked a half in :484/5 July 21
at Belmont, is ready to go after zipping three-eighths in :371/5 on
the Saratoga training track Tuesday. ``He came out of the Dwyer
good,'' said trainer  &UR; Shug McGaughey &LR; . ``We'll bring him down to
Monmouth the Wednesday before the Haskell and school him in the
paddock one day. We want to get him in there and get him settled.''
</P>
<P>
   Jockey  &UR; Gary Stevens &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who rides first call for Baffert, had an
option but he chose to stay on Victory Gallop for the Haskell,
while  &UR; Kent Desormeaux  &LR; will ride Real Quiet, as he did throughout
the Triple Crown. As of now, there are only four horses committed
to the Haskell, including Arctic Sweep, most recently third in the
Long Branch.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gentlemen, who ran third to Skip Away in the Hollywood Gold Cup
June 28, is working extremely well toward defending his
championship in the $1 million Pacific Classic Aug. 15. Gentlemen
went 6 furlongs in 1:104/5 at Del Mar July 24, a brilliant move
accomplished under rider  &UR; Corey Nakatani &LR; . ``He went real nice,''
said trainer  &UR; Richard Mandella &LR; . ``He galloped out 7 furlongs in
1:23, and looks like he's in very good shape.'' ... Skip Away, who
will compete next in the $500,000 Iselin Handicap at Monmouth Aug.
30, is also doing well. The big gray, winner of seven in a row,
sizzled 5 furlongs in :591/5 under  &UR; Jerry Bailey  &LR; at Belmont July
26, the best workout of the day. ``He went very easy,'' said
trainer  &UR; Sonny Hine &LR; . ``That was about as slow as Jerry could hold
him. The big thing about the trip to California was fatigue. I
think he's pretty much over all that.'' ...  &UR; Laffit Pincay
 &LR; suffered a broken collarbone and several cracked ribs in a spill
at Del Mar July 25. Pincay's mount in the 10th race, Sid the
Author, was caught in tight quarters heading into the first turn
and fell. The horse was unhurt. Pincay, 51, will be out of action
for as many as seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Breeders' Cup has restored the order of races to the
original format and will lead off with the $1 million Juvenile and
the $1 million Juvenile Fillies for the 15th running, Nov. 7 at
Churchill. The two races for 2-year-olds will be followed by the $1
million Sprint, the $1 million Mile on the grass, the Distaff,
which has been raised to a purse of $2 million, the $2 million
Turf, and the $4 million Classic. This was the order when the
Breeders' Cup began in 1984 but, in subsequent years, the Juvenile
Fillies was made the first race, followed by the Sprint, the
Distaff, the Mile, and the Juvenile. Only the Turf and Classic have
remained unchanged. ``With its increased stature and a $2 million
purse, we feel the Distaff should be placed after the $1 million
races have been run,'' said  &UR; D.G. Van Clief &LR; , &UR;  &LR; president of the
Breeders' Cup. ``We also believe that returning 2-year-old races to
the beginning of the program provides a better progression of
events for the day.'' ... Sharp Cat, injured while galloping in a
walkover in the Bayakoa Handicap at Hollywood Dec. 7, made an
impressive 1998 debut by winning Del Mar's version of the Bayakoa
Handicap by more than 5 lengths July 27. Previously trained by  &UR; D.
Wayne Lukas &LR; , &UR;  &LR; Sharp Cat is now in the hands of  &UR; Wally
Dollase &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and she won with speed to spare under Nakatani, running
a mile in 1:35 at odds of 4-5 ($3.60 to win).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
