<HEADLINE>
OWNERS IN TEXAS OPEN FAT WALLETS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If it seemed like there were more last-minute trades this year
than in others, it's because there were.
</P>
<P>
   There is still one more trading deadline, Aug. 31, but in order
to make a deal and have a player eligible for your postseason
roster, all the players involved must have cleared waivers, which
is becoming increasingly difficult.
</P>
<P>
   That's the reason for the flurry of trades on Friday. Clubs were
making their last-gasp efforts to bolster themselves while they
could. Of all the trades made, the two clubs that reside in Texas
did the best job. The owners of the Houston Astros (Drayton McLane)
and Texas Rangers (Tom Hicks) displayed that each is willing to dig
deep into his pocket to fortify his club.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros landed the biggest fish when they acquired Randy
Johnson, who last season won 20 games and has a Cy Young Award on
his resume. With Johnson, the Astros now can enter the playoffs
with three solid starters.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Reynolds and Mike Hampton can now drop to No. 2 and 3 in
the rotation, where they probably belong anyway, and let Johnson
take the heat of facing the toughest pitcher on the team the Astros
meet in the first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   It's also the kind of move that probably cements the NL Central
crown for Houston. Only a miracle on Chicago's north side could
push the Cubs past Houston now.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Rangers probably made the kind of move that will
catapult them past Anaheim in the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   Getting Todd Stottlemyre, one of the best big-game pitchers
around these days, as well as shortstop Royce Clayton and third
baseman Todd Zeile strengthens the Rangers and plugs up their most
obvious holes, including having a No. 1 starter for the rest of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile will provide more punch in the middle of Texas' lineup,
and Clayton will definitely provide an upgrade at shortstop on
defense, where Kevin Elster is not quite the same as he was two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Another big winner on the last day of the intense trading season
was the New York Yankees, who decided not to mess with their
incredible chemistry and will go the rest of the way with what has
to be considered the best club in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees analyzed their situation and passed when it came
time to jump into the trading fray. It's the type of decision for
which first-year General Manager Brian Cashman should be applauded,
especially since he seems to have some influence over principal
owner George Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees could only have lost if they had made a splashy
move. By keeping this clubhouse intact, the message is simple: The
club's front office is impressed enough by what it has seen so far
to let this group go at it the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   A big high-five to the Yankees, Astros and Rangers; the big
winners in this season's trading frenzy. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The two NL wild cards? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New York Mets Manager Bobby Valentine predicted his ballclub
will claim the wild-card spot. In Los Angeles, interim General
Manager Tommy Lasorda guaranteed the Dodgers would lock up a
playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard there'll be two wild cards this year,'' San
Francisco Manager Dusty Baker said, tongue in cheek. ``Where does
that leave us and the rest of the teams?''
</P>
<P>
   Said Giants second baseman Jeff Kent, showing off his Berkley
education, ``Did Tommy say something stupid the other day?''
</P>
<P>
   Kent went on to add, ``If we don't make the playoffs, I'll be
eating dinner with Lasorda during the playoffs. I'll even buy the
guy dinner.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Kile file &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Kile just can't get it going in his first season with the
Colorado Rockies, who agreed to shell out $24 million over three
seasons for one of the most dominating pitchers in the game last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Kile enters his 25th start today in Chicago with a disappointing
7-13 record that includes a 5.62 ERA. Kile was the starting pitcher
in the Rockies 12-1 loss to Pittsburgh on Wednesday, a game in
which Kile, who had a deadly curveball last year, allowed nine
runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take notice on the bench,'' Rockies manager Don Baylor. ``A
lot of the hits are off his fastball, not his breaking ball. I
don't know if the word is around the league to lay off the
curveball and sit on the fastball, but a lot of guys are sitting on
the fastball and hitting it.''
</P>
<P>
   And Kile's problems have not been limited to his starts at
hitter-friendly Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an excuse,'' Kile said of Coors Field. ``You still
have to pitch. You make good pitches and do things you have to do,
and you will be fine.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bobby Bo troubles &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Bonilla and the Los Angeles Dodgers seem to be at odds
about what to do with him for the remainder of the season. It seems
Bonilla wants to go home and rest and the Dodgers want him back in
the lineup, presumably so they can attempt to trade him.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers interim GM Lasorda would love to trade Bonilla to
anyone. Of course, Bonilla, who is owed $11.8 million the next two
seasons, is not necessarily someone many clubs are clamoring for.
</P>
<P>
   The only reason Florida was able to dump Bonilla was after
packaging him with catcher Charles Johnson and Gary Sheffield as a
take-it-or-leave-it proposition. But Bonilla, on the disabled list
since July 15, insists he cannot play because of his still-healing
left wrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I'm feeling right now, I can't do what I've proven I'm
capable of doing,'' said Bonilla, 35. ``Ideally, I could just go
home now and start to rehab for next season. That way, I could just
let it start to get better, which would be better for both parties.
They knew I had surgery in December, and they knew what they were
getting when they traded for me.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which came as news to Lasorda.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't said anything to me,'' Lasorda said. ``If Bobby Bo
tells me his arm is bothering him, you think I'm going to ask him
to play? I watched him take batting practice, and he was hitting
them into the upper deck (in Philadelphia). He seemed like he was
swinging the bat real well to me.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
