<HEADLINE>
GILKEY JUMPS RIGHT INTO AC TION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ It certainly wasn't the most productive game of
Bernard Gilkey's career, but he'll take it, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Gilkey, acquired in a trade with the New York Mets on Friday,
arrived here Saturday afternoon in time to put on his Diamondbacks
uniform (he tried several pairs of pants before finding comfortable
ones) and start in left field.
</P>
<P>
   He was hitless in four at-bats, grounding into a double play and
striking out. The strikeout pitch turned out to be a passed ball in
the eighth inning as Danny Klassen scored what proved to be the
winning run and Gilkey reached first in Arizona's 5-4 victory at
Milwaukee County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Gilkey did manage to come up with a big defensive play, moving
in quickly and making a diving catch of a soft liner by Marquis
Grissom to lead off the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Of his busy day, Gilkey said, ``I didn't want to wait (to play).
I wanted to get back into the flow as quickly as possible. I just
couldn't get that string going (offensively) with the Mets. I
figure I'll get some playing time here.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Gilkey remains in left field will play itself out in the
coming days. If he does stay there, it likely would cut playing
time for rookie David Dellucci, who has started most of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Dellucci could move to right, as he did Saturday night, but
Karim Garcia and Yamil Benitez also figure into the mix. Gilkey
also could move to right, leaving Dellucci in left. &QL;  &QL; 
A new life &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Klassen always thought he'd eventually play for the Brewers at
County Stadium or the new Miller Park, but all of that ended when
the team left him unprotected in the expansion draft and he was
chosen by the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers liked Klassen, even though he was error-prone as a
shortstop at Double-A El Paso in 1997 and never reached Triple-A.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have liked to have come here, but they made their
decision and I'm happy where I am,'' said Klassen, who since has
moved to second base and hit a booming RBI triple on Friday night
in the first of the three-game weekend series. &QL;  &QL; 
Short stops &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another Diamondbacks player with Brewers or Wisconsin ties is
catcher Damian Miller, who grew up near LaCrosse, in the western
part of the state along the Mississippi River. Miller had family
members in attendance on Friday night and a busload of people from
the area showed up Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Matt Williams played another game with Triple-A
Tucson on Saturday night as part of his rehabilitation assignment.
He likely will be activated from the disabled list on Monday in
time for the first of a three-game series with the Cubs at Wrigley
Field.
</P>
<P>
   A trade on Thursday by the Diamondbacks slipped through the
cracks: journeyman infielder-outfielder Hensley Meulens was sent to
the Chicago White Sox for a player to be named later. Meulens was
playing for Tucson, but had been with the big club briefly. &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
