<HEADLINE>
SEIGLER STEALS SHOW WITH 2 INTERCEPTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF _ At 5 feet 9 and 178 pounds, Dexter Seigler was the
biggest man on the field Saturday in the Cardinals intrasquad
scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   But who is Dexter Seigler?
</P>
<P>
   Fans who've frequented workouts during training camp already
knew that the newcomer to the secondary has a knack for making
plays. He's been no stranger to picking off passes in daily
two-a-day drills.
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's controlled scrimmage, the coaches' first look at
the team in live action, Seigler twice picked off second-string
quarterback Stoney Case, taking the first interception back 60
yards for the only touchdown of the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   After Case moved the second offense into scoring range on the
next drive, Seigler intercepted him at the 4 and ran it back 35
yards. His 95 yards on the two returns covered nearly as much
ground as the first and second offenses combined in a session
dominated by the defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals rushed for only 48 yards (a 2.8-yard average),
including 12 yards in five tries by Adrian Murrell, the new starter
at running back. Quarterback Jake Plummer was the victim of shaky
protection and completed 3 of 5 passes for 20 yards in the face of
a strong rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still kind of learning the defense,'' Seigler said. ``I
still have some rough edges that I have to fine tune.''
</P>
<P>
   For Seigler, who signed in June as a free agent, this might be
his last chance to make it. He has kicked around, from Toronto of
the Canadian Football League to three seasons with the Seattle
Seahawks to Amsterdam of NFL Europe this past spring. His three
interceptions led a league-leading defense and earned Seigler NFL
Europe Comeback player honor.
</P>
<P>
   With injuries to cornerbacks Tom Knight (shoulder), J.J.
McCleskey (thigh), and Ty Howard (hamstring), Seigler got his
chance Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know much about him before we signed him, but he made
the most of an opportunity, and that's what you look for,''
Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin said. ``He certainly covered those two
throws well. The rest, I don't know about.''
</P>
<P>
   Seigler acknowledged that he goofed on another play, a quick
pass from Case to Fred Brock. Seigler went for the interception,
missed, and Brock went 23 yards after making the catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that Dexter's been in the league a couple of years,
he's not in awe,'' said Larry Marmie, coach of the Cardinals
secondary. ``He's got some experience. Now he's getting a feel for
our system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of small cornerbacks here, although it's not
necessarily by design. Sometimes the bigger guys don't move their
feet and change direction as well. We play a fair amount of
man-to-man, so we're looking for guys who can move and stay with a
wide-out.''
</P>
<P>
   Injuries kept 14 players from dressing for the scrimmage, which
was attended by an estimated 7,000 at Walkup Skydome.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the first offense, which was nearly intact, could not move
against the decimated first defense, getting only a 24-yard field
goal from Joe Nedney in three series.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Dave Brown completed 5 of 7 passes for 31 yards with
the third offense. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-98 0141EDT &QL; 
