<HEADLINE>
RICE SAYS HE'S BREATHING EASIER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF _ Cardinals defensive end Simeon Rice felt so much
better Saturday, he asked team doctor Wayne Kuhl if he could
participate in the scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   Kuhl, treating Rice for asthmatic bronchitis, turned down Rice's
request, but not before pronouncing him ``90 percent improved.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice, who has been out since Wednesday, said he would be back at
practice Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get out there today,'' Rice said after the
scrimmage. ``I don't want to waste time (watching). For the most
part, I was having a real good camp. I'm regaining my weight. I'm
getting my breath back. But since I've been young I've had a
(breathing) problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Denying a rift &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rice said he was aware of a Phoenix radio report that defensive
tackle Eric Swann walked out of Friday morning's workout because he
was upset that Rice didn't practice.
</P>
<P>
   Rice said there was no problem between him and Swann, who had
words with Coach Vince Tobin before storming out of practice in
street clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's cool,'' Rice said of Swann. ``We've always been cool.
It's official with me. I don't sense there is anything (wrong).'' &QL;  &QL; 
Knight examined &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Team orthopedist Russell Chick examined starting cornerback
Tommy Knight's sprained left shoulder Saturday and thinks it is
healing.
</P>
<P>
   But he still wants Knight to have a magnetic resonance imaging
examination Monday in the Valley to make sure he did not damage any
ligaments.
</P>
<P>
   Chick said if it's just a slight sprain, Knight will
rehabilitate the injury for a few days and then be listed as
day-to-day. But he said that significant ligament damage to the
shoulder could put Knight out for the year. &QL;  &QL; 
Gutsy performance &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The long catch of the scrimmage was a 23-yarder by wide receiver
Fred Brock, who continues to play despite suffering fractured
finger in his left hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The doctor) wanted to put a pin in, but he wouldn't let
him,'' receivers coach Vic Rapp said. ``He knows he's got a chance
to make this team and won't come out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   Brock said the finger is painful, especially when he is
blocking, but that a pin would ``keep me out too long.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Short shots &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Second-year outside linebacker Tony McCombs, bidding for a
starting job, led the team with six tackles.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Player was impressive on both of his punts, averaging 46.5
yards. Rookie Marcus Williams, the Arizona State and Tempe
McClintock High School product, had one punt for 38 yards. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
