<SLUG> BC-FBN-SCHOENFELD-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLUMMER'S PLUMP PAYDAY WILL COME AT END OF SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cardinals quarterback Jake Plummer is about six months away from
hitting the jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals will tear up the third year of his $1.6 million
rookie contract and make him the wealthiest starting quarterback in
their 100-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're completely confident that when the time comes, the
Cardinals will take care of Jake Plummer,'' said his agent, Leigh
Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   Taking care of Plummer probably means paying him $5 million a
year, as long as he has the type of season the Cardinals are
expecting.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Johnson, in his first year in Buffalo, recently signed a
five-year, $25 million deal that included a team-record $8.5
million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Leaf, the second pick overall, signed a six-year deal with
San Diego last week that could pay him as much as $31 million, or
$5 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Both Johnson and Leaf are Steinberg clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new salary of $5 million a season is going to be the going
rate for (starting) quarterbacks without a lot of experience,''
Steinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Peyton Manning, the top pick overall, got more. He signed a
six-year deal with Indianpolis on Wednesday that was reported as
$48 million, but, in reality, is worth $38 million, or $6.3 million
a year. He'll have to hit a bunch of incentives that are going to
be hard to earn to get the total deal to $48 million.
</P>
<P>
   At a salary of $302,000 this season, Plummer is grossly
underpaid for a starting quarterback. But he is only in his second
year _ his first as a full-time starter _ and still is on his
original contract.
</P>
<P>
   He's not complaining about his salary. In fact, he said he isn't
thinking about it. But he paid close attention to the deals Leaf
and Manning signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no interest in raising the issue this year,''
Steinberg said. ``Jake is concentrating on playing and only
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have known for some time they will have to pay
Plummer the going rate. They have gotten by cheaply at that
position for most of this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's starter, Kent Graham, made $650,000. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Surprise guest &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Bill Walsh is chosen to replace Carmen Policy as president of
the 49ers, as expected, one of his first decisions could be what to
do about second-year quarterback Jim Druckenmiller.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers chose Druckenmiller over Plummer in the first round of
the 1997 draft over Walsh's objections.
</P>
<P>
   Druckenmiller has struggled again this summer at training camp,
showing little touch or ability to grasp the team's complicated
``West Coast'' offense.
</P>
<P>
   (He's the same guy who missed the team charter to New Orleans
last year when he went to the international terminal). The biggest
stir he created with the team this summer was when his girlfriend,
Julie Cialini, the 1995 Playboy Playmate of the Year, showed up on
the sidelines at training camp in short-shorts.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh and George Seifert, the 49ers' last two coaches, wouldn't
have been impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wouldn't even be in town if they were coaching,'' a 49ers
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Background check &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another former Playboy Playmate, Holly Hart, Miss April, is the
new girlfriend of Cincinnati Bengals wide receiver James Hundon.
</P>
<P>
   Hundon was introduced to Hart by a mutual friend in May.
</P>
<P>
   On their first date, Hart asked him if he knew who she was. He
didn't, so Hart showed him some pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost crashed (the car),'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pain in the back &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former Cardinals middle linebacker Eric Hill has been bothered
by a bad back for most of the St. Louis Rams' training camp.
</P>
<P>
   He first suffered the injury lifting weights in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think rest is probably the only solution,'' Hill said.
``We've taken all kinds of tests but haven't found anything
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Rams Coach Dick Vermeil is not happy that several times during
camp, Hill has practiced in the morning but sat out the afternoon
session.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't bring him here to watch,'' said Vermeil, who signed
Hill to a two-year, $5.25 million deal in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Name that team &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are two of the names that won't be picked when the
Tennessee Oilers get a new nickname next season: the (Tennes) See
to Shining Sea and the Tennessee Tuxedoes.
</P>
<P>
   Some real possibilities are the Tennessee Smokies (after the
Smokey Mountains), the Tennessee Authority (after the Tennessee
Valley Authority), the Tennessee Rebels, the Tennessee Twisters,
the Tennessee Tornadoes and the Tennessee Thunder.
</P>
<P>
   Short shots &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Oakland Raiders dumped defensive end Shannon Clavelle 20
hours after they signed him last Saturday. They didn't realize he
had been arrested in Stillwater, Okla., earlier in the week on
charges of being a prowler. When he was booked, Stillwater police
discovered he was a fugitive from justice in Colorado and one in
Missouri on various charges ranging from felony fraud to writing
bad checks.
</P>
<P>
   During the past two seasons, Rams quarterback Tony Banks has
been sacked 91 times, more than any NFL quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay Packers officials are running out of patience with gay
basher Reggie White, their All-Pro defensive lineman. Team
President Bob Harlan apologized to a national gay and lesbian
political group last week. General Manager Ron Wolf said, ``I
believe everyone is entitled to their opinion, but sometimes it's
time to shut your mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Includes information from other media sources. Steve Schoenfeld
can be reached at steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
