<HEADLINE>
IT'S NO JOKE, JARRETT RUNS OUT OF GAS  
 CREW'S `GREEDY' CHOICE COSTS EARLY LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ An unhappy Dale Jarrett hurriedly vacated
Indianapolis Motor Speedway on Saturday after a discouraging finish
in the Brickyard 400.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett had little to say and even less time to say it. Home
beckoned, and it's a long way to North Carolina from a discouraging
16th-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran out of gas,'' Jarrett said. ``I had a great race car.
That's all I've got to say. What else do you want to know? I drive
the race car. I come in when they tell me. That's all I do.''
</P>
<P>
   End of story. Adios, Dale.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad, because for a time, it was Jarrett, not winner Jeff
Gordon, who appeared to be the driver to beat.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett was strong early, grabbing the lead for the first and
only time on Lap 54, zipping by a startled Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett proceeded to lead the next 27 laps, but in the team's
attempt to hold the lead at the Lap 80 midway point, the
disgruntled driver ran out of fuel between Turns 1 and 2 on Lap 81.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett managed to coast to pit road, coming to a stop near the
entrance. But he was a long way from his stall, and by the time his
crew could retrieve him, he lost four precious laps to the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Several caution flags allowed Jarrett to regain the lost laps as
he continually outran Gordon on restarts.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after a caution flag on Lap 118, Jarrett was back on
the lead lap, 33 positions behind Gordon. Although Jarrett made up
18 laps, it was a case of too little, too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stupid,'' said Steve Allen, a member of Jarrett's crew. ``We
figured we'd go to Lap 79, then tried to get the halfway money
($10,000) for leading. We tried to get a little greedy. But we felt
confident we could do it or we wouldn't have tried.''
</P>
<P>
   Team owner Robert Yates, whose other driver, rookie Kenny Irwin
Jr., crashed while running fourth on Lap 117, wasn't blaming anyone
for the apparent miscalculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've (the team) won a lot of races and I'm sure they're
kicking themselves a hell of a lot more than I'm going to kick them
Monday morning,'' Yates said. ``I'm not going to kick them at all.
I'm going to pat them on the back and try to see what they need for
next time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gordon has been so strong, but we know we can beat him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has finishes of fifth or better in 10 of the past 11
races, including four wins. But he admitted the script might have
had a different closing chapter had Jarrett not fallen so far
behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so hard to pass anybody,'' Gordon said. ``Dale Jarrett
was the only car I really saw that could pass anybody that was
close to his own speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I came up on somebody, I either had to be faster
than them or I'd get stuck behind them.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
