<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON TRADE IS STRIKE THREE ON SAD DAY FOR MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The night had the lose-lose-lose feel of those Mariner
seasons of the '80s at the Kingdome _ only lots more people and no
Steve Trout.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Friday, the Mariners lost the longest game in Kingdome
history, a 9-8 series-sweeping, soul-crusher to the Cleveland
Indians. They left 20 men on base over 17 innings. Two more and
they could played the Seahawks here next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   In the evening, they had to face the New York Yankees, a team so
powerful they have applied for a seat on United Nations Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
   But most significantly, they had a lose-lose situation with
Randy Johnson and the trading deadline. As the excruciating hours
dwindled down, the silence that enveloped the franchise seemed to
signal that the club had no shot at doing anything that would be
perceived as a win.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't going to get full value for one of the most
dominating pitchers in the game. And if he were not traded,
management would perpetuate the stink that has hung over this club
since Opening Day, as well as create the impression the aroma will
continue once Johnson leaves as a free agent after the season with
nothing in return.
</P>
<P>
   So after nine months of holding Johnson, the club and its fans
hostage to its aimlessness, management finally ended the saga _ but
not the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   They traded the biggest Unit to the Houston Astros for two
diminutive units _ a minor league pitcher and a minor league
infielder, each of whom are known primarily by their mothers, a few
scouts and a couple of Houston barbecue joints.
</P>
<P>
   Also included is a player to be named. If it is Jeff Bagwell,
management is off the hook. Since it won't be, the Mariners have
kissed off the 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   While hardly an unusual move in baseball, the abandonment of the
race at the trading deadline is the first here since people started
caring about the team. For those new to the ritual, it requires:
</P>
<P>
   1) overripe vegetable matter;
</P>
<P>
   2) an arm better than the pitcher who will replace Johnson;
</P>
<P>
   3) grocery-sack headgear;
</P>
<P>
   4) new-found passion for Seahawk exhibition games.
</P>
<P>
   Not since Tim Floyd showed up to coach the Chicago Bulls has
there been a sporting constituency left with such a flim-flammed
feeling.
</P>
<P>
   A week full of rumors of veteran, immediate help fueled
expectations that the Mariners will come out of this self-made
ordeal almost whole, particularly since the Yankees were indeed
ready to deal Hideki Irabu.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mariner price _ Irabu and third-base prospect Mike
Lowell _ proved too steep even for the loaded Yankees, because
there was no guarantee Johnson would sign with them after the
season. They bailed out early in the evening, as did apparently
every other team offering major leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   So in the short term, the Mariners ended up with the worst of
all possible arrangements _ no Johnson and no immediate help.
</P>
<P>
   The desperation of July was a direct descendant of last winter's
decision to stand pat. The flawed decision was a surprising tactic,
given that they had won just one playoff game in the previous two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The longer term is, of course, unknowable. Management is
counting on the good grace of its fan base to wait on 21-year-old
Freddy Garcia and 22-year-old Carlos Guillen. But the credibility
was already strained in the first moments when the club's press
release identified the players as ``Freddy Garcia and Carlos
Garcia.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the player to be named is another Garcia _ Jerry. At
least he used to play a little third bass.
</P>
<P>
   The good grace of its fan base was already stretched thin,
because knowledgable fans understand that Garcia and Guillen are
replacing prospects from earlier seasons squandered on trades for
veterans in failed attempts to reach the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Mariner manager Lou Piniella admitted as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure we tried to get players who fit here immediately,''
he said. ``Obviously it didn't work out. We gave up young prospects
to enhance our situation before. Houston is doing the same thing
right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, they'll fill up our basket.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Mariner fans, hope is for spring. The July
trading deadline is for pennant races for teams with $53 million
payrolls full of veteran All-Stars who have expensive seats in a
new stadium to sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' said disgusted first baseman David Segui, ``just makes
our job a lot more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Segui couldn't much stand Johnson, he knew the
brooding giant was important for any late-season rally. But now
he's gone and unreplaced. The void will scream until the end of the
season, and probably beyond _ until the Big Unit quits recording
double-digit K's.
</P>
<P>
   The Kingdome scoreboard periodically replays big moments from
the crackling 1995 season, making Friday night's developments all
the more poignant. The one moment that will never be replayed
remains the most vivid in at least one memory.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth inning of the final game of the Division Series
against the Yankees, the Mariners called upon Johnson to pitch in
relief. His languid stroll in from the bullpen as 60,000 fans stood
screaming and the Yanks sat squirming remains the ultimate
gunslinger moment in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   He went three innings and won the game, the Mariners won the
series as well as the hearts of millions of fans, not to mention a
new ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Unit took another long walk Friday, once again changing
Seattle baseball forever.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-98 1207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
