<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-02 12:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4214 &Cx1f; tth-z
U S &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      08-02 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON TRADE LEGACY: HOUSTON, WE HAVE A RIPOFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ He pitched the Mariners' first no-hitter. Then he won
a Cy Young Award. He pitched 19-strikeout games. Two of them last
season.
</P>
<P>
   And, most important, he pitched the Mariners into the postseason
for the first time in their history.
</P>
<P>
   On Randy Johnson's shoulders, 18 years of Mariner futility were
all but washed away.
</P>
<P>
   That is why, on the night the greatest pitcher the Mariners have
ever had was discarded like some used part, it feels a lot like all
those seasons before 1995: a major letdown.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a bright spot in Mariner history.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson deserved better. At least he deserved a better
ending in Seattle _ a city he helped turn into a baseball town.
</P>
<P>
   And when that new ballpark opens next July, the absence of
Johnson on the mound will be all the more painful.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was traded Friday night to the Astros for two minor
leaguers and a player to be named later. Fine, let's hope the kids
turn out to be good.
</P>
<P>
   But to trade away a star, a commodity, a unique talent like
Johnson, the Mariners should have played the public relations game
better.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson deserved better than what he got. So did Mariner fans.
</P>
<P>
   Mariner ownership must now be shamed for perpetrating one of a
most flawed and embarrassing moves of a front-line, big-time star
player ever.
</P>
<P>
   They said it was bad when Tom Seaver was traded out of New York,
that Seaver cried in the clubhouse, trying to read a farewell
statement to Mets fans.
</P>
<P>
   It was bad in Boston when Roger Clemens' last season was filled
with bitterness, and worse for Red Sox fans the next season when
Clemens won the Cy Young Award with Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The baseball road is littered with franchise pitchers who were
turned loose. Everyone knows the baseball business is harsh, mostly
because it is a business.
</P>
<P>
   But somehow, this one is worse, because the Mariners squandered
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The legacy of this too-little, too-late deal will be all about
what the Mariners did not get for Johnson. No matter how much spin
the Mariners put on these two young Astro prospects, Freddy Garcia
and Carlos Guillen, remember that the Mariners could have gotten
more.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson spent the last eight months agonizing over why the
Mariners did not offer him a contract extension. He felt he
deserved at least an offer.
</P>
<P>
   But from the moment last November they said Johnson would not
finish his career here, the Mariners botched this thing.
</P>
<P>
   And then they made it worse, time and time again.
</P>
<P>
   No deals in winter. No deals in spring. No deal in May, when the
Dodgers were ready to send starting pitcher Ismael Valdes and
infielder Wilton Guerrero as payment.
</P>
<P>
   Never forget that, Mariner fans. The stunned players in the
clubhouse after Friday's game sure looked as if they would not
forget. Not Alex Rodriguez, who knew that last winter, the Yankees
offered David Wells and Mariano Rivera to the M's for Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   We would like to believe it never should have come to this, but
in reality, the moment that the Mariners and Johnson would part
company was predictable.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the Mariners should have crafted a better strategy.
They should have been clearer, stronger in finishing off the
business of getting value for one of the game's best pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, the day after four-time Cy Young Award-winner Greg
Maddux signed his contract extension with Atlanta, Johnson sat in
the Mariner clubhouse and talked.
</P>
<P>
   The subject was his future.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about Maddux's new deal, Johnson said the $11.5
million-a-year contract was great for Maddux. And then Johnson
smiled slyly, knowing that $11.5 million suddenly represented a new
benchmark, possibly for himself, too.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever took place between Mariner president Chuck Armstrong
and Johnson's agent, we may never know. The Mariners said Johnson's
agent wanted too much money. They made a decision they would not
pay.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Mariner fans would have accepted that. Maybe they would
have understood the economics of that. But by their long, drawn-out
indecision, the Mariners were responsible for Randy Johnson's last
days here being so unbearable _ for him, for his club, for the
fans. Now there is nothing but emptiness and regret to be felt over
the loss of the best pitcher the Mariners ever had.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
