<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of Monday, Aug. 3:
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Coded e)
</P>
<P>
   GUGGENHEIM-HOGS (New York) _ ``The Art of the Motorcycle'' is an
exhibition quite different from anything else that Museum Mile on
Fifth Avenue has ever experienced. Bathed in biker glory, it has
become the most highly attended exhibition in the Guggenheim's
61-year history, far outstripping retrospectives of Roy
Lichtenstein and Ellsworth Kelly, and more popular than
authoritative surveys of Chinese, Russian and Italian art. By Carol
Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   VANGOGH-FAKES (Undated) _ For more than a year, art historians
have been arguing over the authenticity of ``Sunflowers,'' and,
less vehemently, over dozens of other van Gogh paintings. Now,
although an article published in March has quelled, but not
completely dispelled, the questions about ``Sunflowers,'' the issue
of the authenticity of many van Gogh works is moving into a new
stage, out of scholarly journals and into the public arena. Some
museums have taken questioned paintings down from their walls for
further study, while others are organizing exhibitions around the
controversy or counting on it to add sizzle to shows with a broader
rationale. By Judith H. Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
   OPENMINDED-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Christopher Lehmann-Haupt
reviews ``Open Minded'' by Jonathan Lear.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded f)
</P>
<P>
   JEWS-PHILANTHROPY (Undated) _ Once the envy of fundraisers of
all faiths, the United Jewish Appeal and the Council of Jewish
Federations were the unrivaled powerhouses of Jewish philanthropy.
But just as Jews have become sharply divided over the most basic
questions of Jewish identity, these groups _ which still raise well
over $1 billion each year _ are struggling to persuade a new
generation that they are as relevant today as they were during the
Holocaust or in helping to create the state of Israel. Attempting
to address the criticism that they are out of touch with modern
Jewish life, the two organizations have reached an agreement in
principal to join forces to create a new national organization that
better reflects the changing priorities of the Jewish world.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-AIRCONDITIONING (Rome) _ While America rushed to cool its
air, Europe traditionally just took summer afternoons off. Stores
in Italy shut for the noonday heat, and Spaniards took siestas. In
the evening, Europe sat outside in the piazza. In the hottest
weeks, it simply shut down, and to this day August remains a dead
month in much of Europe. But the piazza has become polluted by
exhaust fumes, and the pressures of a global economy are
increasingly forcing Europeans to work summers. So Europeans are
belatedly embracing air-conditioning. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   APPLE-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ Apple Computer's ``Think
Different'' campaign with black-and-white portraits of past
renegades has left many people thinking thoughts, like ``Who the
heck is that?'' By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-INTERNET (Hong Kong) _ The Chinese government is using
Hong Kong as its window onto the World Wide Web _ much as it uses
Hong Kong as its window onto the global economy. One big player is
headed by the entrepreneur Peter Yip, whose effort is backed by the
Chinese news agency Xinhua and the Ministry of Communications.
Another is Chinabig, an Internet service backed by China Unicom,
the second telecom player in the country. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   UTILITIES-INTERNET (Undated) _ The electric utilities industry
is getting active in the Internet transport business. By Matt
Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-INTERNET (Undated) _ A follow-up on the Internet tax
legislation. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   IBM-CHIPS (Undated) _ IBM is set to announce a new chip-making
process. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-SUIT (Undated) _ A court filing by the Justice
Department makes clear what big witnesses it intends to call in the
Microsoft case _ including Bill Gates. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   DIGICOM-COLUMN (Undated) _ The Digital Commerce column; details
TK. By Denise Caruso.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-CALENDAR (Undated) _ Key government figures this week.
</P>
<P>
   BOND-CALENDAR (Undated) _ The week's planned offerings.
</P>
<P>
   EQUITIES (Undated) _ Equity issues coming to market this week.
</P>
<P>
   DIVIDEND-MEETINGS (Undated) _ Major meetings this week.
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Major financial stories at a glance.
</P>
<P>
   PATENTS (Undated) _ The weekly patents column. By Teresa
Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   (Coding varies.)
</P>
<P>
   NBC-ONLINE-MEDIA (Santa Monica, Calif.) _ NBC will invest in and
supply programming to a startup online service that is providing
movies, television programs and music on demand to personal
computers. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   I-VILLAGE-MEDIA (Undated) _ Silicon Alley Web startup I-village
has been raising venture capital left and right since it started
three years ago; but the company's mission has changed several
times as the medium has grown. The focus is now on attracting women
users. The constant is Candice Carpenter, a veteran of old media
who attracted investors to the new with her enthusiasm for the
burgeoning Internet. A profile of Candice and a look at what
I-village _ and its investors _ are banking on. By Lisa Napoli.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS-MAG-MEDIA (Undated) _ A look at the prospects for U.S. News
&AMP; World Report under its new editor. By Robin Pogrebin.
</P>
