<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIANS THREATEN TO WITHDRAW FROM PEACE TALKS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The prospects for a new accord between Israel and
the Palestinians dimmed further Sunday as senior Palestinian
officials said they were prepared to pull out of peace talks unless
Israel showed a swift willingness to consider new ideas.
</P>
<P>
   A senior adviser to Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, said
that negotiations scheduled for Monday would be ``the last
meeting'' between the two sides unless Israel came up with a new
answer to an American-backed plan calling for it to withdraw from
an additional 13 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli government of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has
resisted that plan for months, while the Palestinians have publicly
accepted it. Even so, the new Palestinian warning injected a darker
air into sporadic negotiations between the two sides, which
Arafat's Cabinet declared on Saturday to have been ``a waste of
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Nabil Abu Rdainah, an Arafat adviser, said that a meeting
scheduled for Monday ``must be decisive'' and that if it was not,
the Palestinians were prepared to complain anew to the United
States ``about this Israeli intransigence.''
</P>
<P>
   Associates of Netanyahu have said they believe the two sides are
making progress in the talks and that it will soon become evident
whether an agreement can be reached.
</P>
<P>
   But the new Palestinian warning added more urgency to the
discussions, and it posed a fresh challenge to a rash of recent
indications from the Israeli side that a breakthrough might be near
in the talks, which have been deadlocked for the last 16 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't bring new ideas during tomorrow's meeting, it
will be the last,'' Abu Rdainah said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Israel has refused to accept the American-backed
plan, Arafat has until now been reluctant to break off talks
between the two sides. He is apparently not eager to be blamed for
a collapse in the negotiations, despite the lack of progress.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, however, Arafat has come under mounting pressure
from other leading Palestinians to call a halt to the discussions.
Officials of his political party, Fatah, have said such a
declaration would serve to convey that Israel-Palestinian relations
had reached a new point of crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Oslo peace accords between Israel and the
Palestinians, the Israelis were to have completed new troop
withdrawals from the West Bank more than a year ago, and their
refusal to do so has provoked friction not just with the
Palestinians, but also with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The details of the American-backed plan calling for the 13
percent withdrawal have never been made public. But U.S. officials
have made clear their deep frustration at the refusal of
Netanyahu's government to embrace it.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Indyk, the State Department official who oversees the
Middle East, said last week that the quest for a broader peace
between Israel and the Palestinians was ``only just'' alive and
that it faced ``a still uncertain future.''
</P>
<P>
   The sporadic talks between Israel and the Palestinians have
continued in recent days despite the recent rejection by Washington
of a Palestinian request for more vigorous American intervention to
unravel the impasse. Clinton administration officials have said it
is time instead for the two sides to demonstrate the good will
necessary to solve disputes, both now and in the future.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, the Israeli delegation has been led by Danny
Naveh, Netanyahu's Cabinet secretary, while the Palestinian side
has been led by Saeb Erekat, a top Palestinian negotiator. Israeli
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and the top Palestinian
negotiator, Mahmoud Abbas, held higher-level talks late last month,
but those discussions were suspended after they proved
inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
   Unless a breakthrough comes soon, the warning from Arafat's
aides seemed bound to put pressure on Washington either to
reconsider its standoffnishness or to brace for the prospect of
violent new protests in Palestinian-governed areas if the talks are
seen to have failed.
</P>
<P>
   In what has been a firm stand, Netanyahu has consistently
refused to cede any more than another 10 percent of the West Bank
to the Palestinians in the next phase of troop withdrawals, which
are more than a year overdue. For the last several weeks, his
negotiators have been floating a potential compromise.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal calls for what would amount to a 13 percent
withdrawal, but the disputed 3 percent would be set aside as a new
nature reserve in the Judean Desert east of Bethlehem, where
Palestinian building and settlement would be prohibited and where
Israel would maintain a security role.
</P>
<P>
   So far, that proposal has been rejected by Palestinian
negotiators, who have said they could endorse the idea only if the
nature reserve were entrusted to full Palestinian control.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
