<SLUG> BC-NEWS-MAG-MEDIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW EDITOR OF U.S. NEWS ENTERING DANGEROUS TERRITORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo and a graphic are being sent to NYT
photo/graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204, 1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Talk about tough beginnings.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Stephen Smith was struggling last week to find his
footing as editor of U.S. News &AMP; World Report, his predecessor,
James Fallows, was hashing out his severance agreement with the
magazine's owner, Mortimer Zuckerman, and fielding a 10-page memo
from the company's editorial director, Harold Evans, that disputed
Fallows' portrayal of his departure.
</P>
<P>
   At least nine staff members are on their way out or have already
left. Smith, 49, is walking into a job in which few editors have
lasted more than two years. Not to mention that Smith was not even
supposed to have started until the end of August. Instead, events
accelerated in late June because of a now-infamous 19-page memo in
which Fallows announced that he had been dismissed, and Smith found
himself starting at U.S. News from his office at National Journal.
</P>
<P>
   As The New York Post summed it up in the first line of a gossip
item on Page Six last month: ``Steve Smith is doomed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor Steve Smith,'' said one editor at U.S. News who, like
most of those interviewed, insisted on anonymity. ``Things were
delicate enough without Harry or whoever not letting this Fallows
thing die.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Smith said he was undeterred. ``This is a tough
time because I'm trying to learn 225 names, learn how the magazine
works, do some good journalism and stabilize a staff that's feeling
pretty roughed up right now,'' he said. ``Someone said to me when I
took this job that it would require someone as pigheaded as I am to
do it right, and I am absolutely determined to keep moving this
magazine forward and not keep looking over my shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith has some experience to fall back on. He spent a year and a
half as editor of National Journal, taking the weekly political
magazine through a substantial redesign. Before that, he spent a
year as the founding editor of Civilization, the magazine
affiliated with the Library of Congress. And he grew up around
newsweeklies, serving in several positions at Time magazine from
1978 to 1986, including nation editor, and as executive editor of
Newsweek from 1986 until he was dismissed in 1991 after being
passed over for the top job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely the person for the job over there because he
has a very clear idea of what he wants to do,'' said Evan Thomas,
an assistant managing editor at Newsweek, who worked with Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's extensive experience with newsweeklies may serve him
well, given that Zuckerman has said he wants to move the magazine
back to a more conventional news magazine format, emphasizing the
previous week's headlines.
</P>
<P>
   But some reporters and editors inside and outside U.S. News
insist that the magazine cannot compete on that ground; with fewer
resources, a smaller staff and earlier deadlines than Time and
Newsweek, they say, U.S. News needs to carve out its own distinct
role.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he would try to strike a balance between breaking
news stories, enterprise articles and the kind of ``News You Can
Use'' service pieces that have become the magazine's signature.
``You don't have to be a slave to the news,'' he said, ``but you
have to respect it.''
</P>
<P>
   But working for Zuckerman may require skills that would confound
any resume. In the 14 years that he has owned U.S. News, Zuckerman
has gone through five editors before Fallows. ``No editor who has
stood up to Mort has lasted here,'' one U.S. News editor said.
</P>
<P>
   Zuckerman has been similarly finicky at The Daily News of New
York _ which he also owns, along with The Atlantic Monthly and Fast
Company, a business magazine. The newspaper is on its fifth editor
in the five years that Zuckerman has owned it.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Zuckerman has enthusiastically supported Smith. ``I am
so thrilled about how effectively and quickly he has taken hold in
rather difficult circumstances,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To complicate matters, Evans has been added to this mercurial
mix since he left Random House last fall. While some people at
Zuckerman's publications have welcomed Evans' editorial oversight,
they also say that the Fallows situation showed him to be consumed
with appearing in control. After Fallows announced his dismissal in
June, Evans issued a memo to the staff emphasizing that it was he
who had determined Fallows' fate, not Zuckerman, as Fallows had
suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Then last week, Evans wrote a memo to Fallows, first reported in
The Washington Post, accusing the former editor of misrepresenting
his departure as having to do with journalistic differences rather
than more severance money.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, people at U.S. News say, Smith will have to contend
with editorial meddling by Zuckerman and Evans.
</P>
<P>
   Zuckerman has long been known for picking up the phone to weigh
in on a coming article minutes before deadline or to criticize an
editor about something already published.
</P>
<P>
   Now Evans has added another layer; he offered his 2 cents on the
U.S. News article about the departure of his wife, Tina Brown, from
The New Yorker _ saying, for example, that she has generated
profits at her publications and not just buzz. And he plans to run
a 10-part excerpt from his coming book, ``The American Century,''
in U.S. News this fall. Evans also recently told the staff that
anyone who spoke ill of the magazine _ publicly or privately _
would be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said such potential interference did not make him nervous.
``Probably the most meddlesome owner in the 20th century was Henry
Luce,'' he said, referring to the founding editor of Time magazine.
``I've worked at a lot of places, and owners and publishers are
usually engaged to one extent or another with their publications.''
</P>
<P>
   People who have worked with Smith describe him as precisely the
type of level-headed professional to deal with this baggage.
Writers who have been edited by him over the years also praise his
ear for elegant prose and his eye for arresting graphics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was painstaking about the choice of words,'' said Michael
Kelly, who Smith brought in as a columnist at National Journal and
is now serving as the magazine's acting editor. ``Our discussions
tended to be whether this was a graceful enough turn of phrase;
whether there was a funnier way to say something; whether we were
veering too close to cliche.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
