<HEADER>
A4327 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-MAG-MEDIA-ART-2N     08-02 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-MAG-MEDIA-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: to cliche.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But some others have had problems with Smith along the way.
Stories that dog Smith, which he acknowledges are true, include his
accidentally sending an insulting computer message to the person he
was gossiping about, Alexis Gelber, an assistant managing editor at
Newsweek.
</P>
<P>
   Another involves a visit to Newsweek by the Rev. Jesse Jackson
during the 1988 presidential campaign, during which Smith kept
insisting that Jackson had grown up in Philadelphia, and only later
realized he had confused him with Reggie Jackson, the baseball
player.
</P>
<P>
   Some former colleagues describe Smith as rigid and say he can be
snobbish and imperious, though none would criticize him on the
record.
</P>
<P>
   Born and raised on the Upper East Side of Manhattan, the son of
a partner in a Wall Street brokerage firm and an editor of women's
magazines, Smith attended Deerfield Academy and the University of
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   He lives with his wife, the writer Sally Bedell Smith, in
Washington. They have one son, 14, and Ms. Smith has two children
from a previous marriage. Smith describes himself politically as
somewhat right of center. ``I am not an ideological guy,'' he said.
``I got into journalism not to save the world but to do good
stories.''
</P>
<P>
   He likes golf, tennis and shooting and is known for dressing
well. ``He wears bespoke suits,'' said Sarah Crichton, vice
president and publisher of Little, Brown &AMP; Co., who worked with
Smith at Newsweek. ``He never owned a pair of jeans in his life and
is proud of it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Smith also seems to have a sense of humor about his
squareness. ``Let's just say Rabbit Angstrom in his dotage,'' he
said, comparing himself to the John Updike character. ``I don't own
a pair of jeans, but I deny that I'm proud.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess,'' Smith added, ``I would consider myself a stuffed
shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Given that Smith's former colleagues describe him as stiff, his
experience at U.S. News may test his capacity for more touchy-feely
management; healing seems to be what the staff needs most right
now.
</P>
<P>
   Many employees say they are embittered about the ousting of
Fallows and some are mystified by it _ several say Evans had
enthusiastically supported Fallows right up until the end.
Explanations have ranged from personality conflicts to
philosophical differences to the theory that Fallows simply stood
up to Zuckerman one time too many.
</P>
<P>
   Evans said the dismissal had to do with Fallows' performance.
``I tried to be supportive of Jim _ he did many good things,'' he
said. ``But for U.S. News there were rather too many
disappointments, which I told him week by week.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, both Evans and Zuckerman said they did not want to
rehash the past; as of Friday, Fallows was still negotiating a
severance package with Zuckerman. Smith said he was staying out of
it. ``I was advised before I came that this was not my fight,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, people at the magazine say, Smith has done a masterful
job at urging the staff to band together. Nevertheless, the turmoil
has cost the magazine several key casualties, including Ronald
Brownstein, a senior writer, who is returning to The Los Angeles
Times; Timothy Noah, the special projects editor; Steven Waldman,
the national editor, and Stephen Budiansky, the deputy editor.
</P>
<P>
   Given these defections, Smith is trying to hire at a difficult
time. ``It is not exactly an ideal recruiting environment,'' one
editor said.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith said he was pressing ahead, as he must. ``The people
who work here are real pros,'' he said. ``They want to do good
work, and I think if we can make it through this bit of a rough
patch right now _ and I know we can _ we can get in a groove and do
good work and put out a good magazine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
