<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   C0X-POLMONEY _ WASHINGTON _ After months of legislative
slogging, House supporters of the main bipartisan proposal for
cleaning up campaign finances are looking forward to the climactic
floor vote on their legislation Monday evening. Rep. Chris Shays,
R-Conn., who joined Rep. Martin Meehan, D-Mass., in co-sponsoring
the bill, compared Monday's vote to a late-season game in which a
baseball team can cinch an American League pennant. ``I want to get
into the World Series with a passion,'' he said Sunday in an
interview. During weeks of debate, supporters defeated all 15 of
the ``poison pill'' amendments that could have torpedoed the
legislation. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   EDs: The following is the second part of a proposed two-day
package on the controversy surrounding the side agreements to the
North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA):
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-NAFTA _ TIJUANA, Mexico _ Norberto Cordoba says he was
fired from Han Young, a Korean-owned auto parts factory, for a
simple reason: ``They told me I was a 'political man.''' The
49-year-old welder didn't take his dismissal lightly. Cordoba,
Mexican and American labor activists have taken this grievance and
a range of others alleging unfair treatment at the Han Young
export, or ``maquiladora'' factory, in Tijuana all the way to
Washington D.C. (Ferris, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved Tuesday, July 28 in the (i) International and (f)
Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   HISTORIC-CHURCH _ AUGUSTA, Ga., _ A report on the last service
at an historic Augusta, Ga., church that was having a dispute with
Atlanta Gas Light Co., about toxic dumping that affected its
property. The church is 158 years old abd was founded in 1840 by
blacks who left a white church. They raised the money to buy the
freedom of a slave preacher. He's buried on the site. (Davis,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15-20 inches.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHERN-COMMAND _ MIAMI _ As a boy growing up 9 degrees north
of the equator, in the middle of an isthmus that holds the Panama
Canal Zone, young Vicente Ogilvie (CQ) fell under the spell of the
U.S. military. From their cliffside post, soldiers commanded most
of his hemisphere; on weekends they filled the shops and
restaurants of his town. Thirty-seven years later, Ogilvie, now an
Army colonel, serves on a far different post. A Miami business park
has become the new headquarters of the former Panamanian Southern
Command. Hi-tech equipment worth $54 million and protected by
anti-terrorist windows provides the eyes and ears to 32 countries
inhabiting a 12 million-square-mile territory where the command
governs military operations. (Staletovich, Palm Beach Post). 32.
</P>
