<P>
   CUBA-GRENADA (Grenada) _ Castro dedicates a plaque to Cuban
workers at the airfield in Grenada, 15 years after U.S. troops
invaded. Local reactions are mixed. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CRIME (Guangzhou) _ Hong Kong's most-wanted criminal, a
near folk-hero in southern China, has finally been caught. By Seth
Faison.
</P>
<P>
   DOCTORS-FREEDOM (Placerville, Calif.) _ As the managed care
industry transformed American health care over the past five years,
the independence of doctors was often the first thing to go. They
may have adjusted to the burden of more paperwork, they may have
learned a new language of health-care bureaucracy, they may even
have even managed to stabilize their salaries. But they have
struggled to hold onto the tradition of building a practice on
their own terms, with their own philosophy. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   FAKE-CRIME-STATS (Philadelphia) _ Senior police officials around
the nation are concerned that the sharp drop in crime in recent
years has produced new pressure on police departments to show
ever-decreasing crime statistics and might be behind incidents in
several cities in which commanders have manipulated crime data. By
Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Developments. By Katharine Q.
Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   GUGGENHEIM-HOGS (New York) _ ``The Art of the Motorcycle'' is an
exhibition quite different from anything else that Museum Mile on
Fifth Avenue has ever experienced. Bathed in biker glory, it has
become the most highly attended exhibition in the Guggenheim's
61-year history, far outstripping retrospectives of Roy
Lichtenstein and Ellsworth Kelly, and more popular than
authoritative surveys of Chinese, Russian and Italian art. By Carol
Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   TOUR-DE-FRANCE (Paris) _ The Tour de France ends its
drug-plagued journey. Pantani wins the event, with Ullrich second
and Julich third. By Samuel Abt.
</P>
<P>
   BULGARIA-WEAPONS (Sofia) _ Once the renowned supplier of weapons
for the Soviet Union and its clients, this Balkan country has now
become the arms bazaar for rebels and terrorist organizations of
every political, ethnic and religious persuasion. By Raymond
Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   FUGITIVE-SEARCH (Montezuma Creek, Utah) _ This summer, in the
largest manhunt the West has seen in years, as many as 500 law
officers have been searching the same mesas and canyons for two men
suspected of killing a policeman and injuring three sheriffs. Two
months after the fugitives disappeared into this vast no man's land
known as the Four Corners on May 29, police don't know whether the
pair is dead in the desert, hiding in the cool shadows of a cave,
or enjoying life in Mexico. By James Brooke.
</P>
