<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE SET TO VOTE ON CAMPAIGN FINANCE BILL
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House supporters of the main bipartisan proposal
for revising campaign finance laws are looking forward to the
climactic floor vote on their legislation Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Shrugging off months of delay, U.S. Rep. Martin Meehan of
Massachusetts, the chief Democratic co-sponsor of the bill,
predicted that it is ``going to pass'' the House.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Chris Shays of Connecticut, the chief Republican
co-sponsor, was more circumspect. The bill ``should pass the
House,'' he said Sunday in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Comparing Monday's vote to a play-off game for the American
League pennant, Shays said, ``I want to get into the World Series
with a passion.''
</P>
<P>
   The Shays-Meehan bill would close the ``soft money'' loophole
that lets political parties obtain contributions of unlimited size,
and would tighten disclosure and contribution rules for groups that
pay for radio or television ads that mention candidates just before
an election.
</P>
<P>
   Last-minute lobbying by Common Cause, the League of Women Voters
and other Shays-Meehan supporters, as well as by opponents led by
the National Right to Life Committee and the Christian Coalition
wasn't expected to have much effect. If there is one topic that
House members know intimately without outside assistance, it is the
ins and outs of raising money for political parties and campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's supporters hope to get far more than the 218 votes
needed to keep their bill alive in the 435-member House. Nine
possible substitutes for their bill have yet to be considered, and
only the version with the most votes will be considered for final
passage.
</P>
<P>
   The House will complete action on all the bills before it
adjourns Friday, Aug. 7 for its month-long summer break, promised
Majority Leader Richard K. Armey, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Republican filibusters have blocked action on similar bills
twice within the last year. But supporters expect the passage of a
House version to increase the pressure on senators.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the bill passes the House, the American people will
expect the Senate, when it returns from the August recess, to act
on campaign finance reform,'' said Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wis.
``I intend to make sure that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   During the past month, Shays and Meehan united their forces in
defeating 15 different amendments that they said could have made
the bill too weak to bother with or too strong to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Final vote results posted by the House Clerk show that in each
of those 15 test votes, they retained support from at least 175
Democrats and 18 Republicans, while at times picking up as many as
200 Democratic and 118 Republican votes.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
