<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-02 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4335 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VANGOGH-FAKES-2TAKES-     08-02 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VANGOGH-FAKES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASTERPIECES, OR ART BY MASTERS OF DECEPTION? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Conn., Mich., Pa., Calif., Ill., France, Austria,
Netherlands, Canada)  (lb) 
 By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fake!
</P>
<P>
   Is there another word that can cause such a tizzy in the art
world, especially when applied to one of van Gogh's iconic
``Sunflowers,'' for which a Japanese company paid $40 million in
1987, a record at the time?
</P>
<P>
   Is there another art-world subject that can so capture the
attention even of philistines (aside, perhaps, from thievery)?
</P>
<P>
   ``People love to hear that someone spent a lot of money for
something that's a fake,'' said Michael Findlay, a senior paintings
expert at Christie's, which sold that ``Sunflowers'' to the
Japanese and stands by it.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, art historians have been arguing over the
authenticity of ``Sunflowers'' and, less vehemently, over dozens of
other van Gogh paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts contend that fake van Goghs include such works as
``L'Arlesienne'' at the Metropolitan Museum of Art; ``Portrait of
Dr. Gachet'' at the Musee d'Orsay in Paris; ``Three Pairs of
Shoes'' at the Fogg Art Museum at Harvard University, and paintings
in the Wadsworth Atheneum in Hartford, Conn., the Detroit Institute
of Arts, the Kunsthistorisches Museum in Vienna, Austria, and even
the Van Gogh Museum in Amsterdam, the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Now, although an article published in March in a a British art
journal, has quelled, but not completely dispelled, the questions
about ``Sunflowers,'' the issue of the authenticity of many van
Gogh works is moving into a new stage, out of scholarly journals
and into the public arena.
</P>
<P>
   Some museums have taken questioned paintings down from their
walls for further study, hoping to determine if the distinctive
brush strokes that legions of van Gogh fans can recognize at 50
paces were really painted by the artist. And some, seeing
blockbusters in the disputed swirls of paint, are organizing
exhibitions around the controversy or counting on it to add sizzle
to shows with a broader rationale.
</P>
<P>
   The Orsay and the Metropolitan have lighted on a show centered
on Dr. Paul Ferdinand Gachet, the homeopathic physician who cared
for van Gogh in his final two months and whose famous portrait sold
for even more than ``Sunflowers'' _ $82.5 million, the world
auction record for a work of art _ in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   That painting, bought by a Japanese businessman, now deceased,
has not been questioned, but doubters have fingered the almost
identical ``Portrait of Dr. Gachet'' given to the Orsay by the
Gachet family.
</P>
<P>
   Gachet was not only a pioneering collector, whose many Cezannes,
Pissarros and other impressionist paintings were donated to France,
but also a painter who copied the work of his famous impressionist
friends, signing them ``Paul van Ryssel.''
</P>
<P>
   The show, which is scheduled to open in Paris in January and
move to New York in the spring, is still being organized, but
besides Gachet's work it will display his collection of paintings,
most likely including the eight van Goghs he owned. And it may
unite the questioned and unquestioned Gachet portraits.
</P>
<P>
   Questions of Fakery Spark Interest
</P>
<P>
   For 2000-2001, the Philadelphia Museum of Art, the Museum of
Fine Arts in Boston and the Detroit Institute of Art are organizing
a show of van Gogh portraits beyond Gachet. ``I'm not steering
clear of works that have been questioned,'' said Joseph Rishel,
curator of European paintings at the Philadelphia museum. ``I'm all
for sticking my neck out. It will get more people.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, opening at the Art Institute of Chicago in September 2001,
comes ``Van Gogh and Gauguin: The Studio of the South,'' a joint
effort with the Van Gogh Museum in Amsterdam. It will examine the
complex relationship between the men, who wanted to start an
artists' colony to reinvigorate art in France and chose the
sunflower as its symbol. That spawned part of the problem. Gauguin
had so admired van Gogh's early sunflower paintings that van Gogh
not only painted more versions but copied some of them.
</P>
<P>
   If the organizers' wishes come true, this exhibit will unite
five ``Sunflowers'' for comparison (there were 12 or 13 in all),
including the one that Yasuda Fire and Marine Insurance of Japan
spent so much money on, as well as other works, like
``L'Arlesienne,'' that exist in many versions. (Yasuda has not yet
agreed to send its painting.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll understand both artists better if we understand the
context in which the paintings were made,'' said Douglas Druick,
the curator of European paintings at the Art Institute of Chicago,
``and the exhibition will address the question of `Are they by van
Gogh or are they not?'''
</P>
<P>
   (Beginning in October, the National Gallery of Art in Washington
and the Los Angeles County Museum of Art will exhibit 70 van Goghs
from the museum in Amsterdam, which will be closed for renovation.
But these masterworks, drawn from the artist's family, are not
considered dubious.)
</P>
<P>
   Questions about van Gogh's works, while perhaps new to the
public, have seethed, on and off, for at least 70 years. By most
accounts, he died a failure, having sold just one painting, or at
best a handful. But within a decade, his work grew very popular,
inviting both high prices and imitators.
</P>
<P>
   The myth of van Gogh as a mad artist, who did 76 paintings in
the 70 days before he shot himself on July 27, 1890, helped fuel
doubts about his works. What human could have done so much?
</P>
<P>
   ``Van Gogh has three catalogues raisonnes,'' noted Rishel of the
Philadelphia museum. ``What does that say?''
</P>
<P>
   As early as the 1920s, a German art dealer named Otto Wacker was
sent to prison as a fake-monger.
</P>
<P>
   A Long Debate Renewed by Scholars
</P>
<P>
   This time, the controversy flared after the 1996 publication of
Jan Hulsker's ``The New Complete Van Gogh: Paintings, Drawings,
Sketches'' (J.M. Meulenhoff, Amsterdam), an update of his 1977 van
Gogh catalogue raisonne. In it, Hulsker, the dean of van Gogh
scholars, put question marks next to 45 works, but did not explain
what they meant.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Roland Dorn, a German art historian, and Walter
Feilchenfelt, a Swiss dealer and scholar, were questioning a
different but overlapping selection of some two dozen works in van
Gogh's oeuvre. Amateur French and Italian experts also chimed in
with their lists of fakes.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, The Art Newspaper, a London-based monthly, pulled
together all the strands in a huge article that counted more than
100 suspected fakes. Among the suspected forgers are Wacker, the
art dealer; Claude-Emile Schuffenecker, a failed artist and
neighbor of van Gogh who later owned many of his works and restored
at least one version of ``Sunflowers,'' and Gachet.
</P>
<P>
   The Art Newspaper article created an uproar and set off a spate
of media coverage, including a British television documentary last
October focusing on Yasuda's ``Sunflowers.'' It tagged
Schuffenecker as the villain who had the ability, the motive and
the opportunity, because he was hired around 1900 to restore the
``Sunflowers'' now at the National Gallery in London.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Researchers Rely on Detailed Letters
</P>
<P>
   Much of the controversy stems from a peculiarity in van Gogh
scholarship, which has both pluses and minuses. It involves a
dependence on his frequent letters to his brother, Theo, in which
Vincent described his paintings in detail. ``No other artist has
such an anchor,'' said Susan Alyson Stein, a van Gogh expert at the
Metropolitan Museum.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the letters provided a guide for forgers and
created suspicion about any painting not mentioned, perhaps
unnecessarily. ``It's wrongheaded to assume that van Gogh described
everything in his letters,'' Ms. Stein said. Besides, Druick said,
many letters are missing.
</P>
<P>
   The problems are compounded because van Gogh's death was
followed shortly by the death of Theo, who was Vincent's dealer,
leaving the van Gogh estate in the hands of Theo's widow, Johanna,
and her brother. Nonexperts, they created van Gogh's market but
lost control of it as his works grew increasingly desirable. Early
provenance records simply do not exist for many works.
</P>
<P>
   Yasuda's ``Sunflowers'' is one of three paintings depicting 14
sunflowers in a vase. Only two are cited in the letters, one now
hanging in the National Gallery in London, the other in the Van
Gogh Museum. The third, Yasuda's, surfaced in 1901, owned by
Schuffenecker, at a Paris exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   But in the March article, Bogomila Welsh-Ovcharov, a widely
published van Gogh scholar at the University of Toronto, undermined
the naysayers with an article that traced the provenance of the
Yasuda ``Sunflowers'' from van Gogh.
</P>
<P>
   She found evidence in two letters. In 1894, the widow of Pere
Tanguy, a paint merchant with whom van Gogh had left the work for
storage or possible sale, wrote about it to Johanna. Within days of
that letter, Schuffenecker wrote to Johanna thanking her for
agreeing to sell him ``Sunflowers,'' which he had picked up at
Madame Tanguy's.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has put out a lot of fires,'' Rishel said. ``No one
refutes her argument as made.'' Druick, of the Art Institute of
Chicago, agreed, but noted that some experts continue to disagree
with Ms. Welsh-Ovcharov's interpretation of the letters.
</P>
<P>
   And that is where the matter stands. Even after a daylong van
Gogh symposium in May sponsored by the Van Gogh Museum and the
National Gallery in London, ``no consensus was reached,'' the
organizers said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps oddly, auction houses and dealers say that the
controversy has had little effect on the van Gogh market. People
are still buying the few works that have been available and, said
Findlay. ``We haven't yet told a client, `I am sorry, we cannot
offer your picture because it's not accepted in some catalogue
raisonne,''' he said. ``If anyone has a work that has been doubted,
they probably wouldn't bring it forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The Van Gogh Museum has said it would compile a new catalogue
raisonne, though that will take years. It and the Art Institute of
Chicago are also undertaking an X-ray and technical analysis of the
canvas, pigments and preparatory coatings of many works.
</P>
<P>
   They are focusing on those that van Gogh painted in his final
two months in Arles, as well as a sampling of the ``Sunflowers''
paintings, ``L'Arlesiennes,'' the paintings of his bedroom in Arles
and the portraits of Augustine Roulin (``the Berceuse'').
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping to come up with definitive answers'' that will be
published, Druick said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the exhibitions will bring many works together
so that their style can be scrutinized. And the art world will
depend on scholars like Ms. Welsh-Ovcharov for research in the
neglected area of provenance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an international general feeling that we need to know
more about the history of van Gogh's art,'' Ms. Stein said. Not
just museums, but millions of people who own something with an iris
or a sunflower or a starry night probably want to know.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
