</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Aug. 3, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of showers and thunderstorms will surround a
strengthening disturbance over the northern Plains. The disturbance
will move very slowly to the southeast Monday and Tuesday,
heightening the risk of local flooding across parts of the Missouri
and central Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The day will begin dry over most of the Great Lakes and Ohio
Valley. Clouds will increase in western sections as humid air from
the Plains is forced to rise over the drier air in place over the
region. Farther to the east, sunshine will be plentiful for most of
the day although humidity will begin to increase.
</P>
<P>
   Abundant sunshine and comfortable humidity will prevail again
Monday across the Northeast as high pressure remains strong over
the region. Some patchy clouds will reach northern New England as a
weak front moves south from Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Low pressure east of the Carolinas will circulate sultry
tropical air toward the coast. As a result, bands of clouds and
thundershowers will brush the coast from southern Virginia to
Florida. Meanwhile, the interior Southeast will have ample
sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   The mercury is expected to exceed 100 degrees for the 29th
consecutive day in Dallas as sunshine remains plentiful in most of
the southern Plains. A few afternoon thunderstorms will develop
from northwestern Texas to the central Plains.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, heat will spread toward the West Coast as offshore
winds develop. Most areas will be sunny, but scattered afternoon
thunderstorms will develop in the cooler air near the east slopes
of the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Weekend Rhythm
</P>
<P>
   Around Philadelphia, the warm-season weather has had a pleasing
rhythm. Since May 23, the early part of the week has been cooler
than the latter part, Fridays have been wet, and only one weekend
has been a washout. There is scientific basis for the tendency for
the weekend weather to repeat itself. The average speed and spacing
of weather systems in the middle latitudes brings a disturbance
approximately once every 3.5 days. Hence, it is not uncommon for a
pattern to evolve where the weekend weather at a given location
repeats itself for several successive weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-98 1808EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
