<DOCNO> NYT19980802.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-02 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4339 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-ADS-750&AMP;ADD-     08-02 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-ADS-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL TO CREATE THE LARGEST INTERACTIVE AD AGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Calif., Ga.)   (10:45 p.m. ET EMBARGO for print media; 12:01 a.m. ET EMBARGO for
electronic media.)  
(lb) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a combination that will create the largest agency devoted to
creating advertising on the Internet, Agency.com has agreed to buy
Eagle River Interactive.
</P>
<P>
   This deal, which is expected to be announced Monday, is the
latest in a mad game of Pac Man, in which the dozens of small
agencies founded by young entrepreneurs are racing to gobble one
another up.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes in many of these transactions is Omnicom
Group, the huge advertising agency holding company, which has taken
stakes in several of the most prominent start-up interactive
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Omnicom owns 40 percent of Agency.com, which is based in New
York, and all of Eagle River Interactive, based in Chicago. The
terms of the deal have not been disclosed, but Omnicom's stake in
Agency.com will increase to just under half as a result of the
deal, said Chan Suh, Agency.com's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Agency.com has also bought Online Magic,
Spiral Media, Ketchum Interactive and Interactive Solutions. The
last two were also owned by Omnicom.
</P>
<P>
   Interactive agencies provide a range of services, including
helping companies set up their own sites on the World Wide Web and
placing ``banner'' advertisements on other sites to bring in
traffic. While this business incorporates the sort of writing and
design skills used by conventional advertising agencies, much of
the work of the interactive shops more closely resembles the
detailed computer programming typically provided by technology
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``An interactive company is one part creativity, one part
technology and one part business strategy,'' said Felice Kincannon,
who looks after Omnicom's interactive holdings through a unit
called Communicade.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, technology companies have been expanding into this
field. Both IBM and Electronic Data Services Corp. have set up big
interactive design departments as an adjunct to their business of
building elaborate Internet sites for companies.
</P>
<P>
   And two of the most aggressive acquirers of interactive agencies
_ U S Web in Santa Clara, Calif., and iXL in Atlanta _ have been
buying both technology and design companies.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the conventional advertising companies have the greatest
ties to the existing interactive agencies, with True North
Communications, Grey Advertising and Interpublic Group all owning
stakes in at least one of the top 15 agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Omnicom, however, has been the most aggressive, with stakes in
four of the top 15 ranked by Adweek magazine, including Agency.com,
now tied with iXL for first place; Think New Ideas, the
fifth-ranked agency; Organic Online, No. 7, and Eagle River, No.
14. In total, its six agencies have 1,500 employees and revenues of
$180 million. That represents about one-third of what Jupiter
Communications estimates is a $500 million market this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of picking one horse to ride, Omnicom has spread its
bets and has watched how the race turned out,'' said Seth Alpert, a
senior adviser to Ad Media Partners, a New York investment bank
that specializes in media companies. ``So far, they have done a
pretty good job.
</P>
<P>
   As it has with conventional advertising agencies, Omnicom has
been able to buy into the younger interactive agencies by offering
to act as the friendly, but unintrusive, big brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not backseat drivers,'' Suh said, adding that
Agency.com had few client referrals from other Omnicom agencies.
But it has been able to ask executives of the holding company
questions from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like having your own consulting company on call,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Omnicom has subtly encouraged the strongest of its flock to
absorb the laggards. In February it flew the top executives of all
of its interactive companies to a retreat in Miami. While Omnicom
did not play explicit matchmaker, the flirtation was as heavy as on
a college spring break.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a courting thing,'' said Kevin Rowe, the chief
executive of Eagle River. After a first date of a joint project for
Compaq Computer, Eagle River and Agency.com decided to get hitched.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the combination, Agency.com, which was founded in
1995, will have 575 employees in 10 offices and 1998 revenues of
about $80 million. Agency.com's largest clients include British
Airways, GTE and Metropolitan Life. Eagle River, a descendant of a
company that placed billboards on Colorado ski slopes, serves
clients that include Sprint and Disneyland Paris.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Many advertising-industry executives believe Agency.com is
trying to grow quickly in preparation for an initial public
offering. Suh declined to comment on any potential offering.
</P>
<P>
   Others wonder whether many of these young companies are
expanding faster than they can handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get worried for a company like Agency.com,'' said Gene
DeRose, the president of Jupiter Communications. ``I think they
have to be careful about how they integrate their acquisitions.''
</P>
<P>
   DeRose pointed to the example of CKS Group, one of the first
publicly held interactive agencies, which has found melding its
many acquisitions harder than it expected. CKS' stock trades at
less than half of its 52-week high of $64.25, reached last
September; the shares closed at $19.3125 Friday, off 12.5 cents, in
Nasdaq trading.
</P>
<P>
   Others point out that the acquisition price for interactive
agencies is vastly higher than for conventional ad agencies, which
typically are sold for about the total of their annual revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The high water mark for pricing was recently set by ICC
Technologies, a Hatboro, Pa., maker of humidity-control systems,
which recently moved onto the Internet by buying Rare Medium, a
small New York agency, for $45 million, more than 11 times its
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Many other more traditional buyers are turning up their noses at
those prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recently met with a foreign agency who said they were
looking for an interactive shop in this country,'' Alpert of Ad
Media Partners said. ``We told them they would have to pay four or
five times revenue, and they were aghast and went home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
