u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BULGARIA-WEAPONS-NYT &LR;      08-02 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BULGARIA-WEAPONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTERN ENVOYS CALL BULGARIA AN ARMS BAZAAR FOR THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By RAYMOND BONNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOFIA, Bulgaria _ Once the renowned supplier of weapons for the
Soviet Union, this Balkan country has become the arms bazaar for
rebels and terrorist organizations of every political, ethnic and
religious persuasion, Western officials and experts in the small
arms trade say.
</P>
<P>
   Secret weapons shipments have gone to rebel groups forming in
Congo, threatening another outbreak of war there; to rebels in
Angola, who are preparing to take up their war anew there, and to
Eritrea, adding to Washington's fears about the escalation of
fighting in the Horn of Africa. And that is just in the last few
months. Other arms shoppers have included Sri Lanka's Tamil Tigers,
which Washington has labeled a terrorist group, and Rwanda's Hutu
militia, who were responsible for mass killings in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bulgarian arms traffic were shut down or cleaned up, far
fewer weapons would end up fueling today's regional wars,
intelligence and industry experts said.
</P>
<P>
   But Washington and the European Union, while voicing concern,
have done little to stop the trade, diplomats from several nations
said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, both Europe and the United States have put more
diplomatic muscle into getting the Bulgarian government to shut
down the production of pirate compact disks thanks to pressure from
business groups, diplomats said. By contrast, they noted, there is
no business lobby calling for a crackdown on Bulgaria's arms
makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't regard it as a subject on which to make a fuss,'' a
Western ambassador said, slightly chagrined.
</P>
<P>
   The big attraction in Bulgaria is the Kalashnikov assault rifle.
Light, durable and easy to maintain, it is ideal for young soldiers
slogging through jungles or trekking up mountains. And Bulgaria
makes the best. Having lost their traditional Cold War markets,
Bulgaria's arms manufacturers are desperate for customers, whom
they have accommodated with false shipping documents to disguise
both the buyer and the destination of the weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Bulgaria's major arms suppliers declined to be interviewed.
Government officials denied that the country has become a major
center for illicit arms trafficking, as American and European
officials maintain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The official government policy is directed at restraining such
activities,'' said Vladimir Tourtansky, a senior official in
Bulgaria's Cabinet-level Council on Defense Industry and Logistics.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for greater controls on small-arms trade point out
that so-called small arms and light weapons _ assault rifles,
grenades, mortars _ have caused more death and destruction in the
last 50 years than nuclear, biological and chemical weapons, which
are the objects of international alarm and controls.
</P>
<P>
   Bulgaria is not the only place where rebels and rogues shop.
Arms manufacturers in Ukraine, Slovakia, Romania and Belarus are
also major suppliers of weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But at the moment, Bulgarian arms are the weapons of choice.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the trade are Kintex, the state marketing
agency, and Arsenal, the country's largest arms manufacturer, which
is also state-owned.
</P>
<P>
   Founded by Bulgaria's secret police in the 1960s, Kintex has a
history of dubious arms trading. During the Iran-Iraq war, the
company sold to both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Kintex ``offers so many models of Kalashnikov assault rifles''
that Jane's Infantry Weapons, the industry's authoritative guide,
feels compelled to provide a summary. Altogether, Jane's lists 16
Bulgarian models, from the AKT-47, a training version of the
original AK-47, to the AK-74, the latest version of the assault
rifle, which was designed 50 years ago by Mikhail Kalashnikov for
the Soviet Army.
</P>
<P>
   All are made by Arsenal. Bulgarian officials boast that Mikhail
Kalashnikov has said Arsenal makes the highest quality Kalashnikov
today. The company also manufactures the 9-millimeter Makarov
pistol, which is often in the crates of weapons clandestinely
shipped from here.
</P>
<P>
   Kintex and Arsenal denied several requests for interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Arsenal and Kintex, along with other Bulgarian weapons
companies, are still largely in the hands of the men who ran them
during the communist days. In doing business today, they make use
of the expertise and contacts they developed when Bulgaria handled
Moscow's clients, including Libya, Iraq and Iran, and many African
governments or guerrilla groups.
</P>
<P>
   With the collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991, Bulgaria lost
these secondary markets, as well as the Warsaw Pact. Struggling to
survive economically has caused the companies to engage in shady
practices, diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their attitude toward the small arms trade is: We know we
shouldn't but we can't afford not to,'' a European diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   An Asian diplomat put it this way: ``If you can't sell to the
Soviet Union, if you can't sell to the Warsaw Pact, if you can't
sell to Iran, Iraq, Libya, what do you do?''
</P>
<P>
   ``They need capital,'' he went on. ``So I suppose they don't
look too closely at end-user certificates.'' That refers to the
document that is supposed to identify the ultimate destination of
the weapons.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, acting for a British mercenary army, Arsenal
shipped 35 tons of weapons for rebels in Sierre Leone, using
documents that said they were going to Nigeria. In a deal for 77
tons of Kalashnikovs and other weapons, air-dropped to a violent
religious sect in India two years ago, Arsenal used phony documents
saying they were going to the Bangladesh Defense Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Western and Asian diplomats said that the current Bulgarian
government, which came to power last year, was trying more than
previous post-communist governments to curb shady arms practices,
but that it was constrained by the country's economic needs and the
influence of the military industry.
</P>
<P>
   Tourtansky said he was not aware of any arms company that has
been punished for using false documents. He added, however, that
Bulgaria's arms sales policies ``are in line with all international
standards and norms.'' He stressed that Bulgaria was complying with
the so-called Wassenaar Arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Pushed by the Clinton administration, the Wassenaar accord _
named after the Dutch city where it was signed three years ago _ is
aimed at controlling exports of conventional weapons and dual-use
goods, like computers and telecommunications equipment, to
countries like Iran, Iraq, Libya and North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   But Wassenaar, with 33 member-nations, does not deal with
illicit trade and does not require reporting sales of Kalashnikovs
and other small arms, American officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The most comprehensive report on arms sales is published
annually by the United Nations. But it covers only heavy weapons,
like tanks and warships. Assault rifles, mortars, rocket launchers
and other light weapons are not included.
</P>
<P>
   International policies like these allow Tourtansky to say
accurately, ``We are not required to report to anyone about our
international sales.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
