<DOCNO> NYT19980802.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-02 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4350 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPENMINDED-BOOK-REVIE     08-02 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPENMINDED-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OPEN MINDED': DISTURBING SIGNS BEHIND REPORTS OF FREUD'S DEMISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Publication notes at end of review.)  
(lb) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Jonathan Lear was a child, grown-ups would often ask him,
``Are you related to the king?'' As he explains in the preface to
his stimulating new collection of essays on psychoanalysis and
philosophy, ``Open Minded: Working Out the Logic of the Soul,'' he
came to take the question for granted, not even bothering to learn
to whom the questioners were referring.
</P>
<P>
   But when he became older and read ``King Lear,'' he found it
difficult to identify with someone so insecure and vain. And then
one night, during the time he was in analysis, he woke up with a
start and realized that he was related to the king. He was
Cordelia, because he always wanted to be blunt in his appraisals
and at the same time to be loved for it.
</P>
<P>
   In writing the present book, he wanted to say that ``there is
something dead'' in the professions of psychoanalysis and
philosophy, ``and I wanted to be loved for saying so.'' He
concludes, ``This book is above all a response to a sense of
deadness: it is an attempt to bring some life into two activities
which lie at the heart of our humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   At the core of his response is a defense of psychoanalysis
against the rising tide of Freud bashers that has lately battered
the profession. (This chapter, ``On Killing Freud (Again),''
appeared in a recent issue of The New Republic and prompted the
writer Janet Malcolm in a dust-jacket endorsement of the present
book to make the surprising claim that ``since his essay appeared,
talk about `the death of psychoanalysis' has noticeably
subsided.'')
</P>
<P>
   In the chapter, Lear, who teaches at the University of Chicago,
blames Jeffrey M. Masson and Frederick Crews for willfully
misreading the evolution of Freud's theories of childhood
seduction. What Freud actually abandoned later in his career, Lear
writes, ``was blind faith in the idea that alleged memories of
abuse are always and everywhere what they purport to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Lear continues: ``In realizing that one could not take all
memory claims at face value, Freud effectively discovered that the
mind is active and imaginative in the organization of its own
experience. This is one of the crucial moments in the founding of
psychoanalysis.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same essay, Lear also disputes those who insist that
psychoanalysis can't prove ``the cause-and-effect connections it
claims between unconscious motivation and its visible
manifestations in ordinary life and in a clinical setting,'' a
major theme in one of his previous books, ``Love and Its Place in
Nature: A Philosophical Interpretation of Freudian
Psychoanalysis.'' To deny such connections, he argues, is
tantamount to denying that people are sometimes driven by
unconscious motives and behave irrationally.
</P>
<P>
   This relates to what he says is really the object of the attacks
on Freud, namely ``the very idea that humans have unconscious
motivation,'' that what ails us may lie beyond the reach of
psychopharmacology and neuropsychiatry (for all they have
contributed) and that we are capable of meaning more than we say.
</P>
<P>
   Our capacity to mean more than we say is the common thread of
all the essays here, which explore philosophically the phenomenon
of transference in psychotherapy, the nature of the unconscious
mind and the role of Eros in Freud's thinking.
</P>
<P>
   In the chapter ``Knowingness and Abandonment: An Oedipus for Our
Time,'' Lear reinterprets Sophocles' ``Oedipus Tyrannus,'' pointing
out that while Oedipus murdered his father and slept with his
mother, he did not do so because of the complex Freud named after
him.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Lear argues, Oedipus' flaw was to have understood the
Delphic oracle too easily, to have assumed that ``meaning is
transparent to human reason'' and to have ignored ``unconscious
meaning.''
</P>
<P>
   He ``displays a `knowingness' eerily reminiscent of contemporary
culture's demand to already know,'' Lear concludes. ``But there is
a sickness in this `knowingness': reason is being used to jump
ahead to a conclusion, as though there is too much anxiety involved
in simply asking a question and waiting for the world to answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Lear offers similarly astute and original readings of
Aristotle's ``Poetics,'' Plato's ``Symposium'' and ``Republic'' and
Wittgenstein's ``Philosophical Investigations.'' He feels free to
range so widely because he sees the work of these writers as
related; each in his own way was ``working out the logic of the
soul.'' Each knew ``that one of the most important truths about us
is that we have the capacity to be open minded: the capacity to
live nondefensively with the question of how to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, a third of these essays plunge so deeply into
philosophical and psychoanalytic arcana that even a patient reader
is likely to feel taxed, at least in places. But the critical
essays will prove of value to anyone seriously engaged by
literature. And the chapters on Freud and Oedipus are worth the
price of admission alone.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the Freud chapter, Lear makes the point that
``obsessing about Freud the man is a way of keeping Freud the
meaning at bay.'' He continues, ``The many attacks on him, even
upon psychoanalysis, refuse to recognize that Freud gave birth to a
psychoanalytic movement which in myriad ways has moved beyond
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lear concludes: ``Just as democracy requires the recognition
that the king is dead, both as an individual and as an institution,
so the democratic recognition that each person is a maker of
unconscious, symbolic meanings requires the acceptance of Freud's
death. What matters, as Freud himself well understood, is what we
are able to do with the meanings we make.''
</P>
<P>
   The best of these essays prompt us to examine those meanings,
which activity, as Plato famously said, is what makes life worth
living.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `OPEN MINDED'
</P>
<P>
   Working Out the Logic of the Soul
</P>
<P>
   By Jonathan Lear
</P>
<P>
   345 pages. Harvard University Press. $35.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
