<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-POLITICS-630(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAN WHO IS POISED TO BRING CHANGE TO GERMANY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAYREUTH, Germany _ Gerhard Schroder is the man who would be
Germany's next chancellor, and even if the opinion polls did not
consistently paint him as the front-runner in national elections
two months from now, his manner most certainly would.
</P>
<P>
   With his police security detail around him and his youthful
fourth wife, Doris Kopf, on his arm as he campaigned in this
Bavarian town, his step was firm and his smile as bright as the
television lights that feed his inner glow.
</P>
<P>
   The polls indicate that in the elections on Sept. 27, Schroder
could well wrest the leadership of Europe's most powerful land from
Chancellor Helmut Kohl, ending a 16-year, four-term run that has
made Kohl seem like an Olympian. It was obviously an omen,
Schroder's supporters from the Social Democratic opposition
observed, that the coming attraction in Bayreuth _ the high altar
of Wagnerian devotion _ was the opera - ``Gotter-dammerung'' _
``Twilight of the Gods.''
</P>
<P>
   The differences between the two men are all too evident. At age
54, compared with Kohl's 68, Schroder seeks to project himself as
the emblem of a new generation. He speaks with expansive gestures
geared to the TV cameras that Kohl reviles.
</P>
<P>
   Schroder's voice booms and a campaign banner behind him
proclaims: ``Political change for Germany _ innovation and
justice.'' After a 30-minute address, he leaps _ not too nimbly _
from the podium to sign autographs and to mingle. Virtually every
gesture seems designed to project energy and form a contrast with
the appearance of fatigue that sometimes hangs over Kohl.
</P>
<P>
   Yet here and at other election rallies in sports halls and beer
tents across conservative Bavaria, it soon emerged that he and Kohl
are offering some of the same message to court some of the same
people. The contest among undecided voters will be won on one
question: Who can make the better case to Germany's 62 million
voters that their land can be re-invented without pain?
</P>
<P>
   That is the question that preoccupies the people who have come
to see Schroder, ranging from the converted to the curious to the
skeptical, people like Monika Riess, 44, Hildegund Hornegger, 50,
and Mark Henkel, a 22-year-old law student _ all grist for the
``new center'' Schroder wants to mold, and all pondering who will
best strike a balance between renewal and security in these
uncertain times of globalization and unaccustomed competition from
beyond Germany's borders.
</P>
<P>
   `'You have to be modern, but you can't lose justice,'' Mrs.
Riess said, using the code word denoting Germany's social welfare
state.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are those like Mrs. Hornegger, a bank employee and
Social Democrat, who senses that change has already begun to take
away a German birthright. ``I want what we used to have to come
back,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hornegger, who has arthritis, arrived on crutches with her
husband, Anton, 58, a postal worker. ``I'm expecting a lot from
Schroder,'' she said, sitting on one of the hard plastic seats laid
out in the Oberfrankenhalle. ``People expect him to do more at our
level.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she hoped he would reverse the health-care changes that
are costing her $1,250 a year for prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   But some think Schroder is short on substance. ``We don't need a
show _ we've got Helmut Kohl,'' said Henkel, the law student.
``He's the very image of security. And with him, what you get is
what you see.''
</P>
<P>
   But Henkel may be disappointed. If the election were held
immediately, surveys suggest, it would bring a sea change to
Germany _ and thus to Europe _ just as the Continent braces for the
strains of a single currency and a profound debate about its future
as an economic and political bloc.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, this is a change of generation,'' Schroder said in
a brief interview here. ``It's a question of who has the strength
to mold the creative forces into the next millennium?''
</P>
<P>
   Schroder is to meet in Washington on Wednesday with President
Clinton when, his aides hope, he will offset the impression
conveyed by Clinton during a visit to Germany last May that the
U.S. president feels an exclusive bond with Kohl.
</P>
<P>
   But in Bavaria, where a state assembly vote two weeks before the
national vote could become a critical signal of his fortunes,
Schroder's prime concern is to convince his audience that cherished
social benefits _ free, or cheap, health care; good schools; solid
pensions _ will not be sacrificed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Globalization is a reality we have to deal with,'' he
proclaimed, urging the Social Democrats' traditionally left-leaning
and working-class bedrock to show ``flexibility'' in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The raw materials are in the minds of our people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schroder says he knows ``what the loss of material
possibilities'' means because he grew up in poverty. His father
died in World War II; his widowed mother took cleaning jobs to
raise the family.
</P>
<P>
   That differentiates Schroder from Britain's middle-class prime
minister, Tony Blair. But it is not the only difference. The Social
Democrats have not been remolded in the same way as Britain's ``New
Labor'' and Schroder's place in the party is ambiguous: he is its
candidate for reformist chancellor but not leader of its Socialist
core.
</P>
<P>
   And he would come to power at one of Germany's most difficult
times in the postwar era. The cost of hiring workers in Germany is
among the highest in the world. Social systems are creaking under
the strains of an aging society with high expectations of social
benefits financed by an ever-smaller labor force. Unemployment is
at postwar record highs, in excess of four million people.
</P>
<P>
   Schroder's critics say he offers only vague, feel-good
assurances and exhortations without detailed strategies. Underlying
that vagueness, though, is a calculation _ common to Kohl and other
political parties _ that what the voters want in September is
reassurance, not alarms, about the future of their pensions, their
health care, their sick pay and their unemployment benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can only take people with you on a journey to change if
you give them the most basic measure of security,'' Schroder said
after the meeting here.
</P>
<P>
   His adversaries maintain that the journey he has in mind has
less to do with the people than with getting to the chancellor's
office. They say an overwhelming ambition has fueled his political
progress from a leftist Young Socialist to his current position as
premier of Lower Saxony in Hanover.
</P>
<P>
   Under Germany's electoral system, it is possible that he could
win the biggest chunk of votes but be able to rule only in
coalition. But he says he wants only the first prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have told my supporters in Lower Saxony that I either go to
Bonn as chancellor, or I'll stay in Hanover,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
