A4364 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAX-INTERNET-NYT &LR;      08-02 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS WORKS TO RECONCILE 3 VERSIONS OF INTERNET TAX BILL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Va., R.I., Neb., Del., N.D.)   (jw) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A proposed six-year moratorium on taxes in cyberspace would be
reduced to only two years under the version of the Internet Tax
Freedom Act approved by the Senate Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The committee also voted last week to force states and local
governments that tax Internet access to end these taxes, but left
untouched claims for millions of dollars in taxes that America
Online did not collect from customers and may now have to pay at
its own expense.
</P>
<P>
   The Finance Committee's version of the bill differs
significantly from those passed by the House and by the Senate
Commerce Committee. The House version calls for a three-year
moratorium, while the Senate Commerce Committee's version would
keep the six-year moratorium.
</P>
<P>
   Both the House and the Senate Commerce Committee versions would
block states from citing the presence of computer servers to
establish a company's physical presence within a state. The Senate
Finance Committee's version is silent on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   Until most of these and other differences are worked out, the
bill is unlikely to reach the Senate floor for a vote. The Senate
is in recess until the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet Tax Freedom Coalition, the leading electronic
commerce group lobbying to make cyberspace free of taxes and
tariffs, contends that confusion about taxes is hampering the
growth of commerce in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   That argument was rejected by Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I., and Sen.
Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., both members of the Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Chafee, citing testimony by America Online that electronic
commerce will grow to $20 billion by 2000, said a two-year
moratorium was enough to determine how to tax cyberspace
transactions properly.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey dismissed the arguments of industry lobbyists that taxes
are crippling electronic commerce. ``This is no infant industry in
swaddling clothes,'' he said, citing 30 percent growth a month in
retail sales on the Internet. ``Wall Street can't throw money at
Internet companies fast enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The 19-1 vote by the Senate Finance Committee to approve its
version of the bill came on Tuesday, the same day that the Commerce
Department issued a report showing a growing disparity in access to
the Internet among various income groups. People making more than
$75,000 a year are seven times as likely to have access to the
Internet as those making $15,000 to $20,000 a year and more than
twice as likely as those making $35,000 to $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of making the Internet a tax-free zone was
criticized by Michael Maserov, a senior policy analyst with the
Center on Budget and Policy Priorities. ``This is just one more tax
break for the affluent at the expense of the poor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Finance Committee rejected, on a 10-10 vote, a
proposal by Sen. Kent Conrad, D-N.D., that would have allowed
states that tax Internet access and data sold over the Internet to
continue those levies.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad, who was formerly his state's elected tax commissioner,
said he saw no compelling reason for the federal government to
interfere with state tax policies.
</P>
<P>
   The ``ability of states or local governments to collect tax'' on
transactions before July 29 would not be affected by the Senate
Finance Committee's version of the bill, according to committee
Chairman Sen. William Roth Jr., R-Del.
</P>
<P>
   That provision is a serious setback for America Online, the
nation's largest Internet service provider, which collects sales
taxes on behalf of foreign governments but has refused to collect
the same taxes when they are required by the states and local
governments. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
