<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHIRDEWAN-OBIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARL SCHIRDEWAN, EAST GERMANY PARTY RENEGADE, DIES
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Karl Schirdewan, a high-ranking figure in the old East German
communist government who wanted to ``democratize'' the Communist
Party but lost a power struggle and fell into disgrace, has died in
Potsdam, Germany. He was 91.
</P>
<P>
   His death was reported on July 17 in the Frankfurter Allgemeine
Zeitung, which did not say when he died.
</P>
<P>
   Schirdewan was born in Konigsberg, Germany, and became a worker
and a communist functionary. He was arrested after Hitler came to
power for illegal party activity and was interned in concentration
camps.
</P>
<P>
   In the postwar era he rose swiftly in the East German Communist
Party. He was elected to its Politburo in 1953 and came to be
described as the No. 2 man to the dictator Walter Ulbricht, an
uncompromising Stalinist.
</P>
<P>
   But in a 1972 book, ``The Changing Party Elite in East
Germany,'' Peter Ludz, a West German professor of political
science, wrote that Schirdewan and two like-minded Politburo
members came to constitute ``the last political alternative to the
Ulbricht group'' within the party and that the elimination of that
alternative was decided upon by its opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schirdewan's wish to `democratize' the party was perceived as
a threat,'' Ludz wrote, and ``after a decisive struggle,'' the
Ulbricht faction ``succeeded in re-establishing its positions of
power.''
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 8, 1958, Schirdewan and his two allies were expelled
from the party's Central Committee and Politburo. The decision to
expel them was made at a meeting of the Central Committee.
Essentially, the three were accused of wanting to democratize the
party, decentralize the East German economic system and introduce
certain intellectual freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   Schirdewan was relegated to an obscure government post but was
rehabilitated by the party in 1990.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
