<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODWILL-BOXING03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. boxers revel in silver
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Georgians Ebo Elder and Jacob Hudson got a taste of
the New York night life at the theater: the Theater at Madison
Square Garden, where the 19-year-old boxers battled to Goodwill
Games silver medals.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've had three nights of the most fun I've ever had,'' Hudson
said in the wee hours of Sunday morning after he and Elder posed
for team pictures. ''Hard to believe you got two guys from Georgia,
who are like brothers, sitting here with silver medals. This is
awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   The two blonds, who lost decisively in their final bouts, are
developing a reputation in the boxing world. The New York Post
called Elder ''The Albino Assassin.'' Hudson, to his Cuban
opponent, was simply ''The American.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the competition, they had the most vocal cheering
sections of any fighters. Not only did they have family in the
audience, they were supported by strangers willing to hoist
hand-lettered signs that said ''Jacob! Jacob!'' on one side and
''Ebo! Ebo!'' on the other.
</P>
<P>
   Elder, of Newnan, Ga., lost the final to U.S. teammate Ricardo
Williams Jr. in the light welterweight (139-pound) division 16-4
Saturday night. It was Elder's third loss this year to Williams.
</P>
<P>
   About 24 hours earlier, Hudson, of Augusta, Ga., was out-pointed
by Cuba's Mario Kindelan in the lightweight (132-pound) division
13-4. Both bouts were shown on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   The two runner-ups are close, having known each other since they
were about 10, and used to punch in the same weight class.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've had some great fights together,'' said Elder. Both
claimed not to know their record against each other.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ebo was smaller for a long time,'' Hudson said, ''and all of a
sudden, he takes some time off (after the 1996 Olympic trials) and
he's twice as big as me.''
</P>
<P>
   Each is learning from international experience as they head
toward the 2000 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't know what to expect as far as the outcome, but I knew
I was giving 100 percent,'' Elder said. ''It came out very good,
maybe not the best, but we're having fun with it anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   For Hudson, the Goodwill Games offered his first chance to box
against an opponent from Cuba, which has traditionally fielded some
of the world's best fighters.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought I was a little bit stronger than he was, and he
didn't like my strength,'' Hudson said. ''He wanted to lean on top
of me. He knew he was ahead, so all he did was run. I tried to wave
him to come on, but he didn't want to come on, because he knew
that's where my fight is _ inside. He did what was smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Both fighters are in the U.S. mix for the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got a whole team of young fighters who all have the
ability to do whatever they want,'' Elder said, ''as long as they
work for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
