<DOCNO> NYT19980802.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-02 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4372 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIVORCED-DAD-COX     08-02 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIVORCED-DAD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Summer's father-son reunion will last more than a lifetime
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Each morning for the last three weeks my
6-year-old son, Patrick, awakened me with the same words: Dad,
let's go check the baby bird. And each morning we would quietly
exit the back door and add another installment to our backyard saga
of life, death, deceit, cunning, determination and strength.
</P>
<P>
   My son is a product of the new American divorce, a boy who knows
his way around airplanes, airports and the rules of carry-on
baggage. Three weeks is his allotted summer vacation time with me.
Three weeks to connect and then, just like that, disconnect, pack
the bag, make the bed, put away the Legos and pool toys until the
next time.
</P>
<P>
   His teenage sister, Mary, lives here, but the other, Georgia, is
in Paris for the summer studying art. It's the first summer she's
missed, and I miss her. In past years I started counting the hours
to their departure before their plane touched down. Now, I count
just Patrick's.
</P>
<P>
   So, when a family of cardinals set up house in a Chinese orchid
tree just below Patrick's bedroom window, I thought: This is nice.
This is stuff memories are made of. Cozy lessons about life will
devolve upon Patrick, I thought.
</P>
<P>
   First lesson: Birds die.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning Patrick flew in from Boston, three baby birds
squawked in the nest. We erected a stepladder about 10 feet from
the nest, so as not to bother the birds. Then we peeked. Every hour
thereafter Patrick had to climb the ladder to sneak a peek. The
next day he noticed the attrition.
</P>
<P>
   A bird is gone, Dad.
</P>
<P>
   These things happen, Pat.
</P>
<P>
   Find it, Dad.
</P>
<P>
   Late that night, with Patrick asleep upstairs, I sipped a coffee
and watched a rising full moon make long shadows in the yard. And
there on the pool deck, still warm from the afternoon sun, basked a
big rat snake. With a bulge in his belly.
</P>
<P>
   Up the ladder I went, with a flashlight. A look in the nest.
Another bird gone. Just one remained.
</P>
<P>
   I grabbed the long aluminum pool pole and jabbed the snake. It
wrapped itself around that pole in a perfect coil. A sailor
couldn't have done better. Then I launched it over the hedge into a
tall palmetto palm.
</P>
<P>
   One bird left. If that little puff ball went missing, I'd put a
fake bird in the nest.
</P>
<P>
   Next morning I told Patrick of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   From then on, he asked to check the remaining bird every
half-hour. I think he asked in his sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Then the grackles came, devious and cowardly devils that would
flee the tree as I stabbed at them with the long pole. Then they'd
circle back and come from the other side. For two days the grackles
came. Don't hurt them, Dad, said Patrick. Just make them go away.
</P>
<P>
   Then the mockingbirds. Brazen fellows. I lunged at them with the
pole and they'd step off their branches right onto the tip, as if
to say, thank you, now just drop us in yonder nest.
</P>
<P>
   Tree frogs. Do they eat birds? We consult the nature books.
Carpenter ants, curly-tailed lizards. The orchid tree was alive
with peril.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the thunderstorms. And who do we find on the wet
bricks under the nest after one deluge but the bird. It's hopping,
in a pathetic sort of way. Its parents are hopping mad.
</P>
<P>
   Build a nest, Dad. So we put the bird in a big, wicker dog bed
stuffed with leaves and Spanish moss.
</P>
<P>
   More rains the next day. The bird is a wet, quivering ball of
fuzz. I put an umbrella over the dog bed, but I'm sure the bird is
doomed.
</P>
<P>
   For three mornings running I dread the status check. But each
morning, there it is, dry and pouting for food. Patrick keeps his
distance, but he tells the bird everything will be OK. What does he
know?
</P>
<P>
   Then a couple of days later the bird hops up on the edge of the
dog bed. Its parents are across the yard, calling. The chick
flutters off the nest and begins stumbling across the yard with all
the grace of a drunk on a tilted sidewalk. The parents swoop down
and sweep the grass with their wings. The chick imitates them. He's
airborne. Maybe 2 inches high.
</P>
<P>
   The family disappears into the brush. We hear them for two days.
Three voices, one very high. Then, they're gone. Three weeks, start
to finish.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick packs his bag. He's leaving. The nest high in the tree
is empty. I don't look forward to seeing it sway in the fall winds.
I might take it out.
</P>
<P>
   Where's the bird, asks Patrick.
</P>
<P>
   Airborne, gone, growing up, seeing the world, I tell him.
</P>
<P>
   Just like Georgia in Paris, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Yup, just like your sister, I say.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Reid writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
