<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's Bill's fault, but it's Hillary who let us down
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It was about 11 in the morning before I
could pick up the front page of the newspaper. I guess seeing it in
black and white made it that much more distasteful.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agreed to deny it,'' the headline said, and I knew right
then I wasn't going to like what I was about to read.
</P>
<P>
   So I came to work and drank my coffee and pretended to be both
well-informed and well-adjusted about Bill Clinton's shortcomings,
which we've known for awhile now are many. And as the day, and my
nerve, progressed, I began to gingerly digest the details of the
Monica Lewinsky immunity deal almost as though I was snapping back
from the flu and had to start off with a glass of flat ginger ale.
</P>
<P>
   Sips. Little sips.
</P>
<P>
   What's so unfair about all this is that I should be furious with
him. The realist in me knows that. I should hate him. Detest him. I
should forget about the kid from Hope and the bumper sticker I put
on my truck seven years ago and the way he and Hillary looked at
each other as they danced on the night of his first election.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I'm furious with Hillary.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I'm thinking, ``How could she? Why did she?''
</P>
<P>
   It's unfair, I suppose, to turn so quickly on a woman whom I
have always held in such high regard. And if ever Hillary needed a
good friend, it is now. But part of my anger is so simple, really,
so basic.
</P>
<P>
   She's not living the life she's telling us to lead. She's not
leading the life she deserves.
</P>
<P>
   Women supported Hillary Clinton, and thus, her husband, because
she is smart and powerful and appeared to be kind and generous.
Women supported her because she was a good mom. Hillary affirmed
all the things we knew about ourselves but were still just a little
unsure of. We'd hacked our way through the male world for so long
that we still loved the repetition.
</P>
<P>
   But what kind of lesson did she teach us, really? More to the
point, what kind of lesson did she teach her impressionable
daughter, Chelsea? That it's OK to go through a marriage constantly
worrying that your husband might be with another woman? That
cheating's OK as long as the two of you are good and powerful
together?
</P>
<P>
   A big part of me can't wait for someone to hurry up and write
the Clinton's inside story. I am hoping, praying, for a few
late-breaking good reasons that might make it as clear as a bell
why Hillary stood by her man for all these years.
</P>
<P>
   Yet I realize a good explanation is impossible. I think I knew
that back in January when I first heard the words Clinton, intern
and black dress strung together.
</P>
<P>
   I had another column ready to go for today. It was a lovely
story about my dear friend's coming marriage and the fact she's
found her first real love at age 41. But publishing a story about
the bliss of romance four days after I sat at my desk with a sour
stomach and sipped the Monica-Bill story somehow didn't seem right.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed a little like I was going through life with my heart
in the right place _ but my head on wrong. And I'm afraid Hillary's
done enough of that for all of us.
</P>
<P>
   Emily J. Minor writes her column for the Palm Beach Post, West
Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
