<HEADER>
A4374 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RYAN-TRIVIA-COX     08-02 1474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-TRIVIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Saving Pvt. Ryan: How did they do that? What did that mean?
Here's the scoop
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've heard the hype. Read the reviews. Seen the movie _
``Saving Private Ryan.'' Still want to know more about director
Steven Spielberg's intense World War II movie?
</P>
<P>
   Read on. We've emptied our notebooks and spared no trivia in
assembling this story about the drama that has captured Hollywood's
box office and America's imagination.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where's the music? Believe it or not, in this age of big
soundtrack movies, the two-hour, 50-minute ``Saving Private Ryan''
contains only 38 minutes of music. That's according to Spielberg,
who says the silence was intentional _ especially during the nearly
half-hour opening scenes of D-Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Williams, who's done every one of my movies, was the
first one to say, `Thank goodness I don't have to score the war
scenes,''' Spielberg said during a recent Atlanta visit. ``John
said, `I'd love to see a few of the battle scenes from the `Raiders
of the Lost Ark' movies with my music out, to see if it lends more
realism to those scenes without the Hollywood orchestra playing
along.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, a soundtrack with Williams' ``Ryan'' music,
including the moving ``Hymn to the Fallen,'' which opens and closes
the CD.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where's the dialogue? War may be hell, but it's not
particularly chatty. That's according to famed military author
Stephen E. Ambrose (``Citizen Soldiers,'' ``Band of Brothers''),
who served as a historical consultant on ``Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg's film is rife with such realistic touches as mortally
wounded soldiers ``wetting their pants and pleading for mother,''
Ambrose said, adding that gunfire often masks most of the
battlefield talk in ``Ryan.'' That's heresy by the standards of the
Hollywood that turned out such glamorous World War II epics as
1962's ``The Longest Day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In (`Longest Day' producer Darryl) Zanuck's film and in all
the others, whenever there's dialogue, the sounds of battle
mysteriously disappear,'' Ambrose said. ``Zanuck wasn't going to
pay John Wayne all those big bucks and then not hear what he had to
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've seen the Spielberg film. You've gotta lean forward and
you still miss half the dialogue,'' Ambrose continued approvingly.
``It's because of the battle noise. Because that's the way it
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Napoleon not included: Spielberg broke with a lot of war movie
convention in making his film, including the one about rank having
its (height) privileges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The officer is always taller than the enlisted men (in typical
war movies),'' said Lewis H. Carlson, a Western Michigan University
history professor whose oral histories of World War II POWs was
just published in paperback under the title ``We Were Each Other's
Prisoners.''
</P>
<P>
   The height report on ``Ryan''?
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Miller (Tom Hanks) may be the highest-ranking, but ``he's
not the tallest,'' Spielberg said. ``As a matter of fact, I think
Tom Sizemore (who plays the second-in-command sergeant) and Eddie
Burns (a private) are the same size as him. And Vin Diesel (another
private) is taller.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The mystery word: He may be fluent in several languages, but
Cpl. Upham (Jeremy Davies) has never heard the word FUBAR _ a
favorite acronym among the soldiers, standing for a hopeless
situation _ when he joins Hanks' platoon as a translator.
</P>
<P>
   Upham's not the only one: Spielberg admitted he was unfamiliar
with that authentic piece of Army slang until his father, a World
War II vet, brought it to his attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad said, `Do you have the word FUBAR in this film?' And I
said `no,''' Spielberg recalled. ``He told me what it meant and he
said, `We used to say it all the time,' so we wrote the scenes in.
The whole thing came from my dad.''
</P>
<P>
   FUBAR. Upham spends much of ``Ryan'' trying to learn what it
means. So will you. Here's a hint _ the ``B-A-R'' stands for ``...
beyond all recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The very first review? Everything on ``Ryan'' was about 95
percent complete when it got its first full viewing by ... who
else? Spielberg. But Ambrose was close on his heels, although not
without a bit of persuading.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the second person to see it,'' recalled Ambrose, who had
no hand in writing the script although Hanks and Spielberg read his
books. ``DreamWorks called me and said, `Mr. Spielberg would like
you to fly to Los Angeles to see the film and tell us what's right
about it and what's wrong.' And I said, `I ain't gonna fly to L.A.
to see a movie!' They were a little startled at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ambrose said they could send him a video in New Orleans, but
instead, DreamWorks flew in the movie and an assistant producer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They rented a theater and they didn't let a regular
projectionist screen it,'' Ambrose went on. ``And I'm sitting all
alone in this 1,000-seat theater and I went in thinking, `Jesus, I
hope this is better than Oliver Stone! (who Ambrose says drew on
another one of his books for the assailed film ``Nixon'') It's no
fun saying a movie's lousy.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan'' was no ``Nixon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I came out just an emotional, physical wreck,'' Ambrose
concluded quietly. ``The (assistant producer) said, `What do you
think?' And I said, `It's the best war movie ever made.'''
</P>
<P>
   _ Whaddya mean it's not perfect?! While Ambrose says Spielberg
got virtually everything right in ``Ryan'' _ the weapons _ he did
wish the director could've included a few other things to make it
even more authentic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard that movie theaters have played around with
smell,'' Ambrose said several weeks ago in Atlanta. ``I said (to
Spielberg) `You know, you could (ITAL) really (END ITAL) overwhelm
if you had the smell of cordite in the air.' And the other thing
is, there's a lot more smoke on a battlefield than you see in this
movie. He didn't even have to reply to that. I just said it, but I
know perfectly well what the reply is: How do you make a movie
where all you see is smoke?
</P>
<P>
   ``I also suggested that they would not have sent a captain in
command of an eight-man squad. It would've been a second
lieutenant. And I was talking to Tom Hanks on the plane (to
Atlanta) and he said he wished that he (ITAL) had (END ITAL) been a
second lieutenant, you know, it would've been more appropriate. But
Spielberg wanted him to be a captain, so he was a captain!''
</P>
<P>
   _ No kilts this time: Of the large number of extras in the D-Day
scene, 750 came from the Irish army. And they weren't new to
movies. Many had worked on Mel Gibson's ``Braveheart.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Which way to the beach? Since the real Omaha Beach is a
protected historical landmark, and it has become too developed over
the years to use as an authentic WWII movie site, filmmakers found
a stretch of beach on the southeast coast of Ireland that resembled
the famous landing spot. They filmed the D-Day landing on the shore
of County Wexford.
</P>
<P>
   _ The remainder of the film was shot in England, most of it at
an abandoned British Aerospace facility in Hatfield, Hertfordshire,
45 minutes north of London. The wheat field seen as part of Pvt.
Ryan's Iowa farm is actually in Marlborough.
</P>
<P>
   _ Why all the bloodshed? ``Omaha Beach was a slaughter,''
Spielberg says in the film's press kit. ``It was a complete
foul-up: from the expeditionary forces, to the reconnaissance
forces, to the saturation bombing that missed most of its primary
targets. Given that, I didn't want to glamorize it, so I tried to
be as brutally honest as I could.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Historical Q&AMP;A:
</P>
<P>
   Question: In preparing to ambush German troops, Hanks and his
men assemble crude bombs that stick to the sides of tanks. Was
there really such a thing as a ``sticky bomb''?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: The film's military adviser Dale Dye notes that sticky
bombs were commonly used and are referred to in the ``Ranger
Handbook of Field Expedient Devices.'' In light of this knowledge,
an expert contacted by the Los Angeles Times found it odd that
Hanks had to explain to his men what sticky bombs were. ``Anyone
who had gone through basic (training) would have known what they
were,'' said Ted Ballard, a historian at the U.S. Army Center of
Military History in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   _ And yours as a human being? Reviews have been nearly
unanimously positive about ``Saving Private Ryan.'' But there has
been at least one professional naysayer. John Podhoretz in the
Weekly Standard, a conservative thought magazine, wrote: ``Omaha
Beach was a site of tragedy and triumph, and it was triumph that
gave meaning to the tragedy. Spielberg's inability to grasp those
ideas ... shows his limitations not only as an artist but as an
adult.''
</P>
<P>
   Contributing: news services, DreamWorks
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
