</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VETS-RYANMOVIE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Graphic `Ryan' reopening veterans' emotional wounds
 &HT;    By Carolyn Susman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``Whe-e-e-e-ew,'' Chip DuFour whistled
through his teeth. ``Welcome to the real war.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vietnam combat veteran was picking at a hot plate special at
Denny's after viewing Steven Spielberg's controversial new movie,
Saving Private Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   The three-hour film is a graphic and relentless look at the
storming of Omaha Beach in France during World War II, and its
brutal depiction of war has been especially disturbing to some
veterans.
</P>
<P>
   So much so that the Department of Veterans Affairs alerted
counselors nationwide and set up extended hours on its hot line _
(800) 827-1000 _ when the movie opened two weekends ago. The 800
number is still available.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first 30 minutes, I couldn't take my eyes off the
screen,'' said DuFour. ``It stirred up a lot of feelings. I may not
get much sleep tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Homeless until he landed recently at Vetsville Cease Fire House,
a West Palm Beach shelter for veterans of all wars, DuFour attended
the movie with Chris Noel, Cease Fire House's founder. Noel, a
former actress and model, saw the terrors of Vietnam as an
entertainer and radio show hostess who toured battlefields.
</P>
<P>
   Both were especially shaken by the graphic World War II scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen death before ... '' DuFour trailed off, but then
admitted, ``The old arm went up (to protect himself) in defense.''
</P>
<P>
   These reactions are typical and normal for combat veterans,
especially those who thought they had coped well, says Dr. William
Weitz, a clinical psychologist at the Palm Beach Vet Center in Lake
Worth, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Weitz, who hasn't been in combat but has worked with veterans
for 30 years, says the movie ``is unearthing the emotional
component of (World War II) that hasn't ever been resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Veterans) assume they're having a psychiatric breakdown. One
of the things we want to do is say, `That's not the case.' It's a
normal and natural reaction to trauma that's been unearthed at this
time. We can help them understand where this is coming from, so
they're not overwhelmed.''
</P>
<P>
   Right after the movie opened, some 100 veterans called the
national hot line with symptoms such as crying, anxiety and
heightened excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're emotionally responding in ways that are not controlled
or calm,'' Weitz said. ``The stimulus is the film.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Troyer, a Vietnam combat veteran and clinical social
worker, agrees that veterans should understand that an overly
emotional reaction doesn't mean they're crazy or going off the deep
end.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should realize this is connected to something they've
experienced,'' he said. ``I've seen suppressed trauma pop up 50
years later.''
</P>
<P>
   Troyer, the manager of the Mental Health Clinic at the VA
Medical Center in West Palm Beach, says he's had veterans walk in
who were disturbed by the film and said it triggered a bad
reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Other films have stirred similar reactions. The VA set up a hot
line when Oliver Stone's Platoon was released, and Troyer says even
Titanic's drowning sequences triggered a delayed onset of Post
Traumatic Stress Disorder in some World War II Navy veterans.
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted that veterans aren't the only ones
emotionally affected by Saving Private Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter, Fla. psychologist Dr. David Shaw saw the movie and
heard people crying and sobbing in the audience. Even though he
isn't a combat veteran, he said it took him two hours ``to come
down'' after the film was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here comes Steven Spielberg with an extremely graphic film
showing really great details in terms of violence of people being
killed,'' Shaw says. ``It makes perfect sense that anybody who
fought in any war or witnessed violence in any capacity may have a
Post Traumatic Stress reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   He advises anyone who is disturbed by the movie to talk to
someone they trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if it really creates a reaction _ flashbacks, sleep
disturbance _ absolutely, they should been seen by a
professional.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people think talking about it makes it worse,'' Shaw
says, ``but it really would be helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Susman writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
