<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-02 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4377 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-AGING-COX     08-02 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-AGING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GSU prof: Movies cast elderly in a negative light
 &HT;    (EDS: Jaye Shaner is cq)
 &HT;    By Ellen Lee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The emperor in the ``Return of the Jedi'' is the
epitome of bad. So is Judge Doom, who tries to destroy Toontown in
``Who Framed Roger Rabbit.''
</P>
<P>
   They're old, too. Emperor Palpatine, in fact, is probably 100 to
200 years old, at least in the land of the Dark Side.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidence? A Georgia State University professor thinks not. In
a study of 1980s blockbuster movies, Jaye Shaner, an assistant
professor of communication, found that older adults are rarely seen
in major movies and when they are, they are often portrayed as
evil.
</P>
<P>
   Shaner and graduate student assistant Kristen Davis studied the
top two movies for each year from 1980 to 1988, taking notes on the
characters who spoke, their portrayal and dialogue, including any
reference to age or aging. They also counted how many adults older
than 60 appeared in each movie.
</P>
<P>
   The emperor and the judge were two of many characters Shaner
analyzed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to know how many older characters there were and what
they're saying,'' Shaner said. ``We wanted to see the messages
they're sending about being old and young.''
</P>
<P>
   A few movies, such as ``E.T.: the Extra-Terrestrial,'' had none
or very few older adults. In total, 7 percent of the characters
were older than 60.
</P>
<P>
   That's small compared with the actual percentage of older adults
in the United States, Shaner said. In 1990, 12.6 percent of the
U.S. population _ 31 million people _ was age 65 or older. The U.S.
census estimates that by 2020, older adults will number nearly 53.2
million.
</P>
<P>
   Yet more distressing, she said, was that many of the older
characters turned out to be the bad guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not so worried about whether they're present. I'm more
worried about what their presence is like when they are there,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm bothered about the evil in its purest form, but I'm also
bothered because these movies are attractive to children,'' Shaner
said. These negative portrayals of older people, especially in such
popular movies, could promote stereotypes, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Making older adults the bad guys makes sense, said Bard
Lindeman, 69, of Stone Mountain, who writes a syndicated column
about aging and is a former editor of the magazine New Choices,
formerly known as 50 Plus. Because of society's perceptions of
aging, it's a logical and convenient step to make older adults evil
and cruel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to portray this older person (as evil). Perhaps he's
frail, perhaps he's fighting osteoporosis, so he has a hump or
something, so the next correlation is to make him look poorly and
act poorly,'' Lindeman said.
</P>
<P>
   But older adults are not the only ones stereotyped in movies,
Shaner found. The ``perfect age'' in the movies may be somewhere
between the late 20s and early 30s, because she found that both
older and younger adults often fall into certain stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being old is bad and being young is bad. When you're under 28,
you're called `kid' in a derogatory fashion,'' Shaner said. ``But
when you become older, say 35, you suddenly become set in your
ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaner plans to present her findings in November at the National
Communication Association convention. She also intends to continue
investigating the portrayal of older adults in movies from the
1930s to the 1990s. As baby boomers grow older, she's also looking
at whether changing demographics lead to more or fewer older
characters and how they are portrayed. Shaner's findings point to
the responsibility Hollywood and the media have in influencing the
public's perception of older adults, said Charlee Lambert, a writer
and lecturer on aging issues. ``Let's look at what's really going
on and picture (older adults) as they are, not as bad or
indifferent.''
</P>
<P>
   Certain images of older adults dominate: the senile, perverted
old man or the sweet, cookie-baking grandmother, for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have to watch out for is when we use stereotypes
instead of reality,'' said Barbara Payne-Stencile, founder of the
gerontology department at the University of Georgia. ``All older
people are not alike, (the media needs to) show their differences,
that they are both good and bad. Don't make them all senile or
always have Alzheimer's.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
