<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   By LEAH GARCHIK 
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
     MUTTON SUET GILDED THE LILLIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Lillie Hitchcock Coit &LR; , the San Franciscan renowned in the
Victorian era for her passion for watching fires, smoking cigars,
drinking bourbon, playing poker and, on occasion, getting all
dressed up as a man, was also a food-lover credited as an
originator of the first ``California cuisine.'' The Bancroft
Library's new ``Recipe Book of  &UR; Lillie Hitchcock Coit &LR; ,'' printed
by Arion Press, is being sold as a fund-raiser for UC Berkeley's
collection of rare and special books.
</P>
<P>
   Coit, born at West Point, came to San Francisco when she was 8
in 1851. She grew up here and in Paris, married  &UR; Benjamin Howard &LR; 
 &UR; Coit &LR; , a stockbroker her parents hated, and lived lavishly in San
Francisco and in Napa until 1904, when she moved abroad for 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   When she died in 1929, part of her legacy to San Francisco was
used to build Coit Tower on Telegraph Hill. Her recipes _ from
curry to stuffed pigs' feet to ``carne con chile,'' as she called
it _ reflect a grand world view, and a peek into the looking glass,
too: Coit's cold cream concoction uses wax, mutton suet and almond
oil.
</P>
<P>
   The book, around $21, is available from the Bancroft Library in
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; IN THE WHITE HOUSE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Sidney Blumenthal &LR; , aide to &UR; Bill Clinton &LR; , has framed his
subpoena from  &UR; Kenneth Starr &LR;  and placed it on view in his White
House office, reports the National Journal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Tom Johnson &LR; , chairman and CEO of CNN, has sent an apology to
the family of  &UR; Richard Nixon &LR;  for CNN's discredited report on the
use of nerve gas in Laos.
</P>
<P>
   The formal letter included a handwritten P.S.: ``As a former
assistant to  &UR; President Johnson &LR;  ('65 to '73), I am especially
sensitive to the impact of incorrect reporting about a President. I
have many good memories of President Nixon and his family. Pls.
know how much I regret this error.''
</P>
<P>
   - The Secret Service agent who stood next to  &UR; Ronald Reagan &LR;  at
the 1982 White House Easter Egg Roll (says a report in the
Washington newspaper the Hill, citing a story by  &UR; David Greenberg &LR; 
