   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; BARNEY BLASPHEMY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A prankster (probably now an unemployed prankster) got into a
press release that accompanied a collection of ``Barney'' cassettes
and changed some of the text, reports the New York Post.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of having those little s-s clamoring to stop at the
next McDonald's,'' said the release, `` ... or those interminable
whines of `I really gotta go Mommy,' plug their ears with these
latest banalities.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tim Clott &LR; , CEO of Lyrick Studios, which produced the tape,
expressed his regrets. ``It's a shame that Barney, who stands so
much for trust and innocence, can become the target of such a
malicious prank.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; PETE STARK PROTECTS OUR PRIVATES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Representative  &UR; Pete Stark &LR; , D-Hayward, has introduced the ``No
Private Contract to Be Negotiated When the Patient is Buck Naked
Act,'' reports the Washington paper Roll Call.
</P>
<P>
   The text says it is intended ``to limit the ability of
physicians to demand more money through private contracts during
periods in which the patient is in an exposed condition.''
</P>
<P>
   If it passes, Health and Human Services Secretary  &UR; Donna &LR; 
 &UR; Shalala  &LR; would be ordered to issue rules prohibiting the discussion
of a contract when ``The patient is buck naked and the doctor is
fully clothed, ... The patient is wearing one of those short,
flimsy little hospital gowns that don't close in the back; at any
time the patient's legs are in a stirrup device.''
</P>
<P>
   Roll Call says that ``maybe a stripped-down version could pass
by the end of the session.''
</P>
