<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   By LEAH GARCHIK 
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
     MUTTON SUET GILDED THE LILLIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Lillie Hitchcock Coit &LR; , the San Franciscan renowned in the
Victorian era for her passion for watching fires, smoking cigars,
drinking bourbon, playing poker and, on occasion, getting all
dressed up as a man, was also a food-lover credited as an
originator of the first ``California cuisine.'' The Bancroft
Library's new ``Recipe Book of  &UR; Lillie Hitchcock Coit &LR; ,'' printed
by Arion Press, is being sold as a fund-raiser for UC Berkeley's
collection of rare and special books.
</P>
<P>
   Coit, born at West Point, came to San Francisco when she was 8
in 1851. She grew up here and in Paris, married  &UR; Benjamin Howard &LR; 
 &UR; Coit &LR; , a stockbroker her parents hated, and lived lavishly in San
Francisco and in Napa until 1904, when she moved abroad for 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   When she died in 1929, part of her legacy to San Francisco was
