<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HATCH URGES CLINTON TO `POUR HIS HEART OUT' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah, Conn., Mass.)  (lb) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Orrin Hatch, the chairman of the Senate
Judiciary Committee, said Sunday that President Clinton should
``pour his heart out'' to the American people about his
relationship with Monica Lewinsky, and that by doing so he could
take the steam out of any possible drive to impeach him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he comes forth and tells it and does it in the right way
and there aren't a lot of other factors to cause the Congress to
say, `This man is unfit for the presidency and should be
impeached,' then I think the president would have a reasonable
chance of getting through this,'' Hatch said on the NBC News
program ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the American people would breathe a sigh of relief,''
added Hatch, R-Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats too were beginning to suggest that some sort of public
accounting from the president would be useful, although some
actively asserted Sunday on the talk shows that he had already told
the truth when he denied having ``sexual relations'' with Ms.
Lewinsky, a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the truth, members of Congress said that the Lewinsky
matter, which has preoccupied official Washington since January,
had poisoned the culture.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., defended the president and said
that everyone wanted to avoid a constitutional crisis, but he added
that the allegations of an affair had besmirched the public
discourse.
</P>
<P>
   ``This episode is sorry, and it is sordid, and it has brought
down not only our government and the head of our government, but
the whole country,'' Lieberman said on the CNN program ``Late
Edition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, the very fact that I have not been able to
automatically let my young daughter sit with me and watch the news
anymore tells you what has happened here,'' he added. ``And,
honestly, we don't know yet whether we _ about this degradation of
our process and our culture to some extent _ we should blame the
president, Ms. Lewinsky, Ms. Tripp, Judge Starr, or the media, or
all of them to some extent. But the fact is, it's had an effect,
and it's not a good one.''
</P>
<P>
   The comments came as Clinton returned to Washington Sunday from
a weekend of raising money in the Hamptons, in Long Island, N.Y.,
and began to prepare for his Aug. 17 testimony before a grand jury.
The testimony will be broadcast from the White House to grand
jurors, and will be recorded on videotape, the president's attorney
has said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has vigorously denied two sets of allegations, that he
had sexual relations with Ms. Lewinsky, who is now 25, and that he
had urged her to lie about their involvement.
</P>
<P>
   But his agreement last week to testify, after being subpoenaed
by Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel, seems to have emboldened
some here to urge him to be forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton has not been truthful, Hatch said, ``just a mere
apology is not enough here _ he'd have to really pour his heart out
to the American people.'' Hatch even offered an avenue of plausible
explanation for the president _ saying that he lied to protect his
wife and daughter. Going this route, Hatch said, would ``go a long
way'' toward derailing any move to impeach him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he'd be more respected for having done so,'' Hatch
added, ``and I think he could walk away with his head held high.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., a member of the House Judiciary
Committee, which is where any impeachment investigation would
begin, said he did not presuppose that the president was lying.
</P>
<P>
   But Frank did say that after the president testifies, he should
tell the nation ``at some point'' what he told the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the timing is a question,'' Frank said on CBS' ``Face
the Nation.'' ``But I do think it would be useful at some point for
him to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   George Stephanopoulos, a former top aide to Clinton and now a
commentator on ABC's ``This Week,'' said that it was ``unlikely''
that Clinton would stick to his previous denials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is a smart man who cares about his presidency
and he cares about the country,'' Stephanopoulos said. ``And I
think he knows that if there's any chance that he doesn't tell the
full truth to a criminal grand jury, Ken Starr's grand jury, then
the rest of his presidency will be crippled by impeachment
proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that Democrats on Capitol Hill want Clinton to address
the nation. ``Democrats believe the best thing for him to do right
now is to go forward and tell the story and people will forgive
it.'' He said that Clinton should get a sense on Wednesday, when he
is planning to meet with Democrats on Capitol Hill, about how much
support he has _ ``and it won't be a lot right now.''
</P>
<P>
   William Kristol, editor of the conservative Weekly Standard and
also a commentator on ABC, said that Democrats have already
``signaled to the president they could not support his denial
strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Every Democrat you talk to outside the White House
orbit says, `Mr. President, mea culpa is the strategy.'''
</P>
<P>
   Also on Sunday, the attorney for Linda Tripp, whose taped phone
conservations with Ms. Lewinsky prompted the investigation, said
that Mrs. Tripp had seen the cocktail dress that lawyers said Ms.
Lewinsky has told prosecutors contains a stain that is evidence of
a sexual encounter with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``She did see something that appeared to be a stain,'' Anthony
Zaccagnini, the lawyer, said on ``This Week.'' ``What that stain
is, Linda doesn't know. The origin of that stain Linda doesn't
know. Quite frankly, it wasn't something that Linda was quite
gleeful to see.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI is still examining the stain, a bureau spokeswoman said
Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
