<HEADER>
A4407 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-MAIN03-COX     08-02 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-MAIN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McGwire spends lost weekend in Atlanta as Braves win again
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For all 150,095 customers, the weekend menu never
varied. The house special at the Ted? A Big Mac, with flies(cq).
Batting practice flies, nothing stronger. And all the strikeouts
you could stomach.
</P>
<P>
   On the road to Roger Maris and history, Mark McGwire ran into a
familiar, frustrating roadblock. ``Somebody's gonna pay for what
happened here,'' a relieved Bobby Cox said Sunday after the
Braves's 4-3 win over the Cardinals. For the third straight game,
McGwire went not only hitless but deep-less(cq) in Atlanta. He was
0-for-4, striking out his last three at-bats. That left McGwire
0-for-11 for the weekend with seven strikeouts, and stuck on 45
home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Including two games here last August, when McGwire was 1-for-8
with a single and five strikeouts, he's 1-for-19 at the Ted with 12
strikeouts and no homers. In those five games, he hit just five
fair balls; only three were out of the infield, all last year. The
only time he reached base this weekend was Friday when Greg Maddux,
with the count 3-0 and a runner on second base, intentionally
walked McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to go with our normal stuff and hit our spots,'' Cox
said of facing McGwire, who attracted another 49,296 fans Sunday as
Atlanta set a three-game franchise attendance record. ``If you
don't, you know the ball's gonna go bye-bye. You know luck's on
your side when you hold him down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to go out and be aggressive,'' said Kevin
Millwood, who struck out eight (McGwire twice) in seven innings and
raised his record to 12-6. ``Whether he breaks out of his slump, or
whatever they call it, I just tried to go right at him.''
</P>
<P>
   And not peak(cq). On May 14 in St. Louis, Millwood gave up an
opposite-field homer to McGwire. ``He looked like a monster,''
recalled Millwood, who first faced McGwire in spring training.
``You see the guy on TV, you can tell he's a big guy. When he
stands up at the plate, he makes Javy (Lopez) look small standing
there. It's nervewracking. But you've still got to do what you can
to get him out. You try not to look at him while you pitch to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Millwood got McGwire to ground out in the first inning. With the
Braves infield shifted, second baseman Keith Lockhart fielded
McGwire's grounder on the left side of the infield and threw him
out. Millwood opened the fourth by fanning McGwire on a curveball
in the dirt, then threw a fastball by him to end the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know what he's gonna do,'' Cox said of McGwire. ``He
might hit two to seven homers in a series, especially in the
daytime. We feel fortunate to get out of here with zero.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Seanez, who struck out McGwire in relief in the eighth
inning Saturday, did so again Sunday. By then, the Braves had
scored three runs after Card shortstop Luis Ordaz's two-out error
in the fifth was followed by RBI hits by Lopez, Greg Colbrunn and
Ryan Klesko. When Kerry Ligtenberg pitched a perfect ninth for his
16th save, Atlanta again had dodged a large, red-headed bullet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty amazing how we were able to pitch to him,''
Millwood said of McGwire, now 0-for-15 and in a 4-for-41 slump.
``It's tough to shut him down for three days.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
