A4408 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODWILL-WRAP03-COX     08-02 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODWILL-WRAP03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More success on field than off
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The curtain fell on the 1998 Goodwill Games Sunday
after 15 days of competition punctuated by star performances,
political statements and an unforeseen tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   It was only fitting that the man who unintentionally made it all
happen played a role, too.
</P>
<P>
   Former president Jimmy Carter presented the figure skating
medals Saturday night, then was whisked to the boxing arena for
more ceremonies, handshaking and general goodwill.
</P>
<P>
   If not for Carter's decision to boycott the 1980 Olympics in
Moscow _ and the Soviet Union's retaliatory boycott in Los Angeles
four years later _ Ted Turner never would have seen fit to create
his Games designed to promote peace in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years later, more than $5 million in prize money and
performance incentives attracted 1,500 athletes from 67 countries
to New York for an event that some rank just below the Olympics and
World Championships for Olympic-style competition.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwill Games president Mike Plant, in pronouncing this edition
a success, said one of his colleagues at TBS told him, ``It's the
first time people have felt really proud that the Games are a
property that we own.''
</P>
<P>
   But no one's calling them a cash cow. Plant refused to discuss
losses _ ``We always use the word investment,'' he said of an event
that lost a combined $109 million in its three previous
incarnations. Time Warner's policy is not to divulge numbers, Plant
said, but added, ``We still believe that at the end of the day,
this will be the most financially successful Games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Games only had to pay out a $100,000 bonus for one world
record _ Michael Johnson and teammates on the men's 1,600-meter
relay _ and insurance is paying the medical care for paralyzed
Chinese gymnast Sang Lan.
</P>
<P>
   Promotional fees to athletes such as Johnson, Dan O'Brien,
Jackie Joyner-Kersee and Michelle Kwan paid off with gold medals
and with interest _ from members of the public who usually snap to
attention only during the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest benefactors were the Boys and Girls Clubs of
America, which received $2 million from proceeds and a $25 million
gift from Dan and Merlene Phillips of Dallas-based First Plus
Financial. UNICEF also received $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Several sponsors, Plant said, have already asked about renewals,
``which is a big first for these Games.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials expect final TV ratings on TBS to average about 1.7
(nearly 1.3 million households).
</P>
<P>
   ``Our partners are really happy,'' said Greg Hughes, Turner
Sports vice president of public relations. ``Put it in context _
the Braves do a 1.7, the NBA regular season games do roughly a 1.7.
For 15 nights, three hours a night, it's a solid performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Spectators in the seats were a different story. Plant said he
was pleased with the number of tickets distributed in a tough
market: 350,000 from an available total of about 460,000 (not
including the unused upper deck at Madison Square Garden). Of that
number, about two-thirds were sold and the rest went to charity and
sponsors. By comparison, 780,000 tickets were sold at the 1990
Games in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   There were no operational nightmares of the kind that plagued
St. Petersburg, Russia, four years ago, such as green water in the
pool and early lack of ice at the skating rink. Journalists, who
criticized some operations of the Atlanta Olympics, were frustrated
here by the transportation system and erratic news conference
schedule, but found no fault with the reporting of results.
</P>
<P>
   Now that they've played to the busiest city in the world, would
the Goodwill Games ever consider a trip to Atlanta, which has
experience hosting an event of this nature?
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see,'' said Turner Sports president Harvey Schiller.
``We're going to consider any city in the world. Certainly Atlanta
has the venues _ they can build a new track _ and the public
support.''
</P>
<P>
   And Jimmy Carter wouldn't have to travel so far.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
