<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    National League week in review
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   East
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Braves 5-2 (74-38), Mets 4-2 (58-50), Expos 3-3
(43-68), Phillies 1-5 (55-54), Marlins 1-6 (39-73).
</P>
<P>
   _ Final interleague records: Mets 9-7, Braves 9-7, Marlins 8-8,
Phillies 7-9, Expos 6-10.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wildcard hunt: Mets 3 games back, Phillies 6 1/2 games back.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: The Braves remained quiet before the trading
deadline while the Mets picked up 15-game loser Willie Blair and
another catcher (Jorge Fabergas). Also, they acquired the troubled
Tony Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Mets first baseman John Olerud is hitting .340.
The highest batting average in team history is .340 by Cleon Jones
in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Greg Maddux and Tom Glavine combined to shut
down Mark McGwire, who went 0-for-7 against perhaps the two best
pitchers and didn't get a ball out of the infield. Then McGwire
went 0-for-4 against Kevin Millwood on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: Mets catcher Mike Piazza is 1-for-12 against
his former Dodger teammates.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: Montreal's F.P. Santangelo returned to the club
Friday after being on the disabled list with a bruised knee and
then was hit by pitched on his first to at-bats. However, he
survived.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: The Braves made a hard run at Royals closer Jeff
Montgomery but didn't want to give up any of their top prospects
such as Bruce Chen and George Lombard.
</P>
<P>
   Central
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Astros 6-1 (67-44), Cubs 4-3 (63-49), Reds 4-3
(50-62), Brewers 3-3 (56-55), Cardinals 2-4 (51-59), Pirates 1-5
(50-61).
</P>
<P>
   _ Final interleague records: Astros 10-4, Brewers 8-6, Reds 7-6,
Pirates 6-7, Cubs 5-8, Cardinals 4-9.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wildcard hunt: Cubs lead league, Brewers 6 1/2 games back.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: Houston pulled off the biggest deal of the
season, getting Randy Johnson from the Mariners and he paid off
quickly by winning Sundat. The Cubs picked up reliever Felix
Heredia which should certainly help their bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Cubs outfielder Sammy Sosa hit grand slams on
two consecutive nights. It was the first two slams of his career,
coming after 246 career homers.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Pittsburgh's Jason Schmidt is now 0-7 over his
last 11 starts.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: The ball Cubs first baseman Mark Grace into
the swimming pool at Bank One Ballpark in Arizona is the second one
Grace has gotten one wet this season there.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: Reds infielder Pokey Reese tore a ligament in
his right thumb and may miss the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: In 155 games with the Cardinals, Mark McGwire has
hit 69 homers.
</P>
<P>
   West
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Giants 4-2 (60-51), Diamondbacks 4-3 (41-70), Rockies
3-3 (49-62), Padres 3-3 (72-39), Dodgers 3-3 (57-54).
</P>
<P>
   _ Final interleague records: Dodgers 8-5, Giants 8-5, Padres
6-7, Diamondbacks 5-8, Rockies 4-8.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wildcard hunt: Giants 2 1/2 games back, Dodgers 5 1/2 games
back.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: The Giants worked hard before the deadline,
getting outfielder Ellis Burks to add to a new group which includes
Shawon Dunston and Jose Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Dodgers outfielder Gary Sheffield has reached
base in 43 of his last 44 games.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Arizona's Omar Daal threw a four-hit shutout
Wednesday night, the club's first complete game shutout in team
history. The win came over the Cubs. San Diego's Kevin Brown has
won 10 straight.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: Rockies starter Darryl Kile has now lost 13
games and has not lasted five innings in four of his last seven
starts.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: The Dodgers placed starter Ismael Valdez on the
DL with a strained oblique and inestinal muscle on the left side.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: Dodgers righthander Chan Ho Park is 5-0 with a 1.52
ERA over his last seven starts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
