<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-02 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4413 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEC-QBS-COX     08-02 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEC-QBS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SEC coaches short on experienced QBs
 &HT;    (EDS: Runs with SEC-CHART)
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Putting an inexperienced quarterback on the field
means holding your breath on every single play. That's why most of
the SEC's 12 head coaches will spend the 1998 season waiting to
exhale.
</P>
<P>
   Only three teams _ Kentucky, LSU, and Arkansas _ enter this
season with proven veteran quarterbacks. The rest are dealing with
question marks at the position that stem from injury, inexperience
or both.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky has junior Tim Couch, the Heisman Trophy candidate who
threw for 3,884 yards and 37 touchdowns last season. LSU has senior
Herb Tyler, who showed flashes of brilliance last season. Arkansas
junior Clint Stoerner set a school record last season 2,347 yards
passing.
</P>
<P>
   The other schools will each have a quarterback mini-drama that
will begin with preseason practice and play out over course of the
season. A quick look at each:
</P>
<P>
   ALABAMA: Senior John David Phillips, who has thrown exactly 10
career passes, is competing with redshirt freshman Andrew Zow and
incoming freshman Tyler Watts. Watts, a SuperPrep All-American, is
the Crimson Tide's quarterback of the future but many fans believe
Alabama's future is now. Watts will get a chance to win the job as
Alabama continues to install a new passing offense.
</P>
<P>
   AUBURN: Sophomore Ben Leard of Hartwell, Ga., threw only two
passes as a backup last season to Dameyune Craig. Leard will direct
a more conservative offense built around the running game. ''We're
not going to rely on Ben to win the game like we did with
Dameyune,'' said Auburn coach Terry Bowden. ''His job is to keep us
from losing the game.''
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: Junior Doug Johnson, who was in and out of coach Steve
Spurrier's dog house last season, is still recovering from shoulder
surgery. If Johnson is healthy, he'll compete with sophomore Jesse
Palmer, who is talented but has yet to prove it on the field.
Spurrier, unlike many Gator fans, is not worried. ''One of those
guys will step up and if he doesn't, we may have to play both of
them,'' said Spurrier. ''Hopefully, we'll be able to fling it
around as much as we want to.''
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA: Mike Bobo, the SEC's most efficient passer in 1997, is
gone. Jon England (five career passes) and sophomore Mike Usry
(seven passes) have the most experience. Former Parade All-American
Quincy Carter, who has been out of football for two years, may
eventually be the guy but he's got to learn the offense. Incoming
freshman Nate Hybl is extremely talented and confident after
enrolling last spring. Redshirt freshman Daniel Cobb will compete
if he recovers from shoulder surgery. ''We're going to be very
talented there (at quarterback),'' said Georgia coach Jim Donnan.
''We just have to wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   MISSISSIPPI: Two years ago Romaro Miller was one of the nation's
most highly-recruited quarterbacks after throwing 127 touchdown
passes in high school. He threw only 11 passes as a true freshman
because Ole Miss was involved in so many close games. But the
talent is there. ''He's a guy who will make you miss,'' said coach
Tommy Tuberville. ''We just have to put him in situations where he
has a chance to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   MISSISSIPPI STATE: Junior Matt Wyatt had six touchdown passes
and 15 interceptions last season and is being pushed for the job by
a host of players, including junior Rob Morgan, redshirt freshman
Wayne Madkins and junior college transfer Kelvin Love. The Bulldogs
were third in rushing offense (158.91 ypg) but 10th in total
offense (314.55 ypg) in the SEC last season. The reason? Lack of
production at quarterback. Wyatt is definitely looking over his
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH CAROLINA: Anthony Wright had thrown for 1,685 yards and 18
touchdowns last season when he suffered a severe knee injury in the
ninth game against Tennessee. Wright participated only in passing
drills during the spring, and his role will be changed now that the
Gamecocks are going to a more run-oriented offense. How Wright will
respond is anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   TENNESSEE: Junior Tee Martin threw only 12 passes as a backup to
Peyton Manning, but the job was his on the first day of spring
practice. Martin, from Mobile, got a huge shot of confidence when
he drove the team 80 yards for a late touchdown against Nebraska in
the Orange Bowl. Insiders at Tennessee say the Volunteer offense
won't miss a beat with Martin in control. If anything, it will be
more versatile. ''Tee is further along than most players in his
situation,'' said coach Phillip Fulmer. ''We won't treat him with
kid gloves.''
</P>
<P>
   VANDERBILT: When the freshmen report, Vanderbilt will have six
quarterbacks on scholarship. None of them have ever played a down
of college football but junior Hi Lewis has the inside track. To
complicate matters, Vanderbilt is also installing a brand new
passing offense under first-year coordinator Steve Crosby. ''We're
supposed to have pretty smart guys at Vanderbilt,'' said coach
Woody Widenhofer. ''I guess we'll find out.''
</P>
<P>
   So with all this inexperience at quarterback, what's the bottom
line for the 1998 season? Several coaches said the SEC, which had
seven quarterbacks throw for more than 2,000 yards last season,
will be more run-oriented. Beyond that, it will certainly make for
a most unpredictable year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think you'll see more upsets this year because there will be
more mistakes,'' said Tuberville of Ole Miss. ''They will play some
great games and they will play some poor games. They are going to
scare some people to death. It's going to be very interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
