<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-02 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4414 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AL-WEEK03-COX     08-02 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AL-WEEK03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    American League Week in Review
 &HT;    (EDS: Games still out are: Red Sox-Angels, Yankees-Mariners,
White Sox-Rangers)
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   East
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Yankees 4-1 (77-27), Orioles 4-2 (56-55), Red Sox 4-1
(64-44), Blue Jays 4-2 (56-56), Devil Rays 3-3 (43-65).
</P>
<P>
   _ Final interleague records: Yankees 13-3, Red Sox 9-7, Blue
Jays 9-7, Orioles 5-11, Devil Rays 5-11.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wildcard hunt: Red Sox lead league, Orioles 9 1/2 games back,
Blue Jays 10 games back.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: The Yankees blew a lot of smoke about wanting
to make a deal but did nothing while the Orioles picked up starter
Juan Guzman from the Blue Jays and the Red Sox got Greg Swindell
and Orlando Merced from the Twins and brought back old hand Mike
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Orioles outfielder Eric Davis has a 20-game
hitting streak, a career high.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Yankees reliever Mariano Rivera has converted 17
straight save opportunities while Boston's Pedro Martinez now has
15 wins, tied for the league lead.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: Orioles reliever Jesse Orosco has now appeared
in 1,002 major league games, tied for fifth with Goose Gossage on
the all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: The Yankees lost reliever Darren Holmes for at
least two weeks, going on the DL with a bulging disc in his back.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: Baltimore's Cal Ripken played his 2,650th game,
moving ahead of Joe Morgan for 27th place on the all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   Central
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Indians 3-3 (62-48), Twins 3-3 (51-58), White Sox 2-2
(47-61), Royals 3-4 (49-61), Tigers 2-4 (46-63).
</P>
<P>
   _ Final interleague records: Indians 10-6, Twins 7-9, White Sox
7-9, Tigers 7-9, Royals 9-7.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wildcard hunt: None.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: The front-running Indians decided against
making any moves, coming close on Randy Johnson but in the end
losing him to the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Royals second baseman Jose Offerman has a
21-game hitting streak and is hitting .423 (33-for-78) during that
span.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Tigers rookie Matt Anderson has allowed just one
run and 11 hits in his first 16 appearances.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: The Indians picked up their first
season-series sweep at the Kingdome in franchise history, winning
all five games.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: Indians third baseman Travis Fryman has been
bothered by a sore back.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: Mark Whiten can do anything. Having played on eight
teams in nine years, he was called on to pitch for the Indians in a
12-2 loss to Oakland on Friday and struck out the side in between a
few walks. The last time a non-pitcher took the mound for the
Indians was back in 1968, an outfielder named Willie Smith.
</P>
<P>
   West
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: A's 4-3 (50-60), Angels 2-4 (58-51), Rangers 2-3
(58-51), Mariners 0-5 (48-61).
</P>
<P>
   _ Final interleague records: Angels 10-6, Rangers 8-8, A's 8-8,
Mariners 7-9.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wildcard hunt: Rangers and Angels 4 games back.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: The Rangers made a lot of changes before the
deadline, getting a new left side of the infield in Royce Clayton
and Todd Zeile and also picked up Cardinals ace Todd Stottlemyre.
Also Anaheim's Garrett Anderson saw his 29-game hitting streak come
to an end.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Mariners shortstop Alex Rodriguez has 30 stolen
bases and becomes the eighth AL player in history and first Mariner
to steal 30 bases and hit 30 homers during the same season.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Oakland's Kenny Rogers picked up his 99th career
win. He is 8-0 in 13 home starts in his first season with the A's.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: Last Wednesday's game between the Mariners and
Indians went 17 innings and lasted 5 hours and 23 minutes, the
longest in Seattle history and tied the longest in the majors this
season.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: Angels starter Ken Hill is close to making a
rehab assignment.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: The Rangers' Ivan Rodriguez is considered the best
catcher in baseball, at least defensively, and has allowed just 23
stolen bases but nine of them have been Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
