<HEADER>
A4416 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTH-ASIA-SUMMIT-600     08-02 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-ASIA-SUMMIT-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH ASIANS LAMENT ECONOMIC RIFTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka _ When the seven nations of South Asia held a
summit meeting in Sri Lanka last week, their leaders engaged in
what has become an annual lament, acknowledging that the region has
been an economic backwater for decades. Ending their three-day
meeting on Friday, they vowed, as they have at such meetings for
years, to hasten efforts to break down economic barriers among
them.
</P>
<P>
   But as they headed home, the leaders were faced with a barrage
of skepticism. Throughout India, Pakistan and Bangladesh _ the
three large nations in the group _ and Bhutan, Nepal, Sri Lanka and
the Maldives, critics have despaired of ending the suspicions and
enmities that have blocked economic ties that could help lift their
people out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   This time the disappointments had a ready focus in the failure
of India and Pakistan to agree on resuming talks aimed at bridging
the region's largest rift.
</P>
<P>
   The two nations demonstrated again, after several rounds of
abrasive talks about talks, how difficult they have found it to
reconcile themselves to the bitter events of 50 years ago, when
Hindus and Muslims _ unable to agree on terms for living together _
opted to carve separate countries out of what had been British
India.
</P>
<P>
   What was to have been the crowning event of the summit meeting,
a handshake sealing an agreement on new talks, became a moment for
the two governments to exchange old grievances over Kashmir, the
territory divided between them at the partition of the subcontinent
in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   India's prime minister, Atal Behari Vajpayee, accused Pakistan
of engaging in ``fantasies'' and ``propaganda'' over Kashmir;
Pakistan's prime minister, Mohammed Nawaz Sharif, said India's
refusal to make Kashmir the priority issue in talks meant that the
two leaders were ``wasting each other's time.'' The meeting closed
with a sense of failure.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the standoff appeared to mean that India and
Pakistan will not hold early discussions on ways of lessening the
risk of a nuclear war, the issue that dominated discussion in the
corridors of the summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a stipulation in the regional group's charter that
precludes discussion of politically divisive issues between member
states, the nuclear tests conducted by India and Pakistan in May
were not on the agenda and were not mentioned in the concluding
communique.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee set the pattern with a speech that mentioned the
nuclear tests only obliquely, referring to them as ``recent events
in South Asia,'' and then only to say that there was no reason for
the tests to impede new regional economic ties.
</P>
<P>
   President Chandrika Bandaranaike Kumaratunga of Sri Lanka, the
meeting's host, held to the protocol forbidding discussion of
contentious issues, but made her own feelings clear. Calling for an
``ambiance of confidence'' in the region, she added, ``It cannot be
denied that such an ambiance could be affected by recent
developments.''
</P>
<P>
   A leading Sri Lanka newspaper, The Island, captured the gloomy
mood of the group, the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation, with an editorial on Sunday headed, ``SAARC at a Dead
End.'' ``Ten years of summitry has not brought any tangible results
to the billion people of the region,'' the editorial said, adding
that if political hostilities continue to thwart economic
co-operation, the organization's reason to exist ``is in
question.''
</P>
<P>
   Some optimists said that even if the meeting did go aground over
the hostilities between India and Pakistan, it had served a purpose
in underlining the region's dismal economic state.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Several of the leaders noted that the region, with a combined
population of 1.3 billion people, has the world's largest
concentration of poverty. According to figures quoted here, at
least 40 percent of the region's people live without adequate
shelter, food, education, medical care or even safe drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nations that attended the summit, only the Maldives, with
a thriving tourist industry, has a per capita income as high as
$500 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The point was made forcefully by Vajpayee, on his first trip
outside India since becoming the country's leader after elections
in March. ``We represent great civilizations, ancient yet vibrant
and alive, and yet we are among the poorest in the world,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He made a plea for change: ``Enough of sterile ideology. Enough
of hostile nationalism. Enough of conflict on the basis of religion
and creed. Enough of poverty and backwardness. Let us grow rich
together.''
</P>
<P>
   For many years, India was considered the obstacle to closer
regional ties. But at the Colombo meeting, India led the way in
pushing for lowering trade barriers, announcing that it would
eliminate restrictions that have severely limited imports from its
neighbors of more than 2,000 products.
</P>
<P>
   The seven nations also renewed their commitment to establish a
South Asian free trade area by the year 2001, but many participants
seemed doubtful that the goal could be met. A preferential trading
area, under which each member state agreed to make concessions to
the others not available to other nations, has been bogged down in
red tape since it was established in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   According to Indian statistics, only 3.7 percent of the region's
total foreign trade of about $140 billion is from trade among the
South Asian nations, which trade primarily with Japan, Europe and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   As an example of the dysfunctional economic arrangements in the
region, others at the meeting noted that Pakistan imports iron ore
from Australia, Canada and Brazil, while India has a surplus that
it exports to Japan. Other examples abounded.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, officials attending the meeting acknowledged that
achieving economic momentum among their countries is unlikely until
political tensions abate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
