<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-02 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4417 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-KEISSER-LADN     08-02 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-KEISSER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS DODGING THEIR PAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Angels have never been in a better posi ...
oops, sorry.
</P>
<P>
   In their 37th year, the California Angel are ... darn, let's try
that again.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim Angels have been around now for 37 years, and they
have never had a better opportunity to seize the attention of
Southern California's baseball fans.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, once the most stable franchise in all of sports,
are in virtual chaos, players and front office personnel coming and
going like Metro Rail commuters. They have exchanged their
tradition for the privilege of becoming just another team that
always writes its roster in pencil.
</P>
<P>
   It's never been like this. The Dodgers arrived with a tradition
intact in 1958, won a World Series in 1959, opened a gorgeous
stadium in 1962 and swept the Yankees in the World Series in 1963,
establishing in six short years the foundation of a team that can
draw three million fans a season on spec.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels? They've lingered in the Dodgers' shadow since their
birth. They played in a minor-league park their first season
(1961), became stepchild tenants of the Dodgers in 1962, and moved
to sleepy Anaheim in 1966. They've had three different names (L.A.,
California, Anaheim), once had an obsessive-compulsive free-agent
disorder, have played in three different versions of the same park,
and are still looking to play in their first World Series.
</P>
<P>
   All that noted, there are signs that the franchise is coming out
of the darkness, and not just because the Dodgers are in turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney folk may not appreciate the analogy, but the Angels
are in many ways out-Dodgering the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   First, there's the stadium. Disney spared little in turning the
park into a stand-alone attraction, every bit as comfy and cool as
Camden Yards and Jacobs Field. With Fox in charge, who knows what
Dodger Stadium will look like in three years?
</P>
<P>
   There's player stability. Garret Anderson, Gary DiSarcina, Jim
Edmonds, Darin Erstad and Tim Salmon are all signed through 1999.
That quintet plus rookie Troy Glaus represents two-thirds of the
everyday lineup. Troy Percival also is signed through 1999. Six of
those seven players are under 30.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers only have a dozen players left from their
opening-day roster.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the marketing, the Angels' community outreach
program that is both impressive and prolific.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon donates to two different children's-abuse programs and
buys 200 season tickets each year for kids out in the Fish Bowl
(right field pavilion). Erstad donates $50,000 to the Angels Care
program of charities. DiSarcina has worked hands-on with the
Phoenix House, a substance-abuse program for youths, in building an
athletic field.
</P>
<P>
   Percival, a native of Fontana, is helping build youth programs
and facilities in the Inland Empire. Omar Olivares recently hosted
a day at the park for 175 middle schools kids from Santa Ana.
Shigetosi Hasegawa has made several visits to the Japanese-American
Center in Torrance.
</P>
<P>
   Different players visit CHOC every homestand. The Angels put on
a youth clinic once a week; Mark Cresse's school visits Tuesday.
Rod Carew honors the memory of his daughter Michelle by visiting
with cancer survivors. And Percival recently hosted a young child
through the Make A Wish Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're out there,'' said Tim Mead, the Angels' Vice-President
of Communications, who has worked for the organization since 1981
in a variety of areas, including four years as Assistant General
Manager. ``The philosophy is grass roots. We're not looking for a
big kill, but to build a relationship over time. A team can only
win six months a year, but we can work for 12 months.''
</P>
<P>
   All this may be counterpoint to the way the Dodgers have done
things, but the Angels, from the front office to the field, do not
feel they are competing with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way people feel about (the Dodgers) in many ways is just
the natural order of things,'' said Mead. ``They have more history,
and they were here first. But we really don't compete against
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The players themselves hardly feel there's a rivalry, even with
interleague play putting them on the same field four times a
season. ``Nobody in this room gives a (bleep) about the Dodgers,''
said Percival after hearing one question too many about the Dodgers
during the interleague series.
</P>
<P>
   So all that's left for the Angels is to win. That has always
been the toughest part for the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   In the first year in the switch from the ``Big A'' to the ``Big
Ed,'' the Angels are averaging 30,302 a game. At that pace, they
will crack the two-million barrier for the first time since 1993
and surpass the 2.4 million the team drew in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   But there's been only five sellouts through 59 games. Two
mentalities persist here. One is that some fans only come out to
see the opponent the Dodgers, Yankees and Red Sox being prime
examples.
</P>
<P>
   A promotion this week in which fans could exchange any Yankee
hat for a new Angels hat backfired badly. DiSarcina, a Boston-area
native, understands this dynamic better than most. He has relatives
living here who only ask for tickets when the Red Sox visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothered me my first few years here,'' said DiSarcina about
invading armies of Yankee fans. ``It left me baffled and confused.
Now I've become immune to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The second mentality is that Angel fans fear the worst and are
on guard against being hurt again. They point to the swoon of '96,
the one-pitch-away nightmare of 1986, and the upchuck of a 2-0 A.L.
lead in 1982 as evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans are so programmed to believe the Angels will fold,
and we haven't been able to get over that hump,'' said DiSarcina.
``I meet people and hear things like `We hope you finish strong.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that will stop that is to win a pennant, and
play well after winning a pennant. I think the fans crave it, but
they stay reserved because they don't expect it.''
</P>
<P>
   As of Sunday, the Angels were tied with Texas in the A.L. West
with 52 games to go. If they win the division and play their first
postseason game since 1986, perhaps the fans will reach out.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps then the Angels could find themselves on the new
ground, meaning the same footing as Team Turmoil up in Elysian
Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get tired of that `they let us down' mentality,'' said
Mead. ``But that's the reality. We can reach out a 100 different
ways, but it comes down to winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
