<HEADER>
A4420 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUBA-GRENADA-ART-500&AMP;     08-02 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-GRENADA-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASTRO IS RECEIVED WARMLY IN GRENADA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POINT SALINES, Grenada _ Weapons blazing, U.S. troops landed
here nearly 15 years ago and expelled a militarized Cuban
construction brigade that was building an airport at the tip of
this tiny Caribbean island. On Sunday, Fidel Castro returned to the
site of that bitter defeat, but as the recipient of a 21-gun salute
and the cheers of Grenadians.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban leader, arriving at the third and most controversial
stop of his six-day tour of the English-speaking Caribbean, made
the most of the opportunity to turn the page on what he described
as ``that painful chapter'' of history. He said he was eager to
deepen relations with Grenada, and unveiled a plaque in which
Grenada officially thanked Cuba for the role it played in creating
the airport, which now caters to tourists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt that we owe the Cuban people, especially Fidel Castro,
a special sense of gratitude for what he did for Grenada, in the
building of this extremely important facility,'' Prime Minister
Keith Mitchell said to reporters as he waited for Castro, who
arrived from Barbados just before 1:30 p.m., an hour behind
schedule. ``We have not done so officially, and I felt it was time
to set the record straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the visit was bitterly criticized by some here,
Mitchell also resorted to traditional Caribbean hospitality for the
man he had described as ``one of the most distinguished and
dedicated leaders of the 20th century.'' As Castro shook hands with
Cabinet members and other local dignitaries, a Grenadian steel band
played a calypso version of the Cuban song ``Guantanamera,'' and
colorful banners proclaiming that Grenada and Cuba are ``friends
forever'' fluttered in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   The mere fact of Castro's landing at Point Salines Airport was
fraught with historical irony. The airport project was begun in
1980, shortly after Prime Minister Maurice Bishop and his New Jewel
Movement took power here and began to cultivate close ties with
Cuba. The alliance and the project quickly aroused the suspicion of
the Reagan administration, which saw it as an attempt by the Soviet
Union and its Cuban proxies to establish a military foothold in the
eastern Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop plunged ahead, however, and his relations with the United
States worsened while those with Cuba grew ever warmer. In October
1983, after Bishop was killed in a coup attempt led by a dissident
faction of his own party, the United States intervened militarily,
contending that such a step was necessary to protect the lives of
American medical students studying at a university near the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   During the days of chaos and violence that followed, 19 U.S.
soldiers were killed, along with more than a score of Cubans.
Defying Castro's orders, the rest of the Cuban force eventually
surrendered and returned to Havana in disgrace. Most significant to
the 100,000 residents of this normally relaxed and peaceful island,
an estimated 45 Grenadians also died, opening divisions that remain
at the center of local politics to this day.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In his remarks Sunday, Castro, dressed in his customary military
fatigues, also referred to those events, though more obliquely. He
did not mention the United States or its role in completing the
construction of the airport after the invasion, although a plaque
acknowledging the assistance of the U.S. Agency for International
Development was visible directly behind him. He emphasized instead
the renewal of ties between Cuba and Grenada.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were sad days when our collaboration was interrupted and
our blood was shed, though it was not fighting each other,'' Castro
said. ``It was not to recount, to launch accusations or to pass
judgment that I accepted Prime Minister Mitchell's friendly
invitation.''
</P>
<P>
   Talking to reporters, Mitchell denied that his move to
strengthen ties with Cuba was a rebuke to the United States, which
has drastically cut its aid and diplomatic presence here in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have consistently said that our initiative to strengthen
ties is not meant as anti-anyone at all,'' he said, before
pointedly adding that, ``I have made it very clear to President
Clinton and all the American officials I have met that the United
States needs to do more for the region.''
</P>
<P>
   The warm official welcome notwithstanding, Castro's visit has
been the source of considerable controversy here. Opponents had
scrawled derogatory graffiti such as ``Castro is a dog'' and ``Cuba
si, Fidel no'' along the main road from the airport to the capital,
where Castro was scheduled to attend a state dinner Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Some Grenadians maintain that Castro's presence is inappropriate
because it is too closely linked to the political passions and
excesses of the Bishop era. Others see it as a gratuitous slap at
the United States that wins no material or moral benefit for the
country and the Mitchell government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cuba cannot offer us anything we can use,'' said Lloyd Noel, a
prominent lawyer and newspaper columnist who was the Bishop
government's first attorney general but was later jailed on
political charges. ``There is nothing, and I mean nothing, that we
have to be grateful to Fidel Castro for. What happened in Grenada
between 1979 and 1983 was a direct result of Cuban input.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen figures associated with the group that
overthrew Bishop were tried and convicted after the U.S.
intervention and remain in a prison on a hill overlooking the
capital, some of them serving life terms. ``A sizable minority'' of
the population did not want Castro to come, said Leslie Pierre,
editor of The Grenadian Voice weekly newspaper and himself a former
political prisoner under the Bishop government, because they blame
him for the events of October 1983 and ``can't put the past behind
them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days leading up to Castro's arrival, Mitchell was forced
to address those concerns and to attempt to distance Castro from
any responsibility for the problems of the Bishop era. In an
address to the nation last Tuesday, he called on Grenadians to
welcome the Cuban leader ``regardless of your political views,''
saying it was necessary to help achieve national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand and empathize with those Grenadians who suffered
during the People's Revolutionary Government regime,'' he said.
``But President Castro or any other foreign leader cannot be held
responsible for the negative aspects of the PRG's leadership. It
must be understood that Grenadians led and executed the
revolution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
