<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHEFFIELD TO APPEAL SUSPENSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gary Sheffield will meet with National League
president Leonard Coleman today to appeal the three-game suspension
for his part in the June 28 brawl with the Pittsburgh Pirates. But
he is expected to begin serving his punishment tonight in the
series finale against the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield, who became involved in an altercation with Pirates
catcher Jason Kendall after a near collision at the plate, could
have the suspension cut to two games because he did not provoke the
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall elected not to appeal and already has served his
three-game suspension. Sheffield's only defense is Kendall's verbal
abuse after the collision. Both benches cleared and play was halted
for more than five minutes. Sheffield received five stitches over
his left eye after striking his head on Kendall's shin guard during
the brawl.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is never a good time to face a suspension, especially
when you have a guy as hot as Gary,'' manager Glenn Hoffman said.
``So lets get it over with and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield went 2 for 3 Sunday with an RBI double. He also scored
a run and is batting .365 with eight RBI in his past 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla update:!off Third baseman/left fielder Bobby Bonilla
will test his surgically repaired left wrist today for the first
time since receiving a cortisone shot Friday. Bonilla was eligible
to come off the disabled list Thursday but experienced more pain in
his wrist.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are hopeful Bonilla can return to the lineup before
the end of the road trip. After today's series finale with the
Mets, the Dodgers play three games in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla has used the time off to also rest his left Achilles
tendon, which required surgery last winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was an upside to this experience it was that the
Achilles also got better,'' Bonilla said. ``It has been tough to
sit out, but I feel I'm getting close.
</P>
<P>
   Where's Beltre: General manager Tom Lasorda, vice president
Ralph Avila and coach Manny Mota brought rookie third baseman
Adrian Beltre into Hoffman's office before the game to send him a
message.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't about his fielding, which still is erratic. It was
about his hitting. After he went 2 for 4 with an RBI double, Beltre
is batting a season-high .225.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre left the team hotel ahead the Dodgers' bus Sunday morning
and arrived at Shea Stadium well after.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to make sure how important it is to get to the
ballpark on time,'' Hoffman said. ``He had a brother take him, and
I guess they got lost. Up here, you can't let that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick Hits: Charles Johnson was given the day off after playing
Friday and Saturday night. Tom Prince took his place and went 0 for
3. Prince started Tuesday in Philadelphia when Johnson remained in
Los Angeles while his wife Rhonda gave birth to their first child,
Brandon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
