<HEADER>
A4423 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICHIGAN-GOVERNOR-560     08-02 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICHIGAN-GOVERNOR-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATIC CANDIDATE SAILS AHEAD IN MICHIGAN POLLS, POWERED BY
INVECTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(js) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Before jumping into the race for the Democratic
nomination for governor, Geoffrey Fieger was best known as the
lawyer for Jack Kevorkian, the suicide doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is known as a politician who hurls insults like Thor does
his hammer. A millionaire lawyer in a state that prizes the
lunch-bucket ethic, he has never held political office. Worse yet,
he has been seen driving a Swedish-made car on the streets of Motor
City.
</P>
<P>
   And he is winning, much to the horror of the Democratic Party
and leaders of the United Auto Workers.
</P>
<P>
   Fieger, who leads in opinion polls in Tuesday's contest over two
more conventional politicians, Larry Owen and Doug Ross, cannot
wait to throw insults at Gov. John Engler, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   He has characterized the governor as racist, a moron, a liar,
fat and effeminate. ``Dumber than Dan Quayle and twice as ugly,''
Fieger said about the governor one recent morning, then stopped to
chuckle. A brash populist, Fieger has taken the lead largely by
building support among black voters in Detroit, who like his
irreverent style and unvarnished talk about racism. As a lawyer, he
has won some high-profile civil rights cases. And he talks loudly
and proudly about his father's work as a Freedom Rider in the
segregated South.
</P>
<P>
   ``With his no-holds-barred style, he reminds many
African-Americans of Coleman Young,'' said Mario Morrow, a
political consultant, referring to the first black mayor of
Detroit. ``And Fieger's got this tree-trunk of anger on his
shoulder, which resonates among people who feel disenfranchised by
the system.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidate favored by the autoworkers union, Larry Owen, a
wealthy lawyer and former mayor of East Lansing, has been
desperately trying to court black voters. Earlier this week, he
broke with Michigan tradition and named his running mate for
lieutenant governor, Teola Hunter, a black woman who is clerk of
Wayne County.
</P>
<P>
   Owen has been compared with the former presidential candidate
Walter Mondale, a Democrat who has positions that labor and
liberals find impeccable, but who has little charisma. Political
analysts say it is unclear how the selection of a black running
mate will play: it could win the support of black voters, but it
could also backfire as a transparent political move.
</P>
<P>
   While Fieger leads among blacks in Detroit, Owen has had more
success in the industrial I-75 corridor, which extends north to
Saginaw.
</P>
<P>
   Ross, meanwhile, a former Labor Department official in the
Clinton administration, is known as a pin-striped, businesslike
politician with a voice of moderation. He does best with voters in
the middle-class suburbs of Detroit, and in the western reaches of
the state.
</P>
<P>
   But whomever the Democrats pick on Tuesday, the campaign to
unseat Engler will surely be uphill sledding. Engler, who fits the
socially moderate, pro-business profile that voters in many states
have been choosing as governors in recent years, rides a robust
economy in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, this state had the highest unemployment rate in
the nation. Now the jobless rate in Michigan ranks among the lowest
of the big states, at least before the recently settled auto
workers' strike.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats will try to make political hay of Engler reneging on
his campaign promise to serve only two terms by running for a
third, but a prosperous economy tends to make voters very
forgiving.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While polls show that Engler would have a sizable lead against
any of the Democratic candidates, he does best against the
Democratic front-runner, Fieger.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Engler and the Republican Party are licking their chops
waiting for Geoffrey Fieger,'' said Morrow, noting that Fieger's
brash, take-no-prisoners style would seem unlikely to attract the
conservative and moderate voters needed to win a general election.
</P>
<P>
   While Fieger's prominence initially stemmed from his ties to
Kevorkian, the Democratic candidate has kept his distance from the
physician during the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Fieger has focused on the plight of poor Detroiters,
saying he would revitalize the city's neighborhoods by imposing
tariffs on developers who build on open land in the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Fieger dropped in at a recent picnic on the shores of the
Detroit River, looking more Hollywood than politician, wearing a
white T-shirt and a blue blazer. He kissed and hugged virtually
every woman at the picnic, and talked hip with teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview moments later, Fieger angrily denounced
Engler in personal terms, questioned the mental health of a Detroit
editorial writer and fairly shouted profanities about a local
political consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a loose cannon,'' Morrow said. ``The Republicans would
like to portray him as a lunatic, except that he's rich. When
you're rich, you know, you're just eccentric.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
