<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Chip-Making Process Is Expected From IBM
</P>
<P>
   IBM is expected to announce Monday that it has perfected a new
manufacturing process to produce semiconductor chips that can
achieve either higher speed or significantly lower power
consumption. The new technique is known as silicon-on-insulator, or
SOI, technology.
</P>
<P>
   This is the third major advance in semiconductor design and
fabrication that IBM has announced in the last year. The company's
top research executives said that the latest advance should give
IBM a one-year to two-year lead in the highly competitive industry.
</P>
<P>
   An Internet Site Focuses on Women
</P>
<P>
   Candice Carpenter, who created the World Wide Web site
iVillage.com with a group of investors and has raised $67 million
in financing, has turned it into the leading women's Internet
community. It offers news, columns, advice, tips and opportunities
for women to contribute their own views through chat sessions and
message boards on topics like ``Sex After Kids'' and ``Anger
Management.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress Must Reconcile Three Tax Bills
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Finance Committee passed a version of the Internet
Tax Freedom Act that proposes a two-year moratorium on taxes in
cyberspace. It also voted to force states and local governments
that tax Internet access to end these taxes. But the group's
version differs from the bills passed by the Senate Commerce
Committee and by the House.
</P>
<P>
   NBC Offering Shows on PCs
</P>
<P>
   NBC &UR;  &LR; will invest in and supply programming to a start-up online
service that is providing movies, television programs and music on
demand to personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   SEC Contends Trades Were Concealed
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission has accused Sam Schwartz,
a former top executive of a small long-distance telephone company
called Incomnet, of filing false documents to conceal his trading
in the company's stock. He bought about 1.1 million shares of
Incomnet stock and sold about 900,000 shares from June 1994 through
July 1995 without disclosing the transactions in a timely manner.
</P>
<P>
   Utilities Provide Internet Access
</P>
<P>
   Ben Preusser, business manager for Cyber Trails in Phoenix,
which is a subsidiary of Arizona Public Service, said utility
companies are offering Internet access because they already have
expertise in billing, customer service and computer networking.
Also, 18 states have opened their power industries to some form of
competition, and most others are expected to do so shortly. That
means the utilities not only have to learn to compete, but they
have to seek new sources of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   A Communications Chief Resigns
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Kaplan, the head of corporate communications at Conde
Nast, resigned after reading in The New York Observer that Maurie
Perl, the head of publicity at The New Yorker, would take over
Conde Nast's corporate public relations operation. It had been
reported that Steven Florio, chief executive of Conde Nast, was
dissatisfied with Ms. Kaplan's handling of a Fortune magazine
article.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-98 2034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980802.0128 </DOCNO>
