<HEADER>
A4432 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK03-COX     08-02 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves Notebook: Klesko rediscovers swing after surgery
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Having lost his appendix, Ryan Klesko is still trying
to rediscover a consistent batting stroke. He took another step in
that direction Sunday, when he was a pain in the, uh, side for St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   With Bobby Cox resting Andres Galarraga, Klesko batted cleanup
for just the third time this season and seized the opportunity. He
went 2-for-4 with 2 RBIs in a 4-3 victory over the Cardinals.
Klesko's two-out, opposite-field double in the first inning scored
Keith Lockhart. In the fifth, Klesko capitalized on a two-out error
by shortstop Luis Ordaz.
</P>
<P>
   His single up the middle off Bobby Witt scored Walt Weiss and
tied it at 2-2. After Javy Lopez followed with an RBI single, Greg
Colbrunn (starting at first base for Galarraga) got his first RBI
in his second stint in Atlanta with a double off the base of the
left field wall.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just trying to get back to where I was before I got
hurt,'' said Klesko, who missed nine games after having his
appendix removed June 29. After going 2-for-4 for the second
straight game, Klesko's 10-for-33 (.303) in his last 11 games with
a homer and seven RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ''I haven't been consistent since I've come back,'' he said.
''I've been feeling good the last couple of days. I got some good
pitches (Sunday) to hit. And I've worked on some thins with C.J.
(hitting coach Clarence Jones).''
</P>
<P>
   With today's off day, Cox gave Galarraga Sunday off to get two
days' rest. ''To catch his breath,'' said Cox, who also wanted
Colbrunn _reacquired Thursday in a trade with Colorado _ to get
some at-bats. Cox used Galarraga to pinch-hit in the eighth inning,
when he singled. Colbrunn, meanwhile, was 1-for-3 with an RBI
double and was hit by a pitch his first time up.
</P>
<P>
   No word
</P>
<P>
   Neither Cox nor pitcher John Smoltz, tossed Wednesday in
Cincinnati by umpire Hunter Wendelstedt, has heard from the NL
office regarding their controversial ejections. ''But I haven't
been checking my mail,'' Smoltz said, grinning.
</P>
<P>
   But Cox doesn't expect either fines or suspensions from the
incident in which Wendelstedt tossed Smoltz after stepping on his
foot when the pitcher protested a close call at third base.
</P>
<P>
   ''How could there be?'' asked Cox, who came out of the dugout
after Smoltz was ejected. ''I'll accept a fine any time, but nobody
committed anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers update
</P>
<P>
   Despite not pitching all weekend, Mark Wohlers is encouraged by
several bullpen sessions that may improve his control. Leo
Mazzone's hopeful, too.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been way too far over the top,'' said Wohlers, who's been
working with a three-quarters motion. ''It started climbing and
climbing, and getting higher and higher. If I think sidearm, I get
to three-quarters, where I should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Three good sessions in succession have Wohlers optimistic he may
finally be able to overcome the wildness. ''For the most part,
there were more consistent pitches thrown hard in the strike
zone,'' he said. ''There have been three really good days in a row
where I've thrown the ball as hard as I could.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He's thrown more strikes with some juice,'' said Mazzone.
''Before, it was less strikes and he wasn't cutting it loose.
(Sunday), he threw harder and hit his target more often. There's
some hope there.
</P>
<P>
   ''Before, when he said, 'I'm OK,' I didn't think he was. Now,
when he says, 'I think I'm getting there,' I think he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc. ...
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's sellout crowd of 49,296 gave the Braves a weekend
attendance total of 150,095, a franchise three-game record. The old
mark: 148,095 against Pittsburgh, April 22-24 in Atlanta-Fulton
County Stadium. ... Sunday's game was preceded by the annual Braves
father-children baseball game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
