<SLUG> BC-FALCONS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons settled on WR starters, but not backups
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It will be another week before the picture starts
coming into focus with regard to who will make the Atlanta Falcons'
roster, as they approach the preseason opener Friday against
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   But after a week and a half of training camp, it's a little more
clear at wide receiver. It was a given going in that eight-year
veteran Terance Mathis (5 feet 10, 185 pounds) and nine-year
veteran Tony Martin (6-1, 181) will start.
</P>
<P>
   After that, there's a race between nine other players for three
or four jobs, and perhaps one spot on the practice squad.
</P>
<P>
   Undrafted collegians Corey Allen (6-1, 199) of Georgia and
Octavus Barnes (6-2, 200) of North Carolina remain longshots.
Neither has done much to stand out, partly because they don't get a
lot of opportunities. Van Johnson (6-1, 200), who was cut last
summer from his first training camp with the Giants, likewise
hasn't shown much.
</P>
<P>
   Left to compete for the spots behind Martin and Mathis are
third-round draft choice Jammi German (6-1, 187), fourth-rounder
Tim Dwight (5-8, 181), six-year veteran Todd Kinchen (5-11, 187),
two-year veteran Mercury Hayes (5-11, 195), four-year veteran Keith
Crawford (6-2, 195) and Kevin Thornal (6-2, 186), a member of last
year's practice squad.
</P>
<P>
   Martin replaces Bert Emanuel as the team's chief deep threat,
and he's three inches taller than Emanuel. Receivers coach Rennie
Simmons is surprisingly optimistic about a group that, after Martin
and Mathis, has a total of 100 catches. Kinchen has 84, Crawford 12
and Hayes four.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're bigger and more physical than last year,'' Simmons said.
``We have some guys who have just as much speed. And guys
understand our offense better because some of the guys who were
here ... are able to help teach.''
</P>
<P>
   As high draft choices, Dwight _ expected eventually to be the
team's punt returner _ and German are virtually assured of making
the roster, and they haven't done anything to change the team's
solid impressions of them. That leaves four players competing for
one or two jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we got a lot of guys that are kind of in a group,
and I don't know if any one guy is breaking away,'' Simmons said.
</P>
<P>
   Each player has something working against him. Kinchen's chief
role for the Falcons last year was as a punt returner, but Dwight
led the NCAA last year in punt returns, and his quickness has
caught the eye of coaches.
</P>
<P>
   If Dwight wins that job, Kinchen's in trouble unless he proves
good enough to merit a spot as a receiver. He also has been erratic
in camp, though he was very good the last few days.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford, who first played for Falcons coach Dan Reeves in New
York in 1993, caught a career-high 11 passes last year in St.
Louis. He has good speed and is a good special teams player, but a
hamstring injury has kept him out of four straight practices. He's
been working as the third receiver, but he sometimes runs soft
routes.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes, picked up last year at midseason when he was cut by New
Orleans, strained a hamstring Saturday morning. Speed is also his
top asset.
</P>
<P>
   Thornal, who won a spot on the practice squad last year by
catching almost everything in sight as an undrafted rookie out of
SMU, is again catching nearly everything, and is running better
routes. But he's slight of build, and not exceptionally fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how many we'll keep yet,'' said Simmons, noting
that it depends on the special teams abilities of some players.
``And sometimes it all depends on how things play out with
injuries. Sometimes it plays itself out and it's not a real
complicated thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
