<HEADLINE>
TO PICK A PRESIDENT, PARTIES MUST PART  
 ACTOR-DAIRY FARMER TRIES HAND AT POLITICS  
 FABLE REVISED: HARE KEEPS EYE ON TORTOISE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When sponsors of the ballot initiative that resulted in
California's new open-primary law drafted their measure two years
ago, their aim was to loosen up the election process and encourage
participation. But in trying to make things better, they suffered a
memory lapse that may have made things worse.
</P>
<P>
   What they forgot was that the bylaws of both national parties
prohibit the selection of presidential convention delegates in
primaries that are open to all voters. The rationale: Too much
political mischief can occur.
</P>
<P>
   So now California faces the prospect that its delegations to the
next Democratic and Republican national conventions may not be
seated unless the old closed primary system _ under which Democrats
voted for Democrats and Republicans voted for Republicans and never
the twain met _ is reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   Because convention delegations from California are usually the
most important by virtue of the state's having the largest
population, denial of a role in the presidential nominating process
would be a huge and embarrassing political blow. Such rejection
would undoubtedly throw both nominating conventions into turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   What to do?
</P>
<P>
   Come November, Californians will get an opportunity to vote on a
ballot measure that would retain the open-primary law for the
selection of local, state and federal officeholders but would
reinstate the closed, party-by-party voting system for the
selection of convention delegates.
</P>
<P>
   The state Legislature passed a bill calling for the measure,
labeled the Save the Presidential Primary Act, to be put on the
fall ballot. Gov. Pete Wilson readily signed it.
</P>
<P>
   State officials are confident they can persuade voters to
approve the proposition. If it is defeated, however, leaders of
both major parties will be forced to give consideration to choosing
delegates either by holding party caucuses or by calling statewide
conventions, both less politically tidy solutions than primary
voting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever method it would be, it would disenfranchise millions
of Californians who expect that when voting for president, their
vote matters,'' said state Sen. John R. Lewis, R-Orange County, the
chief author of the Save the Presidential Primary Act.
</P>
<P>
   Actor-Dairy Farmer Tries Hand at Politics
</P>
<P>
   Not a lot of people saw it, but a couple of years ago there was
a low-budget movie about a folksy Vermonter who decided to run for
Congress when he couldn't make it any longer as a down-and-out
dairy farmer. His campaign pitch was that he needed the money and,
ahyep, as they say up there in the Green Mountain State, he won,
his opponent being a caricature of an entrenched Washington pol. Of
course.
</P>
<P>
   The movie was called ``Man With a Plan'' and was produced and
directed by a Vermonter, John O'Brien, who hails from Tunbridge,
one of those clapboard farm hamlets on the east-central side of the
state. He persuaded a neighbor, a real Vermont dairy farmer named
Fred Tuttle, to play the lead role.
</P>
<P>
   Now life is imitating art. With O'Brien as his campaign manager,
Fred Tuttle is running for the U.S. Senate, vying with a
millionaire businessman, Jack McMullen, for the Republican
nomination and the right, come the fall, to take on the popular
four-term Democratic incumbent, Patrick Leahy.
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds more like show biz than politics, truth is it's
both.
</P>
<P>
   Tuttle and O'Brien candidly admit that one of their goals is to
stir up some buzz about ``Man With a Plan,'' which is being
considered for a fall showing on national television. But they
insist they also have a serious political goal, which is to keep
the Republican nomination away from McMullen, because he is not a
native Vermonter.
</P>
<P>
   This is no small matter in a state overrun with outsiders in
search of the good life in a beauteous setting. Well before Tuttle
announced his candidacy, McMullen, newly arrived from
Massachusetts, was being hammered by some native-born Vermonters
for being so brassy as to think he was ready to represent their
state in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Tuttle says he does not plan to represent the state in
Washington. He promises that if he bests McMullen in the primary,
the first thing he'll do is endorse Leahy.
</P>
<P>
   Fable Revised: Hare Keeps Eye on Tortoise
</P>
<P>
   The latest polls indicate that in Tuesday's Republican primary
in Kansas, Gov. Bill Graves will breeze to renomination, turning
back the challenge of David Miller, a former state GOP chairman, by
a margin of at least 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Why, then, has the governor, a moderate, spent close to $1.7
million on the race, a record for a Kansas governor's primary?
</P>
<P>
   The answer lies in voter turnout.
</P>
<P>
   Miller may be trailing badly and scratching around for campaign
money going into the final days of the contest. But as Graves sees
it, there is always the possibility that at the last moment Miller
will energize his base of support _ the Christian hard right, which
he once led in the state _ and the resulting turnout will transform
what had looked like a political blowout into a dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, a last-minute outpouring of Christian-right
voters has swung several Kansas races. So the governor is running
scared, deliberately, spending big bucks to warn his supporters
that if they do not turn out, he could be in big trouble.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the Graves-Miller primary contest is a classic
1990s Republican tiff, a battle not just for control of the party
in one of the most Republican of all states but also a battle for
its ideological soul.
</P>
<P>
   The governor favors abortion rights, has vetoed a bill that
would loosen state gun-control laws and opposes legislation that
would make English the official state language.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, by contrast, opposes abortion, wants fewer gun
restrictions and believes English should be made the state's
official language.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Democratic primary on Tuesday, polls indicate that
Tom Sawyer, the minority leader of the Kansas House of
Representatives, will be a runaway winner. But the polls also
indicate that if he goes head-to-head with the governor in the
fall, the governor will be a runaway winner.
</P>
<P>
   Political Calendar
</P>
<P>
   Michigan and Missouri, as well as Kansas, have primaries
Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
