u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-BLINEBURYCOL-OLAJ     08-02 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-BLINEBURYCOL-OLAJUWON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Olajuwon says he still can provide what Rockets need
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Fran Blinebury &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   ATHENS, Greece _ In a back hallway at the Olympic Stadium, he
sneaks up behind former teammate David Wood and gives him a gentle
elbow in the back that interrupts a television interview and then
dances away giggling.
</P>
<P>
   He wraps up Rockets trainer Keith Jones in a happy bearhug, then
looks across the retaining wall that holds back the media horde and
spots a couple of familiar faces from home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, man,'' says Hakeem Olajuwon, as a grin begins to spread.
``This is just like being in Houston. What are you all doing
here?''
</P>
<P>
   Half a world away and the faces, the jokes and the questions
remain the same. He has spent his summer in his usual style, that
of the international traveler, businessman and ambassador for the
NBA, though the latter role is unofficial this year because of the
labor strife and lockout.
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon has made his annual pilgrimage to Mecca, and his
previous stop was in Jordan before arriving to spend a day at the
World Championship of Basketball. His mood is as light as an Athens
breeze. Yet he knows back in Houston there is concern about his
health, about the bad wheels that were responsible for the worst
season of his NBA career, about advancing age that might be eroding
some of his skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess,'' he says, ``it is not permissible to look at what
happened and acknowledge that I had knee surgery and accept that
anyone is going to suffer in performance because of that. There is
always a need to try to find another reason. Maybe the search can
be more interesting, but it does not necessarily reveal the
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing in the shadow of the Acropolis, he seems a perfect fit
here, having always philosophized like Socrates and Plato while
performing the labors of Hercules on the court.
</P>
<P>
   He knows the end is coming. He has seen his good friend Clyde
Drexler head off into cozy retirement, if that's what you can call
the heady task of trying to revive the glory at the University of
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   But at 35, he says there is no reason to put his career behind
the glass display case of a museum, like it was an ancient Greek
artifact.
</P>
<P>
   ``The left knee, which had the surgery, is feeling fine,'' he
says. ``The right knee was bothering me at the end of the season,
and I thought then that I might need surgery on that one. But I had
an MRI and I spoke to (Rockets team physician) Dr. (Walter) Lowe
and he said we should not operate now. He said there were things he
did not want to touch in my right knee and what I needed to do this
summer was to strengthen both of my quadriceps so that there would
not be as much strain on the knees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The right knee began to bother me after the surgery. It's
natural to compensate. I never got my rhythm back. I was never able
to play with the ease and the flow that makes my game what it is.
If I'm thinking about playing, then I'm not just playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I've been traveling, I've been doing exercises to
strengthen both legs. I've walked up mountains. I want to be ready
whenever the season starts.''
</P>
<P>
   But with nothing to prove after one subpar season in a 14-year
career of setting standards for centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never play to prove anything,'' he says. ``To play to prove
something is to be small-minded. I have a bigger picture. I play to
do all that I can. I play to have fun. I play to win, whether it's
a pickup game at Fonde or in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people look at age and say it is a negative. I think of
it as experience. The game is actually easier for me now. I know so
many things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear people say, `Does he still have the drive after two
championships?' That is a low mentality. It assumes I played harder
in those two years. This is ignorance. They say we won because I
learned to trust my teammates and don't ask if it was a different
system that allowed me and my teammates to thrive.''
</P>
<P>
   And he believes they can thrive again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already have three or four new, young players. There is
money to spend under the salary cap. We should be thinking about
getting young talent. Not Scottie Pippen. Too old. Someone like
(Antonio) McDyess. Young legs and young talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Olajuwon knows all championship hopes begin and end with
him, and he can't understand the sudden panic, even trade rumors.
</P>
<P>
   ``To think I can't play, that is ignorance,'' he says. ``I want
to be healthy. I want to play. I will. Doubt me, go ahead. People
have been wrong about me before.''
</P>
<P>
   From ancient Mount Olympus to modern-day Houston, it's a lesson
the Greeks learned a long time ago: don't make the gods angry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
