<SLUG> BC-HISTORIC-CHURCH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    150-year-old church founded by slaves holds final service
 &HT;    By Jingle Davis
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Members of the Trinity Christian Methodist
Episcopal Church hugged, held hands, wept and remembered as they
bid an emotional farewell Sunday night to ``Mother Trinity,'' the
church that has served their congregation for more than 150 years.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1843 by slaves who bought the freedom of their first
pastor, the church is relocating because of toxic pollution in its
downtown neighborhood from a defunct gas manufacturing plant. Many
members brought cameras and video cameras to document the final
gathering, which closed with the hymn ``Til We Meet Again.''
</P>
<P>
   During the final service in the historic red brick structure,
Maxine Wilson Thurmond, a lifelong member, celebrated the
christening of her 2-week-old grandson, Da'Henri Ramsey Thurmond
Jr. Last month, she mourned at her mother's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother was a part of the past and my grandson is a part of
the future,'' Thurmond said. ``He will be worshiping in the new
church.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is no new church. The congregation will meet at nearby
Paine College until land is purchased and a sanctuary built,
according to the Rev. Ronzell Maness.
</P>
<P>
   For about a century, Atlanta Gas Light Co. made gas from coal at
a plant just across the narrow neighborhood street from the church.
The process of ``cooking'' the coal at high temperatures left
behind coal tar, a byproduct now known to contain substances
suspected of causing cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Before the plant closed in 1955, employees disposed of tons of
coal tar at the site. The sticky, black material eventually seeped
into soil and ground water, contaminating the church yard and other
parts of the blue-collar neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the plant site is surrounded by barbed wire fences posted
with ``Danger: No Trespassing'' signs. Gas company officials,
chastised by environmental agencies for foot-dragging on cleanup
efforts, have said they expect to make ``significant progress''
this year toward sanitizing the site.
</P>
<P>
   Coal tar also contaminated parts of the nearby Augusta Canal,
which flows into the Savannah River.
</P>
<P>
   The company did not appeal a court judgment this spring that
ruled Atlanta Gas Light should pay $3 million to the church, plus
$1 million more in attorneys' fees and interest. The church was a
plaintiff in a class-action lawsuit brought against the gas
company.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the settlement, church members voted to sell the
historic building to the company and relocate.
</P>
<P>
   Louvenia Pearson, 81, said it will be hard for her to move to a
new location.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they said this place is contaminated, so I'm willing to
go,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
