<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-MINERS-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA STARTS TO FEEL PAIN AS MINERS BLOCK RAILS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ No other group embodies the frustration with Russia's
hobbling economic system as much as its coal miners, who have held
sit-ins, marched and blocked rail lines for months over their
inability to get paid _ and all to a collective national yawn.
</P>
<P>
   Now it appears that their protests are beginning to bite.
</P>
<P>
   During the weekend, officials on the island of Sakhalin in
Russia's Far East announced that as a result of a protest by
miners, the officials might have to cut off electricity for 24
hours sometime in the next several days to all but essential users
like water-pumping stations and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Already, many of the island's 720,000 residents are without
power for as much as 14 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   The power shutdowns are rooted in a protest by coal miners, who
have prevented trains from carrying fuel to the island's main
electrical generating station for two weeks. The chief of the
island's main utility, Sakhalinenergo, said Sunday that the company
had only a four-day reserve of coal for the generators.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is that the only miners' protest. Near Vladivostok, 61
miners are on a hunger strike to protest a six-month backup of
unpaid wages and are threatening to block the Trans-Siberian
Railroad line to the port of Nakhodka on the Sea of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Much farther west, in the Ural Mountains, more than 300 miners
in the city of Chelyabinsk have shut off a Trans-Siberian rail line
for almost a week, raising fears of environmental problems if power
to the Mayak nuclear-waste reprocessing plant there is cut off for
lack of fuel.
</P>
<P>
   And in Moscow itself, about 200 miners have long been encamped
in front of the main office complex of the Russian Federation,
banging their hard hats on the marble steps in a drumbeat of
complaint about the lack of pay and work.
</P>
<P>
   The miners complain that the government, once the sole owner of
the industry and now a shareholder in many mines, has reneged on
back wages. The Sakhalin protesters, for example, say they are owed
arrears totaling more than $16 million. Miners outside Vladivostok,
in the city of Partizansk, say they are owed wages dating back to
November; nearly the entire adult population of the city turned out
at a rally in their support.
</P>
<P>
   But how much of this is the fault of the cash-strapped
government of President Boris Yeltsin is another matter. Many of
the mines have been privatized since the fall of communism. Others
have been closed because they are simply too inefficient to compete
with lower-cost coal shipped in from Central Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Boris Nemtsov, deputy prime minister in charge of energy
programs, says the miners have in general been paid whatever wages
the government owes them. Their complaints, Nemtsov contends, lie
with the owners of the mines _ in some cases workers' cooperatives
_ and with the miners' unions.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, though, Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko adopted a
harder line, warning that ``the government will restore order''
before the strikes cause a social breakdown.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That prompted the national miners union, Rosugleprofsoyuz, to
warn that it will ask its 600,000 members to engage in civil
disobedience, including blocking entrances to foreign embassies, if
force is used against them.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, government leaders seemed to back away from the
threat of force, but it remained unclear what they could do should
the strikes and protests begin to exact a greater nationwide toll.
</P>
<P>
   On Sakhalin, about 70 rail cars carrying more than 4,000 tons of
coal sit idle, just yards outside the entrance to the main power
generating station. Miners have promised to keep blocking the cars
for another week if their demands are not met.
</P>
<P>
   That would be troublesome, but not nearly as disastrous as
another threat: If their back wages are not paid by this autumn,
spokesmen for the miners say, they will block all rail traffic in
and out of Moscow itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
