<HEADLINE>
HEAD OF PUBLIC RELATIONS RESIGNS AT CONDE NAST  
 PBS STATION SEEKS WAY TO KEEP A FAVORITE ON AIR  
 SCHOLAR PUTS OPINION OF CLINTON AIDE ON RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn.: N.Y.)   (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.)  
(jw) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Someone probably had to take the fall. Conde Nast
Publications, a unit of Advance Publications, is still licking its
wounds over an article in Fortune magazine last month that said
that the company was ``a woeful underperformer'' and that ``truth
is a fungible commodity'' in the hands of its chief executive,
Steven Florio.
</P>
<P>
   A flurry of spinning came from the Florio camp, with supporters
of Florio calling the article ``a hatchet job.'' But no heads
rolled _ until now.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Andrea Kaplan, the head of corporate communications
at Conde Nast, who also handled publicity for six magazines,
resigned after reading in The New York Observer that Maurie Perl,
the head of publicity at The New Yorker, would take over Conde
Nast's corporate public relations operation.
</P>
<P>
   No one at Conde Nast would comment on whether Ms. Kaplan's
implicit demotion was linked to the Fortune profile. But it was
widely known that after granting an initial interview to the
authors, Joseph Nocera and Peter Elkind, Florio had declined to
cooperate further and was dissatisfied with Ms. Kaplan's handling
of the article.
</P>
<P>
   It was then left to Ms. Kaplan to stammer defenses of Florio's
statements that he had played minor-league baseball and college
football and had been a premed major.
</P>
<P>
   But as angry as Florio is known to be about the article, he has
yet to ask for a correction or retraction, said John Huey,
Fortune's managing editor.
</P>
<P>
   Conde Nast executives say that Ms. Kaplan was asked to stay on
as a publicist for several magazines but that she declined and
decided to leave. Ms. Kaplan and Ms. Perl declined to comment, and
Florio was unavailable for comment on Friday. But when asked a few
weeks ago about the possibility of his replacing Ms. Kaplan with
Ms. Perl, he said, ``I plead the Fifth.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ROBIN POGREBIN &QR;
</P>
<P>
   WNET Seeks Way to Keep a Favorite on Air
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dhaliwal and Woolsey? It doesn't quite roll off the
tongue like Huntley and Brinkley, or, perhaps more to the point,
like MacNeil-Lehrer.
</P>
<P>
   But William Baker, the president of WNET/Channel 13 in New York,
has an oddball idea, a way to capture some of the following
attracted by Daljit Dhaliwal. Ms. Dhaliwal is the British news
reader whose weeknight international reports for Britain's ITN News
have been carried on 19 public television stations in the United
States for the last few years but are being dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dhaliwal, a 35-year-old Londoner, is popular among
Anglophiles and PBS news addicts in those 19 cities. Fans have put
up a Web site devoted to her, and this month's Rolling Stone
featured her on its ``Hot List'' as ``Hot News Reader.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Ms. Dahliwal's followers have found her at 11:30
p.m. during the week on WLIW/Channel 21, the Long Island station
that carried ITN's International News for six years. But WLIW plans
to replace it, starting on Nov. 1, with three daily programs from
ITN's better-known rival, the BBC World television news service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daljit is a talent,'' Baker said on Friday. ``But we have a
very tight schedule carrying all the PBS lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   So he is toying with the idea of combining one-minute
international reports read by Ms. Dhaliwal with one-minute local
news reports by WNET's Midge Woolsey and showing them as ``news
breaks'' in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   ``And maybe at the end of the day, after `Charlie Rose,' we
could throw on a longer show with Daljit and promote it in prime
time,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Garron Baines, an ITN managing director, confirmed by telephone
that he had been talking to Baker about creating a news program for
WNET.
</P>
<P>
   ``Midge Woolsey in New York and Daljit in England,'' Baker said.
``That wouldn't be your usual local-station news break, with a
bunch of car crashes and a quick weather forecast.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRIE MIFFLIN &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Scholar Puts Opinion of Clinton Aide on Record
</P>
<P>
   In Washington's interlocking circles of the press, politics and
research groups, people generally have a good idea about who
dislikes whom. But a conservative scholar, questioned last week in
the civil lawsuit accusing Internet gossip columnist Matt Drudge of
defamation, has left absolutely no room for doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Ledeen, a resident scholar at the American Enterprise
Institute, testified under oath that he ``hates'' Sidney
Blumenthal, the White House aide and former journalist, but that he
never suggested to Drudge or anyone else that Blumenthal had abused
his wife.
</P>
<P>
   In his deposition and in a later interview, Ledeen said that the
day after Drudge reported accusations that Blumenthal ``has a
spousal abuse past that has been effectively covered up,'' the
gossip columnist called him asking how to check out such an
allegation. Ledeen suggested examining police records and, if the
accusations proved false, to, in Ledeen's words, ``apologize and
retract immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon thereafter, Drudge apologized and retracted the report.
Soon after that, Blumenthal sued Drudge.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the subpoenas of Ledeen and his wife, policy
analyst Barbara Ledeen, Blumenthal's lawyers have also subpoenaed
John Fund, an editorial writer for The Wall Street Journal, seeking
documents and testimony. This subpoena was deferred Friday after
Journal lawyers said they would move to quash it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attempt to drag John Fund into this case,'' said Richard
Tofel, a spokesman for the newspaper, ``is an attempt by a senior
White House staffer, who says he brought the lawsuit with the
approval of the president and vice president, to intimidate
editorialists whose views they don't like.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, horse manure,'' William McDaniel, Blumenthal's lawyer,
responded in an interview. ``John Fund has been named in
publications from Vanity Fair to The New York Observer saying he's
deeply involved in this.'' Drudge, however, denied in an interview
that he had ever spoken with Fund.
</P>
<P>
   _ FELICITY BARRINGER &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
