<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
`PRIVATE RYAN' DEFENDS POSITION AT TOP OF BOX OFFICE PILE
</HEADLINE>
 BOX-OFFICE-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Steven Spielberg's ``Saving Private Ryan'' easily
won a second box office victory with an estimated $23.3 million at
2,540 theaters nationwide during the Friday-Sunday period, studio
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The much-praised D-Day epic has taken in an impressive $73.1
million in its first 10 days for DreamWorks SKG. Its Friday-Sunday
take fell only 24 percent from its opening weekend, indicating that
``Saving Private Ryan'' will continue to post solid numbers after
the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 24 percent decline is very low for a second weekend,''
said DreamWorks distribution chief James Tharp. ``We think it will
play very well into the fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry tracker Robert Bucksbaum of Reel Source projected final
domestic box office for ``Saving Private Ryan'' of more than $150
million. ``It could get close to $200 million if it gets brought
back following Academy Award nominations next year,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Arthur Rockwell of Drake Capital Securities said he
expects ``Saving Private Ryan'' to receive strong support overseas,
where co-financer Paramount in handling the release.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan'' took in more than double its nearest rival, Disney's
update of ``The Parent Trap'' with $11.5 million at 2,247 sites.
The remake of the 1961 comedy also grossed $5.1 million during its
first two days -- Wednesday and Thursday -- and will generate solid
profits since it was a relatively inexpensive project, Rockwell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum noted that ``The Parent Trap'' drew particularly well
among adults in addition to its target audience of pre-teen girls.
</P>
<P>
   Also performing impressively was 20th Century Fox's third
weekend of the hit comedy ``There's Something About Mary'' with
$11.2 million at 2,145 screens as it moved up a notch to third
place _ an unusual feat during the hyper-competitive summer season
as it lost a mere 10 percent from the prior weekend.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Mary' should play very well for the rest of the summer,''
Rockwell said. ``It's holding up weekend to weekend almost as well
as `Titanic' did.'' ``Mary'' has topped $60 million in 19 days.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros.' opening of ``The Negotiator,'' with Kevin Spacey
and Samuel L. Jackson, followed in fourth with a respectable $9.7
million at 2,436 theaters, beating Fox's debut of ``Ever After,''
starring Drew Barrymore as a 16th Century Cinderella, which took in
$9 million at 1,967 screens.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's other major opening, Universal's low-brow sports
comedy ``BASEketball,'' was a major disappointment as it finished
11th with a tepid $3 million at 1,907 theaters. Its R rating may
have forced many younger customers to buy tickets for PG-13, PG and
G movies at the box office and then sneak into the auditorium
showing ``BASEketball,'' Bucksbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's third weekend of ``The Mask of Zorro'' came in sixth,
with $8.4 million at 2,515 sites, followed by Warner's fourth
weekend of ``Lethal Weapon 4,'' with $7.9 million at 2,602
locations, and Disney's fifth weekend of ``Armageddon,'' with $7.5
million at 2,602 theaters. The asteroid-vs.-Earth spectacular has
topped $163 million in 33 days and ranks 46th on the all-time
domestic list behind ``The Exorcist.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's sixth weekend of ``Dr. Dolittle'' finished ninth with $4.3
million at 2,180 theaters to top $125 million overall, followed by
Disney's second weekend of ``Mafia!'' with $3.6 million at 1,944
locations.
</P>
<P>
   Following ``BASEkebtall'' were MGM's second weekend of
``Disturbing Behavior,'' with $2.9 million at 1,842 locations,
DreamWorks' fourth weekend of ``Small Soldiers,'' with $2.7 million
at 1,701 sites, and Disney's seventh weekend of ``Mulan,'' with
$1.6 million at 1,175 screens.
</P>
<P>
   Overall box office was 2.6 percent ahead of the same weekend
last year. ``This is a strong weekend with a good range of
product,'' Rockwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Year-to-date business has topped $3.8 billion and is about 7
percent ahead of the same period last year, with much of the gain
from Paramount's ``Titanic.'' It posted a still-impressive $1.15
million at 769 theaters in its 33rd weekend to push its overall
domestic total to $595.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Miramax's opening of ``Full Tilt Boogie,'' a documentary on the
making of ``From Dusk 'Til Dawn,'' failed to draw well, taking in
$10,000 at six theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' will face competition next weekend from
two new entries _ Paramount's action-drama ``Snake Eyes,'' starring
Nicolas Cage, and Miramax's ``Halloween: H2O,'' with Jamie Lee
Curtis reprising her role as scream queen Laurie Strode.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-98 2117EDT &QL; 
