<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUR ENDS FOR RIDERS ON THE STORM
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The Tour de France is dead. Vive le Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
   When the most famous race in cycling ended Sunday, the consensus
in the French sports world was that the Tour would have to be
reborn to survive.
</P>
<P>
   The myth of almost superhuman endurance and physical stamina
that made the Tour into one of the great French legends since its
beginning in 1903 died this summer as investigating magistrates and
the police piled up evidence that it was pervasive use of illegal
drugs that made many of those fantastic performances possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all on drugs,'' said Leah Perrissoud, a retired nurse
who comes every year to cheer the racers, as tens of thousands of
people did Sunday, as they race up and down the Champs-Elysees at
the end of the grueling race. ``All sports seem to be riddled with
drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Tour competitors and other athletes would take
issue with that, but by next year, the government's minister of
youth and sports, Marie-George Buffet, expects to have a new law in
place that would take drug controls out of the hands of all sports
federations and put them under the authority of a new nine-member
state council with the power to test athletes, bar offenders from
competitions, and punish teams and doctors who violate the
prohibitions with up to seven years in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doping and medically assisted doping is unacceptable,'' said
Buffet, who has made the fight against illegal drug use in sports a
priority since taking office more than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   That this doping scandal is being openly discussed is in itself
a shock in a country that until recently was almost proud of its
worldly cynicism, the kind that shrugged at crimes everybody knew
were taking place because everybody was committing them.
</P>
<P>
   Since the beginning of the 1990s, many practices that used to be
taken for granted _ shaking down public contractors to finance
French political parties, bribing Third World officials to win
lucrative defense contracts for the French arms trade, using money
to fix French soccer games _ have all been zealously prosecuted by
fiercely independent investigating magistrates like the ones who
hounded the Tour de France around the country these past three
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   French investigating magistrates, a species somewhere between
prosecutors and judges in American law, have enormous discretion to
probe, detain, question and imprison people they suspect of
committing crimes. Napoleon, who decreed the legal code that
created the system, said that only the emperor himself had more
power.
</P>
<P>
   Crusading magistrates have indicted so many politicians and
business leaders in recent years that the French people became fed
up _ not with the prosecutors, but with the politicians and others
who took them for suckers for so long.
</P>
<P>
   A few people in some of the small French towns the Tour passed
through whistled in derision or turned their backs on the cyclists
who struggled to keep the race going amid the scandal, an
expression of letdown after the national mood of jubilation after
France's World Cup championship in soccer last month.
</P>
<P>
   President Jacques Chirac and Prime Minister Lionel Jospin, who
feted the soccer champions at the Elysee Palace on the July 14
national holiday, went on vacations thousands of miles away and
were not here for the Tour de France finish, leaving it to Paris
Mayor Jean Tiberi to do the honors.
</P>
<P>
   There was some public sympathy, to be sure, for the champion
athletes like Laurent Jalabert, who quit the race after complaining
that they were being treated like animals and asked why the police
could not wait until after the race was over to question suspect
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   That was before the Italian racer Rodolfo Massi was placed under
judiciary examination, one formal step short of indictment, on
Friday on suspicion of having used doping substances himself and
inciting other racers to use them.
</P>
<P>
   Now the scandal has taken on diplomatic ramifications. The Dutch
sports minister said the Netherlands would launch a probe of its
own into the conduct of the French investigators, and there was
talk of a boycott of the Tour de France by foreign teams next year.
</P>
<P>
   But on the whole, the French actions have stimulated a new look
at the wider problem of doping in all sports.
</P>
<P>
   International Olympic Committee President Juan Antonio Samaranch
has called a board meeting in Lausanne, Switzerland, on Aug. 20 to
prepare for a doping summit in January, though he created
controversy by saying that in his opinion, performance-enhancing
drugs should be permitted unless they pose a threat to the health
of the athletes who use them.
</P>
<P>
   Buffet, who increased her French sports ministry's budget for
antidoping action from $1.43 million in 1997 to more than $4
million in the coming year, sharply disagreed, denouncing what she
called ``a vast trafficking in doping products that endangers human
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Tour de France director Jean-Marie Leblanc said: ``Sports and
cycling can't find solutions to this problem all by themselves.
There has to be constructive help from the scientists, from the
doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should also be a regular health-monitoring system, so
that the athlete isn't tempted to cross the yellow line under the
influence of shady doctors, trainers and drug traffickers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-98 2135EDT &QL; 
