<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: BRITAIN, CANADA, N.Y.)  
 CULTURE NOTES: REUNITED MONETS; BRITAIN'S TRAVELING THESPIANS;
MARIMBA FESTIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After more than a century apart, two paintings by Claude
Monet &UR;  &LR; are to be reunited, Monday through Oct. 4, at New York's
Frick Collection. The paintings _ ``Vetheuil in Summer,'' from the
Art Gallery of Ontario in Toronto, and ``Vetheuil in Winter,'' from
the Frick _ depict the village of Vetheuil, some 40 miles west of
Paris, from the same perspective across the Seine.
</P>
<P>
   The winter scene was bought by Monet's friend Dr. Georges de
Bellio, a Romanian physician and avid Monet collector, in December
1879, and the summer scene in 1879 or 1880. Eventually, both Monets
came to Wildenstein &AMP; Co. in New York, which sold the summer scene
to the Ontario museum in 1929 and the winter scene to the Frick
Collection in 1942. Information: (212) 288-0700.
</P>
<P>
   Westward Ho
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ In a new collaboration, the Almeida Theater of London
takes to the road beginning this week to team with the Malvern
Festival Theaters to the west, in Worcestershire, for a season of
drama through Aug. 22. Three major new productions are to be
presented, along with a classical revival and accompanying talks,
films and exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   The collaboration, called the Almeida at Malvern, begins on
Thursday with the world premiere of a new version of Racine's
tragedy ``Phedre'' by Britain's poet laureate, Ted Hughes. Aug. 14
brings the world premiere of Edward Albee's ``Play About the
Baby.'' Bertolt Brecht's centennial will be observed with a rare
production of his satirical comedy ``Mr. Puntila and His Man
Matti,'' in a new version by Lee Hall beginning on Aug. 7. Shaw's
``Doctor's Dilemma,'' previously seen at the Almeida, will appear
in revival beginning on Aug. 14. Information: 011-44-1-684-892-277.
</P>
<P>
   Percussive Force
</P>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. _ At the Eastman School of Music, the classical
marimba takes the spotlight through Sunday as marimbists from
around the world, including 60 competitors from nearly 20
countries, participate in the second Leigh Howard
Stevens &UR;  &LR; International Marimba Competition and Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors will demonstrate their versatility by playing both
modern and classical works. The event, including master classes,
performances and a competition in classical marimba offering prizes
totaling $30,000, owes its existence to Stevens, an Eastman alumnus
who has expanded the classical marimba repertory. Information:
(716) 222-5000.
</P>
</TEXT>
