<SLUG> BC-GLF-DUMAURIER-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RECORD IN DUMAURIER SOUNDS JUST FINE TO BURTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDSOR, Ontario _ Brandie Burton had waited five years for this
moment, and the pressure was almost too much to bear.
</P>
<P>
   After 71 holes and four days of superb play, Burton reached the
final hole of the du Maurier Classic still needing an 8-foot putt
to win. If she made the putt, Burton would win an LPGA tournament
for the first time since 1993. But if Burton missed, she would face
a sudden-death playoff against Annika Sorenstam, the tour's most
consistent player, who had been chasing Burton all day.
</P>
<P>
   As Burton lined up the putt, it was a chore to keep her emotions
in check.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can honestly say I don't remember seeing the ball when I was
addressing it,'' Burton said.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam, kneeling on the 18th green, covered her eyes as
Burton prepared to putt. ``I was nervous, and I didn't want to
watch,'' Sorenstam said. ``You can always tell by the crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   The roar said it all. Finishing at 18-under-par 270 for the
tournament _ a record for an LPGA major _ Burton defeated Sorenstam
by one stroke. Betsy King finished in third place, a distant five
strokes off the pace.
</P>
<P>
   Burton's rounds of 68-64-66-72 at Essex Golf and Country Club
broke the previous record of 16 under par for an LPGA major, set by
Jody Rosenthal at the 1987 du Maurier and equaled by Cathy Johnson
at the 1990 du Maurier. While Sunday's 72 was Burton's worst round
of the tournament, she held the lead all day and displayed a superb
short game under pressure that consistently allowed her to escape
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Burton started the final round with a three-stroke lead over
Sorenstam and Meg Mallon. Mallon shot a 75 and faded on the back
nine, falling into a five-way tie for fourth place (276) with Gail
Graham, Dawn Coe-Jones, Deb Richard and Michelle Estill. But
Sorenstam, who shot a 70 despite not playing her best, pushed
Burton to the final shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shaky all day, but I gave it all I had,'' said
Sorenstam, whose second-place share of $111,711 moved her to No. 1
on this year's LPGA money list with $790,495, just ahead of Se Ri
Pak ($773,645). ``I was beaten by someone who played really well.
Brandie's short game was incredible. She got up and down from
everywhere. I'm really happy for her, because I know she has been
struggling, and this means a lot.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It was a pressure-packed afternoon for Burton, playing in the
final twosome with Sorenstam in the final major of the season. The
climax was set up when Burton, holding a two-stroke lead, bogeyed
No. 16 and fell to 17 under par, just one stroke ahead of
Sorenstam.
</P>
<P>
   At the par 5, 462-yard No. 17, both Burton and Sorenstam went
for the green in two shots. Sorenstam hit a powerful 7-wood
approach shot that got a good bounce and came to rest 25 feet from
the cup. Burton hit her 4-wood approach shot over the green and
into the rough, about 30 yards from the pin. Sorenstam was in
position for a possible eagle, while Burton needed an up-and-down
to make a birdie.
</P>
<P>
   But for Burton, who has confidence in her short game, the
situation was not intimidating. She hit a gorgeous chip shot within
5 feet of the cup, and then made her putt for birdie. Sorenstam's
eagle putt stopped a foot short, and she settled for a birdie to
remain one stroke behind.
</P>
<P>
   When the two players reached the par-4, 385-yard No. 18, Mallon
and King had yet to tee off. Sorenstam and Burton were forced to
wait about 10 minutes, and needless to say, the atmosphere was
tense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I drank about six bottles of water,'' Burton said,
laughing. ``I had a little cotton mouth going.''
</P>
<P>
   Both players hit solid drives, but the nervousness showed on
their next shots. Sorenstam hit a poor 6-iron from 165 yards,
yanking it into the rough left of the green, about 20 yards from
the pin. Sorenstam bowed her head in disappointment after the shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed a birdie, and I needed to get it close,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Burton's approach shot was even worse. From the middle of
the fairway, she hit an awful 7-iron shot that sliced right, hit a
tree, then ricocheted back into the fairway, still about 60 yards
in front of the green. Burton had to regain her composure and rely
on her short game to get up and down again.
</P>
<P>
   Just before she prepared to hit her crucial chip shot, Burton's
caddie, Tim Atsedes, gave her encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   ``For two seconds there, I doubted myself,'' Burton said. ``Tim
said, `You've done this 100 times. You can hit this shot.'''
</P>
<P>
   Atsedes was right. Burton hit another superb chip within 8 feet.
But Sorenstam then almost chipped in for a birdie that would have
tied Burton, but her ball slid just past the hole. That left Burton
with her suspenseful final putt.
</P>
<P>
   The victory lifted her from No. 14 to No. 5 in the Solheim Cup
points standings, and the top 10 players receive an automatic spot
on the U.S. team that will face Europe in September. Earning a spot
on the Solheim Cup was one of Burton's goals for the season. To win
again was another. So for Burton, Sunday was a special day. And
after waiting five years to win, she planned to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``After my last win, I went to the course the next day and beat
range balls for five hours,'' Burton said. ``This time, I'm going
to take it easy. Maybe do some fishing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-98 2140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
