<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-GAILEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAILEY TAKES BLAME FOR GAFFES IN OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Chan Gailey spent 3 1/2 hours yesterday
evaluating game film of his new team in the preseason opener. Yet
during all that time, as he painstakingly eyed each frame of the
club's 20-19 loss Friday night to the Seattle Seahawks, perhaps
Gailey's most significant assessment came of himself.
</P>
<P>
   Having spent much of his apprenticeship for the Cowboys' head
coaching job as an offensive assistant, the new Cowboys skipper
said if he is to improve he'll have to ``continually remind''
himself to pay more attention when the club is playing defense or
on special teams.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey also blamed himself for some of the 11 penalties called
on the Cowboys in the game at Texas Stadium. Three of the flags
were thrown when officials spotted the Cowboys with 12 defensive
players on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he graded his decision-making during his first game as
a pro head coach, Gailey said, ``It wasn't very good; we lost.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Gailey has had the final word on game
day. He spent five seasons as a head coach at Troy State, Samford
University and the Birmingham Fire of the World League. But Gailey
was an offensive assistant for eight of the previous 11 years
before coming to Dallas. No doubt during those years, he spent more
time preparing his offense for the next drive than watching the
action on the field. He said he had to think not to do that on
several occasions Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem was making sure I was paying attention
when the defense is on the field and when special teams are out
there, and for the penalty situations _ whether we want to take or
decline the penalty,'' said Gailey, who doubles as the team's
offensive coordinator. ``I kept reminding myself that I'm really
involved in that now. I know I am. But at the same time, when you
get caught up in offense, sometimes you lose sight of that, and
I've got to continually remind myself of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys were called for too many defensive players on the
field during one drive. A different player was involved each time,
Gailey said. Usually, the defensive assistants are charged with
employing the right players on the field at the right times. But
Gailey said he and his staff did a poor job of communicating when
it came time to substitute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have different groups,'' he said, ``You've got a nickel
\Rdefense\S group, you've got a heavy group when \Rthe offense\S
goes to two tight ends. Then you've got your standard defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got all those different groups playing, and you've got
different sets of linebackers and defensive backs with each one.
And then we had injuries, and you're trying to play everybody in
there, and one guy's playing nickel in one, and he's playing dime
in the other, or he's not in on the heavy group, and it got
confusing, and we didn't get the right people on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey is confident that game-day gaffes like the ones Friday
night will not continue. He reminds anyone who seems concerned that
he has been a head coach before and is aware of the mental
gymnastics that it takes to be one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done it before, being a head coach,'' Gailey said. ``I've
got to get back into it. For the last four years, I paid attention
to nothing but the offense. It wasn't like I ignored \Rdefense,
special teams\S the other night. But I had to catch myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
