<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-EUROPE-TEX </SLUG>
 
Overseas duty can be ticket for NFL job 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Notable World League/NFL Europe alumni Scott Mitchell, QB,
Detroit, Orlando, 1992 Brad Johnson, QB, Minnesota, England, 1995
George Koonce, LB, Green Bay, Ohio, 1992 Cary Blanchard, K,
Indianapolis, Sacramento, 1992 Louie Aguilar, P, Kansas City,
Barcelona, 1991 Mike Croel, DE, Seattle, Rhein, 1998 Jon Kitna,
Seattle, QB, Barcelona, 1997 Everett McIver, G, Dallas, England,
1996 Jason Garrett, QB, Dallas, San Antonio, 1991 Wally Richardson,
QB, Baltimore, England, 1998 Kipp Vickers, G, Indianapolis,
Frankfurt, 1995 Adam Vinatieri, K, New England, Amsterdam, 1996
George Hegamin, G, Philadelphia, Frankfurt, 1996
</P>
<P>
   Jon Kitna never thought he would visit the great cities of
Europe. He certainly had no idea anyone would ever refer to him as
``the quarterback of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   He was nobody, a clean-cut kid from a nowhere school with a good
arm but no hope of making it big in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine his surprise, then, to be where he is today _ a seasoned
European traveler and the hot quarterback prospect for the Seattle
Seahawks, both thanks to NFL Europe, formerly known as the World
League of American Football.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it's not such a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember one day I was playing golf with my dad,'' Kitna
said, ``and telling him how weird it is for me to be in the NFL.
But the weirdest thing is that I can actually see myself as a
starter in this league for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   So can Seahawks coach Dennis Erickson, the man who discovered
Kitna playing for an NAIA program at Central Washington, and in the
spring of 1997 decided to send him overseas to help him learn his
craft. Kitna returned as the World League's leading passer and the
most valuable player of its championship game, the World Bowl. He
threw for a league-record 401 yards to carry the Barcelona Dragons
past the Rhein Fire for the title.
</P>
<P>
   Even more important, he came back with a year's worth of
experience at the professional level and the confidence built from
his success. Both served him well on Dec. 14, when Warren Moon and
John Friesz went down with injuries, leaving Kitna to make his
first NFL start against the Oakland Raiders. All he did was lead
the Seahawks back from a 21-3 halftime deficit to a 22-21 victory,
which in turn led Erickson to tab him as the QB of the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that playing in the World League was the
best thing that ever happened to Jon Kitna,'' Erickson said. ``He
learned a great deal about playing his position and about
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   With Moon holding out and threatening to retire, Kitna, 26, is
challenging Friesz for the No. 1 position this season.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna's rapid rise has made him the poster child for NFL Europe,
the example of what a year abroad can do for a young player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I got to see the world and almost got paid for it,'' said
Kitna, who earned $18,000 for his three months of work. ``They gave
us meals and a place to live about 100 yards from the beach and a
chance to play and get better. It was a great experience for me.''
</P>
<P>
   But his is not the only success story. Minnesota quarterback
Brad Johnson spent 1995 with the England Monarchs. Detroit's Scott
Mitchell played for the Orlando Thunder in 1992, the last year the
World League featured American teams. The Cowboys invited six
ex-World Leaguers to their camp, including backup quarterback Jason
Garrett (San Antonio, 1991), guard Everett McIver (England, 1996)
and linebacker/special teams hopeful K.D. Williams, who spent last
season as one of the stars for the Frankfurt Galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great place to be for guys like me,'' Williams said.
``It's like a stage, but the stage is set in a different country.
It gave me enough exposure for NFL teams to give me a chance to
work out for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the people were great. Frankfurt was the best city. There
big crowds there every game. They had a lot of respect for the game
of football.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Frankfurt fans, not to mention the
Galaxy's management, apparently had little respect for their German
rival, the Dusseldorf-based Rhein Fire. Those teams met three times
last spring, all nasty, intense struggles that drew the league's
largest attendance of the season. The Fire won two of the three,
including a 34-10 victory in the 1998 World Bowl before a
boisterous crowd of 47,546 at Waldstadion in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those Frankfurt guys talk a lot of trash,'' said former Fire
defensive end Mike Croel, now in camp with the Seahawks. ``And they
treated us so bad. At the end of one of the games there, they
turned off the hot water in our locker room and hid our laundry.
I've never seen such bad sportsmanship. They made the Raiders look
like angels.''
</P>
<P>
   Croel knows all about that, having faced the Raiders twice a
year in five seasons with the Denver Broncos. He was the fourth
pick in the 1991 draft and was considered among the league's
hottest prospects, but he fizzled after the Broncos changed their
defensive scheme. He was out of football last fall. Now 29, Croel
was an anomaly in NFL Europe, a former star attempting to resurrect
his career among the young hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   Once a speedy, pass-rushing linebacker, the 6-foot-3, 241-pound
veteran had to prove to NFL general managers that he could make the
switch to defensive end, where his skills seemed to be a better
fit. His performance in Europe, which included six sacks and five
passes deflected in 11 games, drew positive reviews, earning him a
spot in an NFL camp and a chance to win a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the only way for me to get back into the league,''
Croel said. ``If I wanted to get invited into someone's camp,
that's what I had to do. It wasn't humbling. Stuff happens in this
business. You do what you have to do. In my case, I just had to
show I could still be aggressive and let people know I still have
some game left in me.''
</P>
<P>
   That Croel wound up with the Seahawks is not surprising, given
Erickson's affinity for NFL Europe alumni. Seattle brought eight
former European players to camp this year, including the MVPs of
the past two World Bowls, Jim Arellanes and Kitna. Arellanes filled
in for injured starter Mike Quinn (now in Pittsburgh's camp) and
threw three touchdown passes for Rhein.
</P>
<P>
   Not all coaches and general managers are sold on NFL Europe.
Indianapolis general manager Bill Polian, for example, brought only
four former World League players to camp, none of whom has played
in Europe since 1996. That group includes kicker Cary Blanchard
(Sacramento, 1992), who is solidly entrenched after five NFL
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sent a punter \RKevin Feighery\S there when I was with
Carolina and had a bad experience,'' Polian said. ``He went there
and actually got worse. They never even worked with him. Now, it
may not be fair to judge on that, but I'd want to see some results
before I sent someone over there. We'd rather the guys stay here
and work in our off-season program than go over there.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing on which Polian and Erickson do agree is that
quarterbacks stand to benefit from a year in NFL Europe far more
than any other position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quarterbacks need to play,'' Polian said. ``Sitting on the
bench watching doesn't do them a lot of good. So, yes, for a young
quarterback, a guy like Kitna or \RSt. Louis' Will\S Furrer I'd say
there's probably some value in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitna doesn't have to be told that. He is convinced his year in
Europe made him a far better quarterback. And now he's ready for
bigger things.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest question about me, because I came from a small
college, was if I could do it against better athletes,'' he said.
``In the World League, I was able to show them what they wanted to
see.
</P>
<P>
   ``That got me the chance, and I want to take advantage of it.
I'm not happy being the third guy or the second guy here,'' he
said. ``I want to be the guy who leads this team to the playoffs. I
have visions of opening our new stadium in 2002 with a Super Bowl
ring.''
1998 NFL Europe Amsterdam Admirals _ Amsterdam, the Netherlands
Barcelona Dragons _ Barcelona, Spain England Monarchs _ London,
England Frankfurt Galaxy _ Frankfurt, Germany Rhein Fire _
Dusseldorf, Germany Scottish Claymores _ Edinburgh, Scotland 1998
NFL Europe standings Frankfurt/.7-3 Rhein/.7-3 Amsterdam/.7-3
Barcelona/.4-6 England/.3-7 Scotland/.2-8 World Bowl at Frankfurt:
Rhein 34, Frankfurt 10
</P>
</TEXT>
