<HEADLINE>
ONLY THE TURNOUT WASN'T FIRST CLASS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ The competition generally ranged from good to
excellent. The athletes were happy and enjoyed the international
atmosphere without the choking tension of an Olympic Games.
Spectators liked the up-close looks at famous athletes.
</P>
<P>
   By most standards, the Goodwill Games, a scaled-down Olympics
that ended Sunday night after 15 days of competition in New York
City and Nassau County, were a success. There were many empty seats
_ Nassau Coliseum was less than half full for such favorites as
women's all-around gymnastics and the start of women's figure
skating _ but crowds were often enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Turner, the media magnate, created the Goodwill Games in
1986 to help break down Cold War barriers between the United States
and the Soviet Union. Now the games are more international, with
1,500 athletes from more than 60 nations competing here in 15
sports.
</P>
<P>
   The athletes were housed at big hotels, often with security
guards on every floor. They were well fed and, in some cases, well
paid. They seemed to enjoy one another's company, as witness a
wonderful television clip in which a Chinese female diver was
trying to teach an American diver, Erica Sorgi, how to whistle.
</P>
<P>
   As Mark Ruiz, another American diver, said: ``Over all, the
games were great. I had a great time and a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   And Mike Plant, president of the Goodwill Games, said, ``The
Russian swimming coach said this is the first time his team has
really shown a lot of camaraderie and worked together toward a
common goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The games are owned by Turner Sports, part of Time Warner, the
media giant. The first three competitions _ in 1986, 1990 and 1994
_ lost a total of $109 million. These games lost money, too,
although not as much. But they did provide a nightly three hours of
prime-time programming (plus a three-hour repeat) for Turner
Broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   Plant had a different spin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always use the word `investment,''' he said at a news
conference to review the games. ``We provide an opportunity for
world-class athletes to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   These games certainly had world-class athletes, including
Michael Johnson, Marion Jones and Jackie Joyner-Kersee in track and
field, Alexander Popov and Jenny Thompson in swimming, Michelle
Kwan and Todd Eldredge in figure skating, Mia Hamm in soccer,
Dmitri Sautin in diving and Felix Savon in boxing. Some of them,
notably Johnson, received six-figure appearance and endorsement
fees, and all performed well in winning gold medals.
</P>
<P>
   The games had their moments of nationalism, especially when Iran
and Turkey wrestled. They had one awful moment when Sang Lan, a
17-year-old Chinese gymnastics champion, broke her neck performing
a routine practice vault and was paralyzed from midchest down.
</P>
<P>
   The empty seats did not seem to bother the organizers. Plant
said he expected a total ticket sale of 350,000 of the 550,000
seats available. Nassau County will be left with two world-class
facilities: the track-and-field and soccer complex here and the
swimming and diving complex a mile away in Eisenhower Park in East
Meadow.
</P>
<P>
   The 50-meter pool will be the site of next year's U.S. spring
championships.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Scherer, an Olympic medalist from Brazil, called it
``the fastest pool I've ever been in.'' And Norbert Rozsa, a former
world record-holder in the breast stroke, said, ``I wish they built
pools like this back in Hungary.''
</P>
<P>
   To escape conflicts with the 2002 Olympic Winter Games and World
Cup soccer, the next Goodwill Games will be in 2001 in Brisbane,
Australia. They will last only 12 days and will be more compact.
The novel swimming format of round-robin dual meets, which led some
swimmers to swim two races within 10 minutes, will probably remain.
</P>
<P>
   At the closing celebration at Battery Park City in Manhattan,
Time Warner Chairman Gerald Levin and Turner, the vice chairman,
presented the Boys and Girls Clubs and UNICEF, the games'
designated charities, with checks for $1 million each. In all,
Plant said, the games have given $5 million to those groups.
</P>
<P>
   There was $5 million more in prize money for athletes, and for
some it was their only sports income of the year.
</P>
<P>
   For being part of the all-conquering U.S. women's swimming team,
Ashley Tappin earned $12,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unbelievable,'' she said. ``This money is going to be my car
payment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
