<HEADLINE>
REYNOSO LEADS METS OVER DODGERS, 9-3 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Armando Reynoso had gone a year and a week between
major-league starts. Nine more days obviously did not hurt him.
</P>
<P>
   In his second start of the season for the Mets, Reynoso allowed
two singles in seven innings in a 9-3 rout of the Los Angeles
Dodgers Sunday at Shea Stadium. The Mets took the lead for good
when they scored five runs, all unearned, off the former Met Brian
Bohanon in the third inning. Butch Huskey drove in two of the runs
with his 12th homer; he left the game in the fifth inning after
injuring a hamstring running the bases.
</P>
<P>
   The only run Reynoso allowed was unearned, too. Reynoso (2-0), a
32-year-old right-hander, who missed more than a year with elbow
and shoulder problems before starting on July 24, has not allowed
an earned run in 15 innings with the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that kind of surprising? Mike Piazza was asked.
``Absolutely,'' Piazza said. ``It looked like he didn't miss a beat
at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the Mets' 10th in 14 games. Coupled with
Colorado's victory over the Chicago Cubs, it put the Mets (58-50),
three games back in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Mets manager Bobby Valentine has a pleasant
problem. Valentine has seven legitimate starters, and six of them
are in his rotation now for at least one turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not for the rest of the season,'' Valentine said. ``But I
think it's needed right now.''
</P>
<P>
   He sees the need to give his starters a little extra rest. And
with Reynoso, Al Leiter, Rick Reed, Bobby Jones, Hideo Nomo, Masato
Yoshii and Willie Blair on his staff, he has too many starters to
begin with. At least for now. Blair, who is pitching in relief, may
have been acquired from Arizona with the thought that he could be
traded again, possibly in a waiver deal to the Baltimore Orioles or
Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens with the rotation, Reynoso just wants to start.
After his first outing, he was briefly available out of the bullpen
until Valentine chose to go with six starters. ``Better six days'
rest than a year,'' Reynoso said Sunday of a six-man rotation. ``A
year is too long.''
</P>
<P>
   It did not look that way. Reynoso allowed a run-scoring single
by Gary Sheffield in the first; it was six more innings before the
Dodgers got another hit.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, meanwhile, tied the score in the bottom of the first
when Piazza's sacrifice fly drove in Tony Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Reynoso and Phillips then keyed the five-run third. Reynoso
reached base when his hard smash skipped past a backhanded stab by
the Dodgers' rookie third baseman, Adrian Beltre. With a 3-2 count,
Phillips drew a walk to give the Mets runners on first and second
with nobody out.
</P>
<P>
   Edgardo Alfonzo followed with a hard shot to center field. Raul
Mondesi caught up with the ball after a long run, but it skipped
out of his glove, and John Olerud came up with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud delivered a sacrifice fly for a 2-1 lead. (He later
extended his hitting streak to 16 games.) Piazza grounded to third
to advance the runners. Brian McRae was then hit by a pitch on the
left wrist _ but McRae acted as if he had not been hit and
continued his at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going anywhere,'' he said. ``I couldn't let Bo get
off the hook like that. We've been talking stuff to each other for
the last three days. I was just hoping he didn't tell me to go to
first, because I wasn't going.''
</P>
<P>
   The plate umpire, Charlie Williams, let McRae continue, and he
grounded a two-run single past Bohanon for a 4-1 lead. Two pitches
later, Huskey hit his first home run since July 9. The Mets had
five unearned runs in the inning on two hits and two errors, and a
6-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Reynoso took it from there, though he was uncharacteristically
wild, walking four batters. ``I didn't have the best control
today,'' he said. ``But I made the good pitch at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said: ``He kept them off stride. He mixed the ball in
and out. He doesn't give in. He either makes his pitch or no pitch.
Armando threw a lot of pitches today. And he looked good throwing
them all.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynoso even added a fourth-inning single for a little gravy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows how to pitch,'' Piazza said. ``Obviously, he knows
how to hit, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
