<HEADLINE>
SEC SAYS INCOMNET EXECUTIVE HID TRADING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (js) 
 By SHARON R. KING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal regulators have accused a former top executive of a
small long-distance telephone company of filing false documents to
conceal his trading in the company's stock.
</P>
<P>
   In a lawsuit filed on Thursday in U.S. District Court in Los
Angeles, the Securities and Exchange Commission said that Sam
Schwartz, a former chief executive and chairman of the company,
Incomnet &UR;  &LR; Inc., bought about 1.1 million shares of Incomnet stock
and sold about 900,000 shares from June 1994 through July 1995
without disclosing the transactions in a timely manner.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz, 58, caused Incomnet to report falsely in filings with
the commission that Incomnet's board had given him written approval
to set up a personal trading account, according to the complaint.
Schwartz is also accused of prompting the company to issue an
erroneous press release to back up the claim.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Schwartz is accused of causing Incomnet to issue
two statements in January 1995 denying that the company was being
investigated by the SEC, even though executives knew of the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint seeks to keep Schwartz, a resident of Encino,
Calif., from committing future violations and seeks an unspecified
monetary penalty.
</P>
<P>
   `` Schwartz was doing undisclosed trading to push up the price''
of Incomnet shares, said Lisa Gok, assistant regional director of
enforcement for the commission in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Company insiders are required to disclose any trading activity.
In addition, when Schwartz's ownership surpassed 5 percent of the
total shares of Incomnet, he was required to disclose that his
intentions had changed from owning the stock as an investment to
active trading, an SEC official said.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz's lawyer, Sheldon Jaffe of Los Angeles, challenged the
commission's contentions, saying Sunday that board members knew
about the trading.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1995 filing with the SEC, Schwartz said he had been buying
and selling stock in an effort ``to defend the price of the
company's stock from the short-sellers.''
</P>
<P>
   Incomnet, a long-distance telephone services reseller based in
Woodland Hills, Calif., consented on Thursday to an SEC order to
desist from violating federal security laws. The company and two
former officers, Joel Greenberg and Stephen Caswell, did not admit
or deny any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone calls to Incomnet seeking comment were not returned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-98 2148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
