<HEADER>
A4475 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATRIOTISM-PRIVATIZED     08-02 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTISM-PRIVATIZED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDEFINING HEROISM WITH SPIELBERG AND PVT. RYAN
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One almost has to avert one's eyes from the chronicle of
carnage: the warrior with a hewn neck bone, hot blood flooding down
his eyes; a skewered skull, mouth gaping, blowing convulsive sprays
of blood; bodies torn asunder in tender, vulnerable spots _ navel,
groin, throat.
</P>
<P>
   The battle on Omaha Beach in Steven Spielberg's ``Saving Private
Ryan''? No, the Trojan war in Homer's ``Iliad.'' But both accounts,
separated by more than two millenniums, make it impossible to treat
warfare casually, showing it in all its brutish force. Both are
also haunted by another conflict in which the individual warrior is
harnessed to a communal will, in which the private is asked to
sacrifice itself for the sake of the public.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a conflict many late-20th-century Americans have
much patience for. How many citizens would automatically submit to
public demands that innocent youths be turned into bloodied pulp?
Our instincts of distrust have been finely honed.
</P>
<P>
   That is why, when the ``Private Ryan'' battle scene ends, and
Spielberg brings us into a room full of typists preparing letters
announcing soldiers' deaths with honorific (if not Homeric)
formulas, we wince again, ready to dismiss impersonal expressions
of compassion. ``Private Ryan'' has already been hailed as an
anti-war film, and it is easy to see why it has been misunderstood
as one.
</P>
<P>
   Actually ``Private Ryan'' is not anti-war any more than the
``Iliad.'' Something else is happening, which is one reason it has
had such an extraordinary impact.
</P>
<P>
   The bulletin boards on America Online are full of veterans'
testimonials of gratitude for the film: accounts by a niece who now
understands her uncle, or a son who now pays tribute to his father.
This kind of sentiment has become rare in America, where even
Memorial Day parades are often treated as quaint
self-congratulatory gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   Something is being restored in this film. But here is where
things get complicated because, while honoring heroism, it does not
really revive the old vision of sacrifice for one's country. Though
``Ryan'' begins and ends with images of an American flag, the
colors are washed out as if it had lost its freshness. There is no
confusing this film with earlier World War II epics.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, in contrast, one of the films Spielberg admires,
William Wellman's 1949 ``Battleground,'' a re-creation of the
wintry Battle of the Bulge, in which icy foxholes provided homes
for thousands of frozen corpses, wounded soldiers were hastily
patched up and returned to combat, and bad weather prevented air
support for the pummeled infantry. ``Skip the commercials,'' quips
a soldier in response to morale-boosting chatter.
</P>
<P>
   But then, in the end, a chaplain speaks to the decimated troops:
``Was this trip necessary?'' He insists it was, reminding the
soldiers that Hitler left no choice, that the alternative would
have been still more horrific, that a purpose was being served.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that lesson _ that public need transcends private
suffering _ seems dramatically pasted on ``Battleground,'' a
reminder to its viewers more than to its trembling characters. But
it is the kind of reminder that World War II demands. It is the
premise on which the war was fought. It also provides the shifting
terrain on which World War II films have waged their battles over
the last half-century.
</P>
<P>
   At times, as in the 1962 film ``The Longest Day,'' that
justification is taken for granted even when Allied foul-ups lead
to wholesale massacres. On the other hand, it seems hardly
acknowledged at all in the 1977 film ``A Bridge Too Far,'' in which
the Allied command is so vain and reckless that the battle becomes
a monument to hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   What happened in between the two films was, of course, the
Vietnam War. That weaned many Americans away from patriotism,
sometimes replacing it with a ready-made cynicism. In ``Patton''
(1970), George C. Scott, as World War II's great prima donna-ish
general, stands in front of a gargantuan American flag, dismissing
the very idea of individuality and reciting homilies we are meant
to dismiss as crankily fascistic:
</P>
<P>
   ``No poor bastard ever won a war by dying for his country. He
won it by making the other poor bastard die for his country.''
</P>
<P>
   We are meant to think of Patton as a mad genius by the movie's
end, one whose principles are nightmares from which we should try
to awaken. It is into that breach that Spielberg leaped, seeking to
rescue the veteran from such cultural skepticism. But he did it in
a peculiar way, redefining heroism by meticulously chronicling its
noble sacrifices, without fully restoring traditional patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the quest to find Pvt. Ryan behind enemy lines,
for example, the recurring question is whether that one man is
worth the sacrifice of the eight sent to do the job. But what does
this mean? What if Ryan isn't worth it? Here, the justification for
sacrifice is not an idea, a country or a battle against Nazism. It
is an individual. The private becomes the measure of the public.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hanks' soldier even preserves his private life from view as
if it were a precious terrain to be defended. Is saving Pvt. Ryan a
mission worth pursuing? ``If that earns me the right to get back to
my wife,'' he insists, ``then that's my mission.''
</P>
<P>
   The justification is personal (and the public goal may even be
mistrusted). Screenwriter Robert Rodat has spelled this out.
``Patriotism,'' he has said, ``ultimately has to do with one's
responsibility to family, to neighbors and to those one fights
alongside in the military.'' Thus, ``Private Ryan'' privatizes
patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   This is a remarkable change and not without problems. For many
in Spielberg's generation and younger, it has become difficult to
imagine surrendering individuality before the demands of a state.
Today, the tendency is to protect private prerogatives ardently and
to suspect public demands aggressively. When the film transfers
those attitudes back to World War II _ a just and necessary war
that required immense private sacrifice for public good _ the
perspective can be jarring.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult for those of us who have never risked death at
the command of others to know this for sure, but perhaps in the
midst of combat the preoccupation with private life is the only
sentiment possible. It is also the main sentiment that armies have
had to quash. It may be that the enormities of war can only be
grasped at the individual level, but at the same time wars can only
be fought _ even just wars _ by subsuming the individual.
</P>
<P>
   There are hints of this in the ``Iliad'' as well: Nearly every
death is individuated, but the greatest violation is excessive
individuation. The epic is not a tale of war but a tale of
Achilles' rage, his refusal to join battle out of injured pride. He
sets himself apart from his compatriots ``like some lion/going his
own barbaric way, giving in to his power,/his brute force and wild
pride.'' Homer, though, honors a different kind of heroism in which
the private and public become inseparable.
</P>
<P>
   The heroism of Homer's ``Saving Beautiful Helen'' is not the
heroism of Spielberg's ``Saving Private Ryan.'' Have sacrifice and
patriotism become purely private because we cannot accept them any
other way? Perhaps. But the widespread impact of the film suggests
that having saved the private, Spielberg may have begun to affect
the public as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
