<SLUG> BC-RAC-SARATOGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALDIZA, 11-1, USES 11-POUND EDGE TO WIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JENNY KELLNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ For trainer Shug McGaughey, the logic
was irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   His 4-year-old filly, Aldiza, had just one victory this year, in
an allowance race. But she had two career victories at Saratoga
Race Course, with two seconds. Then there was the matter of weight.
If she ran in the Grade I $250,000 Go for Wand Stakes Sunday,
Aldiza would get 11 pounds from Allen Paulson's top mare, Escena, a
winner of four straight graded stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, McGaughey thought, there really was no other place to
go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, if we're right about this, we'll be really, really
right,'' McGaughey said. ``Escena is a great filly and she's having
a great year, but getting weight like that, sometimes you can sneak
up on her.''
</P>
<P>
   He was right. Edging to the front in the final strides after a
stretchlong battle, Aldiza beat the prohibitive favorite by a nose
for her first Grade I victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a great mare like that, you never think you really have
them, but I just kept the pressure on Escena and it worked out
great,'' said Mike Smith, who also won Saturday's Test aboard
Jersey Girl. ``It's been a great weekend _ let's keep it going.''
</P>
<P>
   Finishing third, three lengths back, was Tomisue's Delight, with
Runup the Colors, Panama Canal, Mil Kilates and Verinha completing
the order of finish.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first loss for Escena since March, when she finished
second in the Rampart at Gulfstream. From there she went on to win
the Apple Blossom at Oaklawn, the Louisville Breeders' Cup and the
Fleur de Lis at Churchill Downs and the Vanity at Hollywood under
jockey Jerry Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been traveling a lot _ we started with her early and
tried to win what we could,'' said Escena's trainer, Bill Mott.
``There were no excuses for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Aldiza, overlooked at more than 11-1 by the cap-giveaway-day
crowd of 47,607, returned $25 for a $2 bet to win as she completed
the mile and an eighth in 1:47 4/5.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second victory in four starts this year for Aldiza,
who is owned by Helen Alexander, following a
one-and-one-sixteenth-mile allowance at Belmont on July 5. Sunday's
Go for Wand was her first two-turn start on the dirt, but McGaughey
had confidence in his filly even before the undefeated Mossflower
was withdrawn with a slight ankle injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a tough, tough filly and with her wind problems _ she's
had two minor procedures to help her breathing _ I just told Mike
to let her run her race,'' said McGaughey, who has won the Go for
Wand five times, including the 1995 edition with Heavenly Prize.
``It was the right decision.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
