<SLUG> BC-NY-PAROLE-VIOLENCE-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS MORE NONVIOLENT FELONS ARE RELEASED, PAROLE IS DENIED TO VIOLENT
INMATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In a radical change in how New York state uses
its clogged prisons, the administration of Gov. George Pataki has
quietly been pursuing a two-pronged strategy of releasing
nonviolent felons, mostly into drug treatment, while increasingly
denying parole for violent felons.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy reverses a trend that dates to the early 1970s,
when the state under Gov. Nelson Rockefeller imposed among the
stiffest sentences in the nation for low-level drug offenders, many
of them addicts, and others convicted of nonviolent felonies.
</P>
<P>
   For a generation, the number of state inmates imprisoned for
drug crimes grew at a frantic pace, rising to nearly one-third of
the prison population. But now that number has leveled off, and
even begun to drop. At the same time, the Pataki administration has
worked through the state parole board to reduce significantly the
number of violent offenders who are granted parole.
</P>
<P>
   The policies, put into effect over the last three years, are
integral components of Pataki's larger goal of returning the state
prisons to their historic mission of housing mostly violent
criminals. The administration estimates that the influx of violent
felons into the state prison system is likely to accelerate with
the state Legislature's passage of the governor's proposal to end
parole for first-time violent felons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor's position,'' said James Flateau, a spokesman for
the state's Department of Correctional Services, ``has always been
that prison space should be reserved for violent criminals who must
serve each and every day of longer sentences. But at the same time,
he is looking for ways to allow certain nonviolent drug offenders
to get the treatment they need to get out of prison earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Reppetto, the president of the Citizens Crime Commission
of New York City, a private organization, said the Pataki
administration was giving the criminal justice system, and the
public, what it wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1982 and 1996, the number of nonviolent inmates in the
state, many of them drug offenders sentenced under the
Rockefeller-era laws, increased steadily, to 33,865 from 8,297. But
between 1996 and 1997, that figure declined for the first time in
15 years, by nearly 1,000, as the Pataki administration
aggressively used a variety of early-release programs.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the 19-member New York State Parole Board,
under the growing influence of the governor's appointees, began
denying parole to inmates at a significant rate. In 1997, for
example, the board denied parole to 37 percent of the violent
felons who applied for parole, compared with 17 percent in 1991
under Pataki's predecessor, Gov. Mario Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   But the administration's policies have their critics. Robert
Gangi, the executive director of the Correctional Association of
New York, a group that monitors the state's prisons, called the
administration's efforts deeply flawed. For one thing, he said, the
administration is compromising the independence of the parole board
by pressuring its members into making decisions based on political
considerations rather than the merits of the individual cases.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He also sharply questioned the administration's commitment to
reducing the number of nonviolent drug offenders in the state's
system. Gangi said that if the governor were genuine about his
desire to reduce that population of inmates, he would urge his
Republican allies in the Legislature to drop their longstanding
opposition to legislation that would overhaul the stiff sentencing
laws passed during the Rockefeller administration.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1973 Rockefeller drug laws, judges must abide by rigid
sentencing guidelines that require long prison terms for drug
offenses, even for relatively minor ones like possessing a small
quantity of narcotics. Under another law passed that year, the
sentences increase sharply when a person is convicted of a second
felony within 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of 1997, nearly 22,000 of the state's nearly 33,000
nonviolent inmates were imprisoned under the Rockefeller laws, at a
cost of about $600 million a year, or $27,000 an inmate.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Pataki administration has quietly found ways around
those long mandatory drug sentences, it cautions against a
wholesale loosening of the drug laws. Many of the criminals
convicted under those laws, officials say, have prior convictions
or are guilty of large-scale drug dealing, not the penny-ante drug
crimes often cited by opponents of the laws.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Pataki administration has over the last three
years placed nearly 18,432 nonviolent inmates, mostly addicts and
other low-level drug offenders, into early-release programs, like
vocational training, drug treatment and educational courses. Had
those inmates been required to serve their minimum sentences, 4,788
of them would still have been in prison at the beginning of this
year, according to an analysis by state correctional officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are doing is putting incentives into the system for
nonviolent offenders to rehabilitate themselves,'' said Katherine
Lapp, the commissioner of criminal justice services.
</P>
<P>
   As for violent offenders, the administration has used the parole
board as a tool for managing that population. With control over the
board's budget and the ability to appoint its members, the governor
has nudged the board into increasingly denying violent felons early
release.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, for instance, 37 percent of first-time violent felons
were denied parole, compared with 21 percent in 1994, the year
before Pataki took office as governor. Because of the longer
sentences, the number of people in state prisons for committing
violent felonies has gradually increased despite the historic drop
in violent crime. By contrast, the board approved initial parole
requests for 80 percent of the nonviolent felons who applied for
early release in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-98 2209EDT &QL; 
