<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-02 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4482 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEX-CENTER-LADN     08-02 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEX-CENTER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEX RESEARCH CENTER BRINGS PROSTITUTES, PORNOGRAPHERS AND
PROFESSORES TOGETHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SHARLINE CHIANG  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHRIDGE, Calif. -- The Center for Sex Research might be a bit
of a letdown for someone hoping for titillation.
</P>
<P>
   It is housed in a plain office decorated with light blue walls,
a few bookshelves and a computer. On a table sits a framed picture
of director James Elias, 58, playing with his grandchildren and
another of his wife Veronica, a sociology professor at California
State University, Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   The humble office in a CSUN tower is a perfect metaphor for the
way the innovative but low key center and the 20 academics who are
its members have gone about their business the last 30 years in
this &UR;  &LR; San Fernando Valley suburb of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, the center has been working toward becoming a Kinsey
Institute of the West, presenting global gatherings to discuss such
topics as prostitution and cross-dressing, opening eyes to the
sexual practices of Americans in the 1990s in much the same way
Alfred Kinsey revealed the sexual behavior of Middle America in the
1950s.
</P>
<P>
   The center's members are single-handedly redefining sex
research. Take for example its next project: a World Pornography
Conference starting Thursday at the Universal City Sheraton.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 750 professors, researchers, First Amendment lawyers,
adult film actors and producers are booked to convene at the
Sheraton, right around the corner from the more mainstream
Universal Studios.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Researchers) used to all sit around talking with each other
and they were basically pretty boring,'' Elias said. ``All of us
were the same people, with similar points of view. We decided why
not bring in all the players?''
</P>
<P>
   It's a far cry from the staid, academic conferences the center
once staged.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, in attempt to break with traditional forums,
Elias began bringing real-life subjects such as sex-industry
workers and transsexuals under the same roof as academics.
</P>
<P>
   The center's pornography conference will draw prominent players
in the sex industry from the San Fernando Valley, the world's
leading producer of pornographic motion pictures, and beyond. The
center relies heavily for funding on $175 tickets for the
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Topics include a real ``Boogie Nights''; panels led by porn
stars Nina Hartley and Candida Royalle; pornography, cyberspace and
the First Amendment; gay porn, women and pornography _ victims or
visionaries?
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing is mainstreaming marginal areas of society
and focusing people to look,'' Elias said.
</P>
<P>
   Elias began as a researcher 30 years ago at the Kinsey Institute
for Research in Sex, Gender and Reproduction at Indiana University.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father would never come to visit my office,'' Elias said.
``He would wait downstairs. He didn't want to know (what was going
on). And my wife's father was a farmer. He said, `What am I
supposed to say about my son-in-law?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The institute, founded by Alfred C. Kinsey in 1947, brought
discussions about human sexuality to the forefront with its studies
based on 18,000 sexual histories of men and women gathered from
face-to-face interviews.
</P>
<P>
   The Kinsey Institute is sending representatives to Universal
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're very innovative and in a sense blazing
something of a trail,'' said Kinsey director John Bancroft. ``I'm
not sure something like this is being done anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN officials acknowledged getting some complaints about the
center, often worrying about whether state funds are used. They're
not.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a resident of Northridge I think there are some topics best
left alone,'' said Dick Hardman, executive director of the
Northridge Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``It legitimizes issues such as pornography, which I don't think
we, as a community, need to study or give legitimacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Legitimacy is exactly what adult entertainment advocates are
hoping the conference will help them get.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are issues that need to be discussed,'' said Jane
Hamilton, director with Chatsworth-based VCA Pictures, one of the
largest porn producers in the world. Hamilton is also a former porn
actress.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're living in the past and it's wishful thinking if you
don't think it's in the mainstream. It's a huge part of society.''
</P>
<P>
   Will Jarvis, co-organizer of next week's conference, wants to
focus on the issue of pornography industry workers. He is chairman
of the Erotic Entertainers Guild, a national union for the adult
entertainment industry, and a member of Free Speech Coalition, the
industry's largest advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very adamant that this conference be about the sex
workers, about their lives and opinions and that their voices are
heard,'' he said. ``Because, to be blunt, they work with their
(body parts) and that's how they make their living.''
</P>
<P>
   Elias invited anti-pornography activists to attend, but none
accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Days before the conference, Elias was flooded with requests for
tickets but the only media interest has come from MTV.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not interested in publicity,'' Elias said. ``The problem
is a lot of times what people look at is the spin. Last year, at
the prostitution conference, the media wanted to interview the
Happy Hooker, no one wanted to interview the justice of Canada.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-98 2209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
