<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ENID NEMY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A weekly column featuring readers' reports on life in the Big
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   As an artist about to leave on a long trip to Italy, I called a
storage company to have someone pack the artwork in my studio. The
packer arrived the next day with stacks of flattened cardboard and
balls of twine. I went back to my easel as he began unfolding the
pieces of cardboard and fitting them to the paintings, tying and
securing. From time to time I watched as he made one neat package
after another, thinking to myself, ``What a monotonous job day
after day.''
</P>
<P>
   After a while, we took a coffee break and he asked me if I was a
painter, either oblivious to what he was packing, or just to make
conversation. I admitted I was, and this provoked a thoughtful
silence. Then he said, ``Do you do this every day?'' I said I did
indeed. Another silence. Then in a sympathetic voice he said, ``It
must be boring.''
</P>
<P>
   _ HENRY S. GILLETTE
</P>
<P>
   Matthew C. Garcia stopped in at his local Barnes &AMP; Noble to buy
a volume of poetry by Gerard Manley Hopkins. As the salesclerk rang
up the purchase, she said briskly, ``That comes to $10.66.''
</P>
<P>
   Without thinking, he replied, ``The year of the Norman
invasion,'' and was given a blank stare in return.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to explain himself, he said, ``You know, the year the
Normans invaded England, William the Conqueror and all that.''
</P>
<P>
   Another blank stare. But as Garcia handed over his money, the
young clerk looked up, somewhat awestruck, and said, ``Wow, can you
do that with any number?''
</P>
<P>
   John Schiff was jogging in Central Park, wearing his Nolan Ryan
T-shirt with a picture of the retired pitcher on the front and
facts of his career on the back. As he jogged along, he realized
someone was pacing behind him. After three minutes or so, the man
behind him put on speed and called out as he passed: ``Thanks for
the information. Good reading.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Grand Opera Company has been giving free Wednesday
evening performances at Central Park's ``Summerstage'' for more
than two decades. Vincent La Selva, the artistic director, answers
the telephone himself in the company's small office.
</P>
<P>
   This year, he began keeping a record of some of the telephone
queries put to him on performance days:
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you people intend to do about the weather?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to go to the free opera in Central Park. How much
does it cost?''
</P>
<P>
   ``If admission is free, do I get a refund in case of rain?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have a special cast in case of rain or is it the same
one listed in the newspaper?''
</P>
<P>
   ``At what time will you know if it's raining or not?''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the performance starts at 7:30, what time does the
conductor come in?''
</P>
<P>
   ``If `Stiffelio' is postponed because of rain, does it change to
`Rigoletto'?''
</P>
<P>
   During an afternoon rush hour, a man boarded the A train at the
World Trade Center. ``Attention, ladies and gentlemen,'' he
intoned, his voice piercing the humid air of the subway car,
``Jesus is coming, Jesus is coming.''
</P>
<P>
   The man standing in front of Adam Cohen didn't have to think
twice. He turned to his companion and said, ``I hope he's not
waiting for a train, or he's going to be late.''
</P>
<P>
   As good a definition as any: H.D. Causbie overheard an obviously
relaxed diner addressing a companion at the Boat Basin Cafe: ``This
is delightful. It's a poor man's cruise.''
</P>
<P>
   Marti Copleman writes that New Yorkers are sometimes inclined to
forget that not everyone lives in a multiethnic environment. She
was shopping recently in a small-town supermarket in the Berkshires
and asked the cashier if they sold kosher salt.
</P>
<P>
   The reply was ``I don't know _ what else do they make?''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   At 71, I sit down on a bus seat with a sign giving priority to
elderly riders and notice I'm seated next to a younger couple.
Enter a woman my age and the man of the couple immediately gets up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, aren't you nice,'' the woman says, and sits down next to
me.
</P>
<P>
   The man who stood up says, ``Well, that's one advantage of being
elderly.'' The woman my age nods her head.
</P>
<P>
   The young man follows with ``But there must be others.''
</P>
<P>
   I break in and say loudly, ``No, that's about it.'' The whole
front of the bus breaks into laughter.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALFRED GESCHEIDT
</P>
<P>
   Craig and Nancy Sobocinski were shopping for mattresses with
their 3-year-old son, Alec. The hours went by, the number of stores
visited increased and Alec became restless.
</P>
<P>
   As he was wandering through the last store, a young salesperson
invited him to try an adjustable bed. He climbed up, and she
proceeded to show him how the control pad lowered and raised the
bed, and even made it vibrate.
</P>
<P>
   Alec was unimpressed. ``Can you make it fly?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY MORNING
</P>
<P>
   Tucked into an envelope of self
</P>
<P>
   arms folded tight across my chest
</P>
<P>
   as if to hold in all I can of sleep
</P>
<P>
   I hunch past early morning sparrows
</P>
<P>
   paused like commas on a branch
</P>
<P>
   and glimpse a line of sunlight on a leaf
</P>
<P>
   a scrap of praise, scribbled there for me
</P>
<P>
   for making it this far into the day,
</P>
<P>
   just before I reach the stairs
</P>
<P>
   and plunge into the tunneled earth
</P>
<P>
   the roar.
</P>
<P>
   _ CAROL WRESZIN &QR;
</P>
<P>
   It was New Year's Eve, and West Moss was in a fancy hair salon,
getting her hair styled professionally for the first time. She was
nervous, and not certain that she would be able to explain what she
wanted to the stylist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like my hair like Mary Tyler Moore,'' she said shyly.
Which Mary Tyler Moore, he wanted to know _ ``Laura Petrie or Mary
Richards?''
</P>
<P>
   The next year, returning to the same salon, she asked for the
same stylist. He didn't recognize her but she felt a surge of
warmth when he came over and asked what she'd like. ``Audrey
Hepburn,'' she said. ``Holly Golightly or Sabrina?'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   William D. Harney telephoned to make a grooming appointment for
his French bulldog. He was asked for his name. ``Bill,'' he
replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``And your dog's name?'' ``Simon,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The voice at the other end sounded surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funniest thing,'' it said. ``The call before yours was
also to groom a French bulldog _ but the man's name was Simon, and
his dog's name was Bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia E. Noonan, walking along Madison Avenue with a friend,
encountered what must be the city's most enterprising panhandler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, ladies,'' he chirped. ``Have you any spare credit cards?''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   While I was living in Manhattan and on my way to the Museum of
Natural History, an approaching pedestrian and I simultaneously
spotted a $10 bill on the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   The man, closer to the bill than I was, picked it up and put it
in his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   As we passed, he handed me a five! What a town!
</P>
<P>
   _ DIANE PECK
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-98 2219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980802.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-02 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4486 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-RYDER-BID-TEX     08-02 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-BID-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORT WORTH BIDS FOR RYDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH _ In a darkened office at Colonial Country Club, Dick
McHargue closed the hand-tooled leather cover protecting a
half-inch stack of bound documents. He popped a video cassette into
a tape player.
</P>
<P>
   The room filled with the familiar voice of Pat Summerall. But
this time, Summerall wasn't playing straight man to John Madden on
an NFL telecast or hawking hardware supplies. He was extolling the
virtues of Colonial as host for the week-long 2003 Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Other voices joined in the chorus, from golf legend Byron Nelson
to Gov. George W. Bush to Red Steagall, the official cowboy poet of
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In the span of 15 minutes and two videotapes, viewers received a
three-dimensional, computer-generated tour of Colonial's proposed
corporate area in Forest Park and the Fort Worth Zoo. They sampled
some of Steagall's work. And they learned of Colonial's innovative
ideas for the competition, from an Olympics-style opening ceremony
to nightly fireworks displays at the conclusion of play.
</P>
<P>
   McHargue, chairman of Colonial's Ryder Cup Committee, chuckled
as he turned off the final videotape, which served as the
centerpiece of the club's May 15 presentation to PGA of America
officials in Palm Beach Gardens, Fla. He reflected on a
conversation with Jim Awtrey, PGA chief executive officer and the
man who will announce the 2003 Ryder Cup site at some point between
the PGA Championship (Aug. 10-16) and the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim asked us to think out of the box on this one, and we
definitely did that,'' said McHargue, whose committee has spent
$225,000 in quest of the Ryder Cup, including $75,000 for the 3-D
video. ``We hit them with a lot of new ideas. I really believe that
if they come here ... they'll look back at what we did to make
their event bigger and better and make that the standard for future
Ryder Cups in this country. Our event could be the prototype for
the next 100 years.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, future Ryder Cups will be filled with ancillary events
such as parades, fireworks displays and welcoming ceremonies.
Because the PGA of America caps ticket sales for the Ryder Cup at
30,000 daily admissions, club officials sought a way to elicit more
fan involvement.
</P>
<P>
   That led to the idea of two separate-ticket events to raise
money for local charities. One would be a welcoming ceremony at
Alliance Airport, with an aerial show by the Blue Angels or
Thunderbirds preceding the arrival of both teams' charter planes.
The other would be an Olympics-style opening ceremony at TCU's Amon
Carter Stadium, preceded by a parade down University Drive.
</P>
<P>
   McHargue estimated that $1 million in charitable donations would
be ``very realistic'' from the ceremonies, which club officials
expect to attract a combined 100,000 fans. Under terms of the
proposal, the PGA of America could set whatever price it desired on
tickets to the events and would receive the tax benefit of the
charitable contribution.
</P>
<P>
   Both ideas, said McHargue, met with enthusiastic responses from
PGA of America officials, who have never held grand-scale opening
ceremonies in conjunction with past Ryder Cups.
</P>
<P>
   Cramped for corporate space on club property, Colonial officials
received permission to use facilities at Forest Park and the Fort
Worth Zoo to set up more than 100 corporate chalets, as well as a
40,000-square-foot merchandise tent. A 90-bus shuttle system has
been established to transport Ryder Cup spectators to the course
from 23,000 parking spaces in a variety of public lots within four
miles of the course.
</P>
<P>
   Colonial officials used 22 color-coded maps or drawings to
outline their logistical plans for PGA of America officials. To
give their presentation a Western flair, McHargue enlisted Steagall
to write a poem titled ``The Ryder Comes to Texas'' and had Joey
Jemison, a Fort Worth saddle maker, hand-tool leather covers for
each of the 10 proposals they left with PGA officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll promise you, they've never been courted like we've
courted them,'' said McHargue, whose committee has tapped funds
from club coffers and local businesses during a quest that began in
February 1996. ``From the beginning, we knew if we were going to be
seriously considered, we had to go above and beyond what other
people did. We made sure nobody can outproposal us.''
</P>
<P>
   Such aggressive thinking, said Colonial president Clark Martin,
has helped Colonial clear its two biggest hurdles _ concerns about
parking and corporate space _ and move from ``nowhere to a
contender ... with about a 50-50 shot'' of playing host to the 2003
Ryder Cup, based on feedback from industry insiders.
</P>
<P>
   Lanny Wadkins, 1995 Ryder Cup captain, has identified Colonial
and Pinehurst (N.C.) Country Club as the probable front-runners in
the race to land the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be my guess, based on what I'm hearing'' from PGA
officials, Wadkins said. Other clubs bidding to hold the event are
Medinah (Ill.) Country Club; Congressional Country Club in
Bethesda, Md.; Pebble Beach Golf Links in Pebble Beach, Calif., and
Oakland Hills Country Club in Bloomfield Hills, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Citing policy, PGA of America officials declined to discuss the
merits of sites. They did confirm that Colonial was the first club
to make a detailed, formal presentation in its quest to land the
Ryder Cup and suggested such a step might set the standard for
future suitors.
</P>
<P>
   How much weight Colonial's proposal will carry during site
deliberations is unclear. But there was no denying the presentation
was well-received in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was spontaneous applause when we finished,'' Martin
said. ``It kind of surprised us.''
</P>
<P>
   The warm reception convinced Colonial officials that their
$225,000 outlay could prime the pump for a financial bonanza for
Fort Worth-Dallas. Officials from Rochester, N.Y., site of the last
Ryder Cup held in the United States, estimated an economic impact
between $30 million and $50 million from having the 1995 event at
Oak Hill Country Club. Since that time, the Ryder Cup has
mushroomed in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth Mayor Kenneth Barr, who accompanied Colonial
officials to their final presentation in May, said a Ryder Cup at
Colonial would give Fort Worth ``a world visibility that we don't
have.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a great showcase for Colonial and for golf, which
is very important in Texas,'' Barr said. ``It would be a great
economic generator for us. There's no question, if they get the
event, we will commit whatever resources we need to make it
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The question, at this stage, is getting it. Only those inside
the PGA of America know the exact pecking order of clubs vying to
hold the event. And they're not sharing that information.
</P>
<P>
   Like PGA officials, Barr said he was taken aback by the
thoroughness and quality of Colonial's proposal, which he termed
``awesome.'' Club officials, he said, played every card in the deck
to sell a Texas-based Ryder Cup to PGA officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't get it, I think it would be because of politics
within the organization itself,'' Barr said. ``We've given them
every reason to choose Fort Worth that we possibly could.''
</P>
<P>
   McHargue concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how they can tell us, `No.' It just makes too much
sense to me,'' McHargue said. ``I've convinced myself that we're
going to get the thing. I don't know what more we could do, quite
frankly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
