<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAY CAN'T OPEN HOLES AND RUN THROUGH THEM, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Although he is the Giants' fullback, Charles Way
was the team's leading rusher last season. This year, the Giants
would like to expand his role, making Way the team's featured back
more often.
</P>
<P>
   There is one problem. Nearly every good running play involves a
fullback blocking ahead of the ball carrier. Way is by far the
team's most dependable blocker, but he cannot block for himself.
</P>
<P>
   That is why one of the principal goals for the Giants in
training camp is finding a reliable backup fullback _ someone they
can trust to pave the way for Way. Competition for the spot is
between Eric Lane, a second-year player, and the rookie free agent
Greg Comella.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of the few jobs on the team that has not been decided.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing between Lane and Comella was not made any easier after
Saturday's intrasquad scrimmage. Both players blocked and ran well,
even though the Giants offense was dominated by the defense.
</P>
<P>
   Comella, a Stanford graduate, seemed particularly at ease as a
receiver, making eight catches for 29 yards. One of those
receptions was a one-handed over-the-shoulder catch at top speed
along the sideline. Comella also rushed for 18 yards on three
carries.
</P>
<P>
   Lane had 11 rushing attempts for 24 yards and one reception that
lost yardage.
</P>
<P>
   Both showed promise with their blocking ability.
</P>
<P>
   Lane, signed by the Giants as a free agent last year after a
four-year career at Tennessee, was the backup to Way last season.
But the Giants coaching staff was hesitant to use the
6-foot-2-inch, 240-pound Lane in front of Way.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Giants are determined to find a backup fullback
they have confidence in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are aware that getting the ball to Charles is
important for us this year,'' Lane said. ``I have been working on
sustaining and finishing my blocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Giants coach Jim Fassel has not yet indicated that either player
has an edge in the competition for the job, though he appears to be
leaning toward Comella, whom Fassel never fails to praise for his
football instincts. After Saturday's scrimmage, Fassel had good
things to say about both players.
</P>
<P>
   Of Comella, Fassel said: ``He's a good multipurpose back. He can
run, block, catch, and he's smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Comella, who is 6-1 and 240 pounds, expected to be drafted, and
heard from nine National Football League teams when he was not. He
chose to sign with the Giants because he was assured there was
going to be a competition for the backup job.
</P>
<P>
   Lane and Comella each said there was no friction between them,
despite their competition and even though one of the two will
almost certainly be cut from the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a first-class kid,'' Lane said. ``I wish him the best.
And I'll be all right no matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   Comella said: ``You don't wish anyone ill will. It's not me
trying to beat him out or him trying to beat me out. We're both
just trying to do the best we can.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue will most likely be settled by performances in the
Giants' four preseason games. As Lane said Saturday, ``There's a
long way to go yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
