<DOCNO> NYT19980802.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-02 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4492 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-LAWSUIT-COX     08-02 2159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-LAWSUIT-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Circumstances of cycle shop shooting conflict between cops,
witnesses
</P>
<P>
   By Bill Rankin
</P>
<P>
   C. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When W.T. Standard and Associates employees heard
gunshots outside their building on the morning of Dec. 7, 1995,
they stepped out of their office to investigate the noise.
</P>
<P>
   Two employees of the automotive company saw a man holding a gun,
running toward them and away from the Moto Cycles shop across the
street. One of the workers ducked into an alley and the other hid
under a car. From there, they watched the gunman collapse on the
pavement and cry out for help, pleading that had been shot.
</P>
<P>
   The two office workers hesitated until Willie Sauls told them he
was an Atlanta police officer. With the help of another Standard
employee, they dragged Sauls inside their building. ``After we had
pulled (him) inside, he reached into his sweatshirt and pulled out
a badge,'' Matt James, a company manager, said in a sworn
affidavit. ``He held it up and said, `I'm a cop.' I did not know
this before the man pulled out his badge.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Officers Sauls, Waine Pinckney and Ivant Fields wore
their badges in plain view and properly identified themselves that
day remains a central questions in the Moto Cycles shop shooting
that killed Jerry Jackson. But a clearer picture of what happened
that morning is emerging as two lawsuits against the city and the
three officers make their way through federal court.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits were filed more than a year ago _ one by Jackson's
mother, Brenda Jackson, and another by two friends who were with
him that day, Toddrick Williams and Quentin Wimbish, who was shot
in the leg. Corey Dean, who also accompanied Jackson to the
motorcycle shop, has not sued.
</P>
<P>
   Senior U.S. District Judge Robert Vining ruled against the
officers last week, saying they violated the constitutional rights
of Jackson and his three friends by conducting an illegal stop and
seizure.
</P>
<P>
   A trial set for today has been postponed to allow the city to
appeal. It could take as long as a year before the appeals court
rules.
</P>
<P>
   The events of that day and the ensuing weeks _ the death of one
man and wounding of two, including a police officer; conflicting
accounts of the incident; accusations of some witnesses against
police, involving both the shooting and subsequent investigation _
coalesced in charges and countercharges and criticism of police. A
Fulton County grand jury considered murder charges against the
officers, but declined to indict them. The U.S. Justice Department
investigated civil rights violations but declined to seek charges.
Mayor Bill Campbell revived a dormant Citizen Review Commission,
which has yet to consider the case because of the pending lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   A routine investigation by the Atlanta Police Department's
Office of Professional Standards initially found against Pinckney
and Sauls, saying both improperly used their guns and gave
conflicting statements to investigators, according to documents in
the lawsuits. A draft memo by Maj. S.M. O'Brien, head of OPS,
expressed the same conclusion as Vining did on Monday. ``Based on
the statements of the officers and witnesses, there was not at this
time period reasonable suspicion to make a ... stop and frisk,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the shooting, the three officers followed Jackson
and his passengers into the Moto Cycles shop because, the officers
said, they suspected Jackson's car was stolen. Depending on the
version of events, the officers either approached the men with guns
drawn, or quickly drew their guns in response to what they
perceived as a threatening situation.
</P>
<P>
   When OPS issued its final report, it found only that Pinckney
improperly used his firearm during the incident. He was suspended
for five days for violating police procedure.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien testified that she backed off her original finding
because conflicting statements given by officers and witnesses were
never resolved. She testified that she now believes, ``The officers
had reasonable suspicion to conduct a field investigation'' of
Jackson and his companions.
</P>
<P>
   Setting the scene
</P>
<P>
   Through court motions, the lawyers representing the Jackson
family, Wimbish and Williams accuse the police officers of creating
a volatile situation fraught with danger and then intentionally
killing Jackson, who was unarmed and had committed no crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was the work of inadequately trained and supervised
officers whose actions in this case were reviewed by the department
and then covered up by the highest-ranking people in the
department,'' said Atlanta lawyer Al Pearson, lead attorney for
Brenda Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The city and the police officers strongly deny improper force
was used or that the rights of Jackson and his friends were
violated.
</P>
<P>
   Pearson, a former University of Georgia law school professor,
works for a law firm with a history of winning multimillion-dollar
verdicts. In 1993, Pearson's firm obtained a $9.8 million
settlement from Gwinnett County for a businessman investigated by
police officers who incorrectly suspected he was involved in
illegal drug activity.
</P>
<P>
   In mountains of documents filed in the lawsuits, police
testimony paints a picture of three officers doing a job.
</P>
<P>
   According to the officers' testimony, shortly after 11 a.m. on
Dec. 7, 1995, Fields, Sauls and Pinckney, all in plainclothes, got
in an unmarked, gray Pontiac 6000 and drove toward an International
House of Pancakes for breakfast. They saw a blue Pontiac 6000
driven by Jackson with passengers Wimbish, Dean and Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was driving to the Moto Cycles shop to discuss how much
it was going to cost to get a motorcycle repaired, his friends
testified.
</P>
<P>
   According to the officers' testimony, when they got close to
Jackson's car, Jackson and his friends began acting suspiciously.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's friends said they noticed the gray Pontiac was
following them, although they had no idea that it was an unmarked
police car. ``We were just thinking they were just regular young
fellows probably wanting to race because we had two of the same
type of cars,'' Wimbish said. ``We were thinking they wanted to put
the car to the test or whatever. We wasn't suspecting any drama.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinckney testified that some of the passengers in Jackson's car
made ``darting glances,'' leading the officers to suspect
incorrectly that the car was stolen. Fields, who was driving the
gray Pontiac, drove up to Jackson's car as Jackson turned into the
Moto Cycles parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Fields said Jackson made an ``abrupt'' turn into the Moto Cycles
shop parking lot, making him think that Jackson and his friends
were trying to elude them. ``The turn that they made was suspicious
to me...not illegal, just odd in my opinion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fields turned around and drove back to the parking lot to see
that the blue Pontiac was empty. As the officers checked to see if
the car was stolen, a car crash a block away brought employees and
customers in the Moto Cycles shop outside to take a look.
</P>
<P>
   The police version
</P>
<P>
   Up to this point, the officers and witnesses generally agree
about what happened on the day of the shooting. But versions of
what happend next conflict on almost every key point.
</P>
<P>
   According to the police officers' pretrial testimony and
statements they gave detectives, Sauls walked up to the crowd and
yelled out, ``Police. Let me see your hands.'' After he said this,
Sauls said, one of the men, later identified as Dean, ran into the
shop. And when a couple of the men kept their hands in their
pockets, Sauls said, he ordered them to get on the floor and took
out his gun, pointing it at a 45-degree angle toward the ground.
</P>
<P>
   As he walked up to pat down one of the men on the sidewalk,
Sauls said, he holstered his gun and was then shot. Mechanic Thomas
Stearns, who said he thought the motorcycle shop was being robbed,
fired three rounds at Sauls, who was shot in the stomach and wrist.
</P>
<P>
   Sauls said he then emptied nine rounds from his 9 mm Smith &AMP;
Wesson toward the door of the shop as he retreated across the
street before collapsing. All the while, he said, his police badge
was hanging on a chain outside of his sweatshirt. ``I remember as I
went to pat-search one individual, my badge was near my face,
dangling from the chain as I bent down,'' he told police
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Pinckney has testified that he was trying to determine if
Jackson's car was stolen when he heard the gunfire. He said he ran
toward the shop and saw the muzzle of a gun sticking out the door
toward Sauls. Pinckney said he then quickly fired two shots at the
muzzle and sought cover by a brick wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember seeing anybody,'' Pinckney said. ``All I
remember seeing was the muzzle. It all happened so quickly.''
Pinckney also insisted that he heard Sauls identify himself as
``police'' and that his badge was ``outside of my shirt, on a
chain, in plain view.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinckney's bullets ricocheted off the ground and killed Jackson
as he lay in front of the shop, GBI forensic tests concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The civilians' version
</P>
<P>
   While the police officers' pretrial testimony and statements to
investigators are similar in their accounts, Wimbish, Dean,
Williams and Moto Cycles shop employees have described a strikingly
different chain of events that led up to the shooting: Sauls walked
up with his gun already drawn. He did not identify himself as a
policeman and instead issued orders laced with profanity for the
crowd to get back in the shop and get on the ground. Sauls was
accompanied by another armed man who stood behind him in the
doorway, and neither man wore a badge.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous other witnesses to the shooting also say that none of
the officers wore identification. Mona Myer, another W.T. Standard
employee, said her co-workers were surprised to learn that the
injured Sauls was a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't know whether to go out and pull that man in,'' she
said of her co-workers. ``If they knew he was a police officer,
they wouldn't have hesitated to go get him....I am certain he
didn't have a badge on.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Lewis, part owner of neighboring Clearvue Glass &AMP; Mirror
Co., said that he witnessed Sauls running down the street and
firing at the motorcycle shop. Shortly after the shootout was over,
Lewis has testified, he got a phone call from a friend who was a
Fulton County deputy and who had heard a police officer had been
shot in his neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I didn't see a policeman. I saw a guy running and
shooting,''' Lewis testified. During a deposition, Lewis was shown
the Atlanta police report of his statement and asked to show where
the investigating officer had written down his statements that he
saw no badge around Sauls' neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be honest,'' Lewis said after reviewing the police
report. ``I don't see it. And I do recall the two or three
questions about identification on the person who did the shooting.
I remember specifically they asked me because that's the first
thing that they _ they wanted me to say one thing, but I knew
exactly what I had seen or hadn't seen and told them very
emphatically that there wasn't any identification visible.''
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the confusion is testimony from three eyewitnesses
who saw segments of the shooting from a fourth-floor loft across
the street. The witnesses, Bill Hallman, Serina Whitener and Jeanna
Shiver, said they saw a man wearing a gray plaid shirt stand over
the prone Jackson, who had raised his hand in an apparent plea for
mercy, and shoot him dead.
</P>
<P>
   But Fields, whose weapon was not fired, was wearing the gray
plaid shirt. Pinckney, who fired the bullets that killed Jackson,
wore a dark blue sweat shirt.
</P>
<P>
   In court motions, Pearson offers an explanation: By the time
Fields stood above Jackson, pointing his gun, Jackson was already
shot by Pinckney. Fields did not fire, but witnesses apparently
heard shots fired by Sauls as he retreated across the street.
</P>
<P>
   Pinckney shot at Jackson ``with the intent to kill,'' Pearson
said in a court motion.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by police investigators about a month after the shooting
if he intended to kill Jackson, Pinckney denied it. ``I would never
do something like that,'' he said. ``God knows, I would not do
something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   After 2 1/2 years, three investigations and more than a year of
discovery in the civil lawsuits, Pinckney's involvement in the
shooting remains one of many unanswered questions: Did the officers
wear badges and identify themselves? Did Sauls order Jackson and
the others to lie on the ground inside the shop or outside it? Why
did witnesses say a man in a gray plaid shirt appeared to shoot
Jackson when Fields did not fire his weapon?
</P>
<P>
   ``Only a trial is going to get the truth out,'' Pearson said.
``And we will be ready for trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
