<SLUG> BC-HOSTAGE-FREED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN AGREES TO WED TO HAVE DAUGHTER FREED
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANIEL VASQUEZ   AND ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHATHAM, Mass. _ The last time Lori Urs agreed to marriage, it
was to a death-row inmate about to be executed. Sunday, in the
presence of armed police units, she accepted a wedding proposal
that was arguably more unusual.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 hours after a former boyfriend stormed her house,
holding her and her 14-year-old daughter hostage at gunpoint, Urs
helped end the standoff by agreeing to one of his demands: that she
marry him immediately.
</P>
<P>
   John Nutter, 33, surrendered about 11 a.m., two hours after Urs
consented to his proposal, police said. He was arrested and charged
with rape, assault, and kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   Urs's daughter, Jennifer, was taken to Cape Cod Hospital for
evaluation and released at about 5:15 p.m. She and her mother
returned to their home about an hour later accompanied by police.
Mother and daughter said nothing to reporters and stayed only long
enough to collect overnight bags.
</P>
<P>
   Nutter apparently believed that the marriage would take place
after his surrender, and was told a minister had been summoned to
the scene of the standoff to perform the rites.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to be married in the ambulance,'' said State Police
Major John Kelley.
</P>
<P>
   Urs _ who had escaped from Nutter the night before, leaving
Jennifer behind _ helped negotiate the peaceful surrender by phone,
talking with the gunman from approximately 7 to 11 a.m., police
said. She accepted his marriage proposal at 9 a.m., as police were
trying to fill other requests from Nutter.
</P>
<P>
   State Police said they did not know whether Urs, 44, really
wants to marry Nutter.
</P>
<P>
   ``She went along with'' the proposal, Kelley said. ``It wasn't
easy for her. She helped us.''
</P>
<P>
   Urs made headlines worldwide last July when she married Joseph
R. O'Dell, a convicted murderer who later was executed in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Urs, then a student at the New England School of Law, had taken
up his cause as a member of an anti-death-penalty group, believing
his innocence could be proved by DNA tests. She later traveled to
Italy and struck up a relationship with Mother Teresa on her
husband's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time, Urs apparently befriended Nutter, and
police said he lived in her Chatham home for a time. But the
relationship quickly soured. And in an incident similar to
Sunday's, Nutter kept police at bay for six hours at Urs's home
last September, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Nutter was given a suspended three-year sentence in the earlier
crime, in part because Urs defended him in court, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted of the current charges, Nutter will face a
mandatory life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend standoff began at around 11 p.m. Friday, after
Nutter apparently broke into Urs's home at 118 Cross St., according
to police. There, he encountered her daughter and took her hostage,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   Urs arrived home a short time later and Nutter, waving a
shotgun, kept them hostage overnight, as more than 50 officers
surrounded the gray, two-story home near Chatham's tony tourist
strip.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Nutter raped Urs during the early hours of the
standoff. She then escaped while he slept Friday night, and was
treated at Cape Cod Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   It is the Globe's policy not to name rape victims unless they
agree to be identified. But since the two women allegedly taken
hostage had previously been named in published reports, the Globe
decided to report that Lori Urs is the alleged rape victim to make
it clear that is not her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, federal, state, and local agents continued to
surround the house, attempting to negotiate with Nutter, who placed
at least one phone call to the newsroom of a local newspaper,
demanding to ``let the world know the real situation.''
</P>
<P>
   In a conversation reprinted in The Cape Cod Times, Nutter
demanded cigarettes and the phone number of Sister Helen Prejean,
the author of ``Dead Man Walking,'' the story of a death-row
inmate.
</P>
<P>
   Nutter also admitted to slapping Urs because ``she deserved
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All she does is lie,'' Nutter told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   At 7 a.m. &UR;  &LR; Sunday, Urs reached Nutter by phone. At about that
time, Nutter tossed the 12-gauge shotgun out a second-story window,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   Urs managed to keep Nutter on the phone for most of the morning,
and though she was upset, ``she was pretty strong,'' Kelley said.
</P>
<P>
   As the standoff dragged on, neighbors were ordered to remain in
their homes, even though police did not believe Nutter posed a
genuine threat to anyone's life.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, several Chatham residents expressed irritation with
Urs, saying she should have been warned by her former boyfriend's
earlier behavior.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
