<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-VOTE-ART-390&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNING PARTY SEEMS TO HOLD PIVOTAL MEXICAN STATEHOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(js) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Miguel Aleman Velasco, a wealthy television
executive and son of a former president, appeared to be winning
victory by a broad margin as the Mexican governing party's
candidate in gubernatorial elections in Veracruz, one of three
states with local elections on Sunday, exit polls showed.
</P>
<P>
   President Ernesto Zedillo's party, the Institutional
Revolutionary Party, also seems to have held onto a governorship in
southern Oaxaca, tallying a narrow victory over the leftist Party
of the Democratic Revolution, according to exit polls.
</P>
<P>
   But in Aguascalientes, a small manufacturing state north of
Mexico City, the governing PRI party appeared likely to suffer an
important defeat.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI, whose presidents have led Mexico without interruption
since the party was founded in 1929, has never lost a gubernatorial
election in the three states that voted on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The balloting was part of a series of local elections that began
last month, in which new governors will be chosen in 16 states by
the middle of next year. All the contests are seen as tests of
party strength in advance of presidential balloting in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   An exit poll conducted Sunday by TV Azteca, one of two main
national networks, showed Aleman's winning 43 percent of the votes
in Veracruz, on the Gulf Coast, and his closest challenger, a
university professor from the National Action Party, receiving 25
percent, Sergio Sarmiento, the TV Azteca news director, said in an
interview. Televisa, Mexico's other leading national network, also
gave the victory to Aleman.
</P>
<P>
   The Veracruz balloting drew attention because in terms of raw
electoral weight, it was the most important race on Sunday. The
state is the third most populous in Mexico, with 6.7 million
people.
</P>
<P>
   In Aguascalientes, TV Azteca and Televisa said Felipe Gonzalez,
the National Action candidate, a newcomer to politics who heads a
family grocery business, was receiving at least 50 percent of the
votes. The governing party's candidate, Hector Olivares Ventura, a
former senator and party bureaucrat who is the son of a former PRI
governor, was trailing by more than 10 percent of the votes, both
networks reported.
</P>
<P>
   The exit poll results, if confirmed by official tallies, would
amount to a stinging defeat for the PRI.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The National Action Party, which was founded in 1939 and has
strong Roman Catholic roots, controls six of the 31 state
governorships. But its governor in Chihuahua, which borders Texas,
is a lame duck, because last month the party lost gubernatorial
elections to the governing party.
</P>
<P>
   That loss was humiliating and made Sunday's apparent victory
crucial for the National Action Party. Aguascalientes has a
population of 830,000. But it is the only state left this year or
next in which the party had good chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are extremely encouraging results,'' Felipe Calderon,
the party president said in a news conference Sunday night. ``They
show the PAN is not a party in decline.''
</P>
<P>
   In rural Oaxaca, where rebels are making inroads among the
Mixtec Indians and plantation peons, Televisa and TV Azteca said a
senator from the governing party, Jose Murat Casab, would defeat
Sen. Hector Sanchez, a popular former socialist from the Party of
the Democratic Revolution. Televisa said the governing party's
victory margin was 51 to 34 percent. TV Azteca said the results
were closer, 43 to 37.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders complained that the governing party was
pressuring rural voters in Oaxaca, but it was not possible to
confirm the assertions or to learn whether that might affect the
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   The Party of the Democratic Revolution was founded by Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas Solorzano, who won election last year as the first
opposition mayor in Mexico City. The party controls no state
governorships.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas, son of Lazaro Cardenas del Rio, the president who
nationalized the oil industry in 1938, is widely expected to make
his third run for the presidency, in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Partly for that reason, Aleman's candidacy in Veracruz has
aroused national interest. There is speculation that he, too, could
eventually seek the presidency. That would set up a race that would
include as candidates the sons of two former presidents who
governed with starkly contrasting visions.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas del Rio was a revolutionary general who championed the
working masses. But the Veracruz candidate's father, Miguel Aleman
Valdes, was the party's first civilian president, a businessman who
administered the postwar economic boom known as the ``Mexican
miracle'' from 1946 to 1952. A recently published history of Mexico
portrayed Aleman's presidency as one of the century's most corrupt.
</P>
<P>
   Aleman, 66, has appeared to unify behind his candidacy leaders
from feuding wings of the governing party, including so-called
dinosaurs like former Interior Minister Fernando Gutierrez Barrios
as well as powerful young executives like Emilio Azcarraga Jean,
the heir to Televisa.
</P>
</TEXT>
