<HEADER>
A4498 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUNNINGHAM-DANCE-REVI     08-02 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUNNINGHAM-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCE CUNNINGHAM: LYRICAL YET LARGER MOVEMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Mass., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BECKET, Mass. _ The curtain rose on a stage full of
already-moving bodies at the start of the evening. Those bodies
were still in motion when the curtain fell on the last dance of the
night, in two programs presented here by the Merce Cunningham Dance
Company on Friday and Saturday in the Ted Shawn Theater at the
Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Pure movement has seemed Cunningham's primary concern over 45
years of making dances for his company. It is a concern reflected
in the programs' earliest choreography, created in 1956, in the new
work on the program and in his latest explorations of computer
dance, the subject of a panel discussion and video installation
that were also part of this dance-packed weekend at Jacob's Pillow.
</P>
<P>
   One can see stories or human relationships in the dances,
certainly, and even in the elegantly drawn figures that work their
way across the video screen in ``Hand Drawn Spaces,'' the
installation created with Paul Kaiser and Shelley Eshkar. That is
part of the pleasure of Cunningham's dances, which tend to welcome
the viewer in and encourage a greater amount of participatory
imaginative play than work by most other choreographers.
</P>
<P>
   There is a hint as to the direction that play might take in the
title of the new work on the programs, ``Pond Way,'' in the hush
and hum of Brian Eno's score and in Suzanne Gallo's luminous white
costumes, in the calm abstraction of Roy Lichtenstein's ``Landscape
With Boat,'' which serves as a backdrop, and in the shifts from
warm to red side lighting, designed by David Covey, which subtly
suggest the passage of a day. ``Pond Way'' is one of Cunningham's
serenely lyrical ``nature'' dances, a work that is lightly dreaming
enough to serve as a program opener.
</P>
<P>
   The overall feel of ``Pond Way'' is of drifts of bodies, moving
at a gradually building pace only to disappear at the end, leaving
a single dancer to leap out of sight like a beautiful
water-skimming insect suddenly taking flight. In between, the
dancers draw close in stage-filling clusters that at first look
elegantly disordered, and in smaller ensembles typical of the
accidental-seeming encounters in Cunningham dance. The shifting
patterns are very like the large and small black circles that form
the suggestion of an image in the white canvas behind the dancers.
</P>
<P>
   Several of those encounters stand out in the flow. Thomas Caley
and Derry Swan, at first apart in spikey elegance, join to form a
thicket of crossing limbs. A duet for Jared Phillips and Jeannie
Steele follows, with Ms. Steele the sensuously oozing, slightly
disjointed near-still center of Phillips' urgent circling. A
sphinxlike Banu Ogan claims the stage for a slow, majestic crossing
through which she remains impervious to delicate male attempts to
impede her progress by touching her leg, her waist and her foot.
And five women emerge as a chorus of antique graces in a slowly
unfolding quintet that merges with the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pond Way'' and the programs' excerpt from a work in progress
suggest that Cunningham has become interested in much bigger
movement, like the totally unexpected split jumps and runs late in
``Pond Way.'' That new look is embodied in the stirring urgency,
and warmth, of Phillips' dancing, in Jean Freebury's endearing
wild-pony look and in Maydelle Fason, a fierce flea of a dancer
with long liquid arms. It will be interesting to see ``Pond Way''
on a bigger stage. But the intimacy of this theater allows the
viewer an unparalleled close-up look at the individuals who form
this inspired group of dancers. The cast of ``Pond Way'' was
completed by Lisa Boudreau, Holley Farmer, Matthew Mohr, Glen
Rumsey, Robert Swinston and Cheryl Therrien.
</P>
<P>
   The Cunningham company was far too generous in its programming,
however, making for a long night and dulled focus. It was good to
see excerpts from Cunningham's dark, charged 1964 ``Winterbranch''
on Friday and from the exquisite formalism of the 1956 ``Suite for
Five'' on Saturday, with Caley the epitome of earthy classicism in
the solo. Both pieces were parts of the programs' ``Event,'' which
concluded each night with dance from the work in progress. The
closing tableau of the unfinished piece was quietly stunning. But
by the time one made one's way into ``crwdspcr,'' which ended the
program, it was hard to revel in the surging rush of the
choreography and in the glittering clatter of John King's exciting
score.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which also included David Kulick and Daniel Squire,
will perform in Manhattan on Friday night at the Lincoln Center Out
of Doors festival.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
