<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-02 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4508 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-555&AMP;AD     08-02 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-555&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST ITALIAN IN 33 YEARS WINS TOUR DE FRANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Italy)  (lb) 
 By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Marco Pantani on Sunday became the first Italian in 33
years to win the Tour de France, but it was a depleted and
demoralized group of riders who crossed the finish line on the
Champs-Elysees.
</P>
<P>
   After dominating his rivals in the Pyrenees and Alps, Pantani's
lead was so secure that he was able to ride the final 91-mile leg
from Melun to Paris in the middle of the pack and withstand a flat
tire late in the leg. But his victory was accompanied by little of
the usual clowning and antics by fellow riders, because of the
ever-present drug scandal that enveloped the three-week race even
before it began in Dublin, Ireland, on July 11.
</P>
<P>
   In a normal year, this Tour would be recalled for some wonderful
racing, including what could become a legendary stage in the rainy
and foggy Alps in which Pantani crushed his main rival, Jan
Ullrich, the defending champion from Germany.
</P>
<P>
   But as Bobby Julich said after becoming the first American since
the three-time winner Greg LeMond to finish in the top three in the
Tour, ``Ten years down the line you may see an asterisk.'' Ullrich
finished second this year, 3 minutes 21 seconds behind. Julich was
4:08 out of first.
</P>
<P>
   Pantani at least will receive a hero's welcome in Italy on
Monday, where he will be acclaimed Campionnissimo _ champion of
champions. The last authentic one was the fabled Fausto Coppi, who
won the Tour de France in 1949 and 1952 and dominated the sport in
the 1940s and early 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   It is a title that is not easily earned, but one that Pantani
claimed by winning the Tour only two months after winning the Tour
of Italy, the world's second-ranked bicycle race to everyone except
the Italians.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a throwback, the old-fashioned kind of rider,'' Italian
Prime Minister Romano Prodi said in a telephone interview Sunday.
Prodi, a devotee of professional racing, meant that Pantani did not
base a season on one major race.
</P>
<P>
   The future of this 95-year-old race remains an open question.
Already there is talk of a boycott next year by foreign teams, with
the Spaniards leading the way. Four Spanish teams and an Italian
team quit the race last week to protest what they regarded as the
violation of human rights by the French police who have been
investigating allegations of the use of illicit
performance-enhancing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The unprecedented turmoil included the expulsion on July 17 of
the world's top-ranked team, Festina from France, after its coach
said he had supplied his riders with illegal drugs. In all, two
dozen riders, coaches, team doctors and masseurs have been taken in
for judicial questioning, and a quarter of them have been charged.
Five Festina riders have admitted that they practiced doping with
the artificial hormone EPO, or erythropoietin, and the TVM team
from the Netherlands is due in a French court Monday to testify in
a related case.
</P>
<P>
   Besides those two teams, members of two others have been taken
into custody and suspicion has fallen on two more in the Tour's
rolls of 21 teams. A leading rider, Rodolfo Massi, an Italian with
the Casino team from France and the former best climber, has been
arrested, and more Festina riders will be heard in court this week.
</P>
<P>
   The 96 riders remaining of the 198 who started made up the
smallest total since 1983, when 88 finished what 140 began.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Frankie Andreu, a U.S. Postal Service team rider from Dearborn,
Mich., summed up Sunday's atmosphere by recalling a recent
conversation with Patrick Jonker, a Dutchman with Rabobank:
</P>
<P>
   ``He said that when he came onto the Champs-Elysees this year,
he wouldn't have the same kind of tingling sensation of `I finished
the Tour and accomplished something.' It's more like, `We made it
to the Champs-Elysees and now we can get out of here and be done
with the race.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Marie Leblanc, the director of the race, echoed the
sentiment. Asked if he was happy that the race had continued
despite two strikes by riders and a threat by them to go home
before the finish, he said, ``Happy? I'm happy only to reach Paris.
Otherwise I'm not happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Claude Killy, the 1968 Olympic ski champion who is now
president of the Societe du Tour de France, the organizers, was
confident that the Tour would survive. ``You can't destroy a
myth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But others were not as resolute.
</P>
<P>
   Graham Jones, a Briton who rode five Tours from 1979 to 1987,
characterized the situation as a crisis, ``the biggest that we've
ever seen in cycling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A pity, a shame, a crisis for all of us,'' said Eddy Merckx,
the Belgian champion who won the Tour five times and was with the
race this year to watch his son, Axel, finish 10th overall.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Roche, the Irishman who won the race in 1988 and played
a leading role at the start in Dublin, called this ``a very rough
time'' but added hopefully that ``some good has to come out of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody admits there's a problem and that cycling has to get
its act together,'' he said. ``That's a good place to begin.''
</P>
<P>
   With such a traumatic backdrop for the race, perhaps it was
fitting that Pantani emerged the winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable what he's gone through, the sacrifices and
pain he has known,'' Prodi said.
</P>
<P>
   Pantani was hit by a car in the minor Milan-Turin race late in
1995, fracturing his legs. He spent the rest of that season and
most of 1966 on crutches, learning to walk again.
</P>
<P>
   Last year he had recovered, but bad luck struck again in the
Tour of Italy in June 1997, when, of all things, a black cat
crossed the road and caused a mass crash that took Pantani down. He
finished third in the Tour, the same placing he had in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   This year the 28-year-old leader of the Mercatone Uno won the
Tour of Italy by dominating his opponents in the mountains and then
riding a superlative time trial to finish third.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledged to be the sport's swiftest climber, the
5-foot-7-inch, 132-pound Pantani came into this year's Tour de
France with many complaints: The mountains were not difficult
enough, he said, and only two of the five daily stages in the
Pyrenees and Alps ended on a peak, meaning his rivals would have
the chance to catch him on long descents on three of those stages.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he finished second and first in the Pyrenees and
first and second in the Alps. The final Alpine stage was canceled
when the riders held a protest against the French police for their
handling of the doping investigation.
</P>
<P>
   With a lead nearing six minutes before the final time trial,
Pantani again finished a surprising third, guaranteeing himself
victory when the Tour finished in Paris Sunday. That was margin
enough to subdue panic when he had a flat on one of the first of 10
laps on the Champs-Elysees and had to be rushed back by his
teammates to the main pack.
</P>
<P>
   But Pantani rarely gives in to panic.
</P>
<P>
   Once known as Il Elefantino, the Elephant, because of his large
ears, Pantani has reshaped his image in the last few years. Now he
prefers to be known as Il Pirata, the Pirate, with his ears hidden
under a bandana, his head shaved, an earring in his left ear, and a
mustache and goatee.
</P>
<P>
   It gives him a suave appearance, but Felice Gimondi, the last
Italian to win the Tour de France, said: ``His biggest virtue is
his intelligence. He has an acute sense of the race.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A real star,'' Prodi said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
