u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-620     08-02 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL COLUMN: YANKS' POOR START? THAT'S ANCIENT HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In this season of the 50-game margin over .500, one
strange fact is now largely forgotten: The Yankees actually lost
the first three games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   It's just a silly memory now _ at least until the Yankees lose
another three straight _ but there was a full-fledged frenzy in the
news media when the Yankees stumbled through two games in Anaheim
and one in Oakland with an 0-3 record. Murdochian tabloidists were
waving the garish fright mask of The Man From Tampa, becoming
surrogate bully boys for the great man himself.
</P>
<P>
   Managerial rumors were being spread like cold-virus germs. Names
were being bandied about. Davey Johnson and Dick Williams and all
the old chestnuts were being warmed up to replace Joe Torre as
manager. That was this season, Doctor. Four short months ago. A
mere third of a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember Michael Kay saying that no team had ever lost
the first four games of the season and won the World Series,''
recalled David Cone, who was pitching Sunday night as the Yanks
tried to improve on their 77-27 record.
</P>
<P>
   Kay, a Yankee radio broadcaster, had indeed come up with that
statistic, which made the Yankees' fourth game, in Oakland, vital,
at least so far as panic-button pushers were concerned.
</P>
<P>
   When the Yankees won that game, the pressure was still not off.
They lost the fifth game of the season. ``We were thoroughly
embarrassed,'' recalled Cone, who was lighted up in the Kingdome
the night the Yankees fell to 1-4. ``We had to find a way to stop
the bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   This bunch of professionals held a clubhouse meeting and
promptly won 76 of their next 99 games. It is still true that the
team that has won the most games in one season, the 1906 Chicago
Cubs, promptly lost the World Series to the White Sox in six games
after their 116-36 regular season.
</P>
<P>
   So the Yankees have that dismal precedent to combat in October,
to say nothing of the specter of Randy Johnson, who, judging from
the way he struck out 12 in his winning debut with Houston on
Sunday, will inevitably pitch against the Yankees twice in the
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have faced panic before. George Steinbrenner went
into his Bluster act after the Yankees lost on opening day, with
only 161 games in which to recuperate. Somebody reached the man by
telephone to ask his reaction, which is tantamount to rapping on
the glass at the lion house in the zoo. Thus provoked, the Boss had
to be the Boss, opening up his jaws and emitting the predictable
growl about how the players would not ``have to sit around and read
about how good they're going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``We're behind Tampa Bay right now. That's one way to
look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's hard to look at it from that perspective after
the Yankees went 50 games over .500 on Saturday, and discovered
they like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our job to maintain an even keel,'' Cone said before
Sunday night's game. ``We have suffered tremendous losses in the
playoffs. This team has great perspective. We've had some big
losses in this place. We are very proud of this team, but we have
more to accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a great attitude, and a lot of it comes from Torre, who
seemed so calm in April when people were dusting off the fact that
the last time the Yankees lost three games to start a season was in
1985, and that Yogi Berra was soon dumped with a 6-10 record after
a meager 16 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I start worrying about that,'' Torre said in April, ``I'll
manage scared and distracted, and I can't do that. If we lose
three, four or five games, I'm not going to change what I do and
how I feel. That's not to say I don't feel bad about the losses.
They drive me nuts. But whatever the fallout of this is, that's
what it is.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Torre admitted Sunday evening that the poor start had concerned
him. The Yankees had not worked out much in the previous week
because of rain along the West Coast, and they were looking sloppy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we were better than that,'' Torre said, ``so we just
held a meeting and I pointed out that we had to play harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre remembers the meeting as calm. Another version is that
Paul O'Neill and a few other players railed at the Yankee pitchers
to protect them better with brushback pitches. In the sixth game,
David Wells lofted a couple of pitches over the head of Junior
Griffey, and when Griffey stared at him, Wells said, ``If he can't
take a joke, the heck with him.'' The tone was set.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had been more worried than he let on, Torre said:
``We had to believe that everything we had done in two years
wouldn't be erased by a week of bad baseball. You hope, and if it
is, so be it.'' Nothing like that happened. The Yankees are on
target to beat the Cubs' record. Somebody should call up the Boss
and remind him that the Yankees are not trailing Tampa Bay anymore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-98 2254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980802.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-02 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4514 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATINKIN-MUSIC-REVIEW     08-02 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATINKIN-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANDY PATINKIN: SINGING OUT IN A QUEST FOR ROOTS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: N.Y.)   (jw) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In America, we like to think of history as flowing in
a straight line, from the 19th century toward the 21st, from the
Old World to the New, from a rustic village on another continent
into the ``happily ever after'' of the great American melting pot.
It isn't that simple, of course. Whether we recognize it or not,
the flow goes in both directions. Wherever we go, we bring the past
with us, even if we don't realize it.
</P>
<P>
   You could describe Mandy Patinkin's inspired one-man show
``Mamaloshen'' (``Mother Tongue''), an evening of Yiddish songs
interspersed with American popular standards, as an intimate
dialogue between the Old and New Worlds, between Jewish tradition
and Jewish assimilation. The show, at a former synagogue on New
York's Lower East Side, is a theatrical elaboration of an album of
Yiddish songs Patinkin released early this year on Nonesuch
Records. The album and the show are part of an emotionally
supercharged restoration project by the 45-year-old American Jewish
singer and actor in which he seeks to recapture and honor a
tradition that many don't realize is a direct forerunner of
Broadway musical comedy.
</P>
<P>
   The thread Patinkin uses to connect a dozen or so Yiddish songs
is Paul Simon's austere 1973 ballad ``American Tune,'' a morose
folk-pop hymn that when it first appeared was read by many as a
sad-hearted lament for the decline of American idealism in the age
of Watergate. Here, Patinkin recognizes it as a song about the
immigrant experience, breaking it into fragments that become
chapter headings in a program that includes a playful children's
alphabet song, ``Oyfn Pripetshik,'' and a searing Holocaust song,
``Unter Dayne Vayse Shtern.''
</P>
<P>
   As deconstructed by Patinkin, ``American Tune'' becomes a
surreal reflection in which he travels through time and has a
series of visionary flashes that suggest the images and colors of a
Chagall painting.
</P>
<P>
   Other familiar standards woven into the program and sung
sometimes in English, sometimes in Yiddish, sometimes in both,
include Irving Berlin's ``God Bless America'' (performed while a
giant American flag unfurls at the back of the stage) and ``White
Christmas'' (delightfully re-interpreted as a dizzy skipping
instrumental duet by Eric Stern on piano and Saeka Matsuyama on
violin), and Leonard Bernstein and Stephen Sondheim's ``Maria''
(``Mayn Mirl''), from ``West Side Story.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Take Me Out to the Ball Game,'' composed in 1908 by Jack
Norworth and Albert Von Tilzer, is offered as a proto-melting pot
celebration in which America is a great big happy American family
munching peanuts and Cracker Jacks at a baseball game. In the
hourlong show's corniest moment, Patinkin coaxes the audience into
standing up and dancing the hokeypokey.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, the singer, dressed in black, brings his
characteristic ferocity to the material, turning it into a
sustained drama of his spiritual and esthetic quest for roots. Some
of the Yiddish songs, like ``Motl der Opreyter,'' the story of a
tailor working in a sweatshop who is killed in a union strike, are
wrenching. Patinkin dramatizes everything in a sharply etched
vocabulary of hand gestures that range from the explanatory to the
fist-shaking. His voice can dip from a reedy, brittle falsetto
filled with a childlike wonder and longing, into a deep feral
growl.
</P>
<P>
   There are no emotional halfways. You feel the agony, anxiety and
joy that fueled Jewish immigration from Eastern Europe to America.
Just as powerfully, the show conveys an abiding nostalgia for the
language and culture left behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mamaloshen'' runs through Aug. 22 at the Angel Orensanz
Foundation and Center for the Arts, at 172 Norfolk St., on the
Lower East Side.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
