<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Sunday 8/2/98. Photo clients
will automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or
may download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) DETROIT -- Aug. 2, 1998 -- MICHIGAN-GOVERNOR, 8-2 --
Geoffrey Fieger campaigning for the Democratic nomination for
governor of Michigan, at a picnic for the elderly held on the
Detroit River. Fieger, leading in opinion polls in Tuesday's
contest over two conventional politicians, is a millionaire lawyer
who has never held political office. A brash populist, he has taken
the lead largely by building support among black voters in Detroit,
who like his style and talk about racism. (Peter Yates/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) PHILADELPHIA -- Aug. 2, 1998 -- FAKE-CRIME-STATS, 8-2 --
John Timoney, who became Philadelphia's Police Commissioner in
March, found that crime was being seriously underreported in
Philadelphia, forcing withdrawal of some of the city's numbers from
FBI reports. ``I can guarantee you crime is going to be way up this
year,'' says Timoney. ``But I don't care. If we are going to get
this right and reduce crime, we have to start with accurate
statistics.'' (Sal DiMarco Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) PLACERVILLE, Calif. -- Aug. 2, 1998 -- DOCTORS-FREEDOM-2,
8-2 -- State-of-the-art clinics, including this one in Placerville,
Calif., built by the Foundation Health Corporation, with enough
space for 12 doctors, is sleek, expensive and bankrupt. In October
1996, FPA Medical Management Inc., a San Diego-based company paid
$220 million for the Foundation doctors' group, and leased the
half-empty medical centers. Companies like FPA have come to realize
that buying a medical practice may not be such a good investment.
(Don Preisler/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) PLACERVILLE, Calif. -- Aug. 2, 1998 -- DOCTORS-FREEDOM-1,
8-2 -- Dr. Earl Washburn III examining Kurt Hogan, 13, at the
pediatrics practice he started 22 years ago in Placerville, Calif.
Today, Washburn has four partners and one associate in the El
Dorado Pediatrics Medical Group. Like doctors across the nation,
Washburn and his partners have been swept up in a rolling wave of
medical mergers and acquisitions. ``It's like some science fiction
story, a parallel universe,'' says Washburn, ``where they keep
switching you from one universe to the next with a new set of
rules.'' (Don Preisler/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) MONTEZUMA CREEK, Utah -- Aug. 2, 1998 -- FUGITIVE-SEARCH,
8-2 -- A tourist from Tennessee reading a wanted poster for Jason
McVean and Alan Pilon, in Montezuma Creek, Utah. As many as 500 law
officers have been searching the red-rock canyons and mesas of
southeast Utah for the two fugitives, suspected of killing a police
officer and wounding three sheriffs. On May 29, the men vanished
into this vast no man's land known as the Four Corners, where the
boundaries of Colorado, Utah, Arizona and New Mexico meet. (Kevin
Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Aug. 2, 1998 -- GUGGENHEIM-HOGS-2, 8-2 --
Rich Dragos, at right (pointing), Bruce Bigelow and Michael
Rathmann, bikers from Lake Ronkonkoma, Long Island, viewing a
vintage motorcycle at the ``The Art of the Motorcycle,'' an
exhibition now on display at the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum.
Bathed in biker glory, it has become the most highly attended
exhibition in the Guggenheim's 61-year history, far outstripping
retrospectives of Robert Rauschenberg, Roy Lichtenstein and more
popular than authoritative surveys of Chinese, Russian and Italian
art. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Aug. 2, 1998 -- GUGGENHEIM-HOGS-1, 8-2 --
``The Art of the Motorcycle,'' an exhibition now on display at the
Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum, is quite different from anything else
that Museum Mile on Fifth Avenue has ever experienced. Bathed in
biker glory, it has become the most highly attended exhibition in
the Guggenheim's 61-year history, far outstripping retrospectives
of Robert Rauschenberg, Roy Lichtenstein and more popular than
authoritative surveys of Chinese, Russian and Italian art. (Edward
Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BECKET, Mass. -- Aug. 2, 1998 -- CUNNINGHAM-DANCE-REVIEW,
8-2 --The Merce Cunningham Dance Company in ``Pond Way,'' a new
work at the Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival, in Becket Mass. Pure
movement has been Cunningham's primary concern over 45 years of
making dances for his company. ``Pond Way'' is no exception, being
one of Cunningham's serenely lyrical ``nature'' dances. (Alan E.
Solomon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 2, 1998 -- NEWS-MAG-MEDIA, 8-2 --
Stephen Smith, 49, the new editor of U.S. News &AMP; World Report,
which trails Time and Newsweek in both circulation and ad pages.
Smith's extensive experience with newsweeklies may serve him well,
but he is still walking into a job in which few editors have lasted
more than two years. ``I am not an ideological guy,'' he says. ``I
got into journalism not to save the world but to do good stories.''
(Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Aug. 2, 1998 -- VILLAGE-MEDIA, 8-2 -- Candice
Carpenter, 46, the chief executive and co-founder of the Web site
iVillage.com, provides advertisers with access to well-educated
women with high incomes. iVillage.com began with little more than
the premise ``Internet for the rest of us'' and a focus on baby
boomers. It has evolved into the leading women's online
``community'' on the Web. ``We offer the intimacy of community with
the scale of media,'' she says, describing iVillage.com as
``utilitarian.'' (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
