one of Cunningham's serenely lyrical ``nature'' dances. (Alan E.
Solomon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 2, 1998 -- NEWS-MAG-MEDIA, 8-2 --
Stephen Smith, 49, the new editor of U.S. News &AMP; World Report,
which trails Time and Newsweek in both circulation and ad pages.
Smith's extensive experience with newsweeklies may serve him well,
but he is still walking into a job in which few editors have lasted
more than two years. ``I am not an ideological guy,'' he says. ``I
got into journalism not to save the world but to do good stories.''
(Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Aug. 2, 1998 -- VILLAGE-MEDIA, 8-2 -- Candice
Carpenter, 46, the chief executive and co-founder of the Web site
iVillage.com, provides advertisers with access to well-educated
women with high incomes. iVillage.com began with little more than
the premise ``Internet for the rest of us'' and a focus on baby
boomers. It has evolved into the leading women's online
``community'' on the Web. ``We offer the intimacy of community with
the scale of media,'' she says, describing iVillage.com as
``utilitarian.'' (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
