<SLUG> BC-NY-PORN-CRACKKDOWN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEX SHOPS' LAWYER CHALLENGES INSPECTIONS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: N.Y.)   (jw) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The city's crackdown on the sex industry will face a
last-ditch court challenge Monday by a lawyer for six Manhattan
strip clubs and adult video stores who says he can prove they have
complied with the city's new restrictions and should not be shut
down.
</P>
<P>
   A Supreme Court hearing set for Monday afternoon could decide
the fate of Show World, the labyrinthine 1970s-era sex emporium at
42nd Street and Eighth Avenue, as well as other similar businesses.
The hearing comes two days after three strip clubs elsewhere in the
city were raided by the police and padlocked by building
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, on Friday, a Queens judge ordered three other strip
clubs to stop allowing nudity or also be closed.
</P>
<P>
   The raids and court orders were described as the first wave in a
series of closings aimed at eliminating most of the 144 such
businesses in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But Herald Price Fahringer, lawyer for Show World and five other
Manhattan sex shops, said Sunday that he could show that his
clients had adapted to the city's new rules _ in particular, one
that defines a sex shop as a store that devotes more than 40
percent or more of its business to pornographic material.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Show World has added hundreds of old, G-rated
videotapes to its basement offerings, placing ``Snow White and the
Seven Dwarfs'' and ``Beauty and the Beast'' a few steps from a rack
filled with rubber sex toys.
</P>
<P>
   It has also installed pool tables, at $2 a game, although none
of them were in use during a visit late Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   And at the two Harmony Theaters _ one at 279 Church St., the
other at 161 W. 22nd St. _ the dancers have taken to wearing tops
and bottoms, Fahringer said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the three strip clubs that were padlocked on Saturday _
El Coche, in Hunts Point, the Bronx; Wiggles, in East Flatbush,
Brooklyn, and Sharks Go-Go, in Midland Beach on Staten Island _
city officials said their owners were entitled to court hearings no
later than Tuesday, in which they may ask for a chance to defend
their businesses at full civil trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could challenge our proof at trial, or they may walk
away,'' said Steven Fishner, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's criminal
justice coordinator. ``Their cases could also be settled.
Ultimately, we want these locations to be reopened as lawful
businesses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-98 2311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980802.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-02 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4606 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-CROUSE-LADN     08-02 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-CROUSE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TENNIS ROOTS NEED WATERING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The drive from home to the Los Angeles Tennis
Center winds around a public golf course and past four public
tennis courts. On Sunday afternoon there were kids swatting at golf
balls on the driving range. But the courts sat baking in the sun,
deserted save for a couple of in-line skaters.
</P>
<P>
   It would be simple to look at the hale spectator turnout for
Andre Agassi's straight-set victory over Tim Henman in the final of
the Mercedes-Benz Cup and surmise that there's nothing wrong with
tennis in the United States that a deep, first-rate field couldn't
fix.
</P>
<P>
   But far away from the decorated athletes and the designer
clothes and cars, the fuzz is off the tennis ball. The United
States Tennis Association, slow to recognize the drying out of the
sport at the grass-roots level, is now going to great lengths to
shower the neglected area with attention.
</P>
<P>
   Last year USTA president Harry Marmion appointed a committee to
explore ways to improve the junior-developmental program.
</P>
<P>
   Pumping millions of dollars into it is a start, but it'll end up
being so much overrun without the proper caretaking. For years, you
see, the USTA has been like the home owner who meticulously
maintains his front yard to keep up appearances while allowing his
back yard to get choked by weeds.
</P>
<P>
   As far back as 1987, a monthly tennis publication was running
stories on ways to resurrect American tennis. The U.S. continues to
lag behind Europe in the cultivation and care of tennis talent
because funding for junior programs was not appreciably greater in
1997 than it was 10 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, deep pockets have tended to be more of a precursor
for net success in the U.S. than solid ground strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, tennis remains very much a high-end sport. After all,
it wasn't the Saturn Cup that concluded Sunday. And those were
Tommy Hilfiger shirts the volunteers were wearing, not Hanes.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for the USTA, said the 11th-ranked Agassi, ``is to
get kids with the most ability as opposed to kids with the most
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Money matters less in the European countries. There the most
promising young players, particularly the boys, are routinely
funneled into tennis camps, where they receive top-notch training
and coaching _ along with an education _ in a highly controlled,
ultra-competitive setting.
</P>
<P>
   There are private tennis academies in the U.S. that provide the
same environment _ Nick Bollettieri's camp in Florida, which Agassi
once attended, is perhaps the most renowned of the lot. But the
costs of attending one effectively exclude all but the well-heeled
or the well-grounded whose superior skills afford them a free pass.
</P>
<P>
   The USTA, instead of embracing the private academies, has often
viewed them as an adversary. That needs to change, as does the
patently American affection for tiptoeing around children's psyches
for fear of disturbing them.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, the top young players have a wealth of tournaments in
which to hone their games, more than four dozen a year. That's not
the case in the U.S., where the number of International Tennis
Federation events have been restricted to fewer than a dozen by
administrators concerned over the possible psychological
ramifications of exposing young kids to too much cutthroat
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Even when a young player's psyche is willing, the cost of
tournaments can be prohibitive, what with the entry fees and travel
expenses. Former UCLA standout Justin Gimelstob is among the
current crop of up-and-coming kids to have benefited from the
USTA's growing largess. Twenty-one-year-old Jan-Michael Gambill,
No.65 with a bullet, is another.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the time I was 12, the USTA has helped support me with
coaching, with everything,'' said Gimelstob, 21, who upset
top-seeded Patrick Rafter in the quarterfinals here on Friday
before losing to Agassi in the semis. ``It has been a huge support
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The ascension of sisters Venus and Serena Williams, who learned
the game on the courts of Compton, could democratize tennis the way
Tiger Woods did golf. But they remain at least a Grand Slam title
away from transforming their sport. In the meantime, Agassi wishes
more tennis players could be culled from the inner cities.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, of course, as described by Agassi, is, ``it's much
easier to find a rim somewhere and get one basketball than it is to
find rackets, balls and another player.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennis in this country has undergone more rebirths than Agassi,
so perhaps all is not lost. There are some foreign-born players who
question whether or not it even has been misplaced. Listening to
Henman, a Brit, you're reminded that one country's definition of a
crisis is another's idea of a craze.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you've had your fair share of great players,'' Henman
said testily. ``When you can just name off the top of your head
(Pete) Sampras, (Jim) Courier, Agassi and (Michael) Chang, you
shouldn't be complaining.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
