<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS BEAT DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Now, the Dodgers are hoping Hideo Nomo is the pitcher
they remember.
</P>
<P>
   They don't want to see the one with fresh memories of Nomomania
or the no-hitter or all those strikeouts, but the struggling
right-hander whom they traded in June to the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, they want to see on the mound at Shea Stadium a pitcher
who can still bounce a few forkballs and help !ital!them!off!
salvage a split of a four-game weekend series after a dreadful 9-3
loss Sunday in front of 33,843.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy did a lot for this organization,'' said general
manager Tom Lasorda, once Nomo's manager. ``But now he is standing
in the way of where we need to go.''
</P>
<P>
   With any luck the Mets should be sending Nomo to the mound to
complete a sweep, but the Dodgers won the series opener Friday on a
couple of ninth-inning blunders by New York. Saturday, the Dodgers
gave that one back with a messy ninth of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 24 hours later, the Mets moved 2{ games ahead of the
Dodgers in the wild-card chase. The Chicago Cubs lead San Francisco
by 2{.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, Nomo will face Dave Mlicki, one of the pitchers the
Dodgers got in the June 4 deal with New York.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Dodgers listened as the boos got louder for their
old catcher Mike Piazza, who finally managed an infield hit after
going hitless in his first 10 plate appearances in the series. But
the visitors had their own problems. Errors by third baseman Adrian
Beltre and center fielder Raul Mondesi in the third inning led to
five unearned runs and buried left-hander Brian Bohanon (4-7).
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi was back in the lineup after missing two games with
lower-back pain, but he should have stayed in bed. The rest of the
offense should have, too. On this trip, the Dodgers are 9 for 46
(.196) with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre booted a ground ball by Mets starter Armando Reynoso
(2-0) to start the inning. One batter later, Edgardo Alfonzo lined
to center, but Mondesi lost the ball in a blinding sun and it
caromed off his glove. John Olerud flied to center for what should
have been the final out. Instead, it was a sacrifice fly that
scored Reynoso.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were just getting warmed up. Piazza, who Mets GM Steve
Phillips said is pressing, grounded to short, but Brian McRae lined
a two-run single to center and Butch Huskey crushed a two-run homer
to left. The Mets, who later lost Huskey with a severe hamstring
pull, added three runs in the eighth, two on a two-out single by
Olerud, who extended his hitting streak to 16 games. The Dodgers
had two runs in the ninth, but after the game they were stinging
about the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those conditions are out there for both teams, we can't let
things like that beat us,'' manager Glenn Hoffman said. ``It was
good to have Mondy back, but he needs to make that play.''
</P>
<P>
   Nomo originally was scheduled to pitch Sunday but was bumped to
tonight so Reynoso could get some work. Nomo has adopted a policy
of not speaking to the media the day before a start so he has gone
underground since Friday. But his attempt to come back after a
miserable start with the Dodgers is on the minds of many people,
especially since he has won his last three starts for New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be much bigger when he comes to L.A. for the
first time as a Met,'' said former teammate Eric Karros.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Wallace, the former Dodgers pitching coach and now a
special assistant to Phillips with the Mets, said many disregarded
the severity of Nomo's offseason surgery that removed bone chips
from his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how mild the surgery was, it was still an
operation,'' Wallace said. ``Players need to time to recover and I
think that was a big part of Nomo's problem. There is no question
he struggled with the Dodgers and it has been a slow process. But
we are starting to see good signs.''
</P>
<P>
   One of most frustrating parts of former manager Bill Russell's
tenure with the club was the relationship with Nomo, who wanted to
pitch deep into games even without his best stuff. When Nomo
continued to pitch poorly, scouts pointed to his years in Japanese
baseball when it was not uncommon to throw more than 200 pitches in
a game. Mets manager Bobby Valentine, who managed in Japan for a
year, said pitchers there are no longer taxing themselves that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``They actually learned that from us, the idea that more is
better,'' Valentine said. ``But there have been times when I've
gone to the mound to take the ball from Nomo and he has given it up
willingly. Maybe it is part of the learning process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
